text: the smell is absolutely unique . it has a very herbal nose , after sniffing for a bit , it seemed like a great flavor for a potpourri . one of the best smelling beers i have ever tried .  this is a very refreshing beer . i love a hoppy , complex tasting beer , but sometimes i just want a lighter beer that is n't heavy or dominating the flavor of my food . this beer is light , crisp , and has a great taste . perfect pairing for a good pizza .

very rich aroma . quite sweet - lots of dextrins in the finished beer . still , interesting and somewhat complex flavor and aroma .  this is something that i was really looking forward to at the southeastern ratebeer gathering . the huge aroma is screaming spruce at me . the malt is dry and clean and really comes across as a dry brown ale than a porter . still , it 's tasty and one of the few dark beers i 've had that had dominant hops that i really think work that way .

bottle courtesy of hopdog : poured a deep clear golden color ale with a super huge bubbly white head with average retention but great lacing .  i hate to give a beer ( especially a trappist ) a bad review but this beer was not very good at all . i had a few sips and then poured the rest of the 750 down the drain . i may have gotten a bad batch but i found this beer to be quite bitter and sour and not what i would expect from a tripel .
aroma is grapefruity hoppy goodness .  medium-bodied rather than thick .
great pour to a beautiful dark red-brown thick foamy head , light tan that settles slowly leaving curtains on the glass .  m - a bit on the thin and watery side .
aroma is tons of sweet malts and raisins mixed with some alcohol .  mouthfeel was n't bad , but was n't great either .

a : pours a deep golden brown with a decent head that very much clings to the glass s : obviously coffee shines through in this one . also a sweet malty punch at the end . very nice , especially if you 're a coffee drinker t : a classic brown ale with a mellow coffee layer that lingers throughout m : bitter , dry , slightly acidic d : all day , all night . i second the idea of victory putting this one into a bottle .  mouthfeel - medium..maybe a little on the more watery side , but still creamy-ish .

s-tropical & citrus fruits and hops dominate . i could have sat there for 10 minutes with my nose in the glass , but many beers to get through on this night so i carry on .  a- i had it in a bottle so i ca n't say . also this was the imported munich gold version s- smells like awesome sauce t- the taste is kind bready with some sweet maltige m- not much slides right on down d- goes down the hatch with ease overall i really like this juice !

aroma is very nice with an in your face bourbon barrel punch to the face and a rounded coffee and malt background . ok ... they have lost me now , the taste is ok , but this is a muddled mess . complex ? or ... just too much going on ?  in the mouth , it 's a touch thin and gritty .

poured into a new belgium snifter a - transparent blood red , half finger head , off white almost tan/brown and some serious lacing s - sweet .  high carbonation is the only downfall i can find in this beer .
this beer starts off with a huge , everlasting tan head .  mouthfeel is a little on the light side , but when it comes down to it this is a really amazing beer .
aroma : fresh , fruity ( like peaches or apricots ) , and caramel , but a presence of tartness . comments : a very dynamic beer .  m - the mouth feel is lush and oily but a tad too soft by the end .

very sweet , but not overly so , and with a nice hop presence , but not as strong as i was expecting . a great scent , overflowing with tropical fruit and hops . too much caramel and maltiness combined with very little bitterness makes for one disappointing imperial ipa .  sampled this beer at founders own tap room . the beer was way too sweet . the malts from the stout style could not overcome the maple and and sweetness from the high gravity . that rarely happens , i almost never orphan a beer . founders has many beers that are excellent , this was not one of them .

inviting aroma of roasted malt , espresso , licorice and subtle smokey notes . flavor is disappointing after the very inviting aroma . even mouthfeel , moderate carbonation , good body for the style .  m- this beer is very carbonated and somewhat thin , very refreshing .

flat-out loaded with fragrances . sour cherry , roasted malt , english toffee , cream sherry & many others that my still-budding nose will be able to detect with more training . looks & smells like a winner , just need to let it warm up a bit .  mouthfeel : light to medium .

the beer poured into the chalice crystal clear amber golden with a white tall frothy head which fell slowly to lace the glass .  you could certainly taste the chocolate , but it did n't fill the mouth with the heavy , rich bitter chocolate of some other beers in this same vein . i enjoyed drinking this beer ; it went down easily , but if given the choice , i would take the brooklyn chocolate stout , which is more like comfort food in the fall when it 's getting cold and the leaves are dying . this is supposed to be a beer you can snuggle with next to the fireplace while watching monday night football .

i love hops , and you get strong nostril stinging hop aroma up front . actually smells similar to a hop flower . t- surprisingly sweet , very strong . clearly much stronger than your average beer but still very drinkable .  m- a little on the watery side , a little carb still hangs around .

pours pretty near black with a lightly tanned 1 cm head that keeps lasting several minutes after the pour .  m : pretty low carbonation , which is definitely not a problem for the style . the body 's a little thinner than i 'd prefer , though . a nice , smooth mouthfeel to the beer .

s - sweet , brown sugar with dark fruits ( raisins , dates and figs ) plus a definite hint of alcohol . t - much like the nose with lots of thick sweetness reminiscent or molasses and caramelized brown sugar plus a black peppery spiciness .  mouthfeel is a bit lean , and watered down .

very aromatic and interesting . tastes potently sour tart . i 'm truly amazed they were able to capture the floral essence so well in smell and taste .  mouthfeel : thin to reference the entire continuum of beers , but average for a pilsner .

big , woody , bourbon notes come off this thing . it 's a big aroma , but it 's not offensive . it 's medium , but with the great aroma and solid taste , it really would have rounded this out nicely with a more chewy feel .  m - light-medium body a bit chewy but with a ton of carbonation ... a bit distracting and makes the beer lose steam and fizzle in your mouth .

750ml bottle poured into a tulip glass . very attractive light orange amber , with some flashes of gold and deeper orange in its core ; almost looks like a tequila sunrise with just a splash of grenadine . massive off-white head is the first indication of what 's sure to be high carbonation , and there are lots of bubbles racing to the top , as well . retains a nice film but not much stick . really pretty beer .  m - nice carbonation , but it could be much bigger bodied .

( t ) - similar to the smell in alot of ways . a dry grassy earthy cheese to it . ( d ) - a decent gueuze . smelled and looked great , but some off-flavors keep this from being great . still enjoyable though .  appearance : pours a cloudy amber , moderately carbonated with offwhite foam , leaving moderate foamy lacing . smell : hops are floral and sweet , blending well with the strong raspberry undertones . taste : begins tart , with mellow floral hop taste , very light toasty malts which bring forth the hints of raspberry and honeycomb , finishes witha tangy bitterness that allows a slight yet lasting raspberry lingering . drinkability : very delicious small batch by mbc , its well brewed and the subtle notes of the raspberry are not forced , decent abv as well .

on-tap at the cafe , drank from a 5oz tasting glass ... dark brown with a hint of amber , very clear on the edges , looks great . a big head rises a couple fingers but then fades immediately , light lacing ... the aroma is totally dead , nothing going on ... the taste is light coffee , boring , ca n't even tell rye is here .  f & t : crisp , firm moderate body , more rounded feeling than a lot of macro lagers .

appearance : pours a dark auburn body with 2-3 fingers worth of light tan head .  poured a darkish amber red with a smallish head , big hop nose and very hoppy but not overly bitter finish , carbonation was somewhat low on this beer but as big as it is that does not seem to hurt seems more like how a barley wine would be , as the beer warms up it becomes much more mellow and takes on a carmelly complex flavor . all in all i would say a very good 10 % iipa

smell = very nice scent of brown sugar and malt with a definite hop presence in the background . this is probably the best smelling saranac beer i 've encountered . it certainly started off great in the nose ... the taste was very disappointing though .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied . medium-low carbonation .

this poured a perfect beautiful black leaving a nice thick tan head that lingered for a while .  entry is nice withy carbonation lightly brushing the sides of the tongue with a mouthfeel a little thinner than i 'm used to with an ipa . midtaste hits the sweet spot with a nice pale malt and grapefruity hops .

pours a dark brown with a red tint . a large tan head forms and has excellant retention before settling to a thick cap . heavy lacing is left on the glass . at least it looks good .  this is a pretty good belgian , but the spicy character takes away from the drinkability and the mouthfeel .

appearance this one poured a beautiful bright orange in color with gorgeous yellow hues around the edges and a full , lingering , lacing head .  in a snifter a : deep , dark ruby red ; very little head ; s : raspberry , sweet , bottle fermentation t : outstanding flavor ; perhaps not exactly what i expect in a quad ; strong , complex , bold belgian-style ale with prominent streaks of cherry , berry ; toffee and caramel flavors enter too ; this beer aims toward the flavor profile of a port i liked this beer very much , overall ; although it is quad-style , do n't expect it to try to reach the quad prototype ; quaddish is probably a better name , and you 'll enjoy it all the more .
a-really looks the part . deep dark brown bordering on black with a creamy , frothy tan head .  milk sugar in a beer ?
a very deep reddish-brown with a slightly brownish head .  nice dry finish . a bit too carbonated for my liking .
this smells amazing . it 's hard to put down .  mouthfeel : medium body with a bit of oil that leaves a coat .

s - pungent , fruity hops that are reminiscent of jaialai ipa . d - very nice , the malt and hops are perfectly balanced , especially in the aroma where the fruity notes perfectly compliment the sweetness of the toffee and caramel .  taste : very little carbonation .

a-pours an orange/copper with a head that is four fingers thick . the head is extremely dense and it dissipates slowly leaving a thick lacing on the sides of the mug . there was lacing down the entire glass .  pours black but with some deep red highlights with a slight off-white head that is gone in a flash leaving nothing behind , milk chocolate is very prevelant in the aroma with a little smokiness and a roasted coffee hint.nice deeply roasted flavor with big doses of cocoa and smoke , alot of flavor melding going on but seemed a little light in the mouthfeel department otheriwise a top notch brew.a easy drinker with alot of flavor needs a little tweaking to be great in my opinion .
s - holy crap , this smells insanely good . i did n't want to like this , but if the smell indicates anything , this will be a buy-again .  m : very normal carbonation .
wonderful smelling . it 's like holding a green apple blow pop up to your nose .  m : medium-bodied , but i feel like there 's something missing .

it poured a good foamy one and one half inch head that slowly dissapated and left a slight creamy lace on top that stuck to the glass throughout the entire drink .  the mouthfeel is light to moderate .

sweet citrus hops dominate , i 'm picking up pineapple . the hop smell is also mildly herbal . there is a nice sweetness from the malt , but the flavor is n't as strong as i would like .  it had a medium to light body .

amazing complex aroma , very exciting . taste doesnt quite live up to the great smell . still tasty but missing the fruitiness .  mouthfeel is a bit dry , but that does n't really take away from it 's drinkability .
12oz bottle into a snifter a : pours a hazy amber with a big light tan head that lasts for a while and leaves ton of lacing on the glass .  crisp , largely watery with low carbonation .

i 'm assuming its the same thing.the neck label says dark winter wheat seasonale offerring.poured a huge head that slowly shrank to about half an inch .  m : a bit too fizzy upon sipping , and i was looking for a bit more 'heft ' .

smell : smells unbelievably hoppy . smells very hoppy and promising . taste : meh , i really was expecting a big bold aperican ipa from this .  m : 3 day old ginger ale type carbonation ... o : not a great beer .

intense tropical fruit salad aroma of passionfruit , orange , mango , lime . distinctive nz hop aroma . gorgeous . sweet white wine and sorbet also . very hop forward , full flavours yet for a double/imperial ipa - extremely low on bitterness . o - beautiful beer . extremely tasty and seriously drinkable , absolutely no indication of the 7.3 % abv . but i just love it . more !  this was probably just average on the mouthfeel , imo - whether you consider this a wild ale or bsda .

head dissipates at a quick pace , and lacing is nonexistent ... s - lots of sweet notes come through . caramel , vanilla , oak , and toffee . very smooth and well balanced ( especially considering the abv ) .nothing is over the top or out of place ... m - goes down extremely smooth . medium bodied with a medium/moderate amount of carbonation ... o - one of the better american barleywines i have tasted to date . definitely something that i am looking foward to trying again in the near future .  i really like it and find that , though the mouthfeel makes it sharp and crisp , it does n't help sustain the nice flavors at work here ... wheat , hay , raspberries ( of course ) . yes , nothing overwhelming .

coloration is a nice ruddy brown with a healthy 1 '' khaki head which is simply beautiful in appearance . huge and uneven and thick .  medium carbonation and thin mouthfeel makes this brew very drinkable .

appearance : gorgeous frosted lemon body with a luciously frothy 2 finger white crown . seriously sexy !  i gave the mouthfeel a lower score due to the extremely bitter after-taste and the thin-ness of the body .

pleasantly fragrant . slightly bready with some fruitiness and hop bitterness in the afteraste . taste does n't quite live up to the aroma , but it 's very drinkable .  m-moderate carbonation , medium-bodied beer , with a noticeable hoppy dryness .

i received this bottle in january or february i believe ... pours super thick black , with a dark dark brown head that cascades down and actually looks awesome as it does .  only complaint is it is a little thin but nothing that deters me from wanting more . the rich citrusy hops , leave you wanting another drink to quench your thirst they are so drying , it 's basically a no win situation . mid palate is lacking roundness but otherwise delicious . because of the immense amount of hops it would be hard to drink many of these .

2007 edition of the first barleywine i ever tasted ... a flourishing bouquet of thick head occupying half a snifter , dark crimson to the eye ( slightly opaque ) ... soft hops ( hint of vanilla ? ) come forth ... hops that dig into the teeth !  the only odd thing i noticed was sort of low carbonation , odd because there was a lot of foam on pouring . but it was n't really stale feeling , it just could have had more mouth presence .

a giant tan head forms and for the first time ever i 'm almost worried about my snifter overflowing . smell : fruity and tart . hay , apples , and cherry . this was awesome and i 'm glad to have a whole growler of it .  i found the mouthfeel to be decent , and found it to be very drinkable .

smell is a strong malty syrupy carmel scent , very strong , almost burbon like scent that impressed me .  smells like apples , tastes like hops . very tasty . the fragrance certainly did not match the taste , which is a good thing . the apple/apricot scent is strong but would be overpowering to the tongue , the muted apple notes balanced well . i would definitely order this again .

my mate had this beer in his fridge which to be honest impressed me not because i wanted to try this beer but simply because he didnt have macro swill in his fridge as usual just glad ive got thru to him anyways onto the beer it pours a burnt copper see thru colour with decent carbonation that leaves a two finger head with subtle creamy lacing that is noticable and stays , it has a real clean , grassy , crisp , fresh hop aroma about it very impressed with the aroma , it has a light mouthfeel which leaves you with tastes of malt coated , piney hops but not over the top a very subtle apa thats easy enough to drink .  mouthfeel : dry , grainy texture in a medium-light body with medium carbonation .

big malty aroma , brown sugar , alcahol fumes , cloves , resiny hop aroma with a mostly grassy kick . the aroma is misleading and the taste does not follow the knose 's path .  presented much carbonation when poured.a thick beige head with spotty traces of sticky lace.a strong malt and coffee aroma.very nutty , molasses , and chocolate smell also.the color looks to be a very dark red to almost black.the smell and appearance are above average for most sam adams beers.the mouthfeel is a bit weak and watery.no carbonation bite to it.a very dry finish with a touch of a hop bitterness that stays in your throat.a drinkable stout and goes down smooth but is average .
from the bottle , poured dark brown to black , with a nice foamy tan head , with good lacing .  it 's very easy to drink , crips , and light , but it 's a bit thin in character & feel .
great appearance ! `` kristalklar '' golden yellow in colour with an awesome head .  great finish , though a little thin .

smell- wow . i would venture to say that this beer showcases hops better than any other beer i 've ever had . oh , and again with the honey . taste- again ... wow . weird for a dipa , but very very good and interesting , as they remain just whispers in the background . mouthfeel- simply superb .  let down by light and somewhat watery mouthfeel .

smell : an intoxicating citrusy sweetness bursts forth when i open the bottle . floral notes abound , west coast hoppiness all the way here . i could smell this all day long . taste : pronounced hop bitterness , pretty damn close to pure hop nectar .  mouthfeel is on the thin side , and a bit to the beer 's determent .
great head retention with nice lacing .  unremarkable mouthfeel , but the drinkability is pretty solid on this one .

s : a wonderful sweet chocolate smell with hints of coffee . i was taking a whiff of it before every sip i had . smelling the beer with a sip in my mouth is just fantastic . a nice roasted coffee aftertaste .  mouthfeel : a touch thin .

s : this has the most interesting tobacco note i 've found in a beer yet . its the appealing mustiness of well used pipe with accents of cocoa and cherry playing beautifully off of it . the tobacco is here , just as interesting and as appealing , but the tart , slightly funky cherry is more prominent . d : while i absolutely loved the tobacco i found , i do n't think this was quite what they had in mind .  mouthfeel : i 'm thinking guiness extra stout ( from the bottle ) light . medium body with a decent carbonation . lighter than expected and a bit prickly on the tongue and throat when going down .
an absolute beautiful presentation in a snifter that words truly fail and fall short in description . spongey patches of lacing leave a nice calling card .  m : mildly carbonated and dry .

and you know , its good , but its not for me . beautiful black pours from a clear bottle , smells like a sweeter stout , and tastes the same .  i am almost positive this is living under the assumed name of `` doc mason 's ryepa '' at solana beach . aroma is rye , caramel malt , and hops . nice hop bite up front with a smoother rye and caramel back . acidic and alcoholic finish .
the aroma is of delicious coffee and chocolate flavors .  m : it was watery with lots of carbonation .
a : bright golden with large foamy white head with great retention and lace grabbing glass the enitre way down .  the mouthfeel has decent body , ok carbonation .

poured golden cream-colored with a substantial head that lasted the entire drink . like the other nitro-can ales , the beauty of the drink was in its appearance above all . it has a beautiful cascading effect . there was not much of an aroma .  carbonation is quite high , body is medium but filled with bubbles , mouthfeel is creamy but slick . very flavorful , but the carbonation ruins the mouthfeel for me .
s- bananas and clove ( like with a wheat beer ) , and a big nuttiness . duh , it smells like fresh baked banana nut bread .  m- good carbonation .

huge 5 inch head at first with excellent retention . about 10 minutes later i am served a gorgeous , glowing medium yellow/orange beer with a 2 '' frothy , layered head . after several minutes it settles with a pile of froth in the middle like cartoon dog poop , seriously , and tons of lacing with actual gobs .  mouthfeel is way too light for what i was expecting .
s : like orange tang . really nice natural orange flavor .  as far as mouthfeel , it was rather carbonated and had a bit of a bite going down , especially when it was at its coldest .

smells simply amazing - strong tropical fruit , apricot , wheat and pine notes , all swimming in a yeasty funk . tastes as good as it smells . midway , it twists in a tangy direction and the brett really makes its presence felt . good , complex brew . like it ? certainly  22oz in my piraat snifter i thought this was one of the best pumpkin beers that i have ever tasted . it poured golden to copper and had a huge nose of nutmeg and spice . i did not find it terribly sweet but like a pumpkin cookie . it had some notes of gram cracker to . i think it hides the 9 % abv very well not hot at all . i would have another . i think this bee would pair well with a pumpkin mousse pie very nice because of the gram cracker notes .
pours dark black with a beautiful thick light brown head .  a touch too much carbonation for my liking .

no lacing at all s - sweet dark fruit and rich spices come through the nose that produce great pleasure and a sense of holiday .  full bodied with low carbonation that made it feel a bit flat and dull , mild astringency and a bit of warmth . the texture was pretty good even with the low carbonation .

smells deliciously smokey . lots of rich , dark campfire smoke and bitter black malts .  while not a huge fan of ipa 's i have tried several i 've enjoyed . i ended up regurgitating the three sips back into the glass . the worst beer i have ever tried to drink .

dear indica , you are beautiful , and while you can be intense , i find your range of expression to be rather narrow . i miss the high and fruity moments i share with other india pale ales . maybe your slightly resinous bitter band of flavor hides nuances a more subtle palate could savor .  the mouthfeel is light also and thin .

poured from a 12oz bottle into a delirium tremens tulip glass . the appearance was nice , burgandy colored , clear , with a thin white ring of head .  at the downtown chicago rock bottom , they named it rooftop pilsner for its rooftop dining area ( with a fine view of all the much taller yuppie condos surrounding it ) . they had to brew this in a hurry following the may windstorm that blew their rooftop taps open , draining all of their serving tanks ! pretty good for a style which we 've all had bad examples of . fizzy head leaves a golden yellow color underneath . no off-flaveors to speak of . nice citrsy hop aroma which i found to be a little stronger after a scoop of salsa . a decent session beer .

damn fine looking beer- translucent brown with rusty orange highlights and a kick-ass tan head .  like most light lagers , the only character to the smell and flavor comes from the malt , hops and water . there is a clear attention to the quality of ingredients , and a successful attempt at balance and smoothness . the mountain-filtered water imparts nothing offensive on the palate .

smell is moderately malty , a bit sweet . straw , grass , silage , raw starchy grains , a little lemon and maybe some floral notes . a unique and appealing nose , like standing in a hay field .  moderate to thin mouthfeel , carbonation is ok . my only problem with this is the mouthfeel was n't as creamy as i was expecting , but overall , a very nice stout .

among the best coffee scents i 've ever experienced . an incredibly appealing aroma . pretty strong as well . a lovely coffee porter all around . not as tailored to it as it could be , but all around very complementary .  mouthfeel/drinkability- a very thin beer in general , the carbonation breaks early in the mouth , then goes quickly and smoothly down the throat .
pours a beautiful dark blue with a one-finger head into my glass .  mouthfeel is smooth , but this is kind of thin .

pitch brown/black with a giant , never-ending mocha head . plenty of lace left behind . one beautiful beer . certainly the chocolate and coffee element are there , earth and oak make a solid appearance .  m - high carbonation , but a little watery .
smell has that strong nice balance of rich malts and floral hops . a nice enjoyable hearty ale .  m-to me its a little thin to carry around this level of hops .

attempted to pour a good head to get some aromatics , but failed ... twice . smelled heavy and sweet , like healthy , scalded honey . i would love for this unusual concoction to do something over the next year ( s ) but fear that it may not .  i found this beer to be one of the easiest-drinking beers i 've ever had . now , my review is flawed because i do n't believe i have any other saison/farmhouse ales to compare it to - this is my first . but from the description of the style , i expected something a bit more complex in flavor , and this was not complex at all . low abv combined with a mellow flavor equals very easy drinkability . for an every day summer beer , i 'd choose this hands down over the bmc beers ; unfortunately this runs $ 32 a case , so it could be come an expensive habit .

smells like fresh noble hops .  on the tongue , everything that was on the nose is amplified , bigger , bolder , stronger , more . the body was a bit different than typical , a touch more syrupy and thicker . still nice but not what i 'm really looking for in a wit .

750ml into duvel glass north of 40 degrees . pours with a thick , soft , and pillowy peach-colored head over a deep maroon colored body , with plenty of carbonation flowing up .  m : fairly light , slick body with a low amount of spiky carbonation . mediocre .

pours a hazy amber with two fingers of dense foam that settles slowly to a persistent half inch .  m : this is where this beer turns a bit down for me . to me this tastes a bit undercarbonated , making the mouthfeel a bit watery for me .

pours a very pretty medium brownish-copper color with a large , creamy light beige head . retention is off the hook and it leaves very impressive sheets of lace on the glass .  mouthfeel medium mouthfeel with carbonation that is just over the top in my judgment .
a fruity banana and sweet honey aroma adds alot to the enjoyment of this brew .  the mouthfeel was a little thin , watery which is my only complaint , i expected a bit more of a robust feel to it .

the color is nice , a pretty translucent golden , and the bottle is on the sexier end of the spectrum . pours nicely , smells decent ( very fruity , especially banana ) and has a good sticky head .  m : a bit dry . average carbonation .

a : a careful pour yields an impressive , jet black beer with a dense brown head which hangs around a while .  this is truly a one-of-a-kind beer . the aroma is purely apricot . the taste has the essence of fruit with a dry ale finish . it has a lot of flavor , but that flavor does not linger , making it possible to drink quite a bit of this beer in a session . if you have not tried this yet , try it . you 'll either love it or hate it .
the beer poored dark brown/black with an awesome large , off-white head . absolutely beautiful .  medium carbonation and a slight astringency .
t : a wonderfully complex nose leads to a somewhat lacking ... tongue ? that said there is still a lot of life left in this beer .  m - medium to light bodied . it 's just thinner than i expected .

deep coffee beans , chocolate and licorise on the nose , very pleasant . surprisingly thin up front , coffee flavors subdued , oily , slick charcoal to be noted in the body .  mouthfeel is pretty average .

aromas of pine , citrus and floral . the aromas on this one was all hops .  the mouth feel is very dense and viscous that is entirely too syrupy . a little too thick to be enjoyed , but if you can separate the mouth feel from the flavor , youre in for a treat .

smell : the smell is very complicated . i got notes of hops , and some very intense herbs ( corriander , rosemary , sage ) as well as an over all sweetness .  mouthfeel is very light , a little watery , with a somewhat crisp feel to it .

hazy dark yellow colour . there is a huge off-white head which lasts and lasts .  but overall , mouthfeel was ok. after having a couple bottles of this in the past , felt this was a terrific sixtel to kick off the summer .

in a tulip glass at track 84. i will admit , i did n't get much aroma at all from this . drinkability was off the charts , but that made sense once i saw the abv was at the low end of the imperial stout range .  carbonation is too high , but it tastes pretty clean and fresh .
smell is pretty good , a great balance of the malt and hops .  m - even , with a slight bitter aftertaste .

poured with a large 3f soapy off-white head over a mostly clear , burnt orange body , with tons of visible carbonation and plenty of lacing .  surprisingly carbonated mouthfeel , with a finish of coffee , slight taste of alcohol and dark chocolate . if there is any drawback to this beer , it is the carbonation .

soapy white head that dissipates quickly . s : i expected the grapefruit greeting of the ipa , but my nose was met with citrus combined with tropical fruit , almost a pineapple or mango and hint of floral . t : same blast of citrus and tropicals ; finishes a little bit quickly , without a lot of bitterness or drying , which i missed . a really fantastic beer and a lucky find since i understand hill farmstead is not found much outside of vermont .  the mouthfeel of the beer was a bit on the lighter side , but still acceptable .

sample from bottle ; bottled on 1/22/09 a- poured carefully from bottle to yield a huge foamy , well-retained , cream colored head . as i refilled the glass throughout the sampling , the head became less foamy and a lot more rocky ( proteinaceous ) . the body was a hazy copper color , with lots of active carbonation visible from the sides and top of the glass .  sampled at the paper city brewery on free beer night . i know that this beer was free so i should n't complain about it but there was something wrong with this beer . my guess is this was a bad keg otherwise they brewed it with their dirty gym socks . reflection : i know that this is a harsh review but unless you were there that night and tried it you ca n't understand the horror of this beer .
pours ruby red amber with a large fluffy off-white head that retains well and laces the glass .  mouthfeel is average for the size of the beer , and quite drinkable .
it is a luxurious dark ruby , has a nice head and lacing is good .  mouthfeel is rather light with less than medium carbonation .

a- dark , dark brown with a tan head s- vanilla and caramel , creme brulee ! i hope it tastes as good as it smells ! t- not nearly as strong as the nose -- malts underlie it all with the vanilla and caramel creme brulee taste staying with you for a while afterwards m- full bodied and creamy d- quite a unique beer ! it really tastes like creme brulee !  the mouthfeel is slightly thin and foams up in the mouth a little ; the beer needs some sort of aeration .

very strong and impressive aroma . taste : very crisp beer with a nice wheat taste accompanied by hints of lemon and other fruits . flavor was n't much but the aroma was very impressive . great example of the style .  the woodiness also makes an subtle appearance on the finish mf : very very very high carbonation on this which is sharp on the tongue but seems to work well for the sourness on the palate .

deep mahogany to chestnut colored , still ( not carbonated ) , and smelling of maple syrup , prunes , toffee , and a hint of chocolate . enjoy this novelty `` triple bock '' , think of it more like a brandy and enjoy !  m : the feel is thick and a bit undercarbonated . the carbonation issues detract from the beer slightly though .

a total stunner in the glass : the color is black black and more black , seriously giving any huge bad-ass stout a run for its money in terms of color . the head is an ultra-creamy thing , looking like the froth on top of a root beer float or something .  similar to points cascade pale ale where the hop just shines right through and you taste the hops in every swig . the abv has to be pretty low cuz it was a little watery tasting . but overall a great refreshing , thirst quenching summer brew . i 'm guessing the batch was limited , cuz i heard horizon hops are in real short supply .
the strong aroma of fresh strawberries is uncanny , and overpowers any other scents .  mouthfeel- thin body with medium carbonation .

a- perfect pitch of black hue , a fantastic color of mocha head . lacing is beautiful .  the pluses : the mouthfeel is ok , it looks very good , fruity appearance with a white head . but the taste is sourish and horrid , and something i could not bring myself to have much of .

50 degrees pours black . beautiful . massive dense head that looks like frothed coffee . a steady hand can pour this so that the head rises in a column right out of the glass .  mouthfeel was kind of thin and light and the blueberries gave it an intense sweetness that would make it hard for me to want much of .

everything was tasting weird yesterday , all the aromas were strange . this one was like dipping your face into a fresh bag of weed . aside from the juicy marijuana nose on this it 's pretty uninteresting .  m - the mouthfeel is average for a porter .

had this beer at the brewery poured into a 6 oz plastic cup a- i love dark beers ! the head is tan and looked great in my plastic cup .  m : a tad overcarbonated , a bit watery , medium-light body . a bit astringent .

was a beautiful rich and golden color ; looked like a killer ipa .  i 'm so sorry , but i do n't see what everyone else does in this beer . the malt flavor is too aggressive and tastes over-toasted . in this case , both flavors are too aggressive . still , in all departments i find it profoundly below average , except maybe appearance and mouthfeel , which are standard ( gold with a tinge of brown and not too oily , respectively ) . this is just one of those beers i ca n't get into .

smell : so sick . hoppity hops on the nose . floral , citrus , and earthy hop aromas all combine to create a fantastic smell . the grapefruit citrus aroma seems to be the most prominent .  carbonation was ok , but with the heavier than expected mouthfeel , i think the hops were lost on the palate more than others textures .

it is a very rich scent . the taste is sweet and very matured ( there are some light notes of oak/wood casks ) with lots of marzipan , hazelnuts and brazil nuts .  this is way to watered down for me . mouthfeel and drinkability : finishes somewhat dry . this brew also has a super light body with higher levels of carbonation-okay , these are appropriate for the style .

incredibly balanced aromas . t - there are so many layers to this beer , each so definable .  mouthfeel is okay , but needs to be either thicker or creamier to work with the taste -- as is , it 's just a tad watery .

georgeous dark amber brown with an amazingly thick and creamy bubblebath of khaki head sitting on top .  mouthfeel is light with low carb , which is nitro 's biggest downfall in my opinion . this is a delicious beer , with the only bummer being the lighter , undercarbonated body .

i drink a lot of great coffee , and this beer smells bolder than some of those . the smell is so bold , i even smell a really deep strong smell that i can only relate to leather or rubber ... that may sound weird , but i assure you that it is in a good way t : like the nose , there is an absolute assault of coffee .  i think this means that the same strain of yeast is used . anyway here 's what i thought . they have chucked a lot more than hops into this . well i 've got a case to get through and i 'm not going to throw it away . if my opinion of this improves , if i acquire the taste , well i 'll let you know !

at the very least , this is a great looking brew . a slightly reddish amber and a massive head that retains very well and leaves sheets of lacing .  a very strong and thick mix of bannana and cloves , both interlace and dominate in a very very pleasing way . despite the heavy mouhtfeel , it is very light and very drinkable . imo , only downside is the aftertaste , a little messy and thick , but still , a very nice hefe .

looks like a beer to be reckoned with .  it 's rare that i ca n't even stomach a beer long enough to get a few sips down . this beer gave me one of those rare moments . the smell was a sour , and the taste was dirty and skunky . i did n't want to waste the pack , so i made a couple of michelada cocktails . they were actully quite tasty.. nothing like worcestershire and tabasco to make something taste better !

smell - man this is strong odor of yeast , hops malts and sugars . lots of smell ... taste - well now , where to start . really strong yeasty floral kick with tons of malts and booze . malts are bold and overdone . mouthfeel - too much of a mess to enjoy . bittered then sweetned then burnt . overall - not good . sounded like a good idea but the final product ended up being a mess .  full body with slightly too high carbonation .

this is a very attractive brew . very dark , almost onyx black , but some hits of red with shown to light . inch head that looks like the coffee froth atop a well made espresso .  mouthfeel - average crispness , moderately thin body , i 'm okay with it .

one of my favorite sam adams offerings ... deliciously red with a huge foamy head making this an extremely attractive brew ... malt dominant aroma.. strong caramel notes and maybe even some toffee.. extremely smooth and sweet malts dominate the palate .  this beer drinks very easily ; it is actually pretty light on the mouthfeel , a little creamy smooth , but mostly just light .

a beautiful smell that is good enough to eat . it just smells good enough to skip the drinking part ! it is a unique and tastey beer but i almost feel like it was a shame to drink away that great aroma , sort of how i feel about pipes/cigars .  mouthfeel is a little thin ( but then again , what do you want from a wheat beer ) with tangy carbonation .

a familiar smell i 've come to love from quads . complex . complex as hell . pretty good alcohol presence . outstanding beer none the less .  a delicious golden red , mild mannered taste and aromatic bloom are all qualities of this beer . widely available in all super markets and at a good price . this beers fits in well with any dinner menu . it is n't as hoppy and bitter as its west coast conterparts but still a very excellent beer . sam adams offers a huge variety of different beers so it is easy to good a feel for how they brew their beer and their taste philosophies .

nose is amazing and if i didnt know better i would have thought it was a barrel aged beer . i was really excited by the nose .  it tastes like a quadrupel ... .vinous , lots of sticky caramel malts , somewhat flat mouthfeel ( which i 'm never all that fond of ... i wish quads could be more prickly somehow ) ... but again , the addition of the slightly sour cherry keeps this from being a garden-variety quad .

beer is yellow , mildly hazy , heavily carbonated , nice white head , small bubbles , nice lacing , great retention , this is the perfect witbier look .  the body seems a bit lighter than i would have expected .

enticing aroma . probably the best aroma of any beer i have ever smelled before . vibrant fruit notes ; apple , pear , berries and cherries along with a maltiness of cookies and caramel .  it was very astringent .

best thing about this beer is how to looks , poured a golden orange peach color with a white three finger head that held nicely and good lacing .  to me smelled like wheat/grain , nuts . t : taste just like you would expect , after smelling . d : pretty good beer , surpassed my expectations . could drink this one all night and be satisfied !
deep ruby red/brown color .  mouthfeel is highly carbonated and drying , as it should be .

750ml bomber poured into a flute ; march 2011 bottling an extremely soft golden straw color with streams of tiny bubbles pushing north to a huge , meringue-like cap . excellent retention and loads of sticky lace . it looks awesome .  not a big wit guy , but it is summer in san diego and i just got done playing some b ball and was thirsty . i always see it at places and not big on most japanese breweries . very refreshing and complex at the same time . over all i am glad i tried it and i am actually going to buy a pack down the street right now .

s - i knew i had to get this one when i smelled it from across our table . a tiny bit of sweet caramel malt comes thru but this one is really all about the hops . the taste was n't as good as the nose but i still really enjoyed this one . d - very good . i really like racer 5 quite a bit and this version was even better . a touch one dimensional with all those pungent hops but that really is n't a bad thing .  yes officer i have been drinking tonight as a matter a fact i have a fuck of a lot to drink tonight , i think 12 beers but i ca n't remember . yes i will take a breathalyzer and a blood test . yes my breath does smell like hops . no your machines are n't broken , i forgot to mention the beers i was drinking are 0.5 % alcohol by volume .
body is ruby and brown with an intense head that looks like silk foam .  medium bodied slick mouthfeel , slightly cloying .

why not ? appearance : golden orange , with a pearly white head with gorgeous honey-comb bubbles that were perfectly aligned one next to the other .  medium to thin in the body . i thought the carbonation seemed a bit to high and lessened my enjoyment of this brew .

a -- pours a beautiful amber/copper color with a huge 4 finger head in my dogfish head signature glass . i know the glass contributed to the appearance here , but this is one of the best looking beers i have poured .  mouth feel is medium bodeid really dry with a fair amount of carbonation .

looks like heaven in a glass , slightly hazed golden hue , massive amount of carbonation action ( more fun than watching sea monkeys ) , and a massive chunky white head that stayed all of the way and left some serious lacing .  m- i found the body to be medium , maybe a tad full bodied for apa , but the carbonation was significantly lacking on this one . i think a bit more rye presence and more carbonation would have moved this beer up quite a bit for me .

s-the smell of this beer is amazing ! having had perseguidor 3 , i would say this is the only trait that is better in 4 . insanely complex nose , smells of wood , funk , dried fruit , chestnuts and roasted malt . truely exceptional . there is virtually no stout flavor , i tastes similar to an old bruin , but thiner and less acidic , a sipper to be sure do to the tartness , but very tasty . d-another great offering in this series , captain ron is a master at blending his styles .  mouthfeel : a bit dry on the finish and the aftertaste . little carbonation , and a bit sticky . decent but not special .

) with other hop nuances and malt to balance it out , very nice . taste-spicy hop at the beginning and then balanced out by some caramel malt finish , huge hop hits on the end of the toungue , very nice .  this is an epl through and through . do n't be persuaded by the pilsener title . i had it after a holsen which is a real grain bomb . neither beer is that great but this one seemed inferior . and compared to holsten permium that is n't saying much . i you like stella artois or heineken or something like that in a can then go or it , but it is n't too good .
pours a beautiful orange tinted amber body with a half finger width white head .  m : the only real cavet of the brew is the feel . but it 's generally a bit thin .
tap : clear amber ale with a huge creamy-like head with excellent retention .  mouthfeel : it was a very light beer .

aroma is amazing ( it was perfect when it started but as the beer warmed it fell off , still giving it a 5 ) . it is so hoppy , piny and wonderful overall . no harshness , the level is strong but not overpowering . its great . beer is medium to light in a body with a creamy mouthfeel .  4.5 m a bit on the thin side .

medium amber with a big , tight head that does n't seem to recede at all throughout . tons of lacing . tiny , tiny bubbles rising all the while . man this looks inviting .  a beer haiku for you : '' norwegian beer ? yes ! a great ipa option , seek out and find one ! '' my first norwegian [ that 's what she said ] . nice citrus overtones , not too 'hoppish ' , and very drinkable . a rare find , but well worth the money to have another option .

a - it looks like any of the other bcs series , which is generally impressive . black , oily looking beer with a fine brown bubble head that did n't leave much on the sides .  t & m : slightly alcoholic bite at first . very fizzy taste of citrus with a somewhat sour lemony wheat taste . d : very fizzy so will fill ( bloat ) you quickly . exemplary of the style .

into an imperial pint glass , pours a dark brown that shines ruby through a light , a generous 1 '' head of off-white foam settles to a quarter inch , and leaves bubbles around the glass .  this 'beer ' is weak . this 'beer ' is flavourless . no wait , i can taste some corn syrup , and what 's that ... pickle juice ? honestly , i think i taste hints of pickle juice !

smell : sweet roast , mild vanilla , dark fruit , cinnamon , and some warm bourbon .  good , predictable macro carbonation , not too fizzy , and a softly crisp , dry , thin , light bodied mouthfeel , average , to be expected , nothing to really complain about here , again , predictable , you know what you getting before you pop open the can .
pours a blood orange color , mildly translucent , with a whitish amber head 3 fingers in length .  m - disappointing , frankly .

appearance : dark amber , mahogany color with a moderate head .  had this on top at ye olde boise brewer 's festival 2007 ; enjoyed the beer and enjoyed talking with the brewmaster , who seems to care quite a bit about what he 's doing . this is an extremely pleasant summer fruit beer , and contrary to what has been noted by previous reviewers , i did n't get the sense that the fruit flavor was from any sort of unnatural source . this could have something to do with it being on tap , and therefore theoretically fresher . it did come across very much like other orange tinged wheat beers ; nothing remarkably different , but a very drinkable beer regardless .

like a goblet full of fresh goose blood , it has vibrant color and pungent aroma . tremendous malt complexity , slight oxidation adds brilliantly to the bouquet .  m : a bit light and quite fizzy for the style .

orange/amber color , with a thick creamy eggshell white head ( we 're talking this could be used as a pillow ) , that leaves amazing amounts of lacing down the glass .  overall quite mouthfilling , cakey , dangerously smooth and rounded . the beer takes a bit of a down turn towards the end as the flavors fizzle a bit and the beer seems to thin out and go a bit watery . mouthfeel , while not ever being truly creamy , comes close with real soft and smooth carbonation .
not-quite-opaque black body topped by a massive tan-ish , rocky head .  feel : the carbonation seems to take over much of the mouthfeel vs the flavor .

the aroma is great ! it has a nice malty scent that boasts of pale and crystal malts along with a solid spice content . it has a solid malt flavor , but the spices really take away from the overall enjoyment . it 's just got too much spice .  refreshing ale , i have only recently started drinking ales as a regular drink recently . the sa gold i have is my brothers and id rather rate my ale by , if i grabed another one or not ... i drank 4 bottles last night : ) im guessing this is quite and average ale as fursty ferret tastes remarkbly the same and thats what im going to use as my `` beer to rate by '' or mean `` beer '' id recomend this beer if you saw it available .

aroma is intense : leather , sweet syrup , yeast getting slightly funky . i 'll be honest , it 's a bit too weird for my tastes . i know a lot like this complexity , but i find it disjointed .  low carbonation and medium in the mouth . average feel .
very aromatic ! an quite unique to me . it has some musty yeast , cloves , and hints of orange .  m - syrapy with a decent carbonation .

s : a balanced display of strong lactic and acetic notes , aromatic malt that seems floral and complex , and yeasty fruit . the addition of volatile oak , building in the nose as the beer warms , represents the perfect addition to round out this beer 's aromas . no alcohol is detected .  m : smooth & a little flat ( thanks to the nitro i 'm sure ) .

smell - 5.0 powerful and very , very nice . smells of liquor soaked figs , overripe plums , aged port , damp wood and burnt sugar .  it is a harsh raunchy smell , with a fizzy spoiled fruit flavor . they taste is no improvement this is no beer and if you cant count hard ciders malt beverages should be no different .

pours black with nice head and lacing smells amazing . i get creme brulee with a bit of underlying funk . lovely rich and inviting . blowing me away .  mouthfeel is smooth . so it gets an average score .

12 oz can poured into a brandy snifter a - rich , dense , hot chocolate looking head on top that will not quit . very dark , red brown color that just looks thick . stellar start .  nothing special for the style on the palate but still quite good ; frothy but not especially thick . smooth enough and tasty enough to drink in quantity , one of the better weissbiers for sure but not quite the best .

'' great looking beer -- a golden brown/amber with hints of orange . a long lasting creamy white head with lots of lace ; but the head just lasted forever .  the mouthfeel is a little crisp but does smooth out .

poured a motor oil brownish black with a light brown head of frothy , creamy foam . good head retention and a fair amount of laced sticking .  the mouthfeel is thin with a watery texture , and lively carbonation .

pours a nice dark brown with like 3 fingers of head . looks great !  the mouthfeel is like nothing i 've tasted before ... kinda an awkward feel . '' not necessarily bad , but just very different and weird feeling .

appearance : poursa nice dark brown/red , like stained cherrywood . two fingers of creamy tan head leaves some lacing .  deep red-brown color with amazing billowy off-white head : thick and lasting with good lacing s : hoppy and malty balance with yeasty notes and spices t : orange and nutmeg maltiness with a hoppy bitter finish m : a little thin , but this is towards the end of its season by now .

big three fingers of off-white head , fading to a thick cap with great retention and maybe slightly patchy lacing . looks more like a nice stout than a bsda or black ipa .  taste : flavor of the hops becomes present late in the beginning , and remain throughout the middle and finish ; the tangy undertones are forward followed by a sweeter sensation , finishing with a bittersweet lingering .
inviting . the taste is more of that berry type with hints of wheat malts , all sorts of berry offerings and a cereal crispy palate .  mildly thin body , but not alarmingly so .

sinister jet black pour with a towering head of stiff mocha froth that lasts and clings beautifully . stiff peaks form a crown that eventually settles into a lasting shroud .  medium mouth feel , with decent drinkablity

then , the top of the head begins to condense into a creamy , rich , dense material like melted chocolate ice cream . it all settles into something picturesque , with solid sheet lacing that looks like latte foam .  m- not its most impressive trait , actually evokes a macro in its carbonation level and texture .

a- the beer poured with a minimal head that had nice retention at least , beautiful lacing is due to the extreme amount of hop acids in this bad boy . s- oh my goodness , i went to a homebrew store recently and i smelled some of the hops , this smells like cascade and centenial . not those hops in a beer , it smells like i have a baggy of hops and i am sniffing it , it is glorious ! t- eh , the hops are a little much , i am looking for a beer , not hop soup , this tastes very fresh , as if the hops are still in my glass .  m - moderate to thin body - the backbone appears to be driven by its hefty carbonation .
interesting lace and amazing retention .  mouthfeel is smooth but i couldnt drink a ton of this . thinner than other milk stouts or impy stouts but not a bad change of pace .

s : very nice orange cream like notes with some crystal malt with a touch of hops . t : good balance with the amber malt , piney hops and orange peel .  mouth feel is medium bodied , but i think it could use a bit more carbonation .
a : very funky looking beer .  the mouthfeel is a bit less but certainly the best `` light '' beer i have found thus far .

overall : i really liked the smell of this beer , lots of different but pleasant scents . the flavor was less complex than the scent , not unappealing but it does n't wow .  mouthfeel - average to thin body which could be better . subdued carbonation which i kind of prefer for this coffee stout style .

presentation : 12oz brown pop top , date clearly stamped , nice ditty about the beer on the back ... damn , seven hop varieties ... appearance : nice hazy dark burnt orange beer with fluffy whipped cream ivory cap with good retention and lacing smell : whammo with the hops ... a nice mix between huge citrusy and pine notes , backed up with just a bit of sweet malt taste : actually not as hoppy in flavor as i expected , though the dry , slightly astringent , mouth-drying puckering bitterness is there ... the flavor profile is actually a bit odd ... it 's kind of earthy , woodsy , and raw , but neither the malt nor the hops really stand out , it 's just bitterness , and while the bitterness is n't overly aggressive or overpowering , it 's just that there 's not too much here to this beer ; the aftertaste is a little bit piney/woodsy and that 's nice , but that 's about all i 'm really finding here . drinkability : so-so for the style conclusion : i was kind of disappointed in this , i must say ; it 's definitely interesting , i 'll give it that , the earthy/wood flavors are nice , but it 's just not quite what i typically look for in a dipa .  m - the feel is sharp initially with a chalky and sublime salty finish on the palate .
superb aroma , inviting and heavy . no brew has ever smelled this good then tasted bad : ) nice prickly mouthfeel .  m : a little spritzy and thin for my taste .

second , the label just looks great - a practical riot of color . third , the beer looks great . nice reddish orange color .  clarity 's good , color 's nice but there 's no lasting head to speak of and i could n't really taste malt or hops . it 's sort of like an odd flavored soda pop . miller is one of the many traditional american 'who cares they all taste the same ' beers . i suspect that it 's a pretty healthy dose of cornstarch .

there was some fruitiness but also a substantial malt aroma that i found pleasing . taste : sour .  carbonation is medium to medium-heavy , and mouthfeel is slightly viscous , landing just north of water .

it smells very rich & velvety , though i 've never actually smelt velvet . the rare beer that actually smells better than it tastes , & the taste is excellent .  my first rye . the smell struck me as among the likes of a strong imperial ipa . yet the taste was a lot less hoppy than ipas , more typical average beer . and yes i 'd say there are some flavors in common with rye-based whiskey .

poofy head unceasing and belgian in quality , this is a gorgeous looking light-colored ale . give this to someone drinking bmc just to watch their face pucker up .  m - body is a little thin and watery , but silky smooth from the oats d - this is a really good ris - i have been wanting to try it for a while now .

alcohol and some sweeter malt in the back but alltogether a very fresh and good nose . taste is imo overdone on many occasions .  a nice malty finish mouthfeel is a crisp and clean , quite a bit of carbonation , somewhat dry and sticky aftertaste . a bit more body would have made it excellent for it was a bit light a very drinkable beer .

smells of bourbon and brandy with some notes of chocolate and caramel .  very poor example of an oktoberfest . there seems to be too much of the malt that gives oktoberfests their sweet syrupy quality . this beer is just too sweet and stinks of overly ripened rotten fruit . it has a pickle quality to it as well that i just cant stand . this was a hard beer to finish . undrinkable , and way too sickeningly sweet .

smells like citrus . reminds me of summer and we 're in the middle of a grey november day , so that 's nice . smooth , well-balanced taste , but perhaps a touch too bubbly .  matching , but mild , after-taste m-medium creamy carbonation . somewhat watery finish . the carbonation really bothered me with this one also .

868th review on ba bottle to piraat tulip 12 oz 2010 purchased from craft wine and beer , reno , nv app- a orange , hazy yellow beer with some yellow highlights . a huge three finger head with amazing sheen and cling down the sides .  somewhat thin on the mouth , dale 's pale tastes like citrus hops , only a hint of malt . it 's crisp and clean , quite hoppy . a great example of the style , and very refreshing .

pours a light shade of black with creamy , tan , guinness head .  i hate to rate this beer so low but this is the crowning achievement in the awful stone collaborations . at first interesting and great saison taste , then the herbs kick in . every other sip is horrible . were they trying to brew grass ? 1st they brew a pepper ipa ? then a spice rack saison ? whats next in the grab a random ingredient from the kitchen a brew a beer collaboration . that being said , i will always support stone and its their choice to keep brewing whatever the hell they want .

huge frothy dark tan head ... sticky and clinging lace adorns the glass .  tasted in at the brewery on a breezy december day in tustin . aroma minimal . just a little bready . pale gold in color , minimal head . some chill haze . light body with a noticeable grain sweetness . a very easy touch of floral hops . an excellent example of a drinkable light ale .

bottle purchased at julio 's liquors , westboro , ma poured a somewhat hazy , light straw with a huge , five-finger bubbly head . the resulting chunks of froth eventually faded to a dollop of foam in the middle of the glass , which lasted for most of the drink . tons of bubbly , sticking lacing throughout .  the body does seema tad watery , i would expect more fo a `` fullness '' , but overall i feel the beer is a great scottish ale , overpoweringly malty , no hops that i could detect and pretty much no smoky presence which i can appreciate , since i 've had one too many smoky sottish style ales .

s : this is a huge nose . big alcohol right up front.chocolate , rum , figs , burned sugar , toffee , coffee . really nice nose . t : the oak is really strong right up front .  very mild flavor and mouthfeel , but very lively and well carbonated .

but this beer , the bouquet is fantastic ! and let me set this straight , `` bouquet '' is not a word i use normally but this beer has brought me to a place where `` bouquet '' was the word i needed to use to get my point across .  m : smooth and creamy , though lacking the body found in non-nitro stouts , not bad though , a fuller body than guinness .
lasted quite a while too & left decent lacing . brilliantly clear , pale gold color .  light-medium bodied , needs to be fuller .
pretty great looking beer overall .  mouthfeel is slightly thin .
smell is terrific - pears dominate but do n't overwhelm .  m : the body is perhaps a touch watery with a surprisingly low carbonation .

half the glass is huge , frothy , rocky head . nice !  m - lot 's of carbonation is there making this really move . unfortunately it 's to the point of almost being painful . medium body . it 's sort of an odd one because of the carbonation .

forms a continental size head that has no intent to fade at all . tan and monstrous it leaves chunky lacing . a work of art to look at for sure .  first sip reveals a mild smooth body and fine rolling carbonation . the body gets a little watery on the finish , but it is a mild and the brew goes down very easy and would be an excellent session beer .

s : the smell is terrific , but it did n't carry to the taste . the balance of hops , bittersweet chocolate , and roastiness was attractive .  drinkability suffers a bit from a somewhat awkward and viscous mouthfeel .
pours black with a lasting , thick , brown head and nice lasting .  mouthfeel i liked the fullness of the body here , but the carbonation was quite annoying . otherwise , this felt good .

smell- clean buttery and citrusy hop aroma . the finishing hops are delightful . taste-this beer comes off with a clean , crisp taste that exudes a slight hint of diacetyl .  m-for a beer and a stout this is a very odd mouth feel . it is super creamy and leaves a mess on your tongue .
deep burgundy color with a gigantic , creamy and rocky head of foam . this looks like a belgian for sure .  mouthfeel is the only real weakness for this beer .

the beer begins pouring a deep brown color mixing with the nitrogen and cascades into a midnight black beer with a soft two finger creamy head at the top .  the body has a little chalky hard-water feel to it -- like mineraly .

a pale yellow straw color- very light with a huge white head that never fades and leaves incredible lacing . this beer really is perfect in its appearance .  spices are clearly evident in the flavor ... some cloves and cardamom both come through with a lot of caramel malts , and an unfamiliar flavor , that i am , in my mind , linking with the yeast used . the beer is pretty light for such a dark color . i expected more carbonation , and i was a little bit disappointed at the smoothness .
beautiful aroma and drinkable , especially for the high abv .  surprisingly dry finish in the back m - a bit think , could use some more bubbles or hops to round out the malt a bit .
a : cooper color pour with big long last head .  mouthfeel - very average .

a clear but dark garnet color at first , it clouds up considerably , chunks up actually , with the bottom pour . the head is three to four fingers , and fades to a thin covering with a dark cinnamon-like corona about a third of the way inside the rim .  medium bodied but a bit thinner than expected with a prominent roasted coffee presence that lingers over the dark malts and subtle barrel character into a dry finish .
the aroma is amazing . it smells like the cordials my grandfather gave my grandmother for valentines .  the carbonation is moderate it is perhaps a bit too high for the style though .

special thanks to vapodge for sharing poured into a dogfish head goblet a- dark brown with a small white head s- vanilla , fruity and some alcohol/rum t- caramel , spiced in the end , there 's a nice sequence , one after another with a nutty flavor after the end when you breathe ! m- creamy and smooth with good carbonation d- great brown and easy going !  mouthfeel : medium-thin body .
fantastic ! beer is flat thanks to the leak . its a good thing i have more .  m - medium to light body .
this is one of the nicest looking beers i 've ever seen .  the mouthfeel is a bit lighter than expected but doesnt detract , and drinkability is excellent for the abv .
a surprisingly long life on the head of this . about two and a half finger , creamy and sticky .  m : dry , bitter , light/medium bodied , crisp , too much bite from the alcohol .

pretty looking beer here with a nice ruby red body with some lighter amber hues when held to the light . creamy light shade of tan and about 2 fingers of semi-sticky viscosity make for a nice looking head .  feels thin for such a high abv barrel aged beer but it is easy to drink and the alcohol heat is mild considering .
amazing retention and lacing on top a deep amber body .  m : slightly watery , but forgivable considering its low alcohol content .

smells like a fresh cooked pumpkin pie . this beer smells amazing , which only serves to highlight the disappointing lack of flavor .  the beer 's mouthfeel is smooth , if a bit watery ; this may be the same problem as the vanishing head .

this brew poured a medium head of fine to large brown bubbles and an opaque black body . it has a very mild malt aroma to weak for a good stout and a strong coffee flavor . i did not taste the typical chocolate or roasted notes that are typical of most good stouts , only coffee .  tightly packed carbonation which makes the body feel more medium , feels just a bit too foamy for my tastes .
a monstrous and thick whipped-cream head that is still standing minutes after the initial pour . the best head retention i 've ever seen from a dipa , hands down .  mid palate is substantially thin .

more thanks to weefishheads for this one ... this beer was quite beautiful sitting in my glass . its body was a lovely sunset gradient of yellow to orange , slight haze clouding it .  really interesting for a christmas seasonal . a good amount of spice and hops as it poured into a nice dark orange , with a little bit of lacing and head . i did n't really feel the `` festive ale '' as much as some of the other beers i 've had around this time , but it did have some good spices and taste .
an incredible foamy light brown head rested on top for a reasonable amount of time .  m - heavy , almost cough-syrup consistency with light carbonation .
dark brown with red hues , tan colored head with very good retention and lacing .  mouthfeel : smooth with a relatively full body .

the sauvin hops gives this a very fresh fruity smell , as would be expected . i get passionfruit , a bit of lemon maybe some melon .  the taste ends with a really nice strong bitterness that lingers on the palate for quite awhile . the carbonation seems to be moderate perhaps a little more on the high scale but seems to be average for the style .
looks great , tastes great .  m- near dead flat . it seems to be a bit on the thin side as well . d- despite the feel this beer still drinks deadly smooth .

dark black in color .  the aroma has a touch of stale coffee that then moves to a better defined roasted malt in lager form . the dark malts are great , minus ther adjunt must to it . i ca n't really explain why , but this is one of my , `` right after a hard day of work while you wait for dinner to cook beer . '' easy on the palate and tastes good from the bottle and the glass .

a - a deep golden ale with good clarity and a thick creamy head . loads of lacing .  has a nice malt smell that i find lacking in the lesser expensive pilsners . taste is malt with just enough hop to bitter finishes crisp and dry but not astringent . on a personal note this is the type of pilsner that i classify in my mental list as `` old world '' as apposed to `` lawn mowing '' . i 'd recommend it .

misspent youth has the requisite apa elements -- light caramel malt and american hop aroma -- but combines them in a way you 've never had before . light golden amber pour with an average coupla centimeter head . first sniff is an exceptionally balanced portfolio of hops .  not very extreme in any one area very balanced m : a little bit thin for a stout .

fruity ( mango/guava ) oak and earthy undertones . an amazingly complex and enjoyable ipa thats sweeter than your normal ipa and could use a dose of bittering to completely round it out .  smell : wheat , alcohol , wierd hops , tangy smell , maybe some wine alcohol smell in there too taste : hints of grass , toasted wheat , nice and smooth , mellow , nice malt aftertaste and a bit tangy mouthfeel : a little tart , this one is pretty highly carbonated .

s : loads of hops . piney , somewhat resinous , lots of pungent lemon . very spicy as well , helped along by the yeast . funky but hard to describe .  the mouthfeel however , is not bad - very light and bubbly .
looks almost intimidating .  about 10 seconds after taking a mouthful i had a strawberry aftertaste in my mouth .
winsome dark as midnight porter , the head modest and frothy , lace a fine thick covering sheet .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin .

very strong , very nice . t- very ... bland .  its a huge beer , but the mouthfeel isnt as thick as i would like or expect . good levels of carbonation , and they did a great job of hiding the alcohol .

reviewed 4/7/2009 ( bottle bb 03jul09 ) : pours a very clear , orange-yellow colored body . big creamy white head , very lasting .  the beer did suffer a bit on the palette from the high hopping rates , as this did not glide down in a soft manner , and presented a bit of an edgy mouthfeel .

big aroma of spearmint , grapefruit , lime zest , and wild flowers from the hops ... hint of bready caramel malt and esters in the back . hoppy after taste with a fume of alcohol . this beer has a full on grasp of the style , a great beer all around .  the mouthfeel was pretty thin for this type of beer , but a good beer overall .

poured into a weizen a : dark black very little head ... looks amazing i love the way a good solid dark beer looks s : roasted malts hint of dark choclate t : coffee , roasted malt toffe with a kick of hps m : medium body d : the pint went quickly but i personally would only stick to one a session .  mouthfeel is thick and flat , with a slight prickle that could come from carbonation or just from the alcohol .

s - bananas and bubblegum jump out . i 'm missing the hops for lagunitas ( haha ) , but this smells on point for the style . decent overall , but nothing overly impressive . m - body and carbonation are both on the higher end .  only criticism : powerful aggressive carbonation , would it ease if i left it a while - just too fresh ?
one of the most impressive shows of head retention i 've ever seen .  m : higher carbonation than expected , medium-full bodied .

very attractive dark mahogany colored ale , with an authentically belgian looking head that lasts and laces well .  source/serving : draft smell : coriander , orange flavors , belgian yeastiness , and some brown sugar . overall fairly deep , dark flavors . taste : quite sweet up front with pronounced coriander . the middle does n't really go anywhere , just sustained - or even more - coriander . perhaps there is a ephemeral note of some ripe fruits and alcohol . disappointing . finish is oddly bitter , noticeable alcohol and has a slightly off spiciness .

pours opaque black color with a very dense 2 finger tan head with incredible retention that reduces to a fairly thick lacing cap that lasts .  m/d - a little thin , though probably appropriate for a session beer .

nose is a mix of rich dark roasted milky chocolate , granite , some soft soap , peaks of alcohol , a nice subtle fruitiness , mild touches of earth , fresh roasted grain , mild fire , but just this overwhelming milk and chocolate smell . very inviting . taste is medium to full bodied with lush sharp dark chocolate and extremely strong espresso bean flavor .  no offense ... er..ahem ... gentlemen , however your review of this all time worst pisswater excuse for even a macro beer is to say the least , culpable , at best , dubious , but in truth , how can you live with yourself ? t-non-existent m-ok , not too harsh , but goes flat quickly . good carb up front .
very balanced . easy drinker .  mouthfeel - low carbonation .

a- nice clear , amber body with a creamy , thick white head ( very stout-like ) .  very little carbonation in this beer . the mouthfeel seems pretty unexceptional it 's pretty smooth with a medium body .

a - poured into a squatters ipa glass , it had a deep pruney appearance , big nice-looking head for a doppelbock . s - big and raisin-y , cinnamon-sugar , like a pastry at a bakery . t - raisins encrusted with sugar , this was a sweet brew - too sweet to my palate , i could not find anything to dry it out .  light body and mouthfeel .

very nice color , reddish brown . the beer is very clear , without a hint of haze or sediment . the head is an off-white color , pours a two inch head that settles down to a solid quarter inch through the rest of the beer .  mf : fine . just take it away . thin for a strong ale drinkable ?

poured into my nugget nectar pint glass a : i decanted this one slowly and this reveals a crystal clear ruby red beer with a beige two-finger thick head . pretty !  the scents are the same in the taste though it seems to lose something in the mouthfeel , which is a bit thin .

the beer had great raspberry , fruity aroma . the first sip hits you in the mouth with a deep dark cherry flavor that subsides into a light acidic grapefruit flavor that hits you in the back of the throat .  this was highly carbonated which produced a slighlty unpleasant tingling mouthfeel .

poured a hazy amber/orange color with a frothy white head filling a half inch of the glass . it had both very nice head retention as well as very nice lacing on the sides of the glass .  a little thin in the body for my taste , and a bit low in carbonation .

my overly aggressive pour not only caused a wee bit of spill-over , but also netted me two fingers ' worth of light-tan head with good retention . color was a solid copper ( no amber at all ) with ne-quality clarity . beautiful !  surprising amount of carbination gets you with the first sip , it foams up in your mouth . but the body is alot less than i was expecting ... not think , just mostly carbination on top of a thin to medium body.. ? the flavors linger on your tongue , mainly at the back sides .

a great combination of nutty and bready aromas ; exactly as it should be .  mouthfeel is not very good . the carbonation is almost non-existent and so it 's a bit too slick . still , a nice beer and i 'd have to imagine it would be much better with any semblance of carbonation .

s : aroma is heavenly . amarillo , simcoe , centennial . malt is there a bit but this is all hops .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with low to medium carbonation . smooth , easy to drink , but gets kind of muddy in the finish like some of the other nognes i 've had , which kind of makes my mouth feel dirty , but good winter beer nonetheless .

color is ominously close to budweiser , but dark enough to tell the difference . s-faint undertones of a normal ipa , then the hops gloriously hit your nose like a freight train . t-quite bitter as it should be , but there seems to be an odd or off flavor that does not belong , but dissipates after a few swigs .  weaker on the mouthfeel than i would expect from a stout , although it aids in the drinkability .
dark auburn with ruby hues . thick tan head , 2 fingers tall , great retention and lots of creamy lacing .  mouthfeel is surprisingly thin , with some grapeskin-like astringency on the finish .

pours a beautiful amber with a frothy foam head with nice lacing from a 12 ounce bottle .  smell : piney hops and malts are slightly toasty , tickles the nose readily easily . taste : hop sensation is immediate , blending with the mild toasty-earthy malt taste , progressing to a light , tangy-hop bitterness in the finish , surprisingly balanced . drinkability : darker than a typical ipa , the character of the malts successfully complements the well-hopped taste , very drinkable .

pretty damn close and whats better smelling than bacon ? outstanding . taste : starts with a nice , dark fruit maltiness with a hint of caramel before the smokiness permeates the middle .  this brings us to mouthfeel and i 'm once again taken back to the question of carbonation . in the mouth there is a degree of weight and intensity , however this is beset on both sides by an intense carbonation that strongly effects the overall weight of the beer . the carbonation issue is really just a thing of personal taste but it needs to be put out there , but , overall ; this is a fantastic beer .

the nose offers up a large puff of coacoa and some nice roasted malts smothered beneath it all with just a pinch of coffee beans in the mix as well . taste wise this beer took a step down from it 's wonderful nose . some bitter chocolate was obvious as well as bitter coffee notes but the roasted malts seemed to fade away and the finish offered up an odd tangy quality . overall this beer started out very promising but i think the overall taste failed to live up to the appearance & nose of this beer .  feels like champagne .

winter version this beer pours deep orange-amber and is very hazy -- no filtration here . the off-white , creamy head lingers for the duration and also features great lacing .  a - deep clear brown with some dark amber highlights ; one finger tan head settled down to a nice frothy cap ; light lacing that seemed to slide down glass s - rich , dark coffee starts to come through then milk chocolate and caramel t - coffee is present throughout but it is understated and just part of the profile ; some malt and bread toward the end with a mildly sweet chocolate and caramel finish m - very lightly carbonated ; thin bodied ; no bite or drying finish d - while this one left a bit to be desired in the mouthfeel and taste department it is very drinkable overall - thin body and light carbonation make it go down easy with a nice light , coffee/candy bar flavor ; what 's not to like right ?
