the head is fluffy first and rocky later , ivory white in color and incredibly long lasting . huge peaks and craters cover the surface . as it eventually fades , chunky sea foam lace coats the glass .  i found the mouth feel a little thin , not as think and syrupy , as i would expect , but it 's a minor complaint .
overall , good appearance , aroma , and decent blend .  m : smooth yet just a bit carbonated on the way down ; a little too thin .

s : honey , holiday spice , and cherries . the smell of christmas . d : great winter beer .  rich deep amber red / clear / mild carbonation / mild head sweet sugar almost like a cake / fruity and roasted sweet and tart / significant bitterness / powdery malt / rich roasted / fruity floral hop impact too / interesting sushi flavor must be spices and proteins or maybe it just smells like horseradish / rich caramel sweetness / finishes tart mildly spicy carbonation / medium body beautiful color . would go nicely with sushi . high enjoyable brew .

pretty dang black , with just the impression of ruby poking out around ... .screw it . call it black . big tan foam also .  it 's very refreshing to the mouth ( do i say that about all the beers i review ? ) , with small , present carbonation and what i 'm finding to be a lighter body than i expected from a wee heavy . by virtue of this lighter than expected body , however , this is an extremely drinkable beer .
fantastic nose tons of citric and flower .  mouthfeel - thick and foamy . better than the other aspects of this beer .

appearance and smell were excellent . the dark color and rich scents promised so much . the aroma was fantastic , reminiscent of the dogfish world wide stout .  i poured this guinness into my tumbler at 45 degrees . the beer was very black and bore out a big tan head . the beer smells like a guinness as it should . the taste was big molasses but the brew had a bit of a dry finish . i like the beer and will buy again .

pours a hazy orange with a large white head that retains perfectly as a one finger , rocky and sticky head that leaves tons of lacing as i sip .  mouthfeel is avera- man , this beer is actually giving me a headache .

a - forms a very large , slightly off white head that settles down pretty quickly and leaves good lace on the glass . rosy orangeish color and moderately hazy , really an extraordinary color when you take the time to appreciate it .  the mouth feel is a little thin , unlike some higher-end ales , but the drinkability is very good .
pours a five finger white head that fades very slowly , leaving a good lace .  m : light in body . on nitro , this would be alot creamier ... but it 's still damn good .
appearance : light straw color and very clear . head was about a finger high when first poured and very light and foamy . excellent lacing .  m : lightly carbonated , but bitter for a porter .

i love the style so i 'm excited to give this guy a nice review ( er ... i mean ... my objective review will reflect the beer 's merits ) it is a very stout-looking brew , both in that it looks like a stout and looks stout . tight brown lacing leaves some tight lacing .  the ringwood yeast just tore this up and gave it a slab of butter on top ... m : crisp , but just tastes pretty bad ... d : a pretty bad beer , the ringwood yeast dominates this brew so much that i had to drain pour the rest , too bad .

reviewed from notes a - poured into a standard pint glass a wonderous midnight black that had a one finger mocha head resulting in massive , massive side lacing .  m : slightly flat , with low to medium low carbonation . mouthfeel is likely the weakest part of the beer .

poured into a pint glass appearance : pours a dark chocolate with a thin brown head aroma : huge nose of coffee bean . a little disappointing considering how good this smells overall : a pretty good coffee stout .  it had a medium body but was kind of rough along the palate as it went down .
part of an arcadia sampler : pours almost black with a medium but quickly dissipating light brown head . decent lacing .  3.0 m : something about this beer just does n't sit well on my tongue .

the aroma was really nice . dark fruits , brown sugar , tart cherries , red wine , oak , leather , and a little bit of brett . very complex and interesting . the taste was perfectly in line with all the aromas but a little off .  somewhat thin and watery mouthfeel .

smell : powerful coffee bean aroma . luscious milk chocolate compliments the mocha superbly . taste : the flavor is dominated again by roasted coffee . overall : i was pleasantly surprised as i was n't expecting such a good beer . very good blend of a traditional porter and robust black coffee .  mouthfeel was slightly on the thin side , not quite watery , but close .

the bouquet is a mix of roasted coffee , unsweetened cocoa , and whiskey ... like a liquid mud cake . enticing ... after such an auspicious start , the taste had high expectations to meet ... and i found it a little more than disappointing . i 'm a huge fan of the beers from fbc ( they claim to be `` the official beer of earth '' and may not be too far off ) , but , for me , this is their most feeble offering .  very smooth , all flavors mesh together nicely medium bodied but thin , which is a turn off for me . i feel like this could have been a very special stout if this would have had a thicker mouthfeel ... not very carbonated at all . the thin body was a low point but the smell and taste of this beer is way too good to let that ruin the beer .

poured into an imperial pint glass , formed a 2 '' dark brown head above the opaque , dark brown/black brew . head is dense and lasting , with good lacing .  little thin on the feel as all their brews tend to be but it was not horribly distracting in any way .

the appearance is flawless . the contrast of the thick tan head and deep black body is visually appealing .  source/serving : draft smell : raisins , dark cherries , dark chocolate , nutmeg , a little licorice and even some honey . taste : semisweet vanilla , slightly oaked chocolate malts , and raisins up front are awesome . plateaus at some roasted malts in the middle that has a punch of sweet , ripe prunes and caramelized wood followed by some pepper and more roasted malts and yeastiness . finish is cocoa , semidry , oaky , and ripe prunes .

pours a very dark amber , almost chesnut brown color with dark golden burnt orange hues when held to a light source and a two finger frothy off-white head . excellent retention only slowly fading into a lasting ring that leaves chunks of soapy lacing behind .  mouthfeel was n't terrible , with the nice carbonation going on it actually kinda danced on the tongue .

very balanced . really great . most pumpkin ales smell like pumpkin and spice , this one spells like a baked pie . a more than solid representation of the style , though the taste was a slight light down after the amazing aroma .  aside from the dry end this is an easy to drink beer with an average mouth .

woodsy hops jump right out in the nose . carbonation is kinda stingy and there is that tart sourish thing , but overall this stuff is pretty drinkable .  the taste is of roasted malts , toffee , and to some degree , molasses . the smell is good and the taste is incredible ... but letting this porter get warm isnt such a good idea since it significantly reduces its drinkability . i will definitely pick up another case of this becauce it is probably the best porter i 've ever had . if you like this then definitely give brooklyn black chocolate stout a shot because thats damn good too .

tall creamy head , and yes black as black gets . i have to say this is a great looking stout .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , slightly syrupy , and carbonation is low which produces a somewhat still feel .

a : it poured cloudy light yellow in color with a huge , white head that overflowed from the glass . there is a good amount of head retention .  m - full bodied , low carbonation , dry finish . the body was full , but the finish seemed oddly watery .

label is black and white with a woman 's head on the left side overlooking a countryside . bottle opens with a loud pop and some beer fog . a - pours a beautiful deep orange with a large head that eventually turns into nice lacing towards the end of each glass . this would look great for a fresh saison .  m - somewhat thin to medium bodied but with just the right hoppy aftertaste to leave my mouth tingling for another drink .

appearance : black in color with a one inch creamy head , opaque -- even when poured from a nitro can , beers do not look much better than guinness smell : roasted malt and tobacco taste : dry roasted malt , tobacco , and some creamy sweetness mouthfeel : dry , light bodied , moderate carbonation , sweet and roasty drinkability : a classic and one of the best looking beers i have seen .  slightly creamy body , though it falls flat at the front of the palate . it could use ( i ca n't believe i 'm saying this ) a bit more carbonation . or more body .

nose is excellent ... t- much like the nose in all of the tinges , but finish is very sweet , too sweet . d- quite good , but barely garners an average in the style of tripel , mainly because of it being too sweet .  m : fairly light bodied and the only part that 's halfway decent .
smells quite wonderful . t : i do n't get as much funk as i like in my saisons .  mouthfeel is pretty sharp and fizzy from the bubbles . average kind of body , but mostly just bubbly .
a : pours a viscous pitch black . a tan head gently rises to at least 3 inches , and sticks around .  m - a bit thin .

a : golden appearance that pours 50/50 liquid and foam . i rated this 5 on appearance because this beer has the best head on a beer that i 've seen . it is rocky and tightly beaded , leaving a lace as it slowly recedes .  m : this beer has a slightly creamy consistency that lingers after you swallow , surely due in part to its being unfiltered .
liquid dark bread .  it is perhaps a bit on the thin side , but otherwise rather good .

aroma is evident and enjoyable even from a distance . it has a very nice sour citrusy smell with some of the character of a belgian wheat beer . so , interesting but disappointing .  very clear and bubbly , one finger head that looked like the fizz produced when pouring a pepsi . smells hoppy , lively citrusy orange peel and carbonation galore . the hops mildly dominate the brew , just enough to mask any malty flavor . well worth it . would recommend this brew .
beer pours a beautiful dark copper color with a nice thick white head .  sweet tasting ... m : a little on the acidic and sour side to me .

a thick pour into my tulip glass yielded an opaque black body with a beautiful mocha head that seemed to last through the entire beer . gorgeous .  it does feel a little thin in your mouth , but it smells exactly what it 's name says : a cocoa porter . the beer tastes like chocolate milk made with nesquick or ovalteen or anything other chocolate powder brand with a mild , beer after-taste .

a : poured a nice clear amber & selective yellow body with a creamy one fingered head , rises nicely . the lacing on this is outstanding . t : that lasting head gives this a strong creamy hoppy taste .  it had a medium feel in my mouth with ok carbonation .

11.2oz bottle a- pours a dark brown color with a huge light tan head that sticks around forever and leaves a lot of retention along the glass . this is a really pretty pouring beer .  mouthfeel is a letdown - it may just be this bottle but the carbonation is too weak . only have one of these 750ml bottles as it 's imported and a special occasion but i 'd be keen to have another one , if only to compare the carbonation .

22oz bottle poured into a mexican tulip - fridge temp - 2008 appearance : pours a semi cloudy golden orange with a towering 5 '' yellowish head . it shows great retention .  from notes , bottle to pint look brown , red flares from the side thin head smell : wine , fruity , sweet and sugary taste : grape , fruit , malt and sugary with a slight sour . honestly feels like more of a imperial red taste honestly mouth : good but not great , nothing stood out drink : is tasty cant deny that , but i couldnt do a lot of these
pours a very nice looking darkish gold . darker than almost all macro lagers . an attractive lager .  m : a bit thin . crisp , somewhat dry .
the lagavulin ( scotch ) aroma is very good . the aroma is only of scotch and slight malt .  m suitably moderate to big but nothing extreme like an ris .

neon white head radiates brightly from its position atop my beverage . clear , crisp gold straw colored brew .  mouthfeel : medium bodied i guess . it was definitely carbonated but it was n't something i wanted to leave in my mouth that long .

excellent . the beer is the color of honey , and since this is a honey ale , it succeeds in this area as well . the taste and mouthfeel are light , pleasant , and ultimately forgettable .  m - a little watery . carbonation good for the style .
scent is extremely funky .  m - little carbonation . relatively light-bodied on the mouth .

one of the best smelling beers i can remember . those citra hops really bring it on the nose . tons of tropical fruits . just great stuff . taste- follows the nose . it 's downright tart . however , it gets a little muddled . i had one and really wanted another . this is a very good beer .  m : mouthfeel is thin and light . thin in an offputting way .

it smells fantastic , the hops dancing with the roast barley . a great idea , really , very impressive . it is the rest of the beer that fails to deliver .  ... big foamy head in to the glass that seems to break its neck to dissipate , but leaves a tiny ring ... is very refreshing and tangy but when it warms it can be a beast , serve cold ! ! .. better than most bmc products and probably somewhat better than miller chill ...

the rich smoky aroma has strong tones of roast coffee and molasses and just a whisper of unsweetened chocolate , demanding a taste .  the one area this beer disappoints is in mouthfeel , where it falls into a watery trap .
excellent beer with a strong , spicy aroma that wafts up into your nose , and fills it up . enjoyable to just breathe in .  feels a bit thin , low-medium body and medium carbonation .

appearance was good , i gave full marks as i 've never seen a beer that did n't look as it was supposed to . a creamy head that lasted the entire beer .  m - sharp carbination starts off this beer , and turns almost tart . it seems young .

a : poured a sexy orangle color with good carbonation and a nice fluffy white cap s : bread , caramel , citrus and pine t : starts off with sharp booze , pine , orange peel , other citrus and sharp bite m : medium body , tasty , booze is stinging and pungent but not to bad , lots of flavor here o : this ia big , bold in your face hoptacular iipa .  m - light bodied , thin with a bit of a sticky feel .
s - the smell is stout chocolate that tries to hide the coffee .  well balanced m : a little coppery and bitter .

a : pours jet black with a thin caramel head that laces the glass nicely .  for the most part this is quite smooth , although the carbonation is just a tad too harsh to fully appreciate some of the nuanced flavors .
dark brown color with a quarter inch head and an exceptionally fresh malty aroma . malt dominates flavor all the way through with a malty aftertaste .  the mouthfeel is just average .

a massive white foamy head greets me like a beer commercial . great retention and a crazy amount of sticky lacing .  smells very nutty with mild chocolate roast . the beer fairly sweet tasting with the nuttiness coming through . cabonation is a bit higher than i would like , but other than that it is a very good brown ale .

aroma is pretty intriguing . the hops and yeast esters are both very strong but just about even in proportion . really luscious and potent aroma . simple , lightly sweet malts emerge up front and then a light tropical fruitiness washes into a mild bitterness and a very very clean finish . great aroma , decent flavor , good beer .  m - slick and slightly thin .

s- fruits really come out at me . i detect raspberry , grape , and apple ! ? good sweet buttery malt really kicks in . overall- quite tasty and a surpise to me cause i did n't know what style this was until i started to drink and review it .  the mouthfeel is a little on the thin side , but drinkability is excellent .
pours a rich dark brownish amber with a thick , fluffy head - darker than most ipas i have tried .  little bit of fizziness and a lingering cottonmouth aftertaste i could have done without .

split with airohead2001 a : dark brown with a 3 finger tan colored head that has excellent retention and lacing .  this is miles better than early versions when moo brew was just getting off the ground . nose is very expressive and lifted with intense oranges and tropical fruit . the flavours are much more serious and show genuine pale ale chracter ; firm , bitter hops , some piney notes , but surprsingly the fruit offered on the nose is a bit hard to find . doesnt harm the beer though . well worth its percentile rating .

pours black with a big , thick , firm and pillowy off-white/tan head . nice looking .  im sure this loses ratings for its thin palate , but taste wise this is spot on . more roasted coffee flavors and a touch of smokiness . an imminently sippable brew . nicely done .

appearance - caramel , dark amber , deep and comforting after a long week . small but solid cap of medium cream colored head . impressive sheet lacing on the side .  the mouthfeel is a bit watery , but more substantial than most light beers .

had on tap at creekhouse served in proper augustijn glass which makes for even more authentic experience ... an explosive floral bouquet candy balloons dropping on your tongue kind of taste experience that i 've never had prior to this . kind 've like a tripple with waaay more careful hop chemistry and fragrance . a very elegant beer that could be drunk like champagne is ... this is elite stuff for sure .  m : somewhat thin , especially for the style i hoped for something richer .
a beautiful looking beer .  mouthfeel is too thin .

a : crystal clear golden color with a beautifully thick white head that never really quits . one of the best looking brews i 've seen in a while .  lacks a good bite . it 's dry and nibbles , but i want a good bite in my iipa . not that this is bad , just a bit short . easy drinking , though .
pours a dark black with a dark tan thick head . develops a great collar and excellent laciness .  mouthfeel is average , thin and just a bit too carbonated for my taste .

looks pretty ideal actually .  more of the same in the finish , kept triggering my gag reflex medium bodied , slick with moderate carbonation , skewed way to sweet , needs some alcohol burn to mitigate this horrible drinkability .

delicious aroma of caramelized malts , with some dark fruits , and a hint of alcohol .  decent so far , all the way up to the body , which is askew . slightly too light for the style , and slightly too carbonated ... a couple years should fix one of those .

this beer , when poured , is as black as oil with a great nice tan head that is fairly thick that lasts a good bit . this beer looked so amazing but when i tried it , it tasted really mild as if i were drinking a coffee watered down with milk .  m - a bit dry and rugged to the palate but still fresh . good enough carbonation .

appearance : pitch black with low head retention smell : hughmugus creamy caramel aroma . amazing ... roasted malt , subtle coffee/chocolate , taste : tastes liek it smells and reaslly does capture creme brulee .  m : medium body that could use more carbonation .

stone old guardian ( early 2008 ) is a crystal clear , sparkling , viscous , red-orange-brown ale with a frothy light beige head with oily bubbles . the head has an eggy consistency and leaves great lacing .  had my fifth sn pale ale tonight thought id have another for reviewing purposes and same as always it goes down very smooth very clean light hops aroma with a piney finish taste . even though i love this beer i do think its an extremely drinkable all around beer just a bit hyped maybe ?

nice savoury aroma of smoked cheddar comes off this one.taste is also of smoked cheddar or meat , with some chocolate malt .  a bit light for style , would have like to see more depth . the carbonation is light but balances well . the body is lacking but still a good beer .

the pour begins with an ever-expanding head that forms quickly and sorta takes over . very mousse-like and very sturdy in formaiton and retention . the color is the standard copper-golden and with typical dry-hopped haze . an outstanding look .  m : the body is medium and the carbonation is medium as well .
s - freshly brewed coffee dominates . earthy .  mf is a bit lacking , thin , though creamy .

batch # 4 '09 a : nice lush 1 '' head , tons of bottle conditioned co2 rising , this fat head is staying , almost appears to keep rising s : smells very sour , almost like wine , almost like raspberry ginger ale . i 'm excited .  poured into my maudite snifter and produces a caramel color with a finger and a half of off-white foam . light carbonation . banana , pear and floral aromas . a rather tart , spicy taste with some alcohol taste present . while this is highly drinkable , the experience is more enjoyable as it warms .
pitch black with half an inch of tan head that leaves rings of lacing .  m : on the thin side , and carbonation is on the low side .
bottle , a : pours black with a frothy tan head , gobs of lace , great retention .  m - average carbonation .
s : smells like sweet cocoa . also a roasted nut aroma in the back . the best part about this brew .  m- medium body , slightly carbonated , has a bit of creaminess to it .

basically pitch black with a creamy tan head that just rests and barely settles during consumption . great lacing and just all around excellent to the eye .  the only thing that i wish were improved was the body . yes , it 's nice and smooth , but it could be thicker .

on tap at o'brien night of a million zillion speedways look : black and totally opaqu with a 1/8 inch head and good retention smell : the slovenian hops used to dry hop it created a piney note that did not really work with the coffee backbone taste : sadly the flavor was worse than the smell .  the carbonation is better tasted and felt than seen during the initial pour .
pours perfectly with two fingers of rich sticky off white head that retains quite well .  thin body , decent carbonation .

smell : the aromas are sweet caramel and hint of toffee malts with a surprisingly light hop character . very alcoholic throughout and leaves a dry hop and floral film inside my mouth .  mouthfeel : has a fair body , but nothing out of the ordinary .
pours black and completely opaque with a large inch and a half mocha colored head . excellent retention and some nice lacing as well .  mf - medium body , very creamy , light carb .

the smell is the best part , very fruit with a slight hop scent and a strong yeast scent , taste fruity as well almost like a hard cider , not something i 'm a big fan of , but something thats interesting and an occasional pick up at the beer store  the belgian/wheat characteristics are present in the background but also help to make it such a smooth drinking brew m : average mouthfeel with a slight ammount of tongue tingle d : highly drinkable beer with very smooth characteristics but still beautiful tastes overall i absolutly love this beer and it is my mission to spread its wonder to all
looks nice , good amber color but with very little head .  mouthfeel - refreshing but a little sour-ish on the tongue .

the beer pours with a thin , whine head that is two fingers tall . it fades quickly into the lightest lacing possible . the thing i like most about the appearance , is the beautiful golden color that is hazy with a slight fade to orange at the top/middle . that is pretty much picture perfect for a wheat beer .  a little watery on the feel as the carbonation disappears completely as you work your way down the bottle .

from the bottle . poured black with a medium tan head .  i like the way this beer opens up although it ends up tasting a bit thin for the rest of the drink . m- smooth , sticky , but not thick at all .

looks really promising , menacing deep brown to black colour .  a little , fizzy , cherry hit , followed by with a slightly bitter , tangy , vanilla-y taste . ) after the initial few sips , i start noticing the bourbon influence , and it takes on a slightly woodsy element . it 's warming .

massive chunky head that has amazing retention with a bleached bone white color , and a clean and clear golden body with jets of carbination bubbles constantly rushing to the surface .  i 'm just back from a trip to the bahamas and the place i stayed at offered heineken , kalik and miller lite . i 've had both heineken and miller lite so i thought i 'd try the local brew , kalik . boy was i impressed . i drank quite a bit of this brew while sitting by the pool and each one tasted as good as the last . i sure got a good buzz but even better , no headache ! if you ever get to the bahamas be sure to try kalik .

s : powerful floral and grassy hop aroma . fresh & outstanding . t : big hop flavor - citrusy mostly . out of balance at first but a sweet malt backbone exerts itself a bit as it warms .  i quite liked this beer ! though for a wheat the color to me was not quite what i thought it should be . drank it on my front porch with friends , it was a great summer beer . this is beer # 12 of my 2 new beers a week !

this produced a a half a finger of dark tan head of tiny and tightly packed bubbles . the head dissipated quickly leaving virtually no lacing . a - a perfect dark , dark brown .  m - the pumpkin gives this beer a slick mouthfeel , and it could use a bit more carbonation , too .
great looking ipa .  it 's a little too thin for my taste , but like i said i could easily drink this all night and this is why .

s - whoa ! this brew is surprisingly fruit forward ( dare i say strawberries ! the best smelling barleywine i 've ever had , hands down . t - lots of caramel and toffee from the caramelized light malts . ends quite hoppy and a tad boozy .  the taste is nice , the coffee does n't seem overbearing or anything , but i 'd prefer more a thicker body and maybe more sweetness . very tasty but more body would be nice for a fit with the flavor .

s : great smoky nose . really a mix of islay and schlenkerla , beautiful . t : the heavy smoke has a great interplay with the residual sugar with a lot of dark malt flavour , very tasty .  only knock on this beer is mabye a little too much carbonation .

the smell is rather sweet from lots of chocolate along with some dark fruits ( cherry , plums ) & molasses .  the color was the only thing remotely impressive about the beer i thought , it was a fine dark reddish color with a medium body , there was almost no head ( maybe a half inch ) . this beer has a very weird taste , almost like bubble gum mixed with some fruit and spices . for me this is typical of magic hat , i only really enjoy the heart of darkness . the after taste was even funkier than the initial flavor , i doubt i 'd drink this again .

call me weird , but i thought this was a beautiful beer in appearance . a very cloudy apricot color , half a finger of fluffy head and very sticky lacing .  the beer is a little above average in drinkability , but the mouthfeel left much to be desired .

this is how lagers should look . a beautiful golden color with a steady head that stays well .  mouthfeel is a little thicker than i thought it would be , and it 's drinkable if it 's cold enough to mask its most interesting characteristic : this beer tastes like bananas .
a- pours a beautiful golden orange color with a nice off-white head that possesses excellent lacing and retention .  the mouthfeel was slightly thinner than expected .

could use some more to balance things out a bit . hints of chocolate , coffee , toast and oatmeal but the bourbon really overwhelms and overtakes these notes . overall this beer started off nice with a decent pour and an impressive aroma but it 's very one dimensional with too much bourbon flavor and lingering heat for my liking .  the carbonation is really about where an ale should be and there is just a bit of chewiness . to be honest , i would really like to see the darker malts removed and the carbonation reduced a bit but i suppose at that point it might as well be a whiskey .

wow i have to say iam really enjoying this alot more than some of the others that have reviewed this beer and iam not even a huge fan of the style but iam warming up to it a little more.poured into a small tulip glass a hazed peach color with the chunkies and floaties coming at the end of the pour a clingy two finger bone white head leaving broken bits of lace as it settled very slowly atop.man where to begin in describing the aromas of this beer lemon essence and ginger are what i notice at first then as i dig deeper a very root-like vegetable note comes through almost like radish or turnip i think the first time i have ever come across that in any beer , a leafy hop presence rounds out the aromas with a hit of medicinal essence.alot of the same stuff hits the palate although not quite as complex lemony and citrusy with a hint of funk and clove a big herbal finish , the lemon seems to linger on the back of the tongue for quite awhile.wow just a mad good american brewed saison honestly it may be my favorite of the style i have had , there isnt alot of funk so purists may not be so keen on it as me but hot damn i love it !  this is a quite a bit thicker than other ris that i have tried which i liked , it doesnt have an overpowering taste like others that i prefer .

it left sudsy trails of lace on the glass . s - it actually smells like christmas , if that 's possible . really an amazing aroma that comes through in taste , too .  m & # 8211 ; the feel is , surprisingly , a little under-carbonated .

poured black with a thick tan head covering the top of the beer . the head faded and clung to the sides of the glass but left some nice lacing .  taste is crisp grain , fizzy carbonation , dry aftertaste . really enjoyably light , but with reasonable malt flavor and thankfully without the taste of corn .
taste isnt as good as the aroma but still nice . more roastiness but not overly roasty , figs , chocolate , caramel , some weak hops ... tad thin .  feel is light bodied with little carbonation .

beautiful aroma . taste is also excellent . bourbon , cherries , dark fruit , caramel sugar - but not overly sweet . not terribly complex , but delicious . mouthfeel is dissapointing .  m - thin to medium body , but not watery . the carbonation is at a moderate level . the mouthfeel overall is at the appropriate levels , but nothing jumps out as distinct or mind blowing .

amazing . even though the hops are not afraid to show themselves in the flavor , this definitely works as an english barleywine , as the malts stay at the forefront . feels resiny and creamy in the mouth without being overly thick .  mouthfeel : a bit loose , i expected it to be a bit thicker . carbonation is spot on though .

hopdevil pours a red-ale color topped by two fingers of beautiful , frothy , sticky foam . the head has excellent retention and leaves plenty of lacing all around . a bit redder than i like my ipa 's but otherwise a picture-perfect appearance .  this felt very light on the palate , but given it is a pale ale it does what it is supposed too . again the sense of freshness was brought through to the taste .
smell is citrus and piney hops .  on the flip side , it 's bitterness is comparatively mild , and the body is lighter than most as well , which leads to very high drinkability .

d - it smells great , but the flavor is a severe disappointment .  poured on tap . big thanks to sean for this ! pours a deep cloudy golden color with almost no head at all . smell is nice and sweet with a great maple aroma . taste is nice and sweet , maply but sweet enough to even it all out , easy drinking and super excellent , very awesome !

it 's hard for a high original gravity beer too look great.. smelled of tons of maris otter malts , syrup , brandy , grapefruit , roses , and tiny hop leaves . lots going , but mostly toward the sweet side . had some strange creamy but earthy notes too , and also some strange alcohol and hops flavor in the finish .  taste is malty sweet goodness with a light hop finish . this is a nice session beer very drinkable . it has the malty sweetness i have been craving lately mmm .

it just looks fantastic in a glass .  although moderate in body all around , the mouthfeel is a touch too fluid , and needs additional viscosity . eeriely akin to an aged osa 2002 , albeit with less body .

it 's very similar to pliny in aroma and i consider that the ultimate compliment . great flavor to complement the aroma .  mouth is one area where i feel this beer falls to average . way too carbonated and a tad on the thin side for where i prefer an imperial stout .
great smoky , woodsy , ashy smell , full of earthiness and dirt . truly spectacular . smoke flavor is huge . nutty , walnutty flavor .  m - seems thick at first yet fails to stick .

full three fingers of stark white head .  far from a traditional belgian , this beer is a good replacement for cider in the fall , or a refreshing change-up for a summer day . m - nothing special here , especially due to the lack of head .
poured into a rapscallion glass , formed a 1 1/4 '' tan head over the clear burgundy brew . head fades sedately , with heavy sticking froth lace .  fairly light body and a slightly watery mouthfeel .

the aroma was of fresh harvest hops . in fact the lovely dry hopped aroma of this beer made my mouth salivate wildly in anticipation of the wonderful nectar that was forthcoming .  the body is a bit lean and draws somewhat thin in the finish .

here we go ... this stout arrived at my table just as i remembered . very dark brown ( almost black ) , fine bubbles just churning away in the liquid . the whole inner surface is completely coated with creamy foam ... not resembling lace at all . this may not be the best tasting stout , but is sure is the best looking .  the mouthfeel is a little weak .

pours a nearly black color with a thick and frothy mocha hued foam . retention is superb , as is the lacing . for a non-imperialized stout , this is about as good as it gets for appearance .  the carbonaton is a bit high and detracts a bit from the quality of this beer , but overall an excellent , potent stout that is sweet without being too sweet .

displays awesome retention , forms a mesa in the middle of the glass and shows off an impressive formation of 3d lace . an awesome appearance and nice aroma save this one from finding the 'c ' range .  this is one of my favorite beers . had it at a fall rennaisaunce festival locally . hate that it 's seasonal . it was light , and very refreshing on a hot autumn day in the south , and yet warm and comforting on the cool ones .

s - robust bitter hop nose up front with grapefruit , orange rind and pine . some sweet caramel malts in the background but definitely a hop forward ipa nose .  t-coffee up front followed by a grape raisin in the middle and a cocoa powder/unsweetened chocolate finish . m-kind of watery and a bit syrupy , not unpleasant but not great d-alcohol very well hidden , but warming and at 4.50 $ a bomber could be quite dangerous .

aroma is bright with citrus and syrupy with alpha acid promise . this is without a doubt the most unique and hardest nose to describe that i have ever come across .  m - nice light carbonation and creaminess , but the body is a little light and watered down .

a - cloudy reddish brown body with a pale tan head that lasts forever at a height of two plus inches .  the carbonation is medium strong ; the few medium sized bubbles are fresh . the liquid is semi-smooth . a lager with lots of off flavours .

dark amber color with a large , pillowy white head . great retention that left a foam trail in the shape of a christmas tree .  taste : thin malt levels , corn , honey , green grapes , grass , and no bitterness . mouthfeel : lightly crisp to start , dry and smooth at the finish . light in body , thin in flavor . clean aftertaste .

dark , golden brown with a nice , thick head that leaves significant lacing . a good looking bier .  i had this on tap at victory brewing a - a very pale golden with good clarity and small snowy head with small bead , little lacing collects s - the smell is yeasty , with subtle sweet malt and mild floral hops m - the feel is thin , but apropos to style w/ light malt texture sweet herbal hop feel and kind of watery finish t - the flavor is crisp , clean and sweet w/ floral hops not really adding any contrast in the way of bitterness .

forms a 1 '' tan head , slowly receeds to leave a foamy cap of retention and plenty of sticky thick lace drapes . color is a darker brown with alot of red hues glowing when held to light .  m : the body is medium with a moderate to high level of carbonation .
smells great . t : a little sharper here than in the nose .  m : good but nothing outstanding d : i could drink a lot of this .
this is a terrific ipa ! great head , great lacing , and sweet , malty , and citrus smell . drinks unbelievable . not many ipas better , if you can find one .  mouthfeel is strange .

lots of obvious coffee smells . chicory of course . yummy dark roast coffee .  good flavors , with excellent roasted grains and a huge creaminess ; very little detectable hops , which was fine ; perhaps just a bit too much on the creamy , sugary side . a little rough , going down , but not too bad ; it just would n't be an all-the-time beer because of this .

waitress brings a beautiful , slowly cascading pour that develops into a thick , creamy , homogenous bone-colored head . retention is near-perfect and good lacing is left behind .  medium light body with moderate carbonation . somewhat astringent .

pours a clear orangish red color with a heavy thick wite head that stays around for ever , the smell of hops in all ther floral glory take my nose on a rush of excitement .  it was watery and smooth with just a little carbonation and a strong malt aftertaste .
a great smelling beer . a nice strong chocolate malt aroma can be detected without even drawing up the glass .  its actually too carbonated for this type of brew .

a : the beer pours a dark brown/red hue . a big , pillowy head sits on top and leaves some nice lacing on the glass as it recedes . it is a beautiful beer .  in terms of style , the mouthfeel was flawless . however , since it is packaged as a winter brew i feel it falls short of the mark . imo , the carbonation is too coarse , or the body a bit too thin , for a `` winter warmer '' .
amazing fluffy tan head with excellent retention and lacing .  it was thin and gave a slight hoppiness that did n't last long in the mouth .
the penny red-copper color of beer is gorgeous as well .  mouthfeel is a little lacking in my opinion but does not detract from the beer too much .

beautiful copper/orange body with a slight haze topped with a thick , dense , long lasting head . looks beautiful , tastes good , drinks easy .  weakest aspect of this beer is the body , which is a bit on the thin side , with light carbonation .

i know that is n't in it , but that is the cool smell i 'm getting ... at least tonight .  unfortunately this seems a bit thin but very tastey though . well for a sawbuck per growler it is real nice .
pitch black with a large 3 fingered rocky chocolate colored head . charred aroma .  m - medium-bodied , but a bit too hoppy on the finish to be as refreshing as it should be .
overall , the scent was wonderful and the taste started off good , just too much sweet molases .  mouthfeel - prickly and a little thin .
lacing and retention are amazing . gorgeous beer !  m- now this is a little off , the body is a little flabby , and even slightly watery .

poured from the bomber into a duvel tulip glass the beer was jet black in color and topped with three fingers of sticky head that retains very well .  m : smooth and creamy mouthfeel , thin body , light carbonation . a bit light on the body that i think affects the flavor , but it 's still very enjoyable .
st-ambroise oatmeal stout from mcauslan brewing pours dark in my glass with a 1 finger light brown head .  mouthfeel is oily and slick , and a little fizzy .

2009 reserve pours a dark oily color body with a big bubbly tan coffee colored head that last forever .  not sure what 's going on with this one . smells and tastes like a bucket of water with household cleaner thats been laying around for a couple of days . try for yourself , but i guarantee you wont want to try it again . also , ive read about people paying upwards of $ 9 for a 22 oz . bottle . i paid $ 6.49 . pay no more ...

from the hand pump into an imperial nonic this brew appears a dark brown that displays some ruby clarity when held to the light . a beautiful fluffy tan creamy head sits atop the brew with a finger 's strength and it retains perfectly throughout the duration of the experience .  a fruitty flavor , like a pure english beer , i try this beer from carrefour , almost a year , a rare beer in my country , well ballanced ingredients , very flematic like english men , i visit its site regularly `` www.oldspeckledhen.co.uk '' , very attractive , its holding greene king , its famous for good beers ; recommended for a six oclock with a snack or american food .

poured with a huge frothy , bright white head . edit : just poured a second from the bottle , another great looking pour .  light and effervescent , with a hint of caramel malty sweetness . i bought a six pack of this , and after drinking the first beer , immediately grabbed another six . definitely the best 5.99 beer in the store . do n't pick this up if you 're looking for a complex thought-provoking brew . but if you want a session beer that 's a good alternative to macro-swill and are n't into over-hopped domestics like sam adams and goose island , this is a great seasonal . similar to a leinenkugel brew . a friend said that this was what you 'd get if newcastle brewed an amber . drink straight from the bottle - not really enough nuance to bother with a glass .

12 oz can a : black body under a medium sized tan head . good lace and retention . good looking beer .  a bit too thin , and a tad over-carbonated . the body was n't quite there , but still a winner .

good lacing , but a few clumps of yeast prevent a perfect score for appearance .  solid brew ... have had several river horse 's over the years with mixed results . by far this is the best beer that i 've had from this brewery . good amber/red beer flavor that 's slightly crafty but not overpowering at all . could not drink these all night but definitley 2-3 not a problem . do give this one a try , if tasty amber/red beers are your thing . you will be happy with this one .

i thought it delicious . aroma is tons of pineapple , and is totally delicious . flavor is also quite good although not quite as good as the aroma .  mouthfeel was medium with a heat that would be completely incorrect for the style .

750ml capped and sealed bottle . appears jet black .  5.5 % abv . fizzy off-white head . ) & ginger..macro-ish metallic attributes as well . plenty of sweet honey right off the bat..the combination of that and the tangy overuse of lemon peel made me feel like i was eating a pack of skittles . a ton of ginger thrown in for good measure.. wow , is my palate confused on whether or not this is a beer . certainly a bold taste from an interesting beer , but the flavors honestly do not blend together well at all . it 's hard to believe our forefathers would drink this stuff.. i hope they had better taste , because yeah , this one did n't work for me at all .

served from the bottle into a tulip glass a- poured black with tight creamy mocha head that leaves some spotty lace s- big sweet citrus and piney hops , dark roasted malt , currants , and molasses t- some citrusy/piney flavors in this beer , big licorice , molasses , some currant , and chocolate like flavors . odd soy sauce like taste developed as i got towards the bottom quarter of my glass .  mouthfeel was alright but nothing to write home about .

a - pours black without much of a head s - smells of pumpkin , spices ( cinnamon and brown sugar ) , with some nice chocolate tones . fantastic nose . t - the taste follows the nose . d - this was a very solid pumpkin stout ... the first i have tried of its kind . big thanks to boglehill for sending this unexpected extra my way !  m : very medium-light body and a slightly bitter but almost watery finish .

the aroma is very nice , with big chocolate , both bittersweet and a bit of milk , and dark fruit notes dominating .  bready malts and a faint aftertaste of alcohol is also present beer is way over carbonated . only thing that got to me was the over carbonated .
head falls at an average pace , down to a smaller mountain of froth , with coating sticky lace prevalent .  mouthfeel is a bit thin for my liking .

a - an excellent-looking beer , with deep amber hues and a thick , foamy head . head was a very light yellow , 3 fingers . sediment observed toward the dregs of the bottle . good legs .  it smells and tastes like a cheap beer . it is not worth the money that a premium beer can ask . i ca n't think of anything good to say about this beer other than i 'm hoping it will be gone soon . i 've tried pawning the beer off on people and they did n't want to drink it either .

smells like porter heaven . great , spicy scents of cinnamon and sweet chocolate malt . it almost smells like they put some artificially engineered scents in there , in a good , science-is-progress kind of way . the balanced flavor and great smells make this a pretty appealing brew .  gorilla vanilla was billed as light in body & alcohol and it was exactly as described . my wife that hates beer said she could drink this with no problem .
oil black body with a thick pale tan head and huge amounts of lacing .  mouthfeel is on the thin sider , and a bit oily , but there 's enough carbonation to keep it pleasant .

great head retention .  the lack of flavor is the most important part , it 's more like a watery , sour drink with a bit of beer added . i guess that is malt , but it 's ... light . on the bright side , it 's refreshing at first and there is no really offensive `` off '' flavor 's , i 'm not picking up any metal and it 's rather clean .

s : this smells right one the balance of the bourbon , chocolate , and vanilla bean are perfect . the nose on this is really inviting , there 's trace of any off aromas you sometimes get that overpower what trying to be represented . the bourbon is really tame in this one , its lending a nice charred backbone that helps to really life the vanilla to the front .  smells slightly watery faint tones of chocolate malts and coffee good although slightly watery tastes of slightly toasted coffee and powerful malts chocolate is also in there mouthfeel well carbonated yet slightly watery some of the best drinkability i 've experienced in a stout however this comes at a cost and the cost happens to be its mouth feel , taste and smell overall its a pretty good drinkable stout it really is not very good unless it is poured from the tap i 'll order at a pub if i want a stout and they do n't have a good micro brew on tap
the aroma is quite nice . nice blend of the pumpkin pie spices ; nutmeg , cinnamon and allspice . very nice .  m - mouthfeel was alright ... carbonation was high and body was light .

aroma-this beer has such a phenomenal hop bouquet-super floral , piney , light resin , big citrus with notes of grapefruit and lemon-this beer just plain smells awesome . lurking under the hops is some nice support from the malt , with toast and caramel peaking through . the flavor is good , but the nose just blows other beers out of the park-it smells incredible . love this beer .  mouthfeel- a tad thin for the style but still got a nice solid body .

see thru light orange with a swirl of vigorous visual carbonation feeding the thick and fluffy cap of foam on top .  102 ibu ... tastes sweet , like honey and ginger ale with a touch of malt . little too syrupy to be super refreshing but still awesome .

when i poured this brew into my glass i was impressed with how dark and thick it is , like a cross between melted chocolate and molasses . because of this i expected it to be rich and hearty , i hate to say it is n't as dense as it looks . the body actually seemed a bit watery for the style .  m : for a stout the mouthfeel is awfully simple , though the sweet notes add some much needed depth .

the smell is the best part of this beer . too many kosch style beers are lacking expressive notes , while this really pops with flowery hops and crisp , slightly sweet malt . really nice and just under the top of the heap for the style . too bad my excitement over the pleasant smell did n't continue as i took my first few sips . the rest of the beer is nice , clean and just slightly sugar-kissed malt couples well with flowery hops that are n't bitter at all . major bummer , this could be up there with the coast kolsch , summit kolsch , or even victory 's amazing rendition .  m - feels very smooth going down . nothing too speial about it .
really wonderfully complex . body is medium with a velvety smoothness and a lively carbonation .  moderate carbonation and a light , slightly watery mouthfeel .

smell : one of the best hefe smells ever , since i 'm not the biggest banana-hef fan .  a light to medium body , with prickly , active carbonation . the carbonation was just a tad bit higher then i would have liked , but was still enjoyable .

a great aroma . reminds me of a brisk fall afternoon near halloween .  [ postscript : 18 months later , and another 6-pack of this enjoyed , the mouthfeel was much less sticky , but way too carbonated .

always impressed by unibroue packaging . a : gigantic white fluffy head . semi-clear orange-straw color . perfectly carbonated .  somewhat substantial body , nothing too heavy . if any hit , a little too much carbonation but that is stretching it .

as with most stone brews , the nose was out of this world . even for the basic pale ale.. plenty of hops , this brew starts out smelling of mile hops , kind of like a watered down ipa but then as the beer warms there are big biscuity malt scents which i have never quite understood until now . pilsbury grands in my glass tasted good but not incredible , i have to keep myself in check with this review because it was so great to sniff . i could drink this beer all night long and i plan on it some day.. great `` go-to '' beer folks .  the mouthfeel was much lighter than expected with a slight buttery feel .

a - golden with an orange hue . big eggshell colored head . lots of lacing sticks to the side of the glass .  i think that it is a bit overcarbonated and that the body is a bit thin , but the smell and taste are absolutely wonderful , and i could drink this all night .

12 oz bottle poured into a nonic 2008 vintage a - the usual ris color with a 2.5cm tan/brown head that would have been larger had the glass been taller . d - the beer itself looked beautiful , but its flavor and aroma were really weak .  mouthfeel was a bit thin , pretty amazing for a beer of this gravity , making this dangerously drinkable .

not quite as strong as some imperial stouts , at only 7 percent alcohol by volume , but still a very tasty stout . this stout is n't very roasty and tends toward being sweet . '' a decent stout , but better examples of this style are out there .  it is perhaps on the thin side and sweet side and is not too complex , but has good character that hold up well .

bottle labeled , `` limited spring 2003 release '' the apperence is a nice thick stout with a deep dark brown body and a chocolate-mocha colored head that retains low but the thick lacing proved to be quite nice .  mouthfeel : very light/somewhat watery with a high degree of carbonation .

lots of character in this nose . i pull off some roasted malt , dark chocolate , fresh cut wood , caramel , molasses , fig , and a tinge of brown sugar . overall this beer is very good .  body is a little thin for an oatmeal stout , but it still has the smoothness . carbonation feels a little too heavy for this style i think .

appearance - clear golden brown color with very nice 2 finger frothy head smell - wonderful citrus/hops scents .  m - started off smooth but had a monster tart kick . really the only element that was a bit rough .

nice light straw-colored pour with a resilient fluffly rocky head that remains to the last goddamned drop .  after my first taste i really was able to feel how refreshing this beer truly is , and i enjoyed ever sip . not your normal fall seasonal , due to the lack of heavy sweet notes , but none the less one of the better seasonal beer i have had .

hinninger kaiser pils looks beautiful , and almost unmatched when poured into a regular stein . there are vast amounts of bright white and soft pillowy head , and the body is gold and crystal clear .  it 's a bit thin in the mouth .

pours black as night with nice ruby highlights around the endges when held to the light , has a nice thick tan head .  m : an average , slightly crisp mouthfeel . however , once the taste of it hit the buds on my tongue , i did n't care much to think about mouthfeel .

the aroma is fantastic ; the hop aroma is simply fantastic with the citrus smell that highlights grapefruit . that hop mixes well with the sweet malt aroma , very inviting ! the flavor , while good , does not live up to my expectations based on the nose .  sweet maple syrup aroma with herbal hops and some yeast . the malts have a very sweet taste and also there is a toasted bread taste that really develops in the aftertaste . very good ale !
pretty good beer , not a huge bitter-beer lover but being on the low end it 's pretty enjoyable and wouldnt mind grabbing some in the future .  m- medium body , definitely unfiltered .
very dark , nearly black , nice brown foamy head , lots of sticky lace .  very good beer but does lack with a thin somwhat over carbonated mouthfeel for a stout .
it smells really , really wonderful though .  m : very light . a bit over carbonated but not overwhelming .

pours a hazy copper to orange color . very nice head retention . great patches of lace left coating the glass .  m -- maybe i should n't have drank this after sipping on a j.w . its not quite what i would call `` watery , '' but it could use a little more body . carbonation levels are fine .

this elixir pours into the glass with a beautiful clear amber body topped by a thick off white creamy head with a good amount of lace left behind .  it was a bit thinner with more carbonation than i would have liked , but overall very drinkable .

was holding on it until i receive the oak age version to do a side-by-side comparison with some friends , but none are hopheads like me . s : wow , a very strong aroma . i could smell this beer without my nose being close to the glass . i get mainly hops , resinous and some grapefruit .  mouthfeel - thin and mid to low carbonation .

appearance and color , just what you would expect from a quality ipa aroma : wonderful , very piney hops , and even a little bit floral i would say taste : better than i would expect from an average ipa , but i just cant quite taste the hops they way i can smell them in this beer . overall an excellent beer , hoppy to the core , a very solid ipa  m : somewhat chalky d : high
pours a bright gold color with a nice white head , good lacing too .  m : really carbonated , even a bit much . thin body otherwise , however -- just a bit more oomph here and this would be epic .
appearance : clear golden yellow in color sporting a bright white one finger head that lasted a while .  body is light and mouthfeel is fairly thin and bubbly , with a very clean finish .
appearance : the color of the beer is black and opaque . the deep mocha colored head is thick , rich , lustrous , and long-lasting .  the feel is alright but it does n't matter at this point .

this maerzen came out to be with a decent two finger thick , light tan head . the body is a picturesque dark golden amber color , and very well filtered .  m-lighter , a little thin and the finish seems flat as well .

clear yet dark purple mahogany without any carbonation under a cloud like frothy khaki surface of the moon cratered pour into me pint . plenty of visible lattice lace in the pint . liquid dessert appearance . it looks good , but this is all down hill from here .  acceptable in the mouth . horrible beer .

imperial is the perfect name for this outstanding beer appearance : black . has a dark brown/light black one-finger head which lasts a good minute or two and leaves nice foamy lacing on the glass .  this has got a lot of hop bitterness to it , this reminds me a little of hopslam . i did n't really notice the `` hop backbone '' like everyone else has mentioned . like hopslam , this is best drank slowly due to the high abv .

my memory serves me correctly - this smells lovely . malted milk , burnt sugar/golden syrup , some kind of christmas dessert with plums and a green hoppy smell .  still , it seems a little light in body and the carbonation is low . without a doubt another quality beer by dogfish head , but i have a feeling that the pricetag of a 750 ml bottle would scare me from its purchase .

a ) pours with a very active tan colored head . great head retention . creamy with some big bubbles , but amazingly sticky .  m - carbonation is on the low end of high with a sturdy medium body . i do n't much like the huge carbonation and the taste suffers because of it .
dark brown pour . huge , thick frthy head lokks like a chocolate milkshake from the top .  it 's medium bodied ; watery , but smooth . the finish is a little watery .
lacing is pretty good too . very nice looking beer .  the mouthfeel is not a complex one and is rather unbalanced and nondescript .
the aroma projects bright floral hops very nice really though i initially caught a whiff of something that said , miller high life to me .  its not a bad mouthfeel , just a bit light in the ass .
a : the beer looks like perfectly clear dark caramel , topped with a foamy tan head which provides generous lacing , and sticks around for a while after the pour .  mouthfeel is oe 's strongpoint .
smell : i ca n't put a finger on what it is i 'm smelling , but the aroma of this beer is incredible ! !  mouthfeel is average , not too thin , and i think appropriate for this beer .
nice head and great retention .  mouthfeel is about average , very drinkable to anyone that enjoys a hoppy bitter beer .

the aroma is one of the best from a wit i 've ever had . the taste disappointment after the great aromatics . it 's pretty bland , and it misses all of the citrus and spice found in the nose . slight spice , and a lot of the strange , off flavors i find in a lot of adjunct lagers .  i 'm 90 % sure this is the same beer as their `` gretchen 's gold '' , which is really what i 'll be reviewing . the bottled version leaves much to be desired vs. on draught . i 've not tasted such a difference between tap and bottle in any other beer . extremely refreshing and drinkable , pleasant sweet malt w/ barely discernable hops for structure . scant head . overall a great beer in its style , with no real flaws . if you can get it on tap , it 's well worth it .

produces a firm and sticky two finger thick white crown , which retains quite well . the body is dark gold in color and is cleanly filtered .  flavour is incredibly light , almost nothing resembling either a smoked stout or an oatmeal stout . i do n't know why i bothered buying another trafalgar product . i 'm tried of drinking this after a few sips .

pours a deep golden with cascading bubbles that create a dense and very very creamy head . absolutely beautiful .  m - on the lighter side of medium body with a good amount of carbonation . this is the biggest problem with the beer , it is just a bit too thin and light .

lovely . a bit of grassiness as well . it 's like they have left a shadow but the hops totally overwhelm everything .  i have been drinking a few imperial stouts and imperial ipa 's recently and thought the mouthfeel was a bit thin , but .

poured 40 degrees fahrenheit into a dogfish head shaker pint . pours a lucid gold with a tall 3 finger white head settling into a persistent cap . endless stream of champagne bubbles coming up from the bottom .  mouthfeel was unremarkable , which is as much as can be expected of any pilsener .

poured a deep oily black hue with a two finger creamy tan head . there was excellent retention and sticky lacing .  mango , lemon , bretty funk , carbonation is light , only thing i 'm really missing is the dry hops here . mouthfeel- i have a feeling this bottle is a little old , could use more carbonation .

great lemony hop smell ! wonderful . soap-like hops in the same way cilantro is soapy . i would actually consider it an ipa . very hoppy , copper-colored and 6.5 % .  m : thin and light with average carbonation .

the aroma reminded me of a cross between the banana peel aroma in a few hefe 's and the yeasty flair of the saison styling it 's attributed too . it 's very easy to drink , matter of fact if my wife was not asleep , i would give her some as she likes this style beer ... but alas , it 's all for me !  man talk about pleasantly surprised ... after the last two i wasnt expecting much from this random brew ... glad i picked the best for last ... pour couldnt get much better with a great levitating head and awesome lacing ... nice floral hop aroma , slight alcohol tone not obnoxious at all ... taste is almost all nutty malt , somewhat dry ... alcohol is amazingly well hidden ... one of the easiest drinking malt liquors ive ever had ... too bad the turks got it right before we did ... keep in mind that this four is rated in accordance to other euro strong lagers/malt liquors ... cheers !
appearance - amber color , decent size head with some nice lace .  the feel was unremarkable .

poured from a draft into a pint glass at san diego brewing company at san diego , calif. color was red amber .  the taste is about the same , with a distinct nut flavor . goes down pretty easy , but there is a lot of carbonation here , and you can distinctly see many small bubbles rising up from behind the brown color . overall , this is a pretty good beer , and a nice looking one . i recommend it .
lacing continues nicely down the glass ( ky ale snifter ) very hoppy aroma . nice citric combined with piney , bright and floral aromas .  mouthfeel : good carbonation , otherwise nothing special .

sampled july 2010 the beer pours with a dense , frothy , pink-tinged , tan colored head that sits on top of a clear , rich red hued beer ( though it is not dark as some that i have experienced on this trip ) .  mouthfeel is light bodied , light carbonation . smooth , but average .
nose is full of spices - pepper , clove and corriander , wheats , and nice softer orange hint .  m : very light , slightly watery , lower carbonation .
wonderful . t : slightly sweetnened grapefruit , a touch of spiciness , and a bit of spearmint on the finish .  m- mouthfeel is carbonated and a bit watery .

very nice . the beer has a smooth taste , but it 's a bit watery .  mf- resinous and sticky with aggressive carbonation . not as soft and luxurious than great traditional belgian ales but rather sharp due tothe load of hops . some powdery yeast feel . it 's so hoppy that i might not have noticed the belgian yeast .

a - looks good s - great smell ! the effervescent hop smell is much like fat tire , but has more depthy and complexity . smells of grapefruit , citris , and underlying malts .  m : this is light-medium brew that is a little thinner than i imagined it to be . although the mouthfeel is thin , the look , aroma and taste make up for it .
the appearance was for me the best part , as it pour a deep amber and white head .  m : thin viscosity ( bordering on being watery ) and moderate carbonation seem out of place here .

a gentle pour produces a clear , glowing , reddish-copper body with a huge , billowing three-finger cap of pale beige foam atop . the stubbornly-sticky , fine-bubbled head consolidates itself around the periphery of the glass , concentrating into a somewhat coarser form that sticks impressive sheeted gobs of 3-d lacing onto the sides of the glass .  the smell is overtly sweet with grain and a touch of honey . it 's terribly sweet with no hops note and truly no redeeming qualities about it . one of my generous gulps actually had me thinking it might come right back up .

this beer looked beautiful when poured but the taste did n't live up to its appearance .  think prunes and raisins , but more complex and infinitely boozier . i ca n't believe that this beer is appearing thin on the palate and i think that it has to be with the insanely high abv . even though it 's clean , it 's still very sweet . i am loving the taste but i am certainly not digging the mouthfeel , that is into the moderate strength liqueur territory . a brewing achievement but not beer like ; delicious nonetheless .
a : copper-bronze with a huge , off-white head , great retention & exceptional lacing .  smooth and sweet , this is pretty nice . carbonation is a bit low , even for my liking .
this brew pours a deep brown with amber highlights .  mouthfeel was pretty average drinkability was pretty good i could see myself having another one .
looks impressive with sheets of cascading lacing on the glass after every drink .  m : carbonation balance is nothing special .

smell : the aroma of this beer is definitely its strongest attribute . great hop/floral character with the typical grapefruit and citrus notes . i thought that the smell of this beer was also a bit sweeter than most ipas ; there is almost a bit of honey detectable resulting in a nice balance between sweetness and bitter hops . taste : the first thing i noticed was the nice creamy texture of this one . again , i could have used a bit more malt presence to balance things out . drinkability : very refreshing .  mouthfeel was fine . a little thin - i think that a big , thick mouthfeel would accentuate the pumpkin pie-like characteristic that i think they 're going for .

very hoppy , partially sweet .  the amount of flavor packed into something this thin and `` refined '' is unusual and noteworthy . it feels a little creamy on the swirl , but i do n't really like where it stimulates the tongue . however , the mouthfeel leaves something to be desired , so how many will you want to down consecutively ?

pours a nice deep rich darker orange color , lightly hazy . big thick creamy beige colored head falls slow and laces well , very nice looking brew .  mouthfeel is pretty thin , nice a smooth carbonation , but just feels weak .

poured a jet-black color , the color of motor oil mixed with molasses and appeared to have the same consistency . small , creamy head definitely laced the glass throughout .  m= body is medium/average but probably a little too thin . i was hoping for a little thicker in the body as well as taste department .

s- hoppy , hoppy , hoppy t- tons of hoppy bitterness and that ghost citrus m-lots of carbonation burning bubbles like when you drink soda to fast d-overall pretty good for your token hoppy beer  m - moderate beer body , strong carbonation . just seems a little thin at times .

s - wonderful aromas of honey , pears , lemon peel , floral hops . i really like this . t - smooth , controlled sweetness . d - just an awesome beer , i 'm so glad i can get this locally now !  mouthfeel is a bit grainy , again , like the bottom of a cup of coffee .

this beer had some wonderful aromas of scotches , alcohol , fruits , chocolates , and more and it tasted like more of the same . rogue should start making this stuff again .  this beer is exceptionally thin in the mouth however .

big peat and smoke that many american versions skimp on . excellent . m/d : a big full body that is low on the carbonation . incredibly smooth , creamy , and decadent . this is really exceptional . maybe the best american version of a wee heavy i have come across ( founders backwards bastard is the only other that comes to mind ) .  it 's quite amazing how such a simple beer can be so good ! perhaps it is its plainness that makes it such good lager . this is not a fancy schmancy beer . the best way to describe this is just plain beer . the smell was slightly grainy , with a hint of barley mash . taste was excellent . this is a very good beer .
this pours a great copper color with a creamy white head .  mouth : very light for the style , heavy on carbonation .

not much head at first , however after setting the glass down the head flows down into the beer for an awesomely presentable beer . color is almost black with a dark head .  review to style as they say and for a mass produced macro swill this is my favorite for just chillin and enjoying some beer thats not gon na get me too wasted . the appearance on all of em ( macro swills ) is pretty nice gold straw with continued effervescence throughout and a good carbonation level . extremely drinkable and the flavor is a very mellow german or czech type hops . they arent making it strong but it still tastes like one of the beers i grew up with .

'' pour was an amazing , thick used-motor oil black ( only a beer geek could find that description appetizing ) .  there 's a really nice level of hopping in this one , that becomes apparent in the middle and finish . could do with having a bit more body , but its okay as it is .

a - this brew is a black as i 've ever seen any beer . it is the perfect black . this has the looks by which all other stouts should be measured . ~ this is a stellar example of what a stout should be .  t- hop fruitiness up front , not particularly citrus from the big c hops but just fruity . aftertaste brings up the rear with a hop bitter whollop . m- average for this style , not great but definately not bad .
it smells like a cup of black coffee . i love the smell . skoal !  m : carbonated and thin .
appearance : deep red body with an active head . looks great .  mouthfeel : highly carbonated for the style .

s : wonderful . the coffee is much more pronounced than i remember . o : a wonderful beer .  the beer poured into the glass to reveal a nice copper color . the aroma was slightly bready with a mild hop character . the taste was mildly malty at first then gave way to a nice hoppy dryness in the finish . the is a nice quaffable beer .

hazy amber body , with lots of tiny-bubbled co2 trails visible . huge , thick head easily rises an inch over the rim of the glass without spilling over .  m/d - light body that could stand to use just a slight bump in carbonation imo .

s- wow , lots of spices . gingerbread and pumpkin are huge in this beer . nice for someone who is concerned about spices dominating , but i think i would prefer them to be a little more noticeable . the taste was unexpected compared to the smell , but i guess that is the beauty of beer .  super easy to drink ... just a little thin on the mouthfeel .
pours ruby with a large persistent head leaving loads of lacing . beautiful .  m - moderate beer body , strong carbonation bite .

look : black and totally opaque with a red ring at the bottom . great 1 inch plus tan head with great retention and some circle lacing as the head resides smell : piney hops mixed with the carafe malt creates a very unique scent that i can only compare to like a fruity pebbles cereal smell taste : upfront is quite a bit of alcohol followed by very sweet i 'm assuming from the carafe malt in the middle and finishes off with that same fruity pebbles smell and obviously taste very unique mouthfeel : medium body and medium carbonation and leaves the mouth just a bit sticky and dry overall : very unique black ipa .  mouthfeel is an average apa .

gorgeous dark brown pour settling inky black in the glass with a mighty thick dark tan foam of mashed up graham cracker-like quality . the lacing is more like shelving as it grabs on to the glass with thickly set curtains of foamy soup .  mouthfeel is ok .

appearance & gt ; dark , almost black.chocolate malt hed with some retention and a heck of a lot of lacing . smell & gt ; like rum-filled dark chocolate candy taste & gt ; intriguing burnt malt goodness , then sweet with a big hang that could give you cancer with its bunt toast taste . mouthfeel & gt ; chewy drinkability & gt ; pretty drinkable , but i just ca n't drink so much chewiness ... and so much rum .  my in-laws bought a leine lodge and this one was in it . leinie 's has a lot of good beers , this one looked interesting so i tried it . i drank if from the bottle so i could not see it but it smelled pretty good . the first sip was in your face nut flavor . too much nut flavor in fact . i kept drinking it because i though it would settle down the more i got used to it but it did not . i actually could not finish this beer . there are n't many beers i would pour down the drain , but this is one of them .

body is a very nice deep dark amber with a fat 1 finger foamy off white head . it really is quite dark .  m - light to medium body , medium carbonation . very slight harsh bitterness lingers on the back of the tongue .

appearance - the deep red color of a perfect pour ( i.e . with just the right amount of head ) make the look of a glass of this beer exceptional .  well done porter ... .looks the part with a creamy tan head atop a black body ... a very nice aroma greets my nose..roasted and sweetish ... milk chocolate as well as some subtle coffee notes milk chocolate and roasted malts are the big players on the taste but the java notes become a little more pronounced ... body is creamy and smooth and slightly thin ... i do n't exect regular ol porters to be high gravity monsters so this is fine with me ... it really drinks easily and quickly ... .
when this porter was poured into my glass , it poured with a dark brown head that unfortunately did not last very long .  m - mouthfeel is a bit on the thin side for my liking .

after drinking my first , and it was a gift , i 've got to tell you that this beer is _seriously overrated_ a- clear straw color , white foamy head , great lacing , nice bubbles , looks fabulous . s - mild t - mostly just a warming of alcohol , everything else is subtle .  mf- medium/light bodied with kind of a watery feel compared to other porters .

has a pretty deep auburn color with a 1/2 inch head .  `` bottled in 2009 '' pours a nice red in color , a hue i have n't seen in beer before , with no head , though it is carbonated . there are also weird vegetable flavors that are not that pleasant . noticeable alcohol flavors and dryness . the more i drink of this the worse it tastes , actually . this beer just does n't do it for me , and it hurts me to give a bad review to a beer from such a great brewery . this is the least distinguished ( a polite way to say `` worst '' ) dogfish head beer .
this looks great . perfect amber color with a steady one inch head that stayed the whole time .  mouthfeel is a bit sticky , like a pretty good ipa .

hazed rusty amber pour produces a mighty , eggshell white head of dense froth that never really falls below a 1/4 inch cap , leaving scores of lace as it goes . beautiful in the glass .  mouthfeel : medium carbonation , almost light body .

s - hop aroma is wood , not necessarily pine as some others are . exceptional smell . t - just as it smells the hops and malt blend perfectly .  that smokiness carries over abundantly into the taste . the lesser side of this is the feel ... bit to far on the light end of things . overall though , solid rauchbier , though probably my least favorite so far of the aecht schlenkerla rauch 's .

pours a slightly hazed copper colour with a massive , massive tan head that foams into a mountain above the rim of the glass and hangs around for a long long time and once dissolved leaves chunks of residue on the glass . awesome stuff .  m : mouthfeel was just okay for me , a bit thin .

11.2oz bottle poured into my darkness glass ... not a gusher but a huge tope head rises about 8 fingers with great retention , decent lacing ... the beer is a medium gold that looks really good ... the front of the aroma is lots of chamomile , not off to a good start in my book .  good beer with alot of taste . i unfortunately drank this with a meal so i feel i may not of appreciated the taste of the beer independantly . but the unfiltered armoa and golden look was your typical hefeweizen . beer has a strong character and is a summer favorite

pours a pitch black color with a beautiful brown head into my glass . definitely the color of the style . roasted malt greets the nose followed by grassy hops that do n't jump out too much in the nose .  m - a bit flat . mouthfeel is so far the best part of this beer .
very nice looking beer , 2 finger head that stayed around for a while , almost clear at the bottom of the glass more cloudy as it builds towards the top .  the mouthfeel is medium/thin .

the body is a thick pitch black , impermeable to light , very impressive . thick chunky tan head , dented with large bubbles .  never having any of post roads products , i decided to give this brew a try . the taste on the other hand was a smooth pumpkin & hops infusion leaving my mouth only asking when it can have more . overall this is a very drinkable beer from a brewery i knew nothing of before now and now only hope to know more of ...

pours a very dark , almost black amber with some reddish tones to it . a very sticky map covers the glass as you drink .  funny , my first craft beer since wv popped the cap and its under 6 % lol nice copper pour.clear and clean leaving pretty rings of lacing with every sip . love that for sure . malty in the nose , not so typical of sierra nevada and i dont mean that in a negative way . sweet , caramel and mixing hops . taste leans towards malt , not tons of hop flavor but nice bitterness . liking this one for sure !

bottle i picked up in seward , into a midnight sun goblet , the artic rhino coffee porter is a dark , inky black , with a small but thick , creamy tan head , leaving thick foamy lace .  on tap .a creamy hazy orange color with loads of yeast swimming around , small white fluff head.aroma is somewhat heffish , with some mild banana , cloves , orange zest , and grassy notes.flavor is wheaty with loads of banana , bubblegum and and spice , maybe even pineapple . very drinkable , refreshing after a long days work . would make a solid summer brew too .

11oz tulip/wine appearance : the color is a dark amber , the head a light tan with sticky lace formed on the glass as you drink .  not exactly a esb by definition but a good beer by my standards . a dark beer in color , with a fruity hint on the nose , of apple and a strawberry sort of smell . the taste is smooth fruity and a bit hoppy all at once . my only complaint was a bit of a bitter after taste , but hey it is a esb
