very enticing aroma . t - burnt dark chocolate malt profile , highly bitter . absolutely terrible when served cold , however it did improve significantly as it warmed .  i must have a bad batch of this fine ale . the last time i drank it the hops were far more bitter and noticable . in fact , it tastes a bit watered down .

a fantastic extra from a fantastic trader rhong187 a really dark burnt chocolate with a dark mocha head that caps a two fingered head that does n't look like it is going to be going anywhere anytime soon . as the beer gets drank and warms down , head stays and turns a deep ruby red alot of carbonation coming from the bottle and gives this beer a real live look .  it has a light body and goes down fairly easy which i guess is average for the style . overall it 's just a cheap beer meant for mass consumption by others , not me .

slowly darkens to nearly black , with a ruby tint . a milky off-white head of about 1/2 inch appears and leaves patchy spiderweb lacing . aromas released during the pour are strongest , then weaken after the head forms ; roasted barley and background english hops .  elements of pine , citrus , resinous elements too -- slightly oily but in a very pleasant manner . the biggest flaw i can find with this beer is that it wastes too much of the carbonation in the beginning when it is first poured . it is slightly flat in the mouthfeel although i have tasted some other ipas recently that were far worse in this department .

10/14/2011 bottling a : perfect pour into an imperial pint . midway between straw and copper , nice bubbling . good head retention .  the carbonation is very low . almost negligible . and that 's an understatement .
smell is an enticing blend of maraschino cherries , macadamia nuts , and just a little wheat around the edges .  m- good carbonation . a little watery for an imperial stout .

the nose ... wow , this is pure deciduous pine with tons of hoppy oils , hop esters , and hop resins . the nose on the beer is great . the taste is really nice as well . the beer is modestly carbonated , thick , heavy , with some abv in the throat , a touch boozy , and very piney hop .  kombucha is usually very vinegary , but this was more in line with a reserved lambic . carbonated to the tongue , but low head retention . m+d- it is a touch watery .

smells of tartness , slight earthy malt , slight must , hint of dark citrus , and a hint of alcohol .  saison du buff appearance- very hazy golden , lively white head that dissipates quickly.4 smell- hops - green buds to the max 5 taste- wow . delicious . sweet and citrusy but with huge hop and wheat finish.complex balanced . spicy nutmeg 5 mouf- easy 3 drinkable - oh so drinkability 4
seriously sexy looking beer .  m : medium , but thicker than expected , this is one of my first lambics , but it really steps up to the plate and is a home run .
smells wonderful . a nice , dark fruitiness like cherry with dark chocolately , charred malts underneath .  if there 's a downside , it 's the watery mouthfeel .

appearance : a thick , rich pour with head that 's slow to come out , but builds to 1.5 fingers high and is creamy tan . a somewhat cloudy deep deep brown .  crystal-clear , pale golden body with a few lonely bubbles of carbonation wandering around ( needs a bit more carbonation - mouthfeel was rather 'watery ' ) . mild malty flavor , with enough hops for balance . great thirst quencher , and overall a pretty damn good summertime brew .

poured an opaque dark baker 's chocolate brown with a slow rising tan head that fills the glass and stays up forever yeilding a thick wall of lace , just beautiful . and that 's just after the pour , i hav n't even smelled it yet !  carbonation seems a bit low ; it may be the swing-top cap , as i 've had bad luck with them lately . in any case , it gives a bit too watery a mouthfeel to my taste .

i believe this is only the second welsh beer i have had to date.poured into a nonic a lighter copper color with a 1/2 finger white head that if it had not been gone so fast would have had a higher appearance rating.fresh green apple in the nose at first , it really was fresh , a bit of iron and biscuit malt as well.pretty thin in the mouth , to me it took away a little from the flavors , some of that green apple tartness and toasted biscuit with almost a sherry vinegar flavor in the finish.not a bad sociable pint , its thin but its `` nice '' .  ( m ) medium bodied and a medium mouthfeel .
golden in colour , great clarity for a bottle conditioned beer and an ample white head .  the carbonation is moderate high .

boldy malt & spiced aroma , smells like my kitchen on a good brew day ! t 2.5 - weak version of the smell , amaizingly weird the taste is given the bold aroma . smell rocks . weak every other catergory .  mouthfeel is pretty average , but not annoying . carbonation 's good , body on the thin side .

presentation : standard vulkan brau to-go bottle , caps are color coded for style . the weizen has a white cap . appearance - pours a slightly milky , faded tangerine . 3 fingers of soft white head , very smooth , lots of big bubbles and pockets . some solid chunky sediment in the final few ounces , most of it settles to the bottom rapidly , some of it remains suspended .  sierra nevada . and newcastle . and needed a change i 'm drinking rogue dead guy for the first time as i type this . for a strong beer .
a shame - this beer had so much promise from that wonderful aroma .  a bit thin but not bad .
slightly hazy dark amber with a big very-light-brown head with great r & l .  a little watery at the end .

gorgeous red-amber colour .  the white head thins out rapidly , but it sticks around all the way through with fantastic lacing . ginger and caramel are the biggest flavors here . the cinnamon adds just a late heat followed by a bite from the hops . maybe not the top tier of winter beers , but i would have no problem doing this again

first time trying this beer . a : this is one good looking beer . red with a cream colored head . leaves good lacing throughout .  hate is not a strong enough word for how i feel about this beer . i 'm looking for the litterbox for something to suck on to get this taste out of my mouth .

the pour is pitch-black in color ; head is immoderate in size , light chocolate in color , and the lace thick clinging sheets that last till the bottom of the glass .  it was a little over carbonated for my likes but still had a great feel to it in my mouth .
has outstanding appearance for a lager .  m - i tried not to destroy by palate by keeping this beer in my mouth for an extended time , so i really ca n't comment on this .

good clarity . pretty amber color .  high carbonation that takes away from the smoothness of the beer . overall , a very enjoyable beer that is a bit high on carbonation so some of the flavors are gone before they need to be .

this one smells great . t : not as sour as i expected , but of course it is still sour .  medium bodied and somewhat slick , yet with a sticky finish that seems to be equal parts sugar and bitterness .

a bit thin , very enjoyable however , and easy to drink . the scent of this beer being remarkable , and a good beer , but there are better pumpkin ales .  mouthfeel is lacking , but the flavors are right on , carbonation is complimentary .
beautiful color , burnt sienna .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with smooth carbonation , slightly watery .

s : wonderful . chocolate and coffee and malt . love it . first 5.0 i 've given in a review in this category . t : good to very good . having trouble separating the taste from the mouthfeel , because it is much more thin and watery that i expected .  it had a medium body , appropriate for a pale ale . mostly just bland with a slight bit of bitterness , the dominant flavour was sourness that lingered on the palate and continued to build through the pint .
pretty damn good looking beer .  mouthfeel is thin , but typical for brown ales ( i always expect a fuller beer based on the smell ) .

s- fruity and phenolic , with alcohol aromas complementing the yeast . very fragrant and nice . t- tart fruity and sweet , again very much like a weakened tripel .  lighter with some fizzy carbonation and a dry finish .

aroma : smells amazing . tons of grapefruit and sweet cotton candy in the aroma . drinkability : this is an amazing ipa , full of great west coast hop aromas and flavors . it 's easy drinking , and quite delightful .  m : the body is medium with a low carbonation and a tooth rotting sweetness . so unbearably sweet and sugary without any sort of balance .
bottled : 12/19/10 a = mostly black in color .  quite a strong tongue-tingling carbonation , a bit too much for my taste .

anchor 's humming ale looks like a nice thick wheat beer , turbid and dense blond in appearance . the first sniff reveals a rich and fresh bouquet of american citrusy hops .  light bodied , and somewhat flat , though perhaps that is just this bottle ?

the nose is super fresh and fruity , floral hops and mango . there 's a nice roasty finish that just seals the deal for me .  maybe some floral hops and a quite malty after taste which i didnt mind at all . the whole mix is very plain .

thanks muenchenerkindl for such an excellent extra 12 oz bottle poured into a duvel tulip an awesome midnight black with a good two fingers of tan head that settles into a large curtain of lace that lasts to the end aromas of oatmeal , malts and grains , yes almost barleywineish with a light alcohol smell oatmeal , chocolate molasses and fruit with a lite hop end note wow i like the taste almost like some sort of hybrid oatmeal stout barleywine palate is medium to thick you need to sit back , relax and sip this one .  o-a nice stout that would benefit greatly from a more viscous and luxurious mouthfeel . with the harsh carbonation it seems more like a coffee soda pop .

smell has sharp sweet cherries .  i am truely amazed to find a lighter version of yuengling 's premium . with a little bit less malt . the smell is spring fresh with no skunk to ruin your day . and blindfolded i dont think you could tell the difference in the taste from the premium . { i am becoming quite a fan of yuengling as one might tell ]

a - clear light straw color with a thick white head that is very well retained ; leaves a nice lacing s - light malt aroma with a touch of hop and a slight amount of spicy phenols t - fairly clean malt with slight clove phenol aspect ; crisp , moderate bitter hop finish m - medium-light body with moderately high carbonation d - this is a drinkable beer , but not much past that .  smell has ton of spice upfront , with belgian yeast and banana . lots of pepper in the taste , which is great because i love pepper . nice bready malts with the belgian yeast flavour . a bit overcarbonated for my preference . this was n't hard at all to get through the bomber by myself .

wonderful hop and caramel aroma that i enjoy so much i could use it as an air freshener in my house .  a slightly over-caramelized ( read : burnt ) sweetness resurfaces on the finish , somewhat diminishing the overall enjoyability of the brew . the beers ' only weakness , a touch thin and yet over-carbonated at the same time . still , this is a winner from a rather uneven stable of beers from new holland . my only concern is how this came to be listed as a red ale ; it 's fucking brown ! ? !

a light brown to dark mahogany ale that pours with a voluminous , rocky off-white head .  mouthfeel : others have pointed out that nuova mattina falls short delivering a creamy mouthfeel . it is highly carbonated and too harsh .

the nose is amazing . it is highly carbonated ... not too much else .  careless dubbel brown colour with lazy , tall top of craterous tan . roman aquaduct upon aquaduct tiered glass crust ( angry ) is drawn in the residue . hops tighten the finish , but i do n't sense any hops varietal character . tea , syrup-soaked breads , dumpster-dived liquids , bad dreams ... it is a beer that shirts brew , hoping for approval from un-firable types , not knowing he/she is un-firable too .
smell is hoppy with cedar and citrus .  medium mouthfeel .

served in a tulip glass , the beer pours a cloudy straw gold color with a couple inch frothy white head that stays around for a long time .  m : smooth but it has a ton of carbonation which i 'm not a huge fan of .
the aroma is fantastic . roasted notes are prominent with chocoalte , and vanilla dominating .  m - restrained carbonation , a little thin in the mouth .

poured from a bomber into a perfect pint a- pours jet black with a one and a half finger tan colored head . head sticks around for awhile , lacing is awesome .  i think the mouthfeel is slightly thin , this was my only disappointment with it .
a : pours clear amber . looks tasty .  almost a medicine-y mouthfeel .

a- nearly opaque due to darker color , but good clarity on the edges head : big creamy head with a tan color to it . intense lacing .  ) sugary vibe starts coming through halfway through the bottle ... dms ? carbonation is a little high , getting in the way of the flavors somewhat . zaps the mouth with micro-explosions of the bubbly stuff . it 's one of the lighter , less demanding triples out theredespite my initial dislike of the near-champagne mouthfeel , im sure others will like that , and it only barely takes away from the drinkability .

a : pours a beautiful golden hued , deep pink color . a slightly off white two finger head . the head dissipates fairly quickly , but retains a nice foam cap for the duration of the glass . moderate lacing .  m- on the lighter side with lots of carbonation .

pours out a copper amber with a thick and sturdy frothy head that stays all the way down to the glass and leaves sheets of lace .  complex . looks like an ale , drinks like an ale , finishes like an apricot wheat . the first time i had this was in burlington vt with a plate of mussels . i could n't get over the intrigue of this brew . i totally forgot about the mussels until my second glass .

a - beautiful deep ruby-orange clear color , carbonation bubbles streaming upward . 2 finger foamy , slightly off white lasting head .  taste : sweet and funky but so refreshing . mouthfeel : lingering taste .

the thing i love about tripels is they always have interesting and unique scents . the taste is a bit more subtle , but it is fantastic .  3.0 m : lighter medium to medium body . carbonation is a bit too aggressive and further takes away from what is n't very creamy to begin with .

appearance : dark brown with a very brown head that abundantly fills the pint glass . it 's also long lasting , this beer looks like a champ .  there 's a strong taste of spices that sets the tone of the drink and towards the end of the mouthfeel it turns slightly bitter although all in all the beer feels fairly balanced .

lacing is superb but head retention is merely `` well above average . '' color is an opaque blackness that turns a reddish brown only when held up to the brightest lights at the thinnest portion of your glass .  m - really , really light mouthfeel , in a sense that it seems a bit thin .
smell : the nose was full of juicy , citrus hops right after the pour . not very complex , but still nice to sniff due to a full , round warmth .  m : yeah , i guess .
appearance - 5.0 two fingers of tight , mauve head sit above a dark , burgundy body . good head retention and left rings of sticky lace .  mouthfeel and carbonation are both slightly low .

a- cork shot off like champagne , pouring pitch black with an ever-growing tan head that retained well and left excellent retention .  taste was somewhat bitter , and more of the hops , with alcohol becoming more evident in both the aroma and taste at mid-glass . finish was slightly bitter aftertaste , but mostly smooth and a bit dry .

a- poured into my dogfish head snifter , this beer pours solid black with a big dark brown head that settles slowly and sticks around for the duration of the beer , leaving some blankets of lacing on the glass .  m - very light and crisp .

superior lacing & head retention s : bready with hints of brown sugar t : bready & fruitty ( dates ) with a little too much boozeyness up front .  was n't crazy about the mouthfeel of this beer though , as i felt it lacked significant carbonation and was a bit thin and lifeless .
nose is simply amazing for this beer . this one is underrated and worth seeking .  my first `` f '' rating here on ba .
nice puffy brown head that looks amazing . good head retention and lacing .  m : not too bad but a bit light for me .
pours jet black with a two finger khaki head .  has a nice cold mouth feel with a decent drinkability .

pours a golden color with great clarity and a huge white head .  this is one of those beers that drinks more like a wine than a beer . aged in wine barrels and carrying the flavors over into the finished product with a unique character added to the tartness of this beer . all the rr products are made to the highest of standards by one of craft beers true master brewers ! i recommend trying all their brews if you can get your hands on them..

pours a light hazy shade of dandelion tinted amber with a monstrous puffy , bright white head and massive visible carbonation .  light-bodied for the style and carbonation is a bit high . i do enjoy the smooth , creamy texture though .

blast of citrus , orange , pine , mango and some sweetness . wow , this is what a fresh ipa is supposed to smell like ! t - strong citrus , pine , resinous hops followed by a drying bitterness . solid malt backbone on the finish along with a hop oil sweetness . o - very solid dipa from surly albeit a tad sweet for my taste .  carbonation scrubs the tongue with perky bubbles ( almost too much , but not quite ) and has a medium-light body .

sweet citrus , fresh sliced oranges and tangerines hit the nose in the initial blast . later on it becomes more `` green '' and herbal , still extremely resiny and pungent . best belgian ipa i 've ever smelled ... though this one has a decidedly american slant .  m - i honestly could n't say .

wonderful . palate is hop floral with a acidic coffee chocolate . nice and tight and clean finish but not lager crisp but bombastic .  medium body , decently cleansing , very dry [ somewhat surprising ] .

pours a & gt ; 2cm head of cream-colored foam made up of fairly small bubbles . this gives the head a very dense , pillowy appeal to it . head descends gradually , but never fading completely ( remains a 0.5cm cap on the body ) leaving enormous amounts of lacing .  overall : very light bodied for the style , but very drinkable .

lot and lots of foam reminiscent of a soda more than a beer , but once gone , left great lacing . it feels a bit thin for a stout but you would never know it was eight percent .  b : medium body/average . notes : this is our only current 100 % organically made brew . hops and grains . this is one of my favorite local brews .

aroma is fantastic : huge notes of pine and herbal resin hit the nose and quickly give way to lush citrus and tropical fruits . a wonderful 'fresh hop ' aroma if i ever smelled it . the flavor 's no slouch , either , although the pungent whiffs of pine are traded for bitterness , and soft are the fruity hop flavors so prevalent in the nose . a bit slick and sticky at the same time , and the bitter finish lets you know those alpha acids are kicking . all in all , a fantastic beer from new belgium that i 'd consider to be in the top tier of their lips of faith program .  mouthfeel this beer is a bit thin for what i expect from an imperial stout .

thick fluffy head that slowly receded into a ring around the glass and left some decent lacing .  alcohol and bolder flavor peak at about 60 degrees m & d : pretty thin on the mouth and not as carbonated as you 'd expect based on the intense head .

aroma of strong carbonated peaches , fresh from a can-like . sweet syrupy taste , peaches and sugar . refreshing . does n't pair necessarily well with spicy pizza .  on the downside the mouthfeel was much fizzier than one would expect ... very thin , too .

lacing is tremendous . the head on this beer is magnificent , probably from the pour , but holds well regardless . beer is dark , dark brown with a light brown head .  this is not a beer for holding onto and chatting this is a beer for downing quick . when it heats up , the taste gets worse . there are alot better australian beers than this .

smell is a lovely hoppy bouquet , a lot of candied citrus rind , some florals , a bit of pineapple . good well-rounded hop but too astringent , the body is way too thin .  mouthfeel : medium bodied . low carbonation .

this beer pours a cloudy orange-amber color . the head is one inch of rocky eggshell white foam that recedes slowly into a firm cap of lacing .  m : thin to medium viscosity , resinous and sticky on the palate but lacking the heft of the other qualities , with moderate carbonation . the bitterness demands a little too much attention here , constraining its smoothness .

pours a brilliant orange with darker amber highlights , i am entranced by the bubble flow.. and quite a frothy head leaving chunks of substantial lacing behind .  smooth and not too powerful , ripened bananas and muffiny taste was not as dark as it looked , tastes of ripened fruit , sweet malts and hops would seem nearly obsolete if not for a brief tish of citrus fair amount of carbonation , bit of dryness , the finish was short and forgetful one of the easier brown ales to put back , not too sweet ( as many are ) the over 6 % abv is n't apparent so be careful , however i drank this before dinner so it went down exceptionally quickly .

poured into a pioneer stein ( # 42 , 2009 edition ) , formed a 2 1/2 '' frothy tan head over the slightly cloudy caramel hued brew . head falls slowly with an audible sizzle of bubbles bursting , with tons of lasting lace .  original rating date : september 4 , 2008 smells great , lots of light fruity , flowery aroma . pours a copper/amber with a bubbly head . taste reminds me a lot of sierra nevada 's brew . lots of light fruit , citrus , apricot , some peach . lots of malt , only a bit of hops . very good stuff here .
pretty clear golden color with a humongous white head . tons of stick here , crazy frothy , and overall just beautiful .  medium bodied , dry feel with not a lot of carbonation .

a - dark , dark brown allowing a mere hint of light through at the base of the pint . the head is substantial at two plus inches and maintains some very nice lacing .  body was reasonably light for the style . perhaps the aggressive carbonation helps with this .

the pour was a dark mahogany with a three finger head that very slowly dissapated and left a thick foam on top of the beer throughout the drink .  on tap at steamworks , the color got me really excited , straw yellowish . smell was decent and faintly sweet could not pick out anything in particular . taste was a little sweet for the style . overall its not a bad brew but there is n't anything that is very special in this one . would drink again but i 'm not going to be hunting it down by any means .

the foamy 2 '' tan head fades to a 1/2 '' trace and leaves bubbly lacing on the glass . this dark opaque beer reveals a red hue when held up to the light . by this time the head is gone but thick lacing remains .  m - thin , lo-carbonation , smooth and easy on the palette .
pours a light , hazy orange with a brilliant head . great lacing of thick and creamy eggshell goodness .  mouthfeel is a hint to the watery side , would have liked it a little chewier .
pours dark black with small off white head .  m : where it falls the shortest with a light-for-style body and overcarbonated .
aroma is potent with sweet citrus fruit -- smells like a hop bomb .  light bodied , with very light carbonation tingle on the roof of the mouth , and a slippery feel .
it looks as appealing as any beer i 've seen .  m~ moderately carbonated , a pretty light feeling beer .
very acidic , complex and enjoyable . t - begins a bit more watery than expected .  the mouthfeel is ok - just slightly under carbonated .

pours a cloudy orange color , with small tints of yellow . the carbonation on this ipa is insane . thousands upon thousands of bubbles streaming upwards . the head was also unusual for an ipa , massive bubbly white head 2 inches thick .  mouthfeel is thin with just moderate carbonation .

massive nose of sweet fruit and jam big soft pink head medium body - more than you would think smooth mouthfeel , slightly sticky sweetness great fruit forward flavor , just enough tartness to finish search it out and compare to the bottle .  nice scent , very bitter with some nice citrus and floral american hops , but with little of the nice sweet , clean red ale scent i expected to go with it . nice hoppy , pale-ale-type flavor , nice american hops , with enough malt to keep it near to balanced ; much hoppier than a regular red ale , but that was what they were going for . goes down fine , if a little rough from the slight unbalanced aspect . pretty darn hoppy for such a low abv red ale .

the aroma is very nice , toffee and butterscotch malt sweetness right off , maybe too much . metallic-roastie herbs over sweet bread . the sweet , butterscotch soaked bread also dominates the flavor , then comes a grain-alcohol and whiskey effect , not hot , very mellow and does not deliver a warming effect , only the flavor .  this one strikes me as kind of flat . needs a tad more carbonation and i think it would be leaps better than it is . nice creamy smooth mouthfeel though .
a- pours a hazy , luminescent orange liquid with a thick and craggy white head that has great retention .  the mouthfeel is ok , not its best feature .
appearance- pours a wonderful amber color with a solid one finger head that lasts forever .  mouthfeel is on the light side , but there is too much carbonation in this .

a- dark amber/gold with a nice white head that leaves perfect rings .  the taste was even worse , vinegar , old cardboard , just really gross . i do n't know if the keg was abused or really old but this was one sorry-ass beer . this was truly bad and i only finished it because i wanted to catch a buzz before my flight . i should have asked for a replacement .
big , dense , rocky head that takes forever and ever to settle down and leaves some big , chunky lacing .  of course . a little high in the effervescence .
from bottle to delirium tulip glass a : dark amber , clear , fluffy , foamy 2-inch head . small but thick patches of lacing .  mouthfeel is slick , but a little too thin .

i really wanted to like this , but i just ca n't do it ... a - stellar . dark thick brown/black , and i even managed to get an good tan brown head out of the pour despite the alcohol s - smells of pure sweetness , syrup , dark barley , coffee , chocolate , and a touch of the booze all together t - here 's where the `` no thanks '' comes in .  mouthfeel : light to medium body , creamy with just a little astringency .

i 've never had this on tap , and as such , feel that canned beer always has a metallic flavor the appearance is excellent with a nice cascade effect as it 's poured with an attractive clear copper color . good head retention as well .  lighter in body than i anticipated .

this beer has a sexy apperance , but is lacking in mouthfeel and taste . it has a wonderful head and is a very nice dark ruby , but something was missing when i tasted it .  this beer really needs to sit a while before the mouthfeel is anywhere near decent . when its freshly poured and a bit too cool , it 's thin and prickly , but just letting it sit a while and come closer to room temp. , it becomes a bit fuller and mellows out a bit . really drinkable ris that has tons of flavor and a decent mouthfeel , once it warms up .
smell is mega malty , sweet bread , hop & alcohol vapors . there 's some nice breadiness in there , and a slight hop bitterness & some alcohol in the finish .  m : very carbonated .

poured this into my pint glass it has a murky orange color with a freaking huge slightly off white 5inch head . lacing is scattered all over the sides of my glass , man oh man this beer looks fantastic .  the hop character , however , does n't overpower the malt and barely-there vanilla . m : not that noticeable to me , but certainly not offensive . the malty taste with a little bit of hops really helps the beer .

very fragrant and pumkin-like , this is see-through yellow body with lots of lace . the taste is primarily nutmeg and peppery , with less clove and ginger and so more enjoyable to me .  this is an above-average premium bitter that , with a little more body and a less watery mouth feel , might have been a masterpiece .

appearance - pours very dark with a faint redish brown and a creamy brown head .  a little grittiness in the texture . m - a little weird and overcarbonated for a porter . it would be better off less carbonated and as creamy as it appears .

perhaps it is the slight measure of wheat malt that gives this lager such a phenomenal head . and beneath this head sits a body of clear sunny yellow . a stunning visual array .  mouthfeel medium -light mouthfeel with prickly carbonation . a bit too carbonated for my taste in a mild , but not too far off .

this has exceptional retention and lacing , especially for the style/abv .  kinda liked this one , the guy at the beer store said the bottle was sitting there for awhile but it held up great.real hazy-orange color with a good head , smelled fresh and citriusy , body was a little thin to me for the style.refreshing taste with some citrius-yeast note very easy to drink.i also think this would be a good warm weather ale .

normally , i avoid boulder beer products , but the price was too good to pass up . pours a solid finger of tan head over a crystal clear orange-brown liquid .  mouthfeel was decent but a bit thinner/watery than i would have liked .

thin , low on flavor , but undeniably sessionable irish dry ___ a : matte black body with dingy ruby highlights topped with a very persistent one finger extremely creamy buff head . the well-known reverse cascade effect is beautiful to behold .  unfortunately , the flavor and mouthfeel do n't fully deliver on what the aroma suggested . this is still a tasty beer but it 's a bit thinner than i hoped for and has a much stronger roast presence than i prefer .

( a ) - pours a cloudy pale blush red color . produced a great frothy off-white head that is clinging to the glass with great retention .  s. rich brown sugar , molasses and smoke t. quite complex with molasses , roasted malt , smoke , brown sugar , cinnamon and clove in the front with a touch of hops in the back m. surprisingly clean , with lingering malt behind medium carbonation d. very drinkable for anyone who likes malt i first tried this beer at a local liquor store 's beer tasting . this is a great example of a fall seasonal for the relaxed craft drinker .

tasted in mid-march 2009. golden straw with slight haze . moderate head is foamy , and developes really nicely on the second pour . fades to thin layer . very good lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and the finish is a little odd tasting .
pours a light copper/gold with a big creamy off-white head .  feels a bit thin , where creamier and chewier would 've done the trick .

pours a deep mahogany , almost red , with a very foamy head .  an astoundingly good dark beer for the price : 10 bucks for a 12-pack at wegmans in state college , pa . it brings some of the unique flavors found in yuengling porter to a slightly lighter beer , but make no mistake ; the stuff is not weak . it might not be the most delicious beer on the planet , but the combination of good flavor and low price are unbeatable for me as a beer-enthusiast college student ( not a drunkard ! ) everyone else has described the taste well enough . my review is mainly economic .

interesting that the smell is so complex and the mouth is so intermixed .  m- not a bad mouthfeel i just felt it to be average . light on the tongue , a little too dry and yet somewhat of a lingering aftertaste .
black color with a brown head that retains well and has excellent lacing .  the mouthfeel is average , medium-bodied , watery ( even slightly oily ) in texture , with soft carbonation .
pure black in color and laces the glass very well . wonderful looking beer .  fairly light bodied and easy drinking .
dense and creamy head .  m : carbonation comes on unexpectedly crisp , but it drinks smoothly .
fresh oily hop aroma of grapefruit and fresh orange-juice .  m : medium body with hardly any carbonation d : drinks good all the way thru that makes it seem like winter in the summer .

pretty unique , alluring .  split with the wife at the eccentric cafe in kalamazoo , michigan . looks like a wheat beer with absolutely no odor coming off the brew . very , very wheaty , to the point of being a bit of a turn off . more cherry & less wheat would have been a better combo , methinks . this got actively unpleasant as it warmed - the aftertaste was a killer .

a - orange/gold , looks like a sunrise in the pint glass . overall , looks great , smells great , i just do n't think i got the flavor they were going for .  aroma of allspice , nutmeg , figs , apples , leathery yeast , and pepper . flavor of dark fruits including plums and cassis . slightly sour . palate lacks expected richness . good but not great like the previews ( appearance and aroma ) lead you to believe .

bomber poured into tulip glass a : wow ! this one is a sight to see . pours with a huge khaki colored head , that reduces slowly and leaves nice full cap on top . tremendous lacing . impressive .  ( m ) - a very high carbonation level .

pours a deep and dark opaque dark brown/black , no light gets through , very thick brown head forms , drops to a thick ring and layer leaving a ton of lacing , huge sheets on the glass , great retention , looks pretty awesome .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel on this beer is kind of harsh , due to the huge amount of hops and alcohol .
amazing head retention .  mouthfeel is a little thin with very little carbonation .
a really beautiful beer to look at .  m - medium body , could use more carbonation given that they went for more of a standard strong ale vs a true winter brew d - very drinkable .
on tap at `` flavor '' in santa rosa ... a good pour , the beer arrived with a thick , sticky white head over a clear , deep gold ale .  medium body , but maybe a bit thin , moderate carbonation .
this really released the great smells with this beer . the nose is spicy greatness .  the mouthfeel is low carbonated almost syrupy , not what i expected .
very nice appearance .  the mouthfeel is light bodied , but a little thicker than i would expect from a beer with such little taste and aroma .

the smell was very nice , piney spicy hops with a sweet buttery biscuit note .  the aroma is hoppy and earthy with some fruity notes , reminds me a bit of orval in this sense . the flavor has a nice character of fruity hopes and a mild malt sweetness , but the beer is dominantly dry . there is a very mild tartness here but generally the beer is dominated by a blend between some spicy yeast notes and pleasant hop bitterness .

the fine and dense head got smooth and aired and it lasted nicely on the hazy and active golden color body .  m - medium bodied with higher than average carbonation . it looks and feels a little chalky .
attractive foam/lacing s - love the aroma . it 's like a chocolate covered banana .  fairly dry with ample carbonation and a lighter body . a bit coarse in texture .

the smell is fantastic . it is fruity , chocolatey , toffee , tobacco , cocoa , raisin bread , apricot , plum , and pudding . it 's interesting .  m - medium body with a pretty smooth texture , but mouthfeel is a little thin for a porter . body is a little thin , but the aromas and flavors are quite pleasant .

the prototypical stout color that i love , deep brown to ebony , the head impressive , the consistency creamy , the lace a latticework to coat the glass .  the body is light and the carbonation is very high .
appearance : deep brown with a large head with good retention .  a good pale and pretty cheap . $ 4.99 a six and 5 buck pitcher specials are easily had . full flavored and nicely hopped w/goldings .

a : beautiful nearly black with milk chocolate brown edges and a baking german chocolate cake head , 2-3 fingers , with prodigious amounts of lace .  very easy to drink ! it has the feel of any other wheat beer , but the watermelon taste is so unique that it simply floored me . initially , i thought the color seemed very artificial which made me expect an artificial flavor . there is little up front beyond a generic wheat beer , but in the aftertaste lies a brilliant watermelon flavor ! it is easy to drink and not very filling . it is slightly more alcoholic than your run of the mill macrobrews making it possible to drink a great many of these at any given time . it 's a good beer to give to new beer drinkers . it 's an excellent example of how diverse craft beers can be !
smells wonderfully citrusy with some tropical fruit smells coming out a bit . nice and dank , this one is .  thin in the mouth , which leads to great drinkability . would make a good session beer .

however the smell is terrific : a slight hint of maple syrup , and a great dose of hop aroma - i 'm guessing fuggles .  taste malty upfront a touch hop metal finish . not very heavy rather light on the carbs . this beer really scratched my spring beer itch .
a- a dark drown , with the head lasting for a good 5 minutes . looks great in the glass .  one slight criticism is a somewhat lighter mouthfeel - thinner than i would expect .

s - coffee , mostly . i was expecting more pronounced flavor , but i 'm kinda taken aback by this odd flavor ... overall , the appearance and the smell of this beer is great , but the taste is off .  a smoked lager from fort collins brewery . 1.0 liter bottle for $ 8.29 . i was somewhat skeptical about this beer especially because i thought there two other beers edgar and doktor were an abomination , but i opted for it and was it ever worth it ! a slight smokinness stimulates the nose as well as some alcohol , caramel and citrus hops . the palate was dominated with notes of butterschotch , smoked malts , cedar , citrus notes , light fruits and the flavor was very lingering on the palate . i did polish off a 1.0 so obviously this brew was pretty damn drinkable !

smells of fresh-baked bread -- specifically , reminds me of the parish-baked communion bread we would eat after church when i was a kid . dissecting the smell reveals some lightly toasty & toffee malts & earthy hops that all add up to this one evocation . pie crust emerges later . the rare non-ipa where the smell is significantly better than the taste . good , & i love that it evokes that specific sense memory , but the booze character is a turn-off .  m - i 'm finding myself rather indifferent towards the mouthfeel .

12oz bottle poured into a tulip glass . pours a dark brown color with a 2 finger creamy tan head made up of little bubbles with great retention , yeast floating around in the glass .  aggressive fizzy carbonation .

the color is really fantastic on this one , a deep reddish brown with a fantastic , yet thin , layer of head that does n't quit .  crisp malts , light fruits and near indiscernible hops all float to the nose . a bit dry going down with some malts , a surprising hoppiness , and a good , somewhat delayed fruit hit at the end . light-bodied and highly drinkable , but still tasty , which is what i look for in a good summer sessioner .

a-deep brown with some reddishness . big tan head on this one . quite the lovely looking beer .  i just think it 's amazing what ab will do to make a quick buck . hopefully this will quickly go into the grave along with new coke and chrystal pepsi .

550 ml bottle , marked sg13b1 , poured into a pint glass apours solid black with a 2 inch dark tan fluffy head that slowly falls down to a pillow top that floats on top , lacing looks like swiss cheese . beautiful .  mouthfeel : at first slightly carbonated but then becomes smooth . one thing though , it kind of stays in your mouth for a while .

hazy gold with ample foamage : sudsy but also merengue-ey spicy , minty hop aroma . very spicy . minimally spicy , which is interesting , given the highly potent aromas .  it was a bit thin on mouthfeel , but the aromas & wheaty , yeasty taste more than made up for this .

good pristine golden color with some seriously fluffy head .  it has a surprisingly thin body for such a bourbon and malty beast . also the carbonation is a bit higher then i would like for the style .
smell is roasty and rich , hints of chocolate .  mouthfeel is medium to full-bodied .

pours beautiful as a stout should with a fuzzy active milk chocolate colored three finger head . body sets in the glass like a big black opal .  pretty average looking . somewhat listless and a touch thin although i would imagine that it could translate better on cask .

the beer is quite aromatic , with sweet honeysuckle complimented by a tart citrus character ( mostly oranges ) . disappointing , after the overall high caliber of this brewery 's other beers and the awesome aroma . i poured most of it down the drain .  the body is bit off with a moderate to fuller body . good carbonation .

the malt was complex and interesting . the beer was quite fruity with no particularly distinguising fruit but more the fruity aromas found in a fruitcake , a complex mixing of aromatics .  nose ... oh , that great `` red '' smell ... hops and spice with some sweentess thrown in for good measure , west coast floral represented well , just a great pleasant hop aroma caresed by cinnamon.. delish.. mouth etc ... carbonation then the real bite of spice and hops , a little watery at times but the flavor is fantastic , refreshing and crisp as it gets toward the end of the glass.. very enjoyable verdict ?
smell is domainated by a tart raspberry balanced by a sweet mocha coffee bitterness . very bold aromas linger in the back of the nose .  m - carbonated ... a little too much actually .

m-thick chewy thorough coating of the mouth o-good beer with exceptional aroma that does n't completely carry over to its flavor .  m - very thick and full . very prickly and effervescent in the mouth - too thick to be a soda , but the carbonation is quite reminiscent . high carbonation is the only detractor to drinkability .

served in an imperial pint glass from a 22 oz bomber bottle a- black as night with an off white head very nice s- roasted hops and coffee t- very nice roasted hop taste with a deep coffee flavor and a clean finish .  m- thin to medium body- highly attenuated- with a coarse carbonation which delivers a slightly bloating feeling . could stand to have some softer carbonation .
tons of pine and with mangoes and other tropical fruits . smells great . taste .  mf : there could be a bit more of a body to back up the full flavor of this beer .

smell : rich coffee aroma .  mouthfeel : i 've never been a big fan of the body of almost all american porters as they just seem thin , a tad watery , and big on carbonation , and this one does n't break that trend .

looks : irrepressible . the beer pours a lovely light mahogany with hues of dark orange tippling about . i let the beer warm for a good ten minutes and the head does n't even budge . spotted lace in varied shapes and sizes , from tracks to webs to full sheets .  saison du buff appearance- very hazy golden , lively white head that dissipates quickly.4 smell- hops - green buds to the max 5 taste- wow . delicious . sweet and citrusy but with huge hop and wheat finish.complex balanced . spicy nutmeg 5 mouf- easy 3 drinkable - oh so drinkability 4

aroma is heavy malt ( cookie , meal ) , average hops ( perfume , grass ) , heavy yeast ( barnyard , earth ) with notes of plum , apple , pear , and ginger . medium bodied , sticky texture , lively carbonation , and a bitter finish .  on-tap at surfrider caf in santa cruz , ca . on to the beer : there 's is n't much life to the look of this beer . the hops have a dull bitterness and a green veggie flavor . lemongrass notes all around , but especially in the aftertaste . pale malt sweetness is not found easily . very `` raw '' , but in a bad way . even compared to the regular bmc 's , american standard fails to even meet that . i struggled to finish my pint , but at least it only cost me $ 2 .

nose was milk , creme , coffee and vanilla beans .  this is a good straightforward ale . light golden yellow color , a little fizzy but nothing a little harder pour into the glass did n't take care of . lighter flavor but has a nice balance for whats there . nice little hop background that comes through the nose.it 's drinkable also .
the nose is pure amarillo hops .  this porter is a little watery .

s : strong smell of resin and caramel malt , pine dominates . t : pine bitterness whacks you when you first taste the brew , with a strong caramel malt presence as well .  the mouthfeel on a doppelbock is a tricky thing -- too thick and you wo n't be able to drink your half-liter bottle , let alone your full liter mass .
toasted coffee & touches of chocolate on nose . gentle upfront , dry nut bitterness & subtle sweetness .  tastes great , but the mouthfeel is a lot thinner than i 'd like for the style .

aroma is promising , with plums , apricots , some yeasty mustiness , and alcohol . i spent over an hour with this one trying to find some qualities i find attractive , other than its fine nose . i suppose it is a fine winter warmer , with the high abv , but the port wine aftertaste does n't endear me very much .  the mouthfeel was thin-to medium with a lightly smoky taste on the palate .
appearance - a hazy/cloudy amber beer with a big head that stiicks for a while and leaves a lot of lacing .  mouthfeel : on the lighter side , lots of carbonation .
appearance : about as dark as you can imagine a beer looking .  overall mouthfeel is okay , but not great . it numbs my tongue a bit ( and not because i 've overchilled it ; i have n't ) .
pours a cloudy golden hue with a big fluffy white head , that really stands up .  it finishes very clean with a hint of carbonation lingering on the palate .
appearance : really nice looking porter .  only bummer part , was a bit too thin and carbonated .
the aroma was very appealing , however , garnering it a 4.5 because of its freshness .  mouthfeel is tough .

a great dark lager that reminds me of yuengling porter when it was made at the old brewery . the color is dark and when poured into a glass creates a nice white/gray head .  m- a thin body- highly attenuated with a nice spritzy non-bloating carbonation .

a - looks quite nice , with a ample off-white head that settles to a persistent thick cap , leaving behind glass-coating lace .  m : the body was actually not terrible , medium , we 'll say . and the carbonation was moderate as well .

one of the best shades i 've seen with a great head to go along with it .  appearance : high carbonation , 1/4 inch head , cloudy , yellowish-green smell : wheat , and melon taste : very watermelon -- almost like a watermelon jolly rancher , bready wheat , with some small hops near the end mouthfeel : sweet , light/smooth body , high carbonation , slight bitter taste in the end .

the aroma is exceptional , and the bourbon notes are packed with vanilla , dark fruits ( raisin , fig , orange peel ) , and a touch of chocolate . i would have liked there to be a touch more chocolate n this one , too , but its still a fantastic beer . in my book schlafly is 2-for-2 with big , bourbon-aged beers , as their barleywine reserve was equally as impressive .  mouthfeel great carbonation . perhaps a little thin , but not a detraction . a bit sticky on the aftertaste .
looks and smells great . light orange , clearish pour .  a nice well put together beer that is easy drinking with medium carbonation and a light body .

nelson is west coast ipa incarnate , and i 'm just talking about the aroma : fresh pine needles and citrus rind pair up to wallop the nostrils something fierce . with the freshness of a dryer sheet and the hops sizzling off this thing in waves , there 's nothing not to like about the aroma here . there 's a spiciness to the flavor that points to the rye used ; it 's an earthy and very bright graininess , electrified by the nelson sauvin hops that give it even more vividness . bitter , vinous , earthy , bright , spicy and fruity , all in equal measure .  not your typical ipa , but you could call it a great hoppy amber with a very fruity , floral melon ball hop character . maybe it 's bitter like an east coast ipa , but the moutfeel does n't stand up to most california ipas . still , there was a bit of balance with bready , toasted

smell is phenomenal . pine , citrus , pepper , faint banana , bready malts , and hints of alcohol backed sweetness . i love arrogant bastard and thought this would be spectacular after smelling it but that was n't the case . it was good , no doubt , i just expected better .  medium-high carbonation prickles the tongue , feels heavier than it looks .
nice tan head with amazing retention .  taste and mouthfeel : medium bodied , mid level carbonation .

with a moderate pour this hazy copper colored brew gives a nice 1 '' of hearty light tan head that creates craters and thick globby lace as it slowly slowly settles . great retention and great lace .  and a bit thin d-easy and enjoyable , drinks almost like a session ale .

it poured ebony black . with a thin white head that dissipated .  m : it doesnt give the mouth a longlasting tingle that some ipa 's give but gives a tasty coat on your mouth that lasts and gives the chocolate taste as well .
appearance : pours a good lucking translucent to clear amber with a moderate head and quick dissipation .  mouthfeel : extremely light feel considering the alcohol and massive aroma .
bottled on 12/15/11 this beer is dark , darkest head i have seen .  smooth light finish . good flavor and average abv .

the aroma is musty and lemony with a distinct dry oaky backbone . some nutty earthiness as well . the flavor is muddled and oaky ... very unique . as a huge fan of gueuze and all things lambic , i really love to get a chance to sample the building blocks . i probably would n't buy it again other than as an experiment in long term aging , but nonetheless i highly recommend this to anyone even if it is merely a way to learn to appreciate the sheer beauty and art of gueuze blending .  mouthfeel has definitely lost some over the years unfortunately , its almost still and lacks life .

bottle courtesy of hopdog : poured a light amber color lager with a super huge foamy head with great retention and lacing .  mouthfeel : a little high on the carbonation and not as thick as i 'd prefer with a stout .
very enjoyable .  body was a smidgen thin , but it held the 8 % back quite well , i knew it was more that 5 % , but thats what i perceived from this great brew .

appearance - perfect looking stout .  on tap the the brewery . all american hops . pungant and resiny . big hop flavor with rye spicyness . caramel , and good bitterness . quite dry and refreshing . my first founders beer every . pretty happy so far .

aroma is outstanding . everything that is good about hops with a little backdrop of sweet malt . the bitterness is actually pretty scathing for an ipa . jagged and rough .  they float the lemon in the beer , so you do n't have a chance to yank it out before it imparts flavor . great example of the heffeweizen style , with banana and clove aroma and flavors . a light beer that can be quaffed in copious amounts .

smell : wow ! bright grapefruit & a smell of pure freshness , like walking through the woods after a light rain . it 's not the complexity of the notes in the aroma or whatever , but the overall vivacity & `` nosefeel '' that makes this so awesome . bitter & citric in the taste , piny , woody . bitter almost to the point of satiation , but inviting .  it feels a bit thin and overly carbonated for a strong english ale .

smells glorious . definately a unique mixture of piney citrus and floral hops . very enjoyable . mouthfeel : a tad tart and carbony with a big soda style bite followed by big hop oilyness .  m - interesting flavors dance around but actual feel is pretty standard light ale d - fun , interesting , pairs well with peppery steak or cheese , not too strong .

clear cherrywood bronze with a tight-cropped bleached-khaki foam that retains and laces equally well .  smells quite strongly of roasted coffee beans . if you chilled an espresso drink and made it into beer , this is how it would smell . then , this transitions into a bit of a licorice taste ... .finishing with what i would classify as an odd citric acid tangy sourness that 's quite pronounced and just seems out of place . my verdict here is that it has a great aroma and starts decent enough ... but in the end , i 'm turned off by what i 'd consider to be `` off flavors '' for a stout .

mmmm ... coffee , mmmmm ... . the lace is definitely forming in rings to my glass here , pretty good head retention for something with whole mexican coffee beans . i heard it 's really hard to pull off , the aroma here is primarily in your face eye opener of coffee beans , a whiff of chocolate tones , dark roasts , and a very light hop aroma is hidden in there . the aroma is the best thing this beer 's got going for it .  low , easy-going carbonation .

some roast , some background sweetness , a bit of that typical oatmeal stout smell , a real nice sweetness in the background .  m : medium body and carbonation . it is a little sticky . some sharpness on my tongue as i swallow .

it pours to a dark golden amber color with a few continuous jetstreams of bubbles rising to the top to support the delicate off-white head .  carbonation is just a bit higher than i like ... .and the liquid is a bit think to be really pleasing . a bit more body would be a good thing .
i was really excited to try this beer but was definitely let down . the appearance and smell are what you would expect from a stout , dark and coffee like .  it somewhat lingers on your tongue .
big foamy off white head , good retention . bright reddish copper in color .  taste-taste 's like water . mouthfeel-very light , crisp .
laced nicely . smell - pine needles with a hint of pears .  palate is a little cloying from the fruity sugars , but ends dry . finishes with a parching pinesness and slick fruit punch .

pours an almost copper color with about 1 finger of firm foamy head that left a strip of lacing on the glass after each sip . interestingly when i finished the beer the glass was perfectly striped with left over lacing .  the body seemed a bit light , and maybe a bit more weight would have made it more satisfying , but that 's a minor quibble .

smell is sweet and very fruity , scents of fig , apple , tobacco brown sugar , rum , brandy , raisins , and dates . extremely complex , too much really , it is like a mouth full of fruit juice concentrate .  m - not bad , but a little thinner than i was hoping for .

pours a clear golden yellow with a monsterous tower of head that engulfs much of the glass and one of the thickest walls of lacing i have ever seen . perfect pale ale appearance , probably the best i 've ever seen for the style .  the looks are not deceiving , in that this beer goes down very easy . the finish is semi-clean with a hint of flavor left on the tongue . p.s . i like this beer better on tap than from the bottle !

smell is very nice , candi sugar and fruit , rum . taste has a bit of the fruit and dark malt , with a strange type of molasses-like syrupy flavor , a bit artificial .  body is a bit lacking , it 's creamy carbonated but a bit light , almost like a light porter or english stout .

the aroma was amazingly sweet , smooth , rich and creamy with a robust coffee presence . on smell alone , i might have mistaken this beer for a rich and complex oatmeal stout . this beer had an aroma that was to die for , yet the flavor profile was far too acrid for my palate .  the only disappointing part is the mouthfeel , which was more thin than i would have liked .

perfectly pictured stout pour -- jet black , no light peering through , dark tan everlasting head with perfect lacing -- from this season 's ( 2005-2006 ) version .  mouthfeel is average , not much to say one way or the other , except , i guess it was smooth .

it pours a stunning clear amber color with a tightly bubbled white head .  i really enjoy the smell of this beer . i do n't know where you buy the nitro-release cans but i 'd like to know . i bought this in texas but i forgot where . apparently this beer can not be bought in kansas so i 'm glad i tried it . i made the mistake of trying this beer when it was cold .

lacing is decent , but i *hate* the way the beer looks ... most of the mikkeller single hops are real cloudy like this , and i do n't like it at all s- the hops smell really sweet and juicy , and the smell is pretty strong and nice ... kind of reminds me of jello . nevertheless , it 's awesome . t- a little sweet .  mouthfeel was a bit too thin and a bit overcarbonated .
not sure how i felt about this one ... poured a beautiful black into a simple glass mug .  m - well balanced , but thin and slightly sweet . was hoping for a medium to full-bodied saison .

a very nice aroma . low carbonation , slick and buttery in the mouth .  light carbonation and light-medium bodied . starts almost sweet but hops dominate , boring , finish is dry and slightly bitter . brewed aug 12 , 2005 . $ 1.79 for a 330ml bottle from lina 's beverages painesville , oh .

1 inch tan foamy head and great retention and some sticky lacing smell : sweet caramel and roasted malts blend together very well to create a nice sweetness .  m- mouth is a little on the light side for a stout .

appearance is an inviting cloudy golden yellow with an outstanding pillow head and great lacing .  shortfalls are slightly thin , flattens out fast , washing out the complexity , and slight sour aftertaste -- which is fleeting . but perfect balance is why i give this super-smooth coffee-style beer a high rating .

thx kev pale orange and clear , nice and cold . lots of bubbles ascending quickly . creamy and dense head that finds its happy place at a slight but thorough coating . uniform , tight lacing . looks light and crisp .  excellent flavor , with a great two-row maltiness up front and a great pine and semi-citrus hop flavor at the end that sticks . there is a bit of hop roughness to the beer that hurts the finish , but it 's still not bad going down .
s- aroma of yeasty dough , spices , cloves , banana , cavendish pipe tobacco .  m- much too thin for the style and something this big .

this beer looks gorgeous in the glass ( which unfortunately was frosted ) rich black body with a frothy tan head that sticks around .  m & d -- mouthfeel was only average as i felt it stung a little more , was a bit more astringent , than i would have expected .
nose of ginger and honey , with hints of sweet apple .  finish is medium length , texture is smooth , but this feels thin in the mouth for an imperial stout .

a light brown very fluffy head with a dark brown body with mahogany light coming through . good lace left on the inside of the glass . interesting , inviting . i really appreciated the look of this beer but the smell , taste , feel and drinkability were like many other more readily available beers in this area from great lakes brewing company .  the hops are n't super astringent and they finish well . mouthfeel : medium-bodied .

thanks to sheepnutz for this tasty brew ... it was sampled in a glass chalice appearance : pours a deep amber with an airy off-white head that lasts during the entire session , and laces incredibly down the glass .  little helper is a good beer . defining it is a bit difficult , i would call it a hoppy but light ( er than normal ) red ale . very drinkable . nearly no head . good beer , but the malt flavor is not very interesting , and not pronounced considering the color . but i am a hop fan so that is just fine . all around great , hoppy , and drinkable red . wish rogue made less expensive beer !

bottle poured a very dark amber with a large off white head that stuck to the glass .  as mentioned before , my only knock is the carbonation and mouthfeel . this is a great beer , i just think it could be even better with a softer and thicker mouthfeel .
pours nearly black and opaque with a huge dense dark brown head .  m- kinda thin , but full of great flavors that wrap around your tongue .
exceptional retention .  m : nice carbonation ... but a slight gritty feel .
poured a beautiful deep amber with a tiny head .  mainly a flattish mouthfeel .

s - i love this aroma ! a lot of 'outdoor ' aromas , including a straw-like yeast character and musty hops , but somehow retains a vibrant nose . overall , a very impressive beer .  m : very light carbonation but there is just a bit to give the beer some levity .
s- very wonderful aroma here . very nice hop smells come from this .  feels too carbonated and light in the mouth . just an average mouthfeel though , not too bad .

big tan head than retains . s-hard to really get a good whiff past the giant head . not a very intense head .  maybe this was chilled too much but it seems to have a little too much bite , which might also be the carbonation .

poured into a snifter , the brew appears black in color with the faintest line of clarity and brown around the edges . a dark brown finger of head appears and as it slowly recedes , leaves spots and a webbing pattern of lace . a swirl revives a full finger worth of dark brown head .  sharp and light bodied .

smell : heavy on the blackberries . just one notch lower is a beautiful lemon-infused sweet-bread tone . very good mix here . a deceiving nose , as the taste is mostly grass and stale bread .  again , this beer was a bit thin for my taste .

in part this was because i was hoping it would be a belgian pale ale , not an apa , but in part also it is simply because tis is a rather standard , and very one-dimensional , bland apa anyway . clear , bright , dark gold , it has a big off-white head slowly shrinking to a thin , lasting foamy top and some nice lace .  huge pine and citrus blast . a bit too abusive in the feel for me . a beer for the s & m crowd , i guess . i 'm not too sure many people would want to pound these given the bitterness and tongue numbingness ( though i 'm sure i 'd do just that if this were available here ) .

extrememly frothy and creamy . leaves large chunks and patches behind . a nice lightly clouded golden colored pour .  m-a little thinner in the body than i expected , but does n't ruin it by any means .
it pours with a large white head ; lots of lace and good retention .  body is on the light side , ends acidic and dry .
the scent is delicious with a mildly sweet and flavorful burst of hazelnut .  carbonation is a little bit higher than i prefer .

batch # 7 , pours a hazy orange/copper color with a huge pillowey , sticky head.aroma is very light somewhat musty and a little earthy not that great , taste is very subtle some light citruis tones and some biscuit malt in the finish but very subtle.seems to be pretty food friendly because it does not over power good with some grilled chicken a nice beer for summer but it wont overpower you in flavor thats for sure .  its has a light mouth feel for a stout .
this sammy pours a bright clear golden orange with a pretty big , rocky white head .  m : mouthfeel is a tad thin and , possibly , a little overcarbonated .

sediment free with fluffy , airy head that stuck like glue to the glass s-huge hop resin protruded at first pour . a deeper smell unveiled the heavy citrus and piney layers . awesome ! t-candy-sweet with a big hop finish .  mouthfeel : murky and low on carbonation . 4.0 mouthfeel : better carbonation than the batch 1 but still fairly moderate which is fine for this style .

the head is a very large frothy , foamy monster ! lots of lacing .  12 oz . bottle into a samuel adams boston lager glass . a- beer s- watermelon t- watermelon beer mf- beer d- served ice cold on a hot summer day , great . one or two is probably enough . lives up to the boast on the label , `` strangely refreshing . '' unpalatable if not cold .

appearance is promising ... the rich dark chocolate color you 'd expect with a minimal top head and thick , light brown lacing that sticks stubbornly to the glass before breaking up into thousands of tiny bubbles and dissolving .  i would have expected a little more body in this beer . a little skinny for my tastes .

truly one of the best looking beers i have even seen ! a nice , light amber colour with tiny , delicate little bubbles flowing into a rock-like head .  the mouthfeel is a bit on the thin side for a stout .
smell : this beer has a very sweet and fruity aroma . you can also smell some of the malts .  the disappointing : wow , what a highly carbonated brew , almost champaign in the fizziness .

smell : a metric boatload of hops . loads of juicy citrus - orange and grapefruit dominate , and sweet fruit hop notes.the hop aroma is backed by some caramel notes . this is a rock solid dipa aroma . taste : loads of hops with a drying quality wash over my tongue . behind all the hops is a nice caramel/biscuit backbone . nonetheless this a tasty dipa .  mouthfull - not very thick tasting , watery would be a better word to describe this . very freshing beer . very well rounded beer , i 'm not that fond of the mouthfeel as it seems to be sometimes a tad to watery but overaul its a good beer .
smell - nice floral hop aroma . very faint pine notes .  a bit thin in the mouthfeel but nothing off-putting .

s : nice nose ! zesty with near tropical aromas . the first sniff was hop heaven . a little bit of orange and pineapple and pine and peach . t : the first sip , unfortunately , loses all of the goodwill that the nose generated . a vegetal hoppiness runs rampant , no hint of the lush citrus aromas . ample caramel , plenty of the malt side , to go around . it 's good but not as good as it smells .  mouthfeel is not quite as full as it could be , but still does a good job delivering and distributing flavor around the mouth .

upon pouring the 2002 edition of the doggy claws , it poured a golden honey color w/ a 2 1/2 inch to 3 inch head which stayed very frothy and heavy , and clinged to the side of the glass for quite some time while i had it in my glass .  the mouthfeel seems a tad too watery as well .
pours a super clear magnifying fiery orange/red . a modest off white to tan head is bubbly from the the profile and creamy up top .  mouthfeel : a little thin , but not bad .

s- like very strong , fresh brewed coffee . its one of the most pungent scents i 've ever whiffed from a beer , and it really does n't hide what its going to taste like . awwwwesome t- the smell does n't lie about what the taste is ... it highly coffee influenced . really nice feel .  this harp was brewed in canada by moosehead . this is a very satisfying beer ; especially when all the over-hopped , over-malted , extreme productions . become too much ... which is the true beauty of this harp . it is straight forwardly flavorful without making great demands on the palate . lively with a clean finish . this is the first harp i have sampled in a few years , and is easily the most tasty i have ever encountered .

a - pours a nice fluffy , two finger head with an off yellow body that is hazy and carbonated .  i would recommend this beer both as a meal beer and a drinking man 's beer , versatile and a solid wheat ... not too fruity , but not to plain ... too carbonated , but i imagine a great american/bavarian weisse on tap .
this foggy light honey colored brew gives an appealing 1 '' of dense ivory foam .  light bodied and hardly any carbonation to speak of .

impressive head is like a cloud . beautiful looking beer .  i was not impressed with the finish at first , in that it was slightly watery . however , as beer warmed at mid-glass , palte was much more full and smooth , and the alcohol gave a warming sensation on the way down .

aroma is killer , sweet , smooth smelling with floral fruity notes .  a pleasant flavor but it 's hard to pinpoint what citrus flavors are making their way though m- carbonation was a little overbearing the first few sips , but the remainder of the beer had a nice , slightly creamy mouthfeel o- a bit more carbonated than i like my ipas , but it 's hard to hold that against what 's an exceptional beer from cigar city .

tawny pumpkin color with a splendid off-white head . great retention and insane lacing , sheets of foam everywhere .  tart up front , with ample carbonation clinging to bitter noble hops . mouthfeel is medium bodied with a lingering puckering finish . a decent overall tripel here .

beautiful nose t - great complex flavor comprising smoked meats , dark fruits and apples and various barrels .  i thought i did n't like saisons until i tried this one . kind of a mild coconutty taste , almost pina colada like ? i 'm going to revisit this one for sure whenever i get a chance .
truly amazing . t : follows the nose .  watery feel for a stout but with just enough body to get you through .

poured from a bottle to a tulip has a great clear copper orange body . the head is pretty large and chunky and leaves nice lacing .  m : sharp at first , fizzy , but lights up as you hold it . still , a bit strong and that cuts down on how much you can have . d : i had 10oz with no problems , but a second might have gotten bothersome due to the fizz .

the white , fluffy head is a good inch thick when poured and has very nice lacing . head settles to a good 1/4 inch and then does n't go away . good retention !  m- even though it is lighter with the smoke , i still think that it could use more malt body .
the smell it good . a rather fresh smell to a beer i thought would smell bitter .  silky smooth in the mouth while maintaining a very lively carbonation ... .just amazing .

a : pitch black with only a hint of light that passes at the edge of the glass , wispy head , looks like charcoal , minimal carbonation noticeable - 3.50 , s : espresso and bakers chocolate , solid charring and ash aromas , some milk/lactose sweetness in the background - 4.50 , t : the espresso on the nose carries through on the palate , dark fruits , lots of specialty grains including chocolate malts , hint of smoke - 2.75 , m : a little grittiness but on the side of thin especially for an imperial stout - 2.50 , d : i enjoyed this beer but in the ranks of imperial stouts it falls short , worth a taste but probably not worth the cad $ 3.00 .  wonderful feel .
nose is a perfect balance of malt pollen , floral hop , and citrus fruit .  mouthfeel is outstanding . the extreme thickness adds to the buttery flavors and is really a high point of the experience .

taste is very fruity with noticable carbonation , not much actual beer taste here the mouthfeel is this beers weakpoint , it 's very thin and almost tea-like , i was hoping for a fuller body to go with the fruitiness the aroma was the best part of this beer , it was not bad by any means but could have been much better with a bit more body imho .  perfect carbonation for the style .
poured a rich 3 finger head , blacker than the blackest black times infinity .  high carbonation . probably the silkiest body in a dipa i 've ever encountered .

aromas full of toffee , caramel , cinnamon , clove , slight ginger , big notes of brown sugar , molasses , some nice spiced rum , nice sweet pumpkin notes on there as well , really big and full .  mouthfeel is exceptional and creamy . this is what makes this beer so spectacular imo .

s - strong spicy , malty , and yeasty aroma bursting fourth from the glass with dark fruit aromas - raisin and plum - with a tiny citrus sharpness to it . d - good but not great in the drinkability department , it has a nice flavor and an outstanding aroma .  really a great beer that has it 's hops really balanced , and the silky smooth malt mouthfeel balances wonderfully with bitterness of the hops .
s - smells just like creme brulee .  mouth is light-medium bodied excellent carbonation .

a - wow a pitch black liquid and with an aggressive pour i saw at least an inch of coco head .  m - carbonation cleans the palate nicely , the tartness and funk does n't linger long . the carbonation is just spot on , love it .
dark golden , sorta amber , about a finger of frothy white head . lacing and retention are both great .  mouthfeel : absolutely fantastic . smooth , dry , and thick .

it has a solid malt backbone with a full ( for a iipa ) body and nice carbonation coupled with hit-you-over-the-head-hops . a strong english presence in the nose and flavour , while the bittering hops cleanse the palatte for the next swig . a masterpiece . plain and simple .  mouthfeel : very smooth body , easy to drink . nicely carbonated .

s- a lot going on here , sweet , spicy oranges and other citrus , light floral hops , lightly vinous , dried light colored fruits ( apricots and figs ) , alcohol shows slowly as it warms . m- creamy , medium-heavy body , good carbonation .  moderate carbonation with a strong sticky pine aftertaste make it very very enjoyable . very strong , flavorful , and pleasant .

the nose is strong plum , figs , prune , dark chocolate , coffee , brown sugar , wheat , just lots of sweetness in the nose . the taste starts mildly bitter with a grapefruit crack of bitterness , this is very interesting ... .it feels like a fruity belgian beer combined with west coast pungent hops finished with a porter 's roasted barley like quality .  m : spot on with the mouthfeel - very thick and almost chewy , with just a hint of alcohol towards the finish .

golden orange body with a super fluffy white cap that make it hard to fill the glass .  there ' a great mouthfeel , it just makes you think that this is the perfect body and carbonation for this beer 's taste and aroma .

poured from the bottle into a pint glass after a long day - looks alright , smells good , hopefully it 'll taste good : ) appearance : pours a lighter coppery/orange color and comes with a short head ( less than one finger ) that is off color and fades to a fairly full and uneven skim ; spotty oily lacing clings to the sides ; body is just slightly hazy and shows moderate carbonation bubbling up from below . smell : smell is good - smells of nice and bitter hops that are more piney than citrus , but there seems to be a moderately sweet presence coming through the nose as well from a firm malty backing .  the mouthfeel on this beer was truly exceptional . i 've never had a beer with such great viscosity that managed to avoid being sticky .

the most remarkable attribute of this beer is the smell , and it might be the best beer i 've ever had in terms of smell . this guy has a very citrus and hoppy aroma - making for a very inviting smell if you 're an ipa fan .  m : medium-bodied with a soft , silky mouthfeel . the thick , creamy head gives a great texture to each sip .
the smell is sour and tart with a good amount of musty funk .  m : leaves a nice stickiness that is not overpoweing .

very fragrant . taste : very clean taste with fruity phenols dominating over any wheaty flavor .  it was medium bodied and the carbonation was perfect . it was very enjoyable to just hold it in the mouth .

appreciate the bartenders patience with the nitro-tap superhead which persisted til and end and may the second washing of the glass ! held to strong sunlight only the thick bottom refracted some ruby glints . all else eclipsed the light as if it were the rock solid moon itself !  d - i love the dessert like chocolate and cream notes , and the mouth feel is outstanding . a really well done brew , but i do n't think that i could take more than one ... it 's a hair to sweet imo .

s- probably the best smelling beer on the face of the planet . not overly complex , but smells of sweet sweet pineapples .  smooth , crisp , dry , and satisfying medium body . clean in the end yet enough texture to let the flavors linger .

excellent aroma of walking into a candy shop with the sweet smell of fresh chocolate and caramel in the air . finish was a little watery , but overall , a stout beer well worth drinking .  mf : masterfully fizzy but light and balanced .

smell : the most varied mix of spices as i have ever smelled ... you got mint , ground pepper , basil , thyme , lavander , cloves , it 's like he emptied his spice rack in there ! unbelievable stuff . taste : pretty complex , quite heavy on the spices .  velvety smooth creamy mouthfeel , moderate level of carbonation , medium to thick body .

exceptional smell : sweet and nutty smell that begs you to drink the brew . one of the finest beer smells i 've encountered .  the mouthfeel is superb : sticky and chewy but also very creamy , with fluffy carbonation .
s- smell is very big , lots of caramel , hints of roasted malt , coffee and brown sugar .  this exhibited a creamy mouthfeel .

the malt is there at the first sip , but then the hops take over from there . smooth and just the right amount of bitterness to go along with the hoppy character of the beer .  mouthfeel is the best part about the rasputin - just the right amount of chewiness and the malt and alcohol linger heavily on the sides of your tongue .
a unique , well balanced , clean smelling brew . the taste brings on a more smoky malt profile .  mouthfeel was exceedingly smooth .

wonderful menagerie of hops . citrus fruits with pineapple being the one i notice most . pine and earthy . while the taste does n't match the strength of complexity of the aroma it 's still a very good beer . imo it 's too hoppy to be a eipa but too balanced to be a aipa . regardless of style it 's a good beer .  m- oh so crisp and so damn smooth over the medium body .
s - pumpkin pie - sweet pumpkin pie , all the way .  the mouthfeel on this is full and creamy , absolutely perfect . very soft carbonation .

beautiful , light beige head that forms a long lasting peak . solidly four fingers thick .  body is refreshing yet almost full in its thickness and rich , creamy carbonation . overall it 's damn delicious and a great collaboration ; no surprise that there 's yet another beer with the dogfish head logo on it that i love .
nice bready and hoppy aroma . the nose is very balanced . on the palate this beer screams american ipa .  creamy mouthfeel . the mouthfeel is very creamy and chewy .

s : huge hops , pine and sticky kind bud with a light biscuit malt presence in there . t : huge malt and huge hops in a wave of dipa goodness . thick and creamy and almost overpowering . not exactly what i 'd call refreshing . value : not much of one ; i paid $ 3.85 for one can .  m/d - full bodied and very creamy . lively carbonation carries the beer through your mouth .

aroma has a lot of citrus and almost tropical hops , very potent and absolutely amazing smell . taste starts out with the same fruity taste as the aroma , almost entirely hops with a touch of malt .  really excellent creamy mouthfeel .
