s : one of the best ipa aromas around with tropical fruit hoppiness of mango , pineapple , and passionfruit , coupled with pine resin and floral notes . pale malt with a little medium crystal sneaks in there to provide a little resistance to hop deluge .  the mouth feel is outstanding , to the point of being lip smacking and among the best i 've had .

the nose is quite fantastic , rich and complex . brown sugar , vanilla , vinegar , oak . very complex . cherry skins , ripe berries and a buttery chardonnay character that reminds me of depuration , this beer is mildly funky . pretty insanely drinkable , this !  mouthfeel is about the creamiest i 've ever had a beer feel . drinkability is great too .

s. the rosemary is jumping out of the glass . it is even more disappointing when the nose seemed to suggest such a wonderful bouquet .  leaves very thick lacing , almost like a nitro s_toasted bread , caramel , not very strong t_burnt toast , chocolate coffee beans , no real aftertaste m_ultra-smooth and creamy , so mellow , balanced , very little carbonation .

2010 bottles on the shelves now are probably not worth buying at $ 9- $ 10/pop unless you have a lot of patience and extra space in your cellar ... i did have the fortune of trying a version of this beer at new beer distributors a few months back in december that was `` randalled '' through coffee beans that had been soaked in bourbon .  the mouthfeel is perfect . it just goes down that damn smooth !

the smell was great ... just like pumpkin pie . pumpkin pie , however , is something i 'd rather smell than eat . also seems a bit watered down . i ca n't really taste much beer here .  fairly soft but noticeable carbonation , thick creamy mouthfeel just like chocolate milk .
1/4 '' white head ... excellent retention . a very nice beer to look upon .  the carbonation was perfect , often porters are too carbonated and heavy , this one hit the spot .

s : pungent hops , loads of citrus up front tinged with some pithy aromas , herbal and spicy hops also hide in the background . t : follows the aroma almost perfectly . loads of citrusy hops giving the beer a strong citrus peel flavor .  m. good body with a perfect level of carbonation .

the smell was quite complex . heavy in malt with mixed fruit smells , citrus , dates and various other fruit . an almost nutty undertone in the rear of the nose . the drink started clean and fruity with just a hint of hops in the middle and a lingering dried fruit flavor to finish . clean mouthfeel , heavy in carbonation at the start but this dissapates and leaves just good beer to speak for its self .  mf - this it where this beer shines the most to me . very nice carbonation that tickles your mouth as you savor it . also reminds me in some ways of an eisbock albeit less vinuous and more carbonated and roasty .

smell : this beer smells great . i smell sweetness , yeast like a biscuit , a slight tangy banana like smell . very good aroma . taste : you can taste the dunkel and the tangy the most .  really impressive mouthfeel with carbonation that really makes it finish well .

a - this is one seriously dark , sludgy thick beer . tall and frothy dark tan head that hangs around for awhile . pure black and highly viscous .  it has a very `` oktoberfest '' flavor which is n't my favorite but really excels with mouthfeel .

the smell is overwhelming hops , mostly citrus , orange and grapefruit .  this lingers for a few seconds before a bit of spice segues into ample , but never overpowering , bitterness- joined by a ridiculously intense fusel alcohol character which adds its own bit of astringency , ensuring that the beer does n't end too sweet but not once interrupting the incredibly smooth texture .

great aroma . lots of whisky character when the bottle was opened , more of a refined alcohol that you get from a good scotch rather than a boozy nose . nice texture .  body is creamy and rich , with mild carbonation , pretty strong abv , but alcohol is not dominant in the taste i enjoyed this beer the more i drank , very impressed .

amazing aroma ! there is some type of wood smell in there , as if aged in a barrel . reminiscent of a belgian strong ale , with the spices and the alcohol content . a beautiful and different beer drinking experience . warms my belleh .  mouthfeel- excellent palate coverage , really covers the entire tongue .

s- rich and malty backbone with some fresh , citrus-and-pine hops thrown in the add to the lovely bouquet of malt , honey , caramel , faint metal , a hont of peat , grapefruit , grape , barley , white bread ... excellent aroma . t- the malt character and hops are well-balanced and enjoyable , and there is a slight caramel tinge to the malt flavor . d- very good . i could have several .  thick and silky with a medium body . velvety smoothness characteristic of only a handful of the best belgians . clean finish keeps me wanting to drink more .

s- bouquet of semi-sweet chocolate , and a hint of smoke and coffee . no warmth .  m/d - mouthfeel is great , this beer briefly coats the mouth but then almost cleans it 's own flavor out of your mouth and has a slight aftertaste .
very good . t : taste is a oaky type bourbon taste that quickly fades into a watery rye with hints of dark fruit .  very smooth and creamy mouthfeel with a nice medium body .
grain and yeast layered behind citrus and floral joys . this is an awesome nose . taste is sweet , tart and a bit bitter . slainte .  mouthfeel is incredibly smooth and thick for the style .

the aroma is eclectic ; the wood of the aging barrels is up front as is the sweetness of the rum . it has a very `` island '' character to it .  mouthfeel is so soft and smooth , and drinkability is very easy .

a - pours with a ridiculous amount of tan foam that takes forever to dissipate and leaves a good amount of lacing .  feel is a nice creamy smooth medium-full with an excellent soft tickling carbonation .
a : golden colored with a thick , 2 finger head . extremely heavy lacing .  m : perfect ! the carbonation melds with the beer in such a way that makes this a one-of-a-kind experience to drink .
it smelled like ruby red grapefruity hops , and i almost wanted to stop there , it was so nice .  mouthfeel was silky smooth with a mild bitterness on the tongue .

aromas of honey and flowers . there 's a bit of a sake-ish sour tinge to the aroma , and you can certainly smell the minerality and fruit of the muscat grapes used to make this . this is an interesting beer , very cool to try , but i do n't find it to be particularly tasty .  smooth and full mouthfeel .
extraordinarily enjoyable , i 've had double ipa 's that do n't smell this good . not nearly as complex as the smell would indicate .  superb feel .

gravity cask @ gingerman in nyc . s : wet and juicy citrus hops all over the place : pink grapefruit & tangerine . has a sweet and really fruity malt background . t : loads of sweet pink grapefruit up front and then a big hit of juicy hop bitterness . d : had this on gravity cask , second day the cask was on .  taste : really complex with an extraordinary mouthfeel and a dry finish .

pours out a black as a moonless midnite black clour with blood red tints . a dark tan frothy head inch high head recedes to half an inch but stops there and leaves ample lacing . looks about perfect as a stout can appear .  carbonation is pretty much perfect , and adds just the right element to the brew .

the smell is absolutely amazing . this is one of the most aromatic , floral hoppy beers i have ever smelled . it practically smells like burying your nose in a couple handsful of hops .  great carbonation rounds out a very good-looking beer . no one flavor takes over , its a combination of them that gives this beer a great mouthfeel .

smells like a boatload of hops with some citrus/fruit undertones , smells absolutely amazing . taste is amazing at first , very hoppy , citrus and piney , some fruit in there too .  medium body with a thick and creamy yet mineralic texture . perfect combination of lively and fizzy effervescence . finish is dry and tart with just enough lactic sourness .

very nice clean , fresh aroma of freh blackberries , yeast , and crisp wheat as well as a touch of orange peel . the taste is n't nearly so clean and fresh and vibrant as the aroma , but still , better than expected and not at all artificial tasting . probably lighter in flavor than it should be , and heavy on coriander and a bit seedy .  m : quite thick and mouth-filling for an ipa , with enough smooth carbonation to keep things fairly clean . just lovely .

s : smells like a mocha latte from starbucks ; chocolate , coffee and a little bit of roast .  mouthfeel is very creamy and fuller than i was expecting . i love the way this beer just coats the mouth .
smell is truly exceptional . sweet raspberries and malt .  mouthfeel was incredibly creamy .

nose is excellent with roastiness and hints of chocolate .  the piney hops dominate the flavor , but a snappy finish makes it 's hard to gripe too much . exceptionally well balanced . in spite of the bold hops , it drinks with amazing ease .
great floral smell that invites you in to taste a beer with some serious hops .  mild carbonation , super creamy body , smooth .

the nose is impressive and attractive in this beer , with considerable dark chocolate , vanilla and coffee . in fact , there 's almost something of a coffee liquer aroma to this beer that is quite attractive . given how good this beer smells , the flavor profile is a let down .  very creamy and full bodied , perfect carbonation to keep it moving .
this beer looks pretty darn good .  very enjoyable , with a medium body and creamy carbonation that is perfect for this beer .

very pleasant aromas on the nose . like the nose , the traditional pumpkin pie flavors come thru immediately . like the aroma , i get decent doses of graham cracker malts and hints of roasted nuts , and sweet baking spices , perhaps some light brown sugar .  the richness and weight is perfect for me .

too sweet , but smells nice and very complex .  i do n't find much to be said really , excellent balance , medium body shows a perfect carbonation to my liking , quite creamy lager , pretty crisp dry herbal hops finish .

every ounce results in a near spill . sharp & intensely saturated with blackened raisins , burnt fudge , charred marshmallows , & a splash of alcohol .  this beer is creamy , smooth in the mouth with absolutely no harsh swallow or bite .

aroma is amazing - rich , thick and full . mom-mom 's holiday fruit cake reeking of dark spirits .  incredibly easy-drinking and gentle on the tongue . the penultimate english pale mouthfeel . there is so much to love : subtle and well-rounded , both quenching and engaging , plus the mouthfeel is impeccable . i feel foolish for not having tried this sooner .

s - amazing aroma of oak , wood and vanilla notes . o - this is a fabulous brew . outstanding aroma and flavor . really great beer .  mouthfeel 5/5 medium bodied , appropriately crisp , and clean finishing , the mouthfeel of this beer is spot on .

s - as i mentioned this beer is pretty funky . great hay and corn husk aroma along with the traditional funky dusty horse blanket . nice grassy hops finish this beer off . t & m - wow what an amazingly delicious brew .  mouthfeel - perfect , the creaminess remains with a twinge of bitter , very hearty and drinks like a filling snack .

the smell is incredible . after smelling the first time , you ca n't believe what you just smelled coming out of this beer . it 's like you 're 6 years old all over again . gobs of peanut butter , wheat bread , slight hint of strawberry jam .  this is a full bodied beer , the soft carbonation lightens it up creating a pleasing experience .

aroma : sweet cotton candy/caramel up front , fruity hops follow . i can smell pineapple and roasted malts .  silky smooth , nice carbonation , and thin enough to drink a few of , but not so thick as to let you notice the 7.4 % .
wow , what a rocky , frothy foam . it 's quite impressive actually .  mouthfeel is wonderfully thick .

aroma was out of this world , with strong scents of pumpkin pie and spice , similar to a really good straight-up pumpkin ale like weyerbacher , etc . after the aroma , i felt the taste was a bit disappointing , but i received cocoa nibs , vanilla , nutmeg , and clove , with some yeasty notes coming through as the beer approached room temperature . as i drank this beer , i thought it was `` okay '' but that it would have been much better and that the flavors would have translated better if it were a stout rather than a belgian dark .  m- the mouthfeel is medium bodied with a perfect amount of carbonation .

smell : a tropical sweet fruitiness . a mix of flowers and grapefruit .  head retention is poor , almost non-existent , a little dissapointing smell is not what i was expecting , surpisingly subtle , with a nice malty sweetness taste comes as a wave , roastiness , coffee like , followed by mellow sweet malt , bitterness like dark chocolate lingers in the mouth , pleasant after taste wonderfully full mouthfeel , thick , fits the beer 's complex flavor the alcohol is apparent , but not overpowering , easy to sip , not exactly quaffable , but pleasant

very nice . this was my final beer . not nearly the flavor i was expecting based on the wonderful aroma . easy to drink but need a little more uuuumph !  it has a perfect mouthfeel and it is extremely drinkable .

not getting a lot of `` unfiltered '' on the first pour , but that 's to be expected . thankfully , the aroma is a thing of beauty : juicy , resinous hop cones dripping with notes of grapefruit and pine . ( and i like it . ) all of this gets balanced with a sizable malt presence that suggests sweet toffee , caramel , and a hint of butter . sticky hop oils attack the tongue and roof of the mouth with a near-wooden pine note , while yeasty tropical fruits linger in the finish . overall , i found squall to be fairly typical of dogfish head 's brews -- innovative and tasty , but ultimately lacking the elusive 'finishing touch ' that elevates other breweries into the upper echelon of the beer world .  exceptional body .

taste is a bit dissapointing after the perfect aroma - sweetish , slightly watery malt , clove , rather fruity and mostly reminds of ripe apples and banana . overall , it was not bad , but after the nice smell and looks i expected much better taste .  m - very smooth and creamy mouthfeel .

smells absolutely delicious . not sure it smells like a brown , but it smells great . tastes watery .  mouthfeel - full-bodied , velvety smooth , and creamy with a semi-dry finish and moderate carbonation .

what a wonderful smell ! very nice . this was n't the easiest beer to drink , probably because of its high alcohol content , but it was certainly very , very tasty .  mouthfeel : no real aftertaste ( remarkable for a malt-heavy beer ) , carbonation is excellent and it plays well on the palate .
really liked the appearance , probably the beer 's strong point in my opinion . deep brown color , redish when held to the light .  mouth feel is great . a beer to sip on a cold night .
smells sweet , citrusy , yeasty , fruity , pithy , and spicy .  mouthfeel : extremely smooth and crisp .

zero lacing & head retention s : awesome sour/lactic odors t : an almost sugary sweetness is quickly steamrolled by sourness tartness & dry/wood notes .  m : exceptional . nice , full-bodied creamy / velvety texture with a low carbonation that provides just enough fizz to cleanse the palate before the next sip .

the smell was very complex , many different things happening and really reminded me of hoegaarden which i have really taken a liking to lately .  mouthfeel is perfection , smooth , crisp , with just the right amount of carbonation ... and the tartness in the finish leaves you wanting to pour more of that big bottle .

aroma : wow , when i popped the top the pumpkin pie like tone just engulfed my senses very intriguing cinnamon and other spices blend perfectly with the malts used here somewhat of a nut quality comes by my senses as well , but it 's safe to call it pumpkin pie . drinkability : i can honestly say one of these is probably enough not something to imbibe in quantity but to really enjoy and treat as a dessert or somewhat of a novelty not bad just not a creation meant to be drank frequently possibly a once a year beer here .  mouthfeel is very rich , smooth carbonation .
it really smells like banana bread .  just phenomenally satiny . in the mouth : satin , silk , creamy , smoothness embodied in liquid .
a bit of citrus and sweet caramel mixed in only makes this better . top notch !  the mouthfeel is outstanding . very creamy and smooth , but with active carbonation as well .

s : rose water , peach , banana , kiwi , spices and some strawberry . t : starts off with a soft blend of pear and banana , really on the basic side and not sweet or sour .  mouthfeel is fantastic , super thick and syrupy , perfect for the style .

s- incredibly deep and complex nose . i could just sit here and sniff this for hours . absolutely incredible . t- an incredibly sweet replicate of the nose with some substantial ( but unoffensive ) warming booziness midway and through the finish .  quite nice mouthfeel on this brew , very soft brew .
quite unique , but i 'm very impressed . the taste is a lot lighter and less robust compared to the aroma .  rich , full , thick , round mouthfeel , with a soft carbonation that is really terrific .
poured from my home tap with a deep dark chestnut brown color and a luxuriously creamy beige head .  an exquisite mouthfeel for a baltic porter .

drank on nitro-tap at dieu du ciel , montreal , quebec served in a nonic the beer poured a near pitch black with a super creamy , beige , two-finger head that lasted the entire drink .  full bodied with a great creamy mouthfeel .

however , this is a firmly coffee-bean brown that does n't let much light through . it certainly looks like a coffee porter . it smells much of coffee than it does of porter , but i am fondly reminded of one of my favorite beers -- moe 's bender ( a limited surly release ) . this beer barely tastes more like a beer than it does a coffee drink . the taste carries all of the notes of the smell : rich and dark coffee grounds , vanilla , and bitter chocolate .  the mouthfeel was full and creamy with a light carbonation .

the aromas in the beer are very sublime and enticing . the esters forge a fruity peach scent . this is one of the best smelling beers i have had .  mouthfeel is perfect , thick and creamy but not too syrupy , and with none of that trub you sometimes get in the bottle , maybe im just not used to drinking from a tap .

a bit too one-sided in my opinion ... hazed golden color with a nice juicy citrus/pine/leafy hop aroma on the nose ... .but the taste is too one-sided for an apa ... .big bitterness on the flavor ... hop tea like ... .needs more malt ( some malt ?  exceptionally smooth mouthfeel and medium/full bodied .
robust and inviting . the taste is of big caramelish maltiness with a touch of citric fruitiness .  thick and chewy with all the perfect elements . the real stand out for me was the mouthfeel .

s - bananas , clove , spearmint , yeasty bread rolls , honey , vanilla , toffee , earthy herbal tones , sweet rolls , white chocolate/macadamia nut cookies , yogurt covered pretzels , carrot cake icing , t - smooth and delightful , with a subtle tangy and spicy yeast that quickly gives way to buttery wheat rolls , caramel , vanilla , and toffee . lacking in some of the funkier aspects of a weisse .  this is the mouthfeel i yearn for in every brew o- very glad i got to sample this one and will most likely re-review it once i have more barleywine experience .

the beer was cloudy through the light and had an amazing floral aroma . it was like nothing i have ever had before . they must have just loaded in the aroma hops in this one . i was very excited to take a first sip . the floral aroma helped , but it was n't a pleasent bitter .  the light body is remarkable . it seems so very neutral which i figure is what makes this beer so very drinkable .
a - pours a dark black with a big frothy khaki colored head and great lacing .  perfect creamy texture and good body and carbonation .
smalls are strong dried fig and currant along with crusty bread .  perfect consistency neither thick nor thin , but to silky to be described as simply `` medium '' .
no hop aroma . very nice taste : alcohol dominates what otherwise would be a nice beer .  the mouthfeel is very smooth & silky . goes down very smoothly . nothing to improve on there , really .

as i poured this golden beauty a nice white foamy head formed , and my mouth began to salivate due to the first whiff of the aroma i got . when i took a closer smell , there was also a nice sweetness to the aroma .  m : i do n't think i 've commented on the feel of a beer 's head before , but here goes ... super soft , silky , airy foam . the head has an ethereal , other-worldly feel ... tremendous . the beer itself is of light-medium body . soft and clean feel . d : definitely a quality brew and one you should seek out now , but i have to say it 's not one i 'd label as exceptional .
strong creamy vanilla smell . sweet caramel .  carbonation is comfortable and helps the round mouthfeel to build an authentically belgian mouthfeel .

bomber , a : pours dark amber with a full three finger white head which maintains it 's structure well above the glass . impressive , great retention and lace .  mouthfeel - super smooth and silky . low carbonation and a big body .

wow ! ! ! nice . on second sip the honey really is apparant , very nice .  appearance : in between brown and black , boasts mocha colored beautiful head , constant bubbling , displays real `` activity '' smell : pretty standard of a lighter stout , slight coffee , chocolate , and malt aromas taste : subtle chocolate flavor and very smooth mouthfeel : very smooth and creamy , excellent finish drinkability : very drinkable , has good flavor and excellent mouthfeel i 'd recommend this beer , especially if mixed with a back road brewery blueberry ale .
a huge , tan/mocha colored head forms on top and is quite dense and rocky .  rich , creamy , and smooth mouthfeel . a bit of alcohol bite , and an excellent overall russian imperial stout .
the aroma was malty with notes of caramel , pears , apples , coriander , herbs , and honey .  light-medium in body .

lots of grape/apple/ and cherry scent . amazing scent ! is there funk ? t - slight `` homebrew '' flavor ... kind of off-putting . very unique . lots of big fruit flavor .  the body is medium with one of the finest , creamiest , super fuzzifyingly , silky-slippery-zippery carbonations i have ever encountered .

i 'm really blown away by how complex and phenomenally enjoyable this is . wow . o : yet another stunningly good beer from the kernel .  this is an interesting brew indeed ... the main feature is the exceptional mouthfeel ... blindfolded i would have expected this to be a very good sparkling wine ( if not a standard champagne ... ) ... smell and taste however lack a bit of outlines and aromas ... on overall i would say this is a very noble brew , which needs a bit of connoisseur spirit ... .

no one gave me a really good answer on availability or how old it is . aroma is very sweet like melted chocolate but there is some roast malt to be found under that . some fruity ale yeast aroma too with black cherries and plums . damn , that 's lots of chocolate . spicy mole chicken or rasperry sorbet it would probably work but i do n't really dig it by itself .  mouthfeel is damn perfect for a pils .

the aroma is awesome : loads of floral citric hops , a whiff of fruity esters and a faint underlying grassiness . what a major letdown .  the mouthfeel is incredibly smooth and coating , leading to an extended finish that eventually coaxes out some espresso and a final touch of nuttiness .

the lacing did n't stay at all , in fact there really was n't any lacing , but it did smell rich and delicious . in fact the smell was decadent that i thought i was going to be in heaven in two seconds .  the mouthfeel is amazing - as good as don de dieu .
s : smells just like a very , nice clean helles lager with a good dose of smoke throughout .  thick chewy mouthfeel that coats the entire tongue and a little burn as it warms .

poured a nice deep clean copper with a big white head , nice lacing , looks very good , hope its not all down hill from here .  m - thick and velvety ; very pleasant . for a ris , this is just about perfect . coats the mouth and then recedes without overstaying its welcome .
aroma is really intreuging .  very nice .

very bold and zesty aroma . lots of bready and yeasty smells with a very spicy character .  medium body with a wonderful rich texture that is soothing in the mouth . just enough carbonation to keep things lively .

nose is amazing - chocolate malts , roasted coffee and vanilla team up for a sweet , rich aroma that has to be one of the best i 've smelled . taste is quite good as well .  m - getting better , as advertised it 's super smooth . lovely and creamy .

s - very very piney . never smelled anything quite like it .  the body is amazing and really makes this beer absolutely stunning to go along with its big hoppy flavors . it 's oily , greasy , beefy , big bodied , and largely bold , with a crunchy , grabbing , snappy , zip line long bittering tone of a ton of orange oils and pine oils .

simply put , it smells like smoke , but it is n't simple at all ... i doubt i can do it justice ... big , roasty , charred-man-food smoke smell , and i love it . great taste . this is still a beer , and a damn fine one .  amazing balance in this beer . mouthfeel is full , and this is very drinkable .
smells great like cherries and chocolate .  mouthfeel is medium and very smooth with the perfect level of carbonation .
aroma was absolutely perfect . strong vanilla dominates with oak and bourbon intertwined .  the mouthfeel is excellent . nice body with a smooth finish .
s. smells good , just like the bottle says cloves and banana , with maybe some yeasty goodness .  m : mouthfeel is very nice .

the smell is strong and elegant with lots of rich hoppy flavours ; lots of fruits ... red apples , raisins , apricots , fresh raspberries . there are some very fragile spicy notes of cinnamon and allspice .  smooth creamy mouthfeel , it 's a satisfying brew for my palate . very good stuff .
s : great smell , oak , vanilla , wine grapes , brown sugar . t : taste is outstanding as well .  m - perfect carbonation .

despite a very dark brown and ideal head retention , the astringency persists .  mouthfeel is really very rich : like a good stout on the palate , smooth and full , thick and chewy , but it 's got that pilsner crispness .
the poured beer looks great too .  the mouthfeel on this beer is superb . very creamy with subdued carbonation and a medium body .
smell is downright excellent , lots of dark sweet fruit flowing out of the pint glass .  its awesome ! as smooth and creamy as you can get . an absolute delight for the tongue !

s= like a lovely barleywine i guess . i was loving the nose on it . the taste is sort of strong sweetness to it with the caramel and a small bit of toffee coming through .  mf : silky and smooth but without compromising its thickness , which is needed as a foundation for the abundance of flavour . not too wet or dry , but the perfect balance between . not a unique mouthfeel , but an expressive suitable one .

wow this is a wonderfully floral blend of citrus hops that warns of hop balanced sweetness and really gets the mouth watering .  a pleasant crispness from the hops and the smoothness and creaminess make for a great mouthfeel and extreme drinkability .

s : a great tart cherry aroma with chocolate malts and some coffee notes . t : i have to say , i 'm very disappointed in this beer 's flavor .  the mouthfeel is super thick , and coats the mouth and lips .
s : citrus , very bright ! spicy yeast , apple and pear cider smell , some nutmeg .  m : so so so smooth and soft .

poured an orange , marmalde color . nice head . good looking .  the mouthfeel was amazing , drinking the beer it had the typical bite of aftertaste that normal ipas have , but i took a drink right when we left the pub and i still could taste the hops about twenty minutes later .
beautiful nose , seriously the perfect porter . it smells amazing , but the flavor does n't seem to live up to the smell too well .  the body is perfect . honestly .

smell : a strong nose of fresh hops , big but not overpowering . the hops taste a bit darker and not as appealing as the smell , but still alright . sweet , like an ipa should be , but not overly so . it looks and smells wonderful , but the taste leaves much to be desired .  mouthfeel/drinkability- just when i thought the perfect mouthfeel of a belgian ale was locked up with tripel karmeliet , this beer dazzles with a sublime , gentle texture that lasts throughout the entire duration in the mouth . absolute perfection , it further emphasizes the already impressive quality of the beer .

lovely . a hint of sweet fruity esters finishes the nose . i like this . d - the beer is pleasing , inviting , and tasty , but that alcohol , ohan that alcohol in the finish ... please go away .  mouthfeel is dead perfect for the style , full and solid .

smell : great woody smokiness ; smoke flavor is distinctive for other generic smelling smoked beers . taste : well balanced smokiness ; does not overwhelm , but weaves nicely between senses of taste and smell . sweet malts complement the smokiness ; alcohol is well balanced by the full bodied flavors .  m : as great as the bottle was , as you can expect , the nitro-tap was a homerun . so incredibly smooth and creamy , one of the best mouthfeels i 've had .

s : the nose is of pumpkin mix and spice . the smell is hot and estery , like boiling pineapple juice , but this brew does conjure images of fresh pumpkin pie at grandma 's house . then , suddenly and overpoweringly , comes the hotness from the alcohol . very tasty , but the bitterness of the hops will cloud my palate , the 11 % alcohol is going to blur my vision , and the fusels are going to give me a nasty headache in the morning .  palate- chocolate milk with some espresso , toffee and campari bitterness , a touch of winy acidity , and a very creamy mouthfeel .
there are chocolate and raisins on the nose and hints reminiscent of the leathery cherry notes from a belgian quadruple .  m : wow , this beer has one of the best mouthfeels i have experienced .
nice complex but balanced smell . t : very complex . overall a very good , complex beer .  mouthfeel was great , pretty drinkable , but not that high of abv for a stout .
smell : malty caramel and toffee .  taste is also quite yeasty , lemon zest as well , the carbonation is bubbly and soft , not harsh , incredibly creamy and smooth for a hefeweizen .
pleasant but not overbearing taste .  the mouthfeel is perfect for a doppelbock .

beautifully strong citrusy hop aroma . very well balanced taste , with grapefruit hops , then resiny pine needle taste and then a superb malt finish .  m : very smooth , sticky , and thick . light to medium carbonation .
the aroma is very good , i think it smelled a lot like french vanilla coffee with cocoa , very very good .  m : i must say , this beer feels great in my mouth .

the aroma is delightful ... huge scents of figs , raisins , cherries , citrus with a slight alcohol twinge if you linger the nose . slightly bitter and dry in the finish and so wonderfully kind on the pallet ... could think of no better way to finish off an evening .  bready yeast also comes across the nose t : again sweet sugar , yeast , dark fruit like notes of raisin or prune , just a hint of the kirek in the backgorund m : mouthfeel is super smooth . beer has a medium body and nice carbonation . finishes extremely clean .

s : fresh crushed raspberries , sweet and fragrant . does n't smell like beer at all .  very tasty indeed mouthfeel was very alive great carbonation with it 's light in the ass body and a very easy drinkability can enjoy anytime of the year .

s - quite strong clove and banana aromas , with the balance leaning towards the clove . a background tartness provides a great balance to the sweetness . notes of grain from the wheat . the aromas promised so much more .  mouthfeel is wonderful . creamy with smooth carbonation .

this stuff smells incredible , the fresh coffee and sweet dark fruit work so well together . finishes with a lasting coffee flavor , very nice . mouthfeel is medium bodied and oily , but thin and fairly flat .  thick , syrupy and silky smooth with just enough carbonation to tickle the tongue . goes down so easily - incredibly smooth .

bottled oct 3rd , 2011 - consumed oct 19th , 2011 a : nice clear light golden amber with a thick creamy white head that laces the glass very nicely and stays around throughout the beer s : wonderful citrus and grass hop aroma coming off the top . very clean hop aroma .  first thing i notice when drinking it is the fabulous mouthfeel - so soft and creamy yet a rather thin body .
pours a solid black with a creamy frothy white head that sticks around forever .  light carbonation and great coating mouthfeel . d- yes .

appearance : as served the beer is a nice cleary lightly coppered amber color with a `` off white head that persists for a while and leaves a nice pattern of lacing on the glass as it recedes . eventually the head recedes to a ring of foam but for most of the beer there are speckles of lacing when sipping and there is also lacing clinging to the sides of the glass .  mouthfeel is the star of this show -- thick , rich , round , full , all very slurpalicious .
smell is awesome with a hint of sweet malty carmel , coffee and anise .  m : great mouthfeel , one of the first things i noticed after drinking . it really coats the mouth .

2005 edition . looks really great ; dark amber pour with a big soft pillowy head that gradually dissipates leaving insane amounts of foam .  mouthfeel was exceptional with just the right amount of body .
very attractive smell , grainy with some yeast and a fresh sweetness .  the cherry tartness and barrel-aging really do some nice things here , and combine for a wondrous mouthfeel .

sweetness abounds on teh nose . beautiful ! a powerful beer on the palate with an abundance of toasty malts , sweet berries , and the rest of the nose .  ( m ) - really smooth and creamy . the carbonation has subdued to a really nice level that balances it out to a totally silky beverage .

the aroma is the winner here , complex and intriguing . the typical holiday spices ( cinimon , nutmeg , all spice ) are all there but are combined with something like pine needles as well as vanilla and plums . its like a lot of talented musicians in the same room , they just have to figure out how to play together and become smoother .  stellar mouthfeel .

bottle : poured a pale yellow color ale with a super huge foamy head with perfect retention and lacing ( somewhat of a gusher ) .  smells great , coffee and chocolate notes right up front chocolate & coffee flavors , dry and bittering at the end mouthfeel is very smooth . much smoother than i remember when i had it last .

poured in to a pint glass a : pours black with a dark chocolaty looking head of about 1 '' the quickly shrunk down to a 1/2 '' s : little chocolate sweetness , roasted character , slight alcohol aroma t : bitter chocolate with a slight roasted character .  the palate has great carbonation interlaced with a strong , dark malt profile with well integrated hops .
smell : brown sugar , obvious alcohol , notes of red wine grapes , and tart cherry .  the mouthfeel is wonderful for a beer that is this bitter .
pours with a very large , stable , light tan head . good lacing .  extremely thick mouthfeel .
smell : strong smell of bacon , smoked ham and woodfire smoke .  good with food , good standing alone , and a wonderful , creamy mouthfeel when on tap .

huge hop aroma . smells like an ipa . tastes of hop bitterness and malty crystal sweetness . in general i really like over hopped red ales , they 're much more interesting than the usual malty , sweet and boring brewpub reds . i had low expectations for this beer and was pleasantly surprised .  it is very smooth with a nice medium to full body . i was most impressed with the mouthfeel . every part of your mouth will be involved in the feel of this beer as it awakens all your nerves right down your throat .

s : what a wonderful dessert smell ; a combination of vanilla , caramel and coffee ice cream . t : taste is super sweet roasted toffee malts with a generous helping of vanilla and some powdered cocoa , even . it tastes sort of spot on as a creme brulee , but i think i might have liked the aroma better than the taste here .  mouthfeel is great . really nice body .

nicely herbal noble hops showcased in the nose . so far i 'm pretty impressed by this .  has good slight citrus notes with a full hop oil and hoppy feel and body , a good finish mouthfeel- very very smooth , it has an extremely soft and smooth body that really helps it going down , the mouthfeel is a real strong point of this beer drinkability- a very good beer that i would definitely want to try few more times and see how it matches up with some other ipa s certainly worth another look .
absolutely beautiful looking beer .  absolutely perfect . drinkability is very high as well . even , balanced flavors with that great mouthfeel make for a nice combination .

s- sweet brown sugar , caramel , hints of belgian yeast and raisin . not a complex belgian . only unibroue and a true belgian can pull of this style it seems .  body and carbonation are perfect for the style .
s : big smell of molasses , caramel , and pancake syrup . t : much like the smell , although more subtle and subdued .  superb medium body with just the right balance of cream and carbonation .

s : this is one very spicy beer . also seems to be pretty sweet with good amounts of brown sugar and light honey . also quite fruity with nice amounts of lemon , clementine and green apple . typical unibroue , typical greatness . t : see above , literally the same but not nearly as well presented or as strong .  m : super creamy mouthfeel . damn this is smooth .
i 'm most impressed by the incredible aroma but i 'd buy this regularly if it was available in my market .  mouthfeel is creamy , perfect for this style .

it has a great complex aroma of chocolate and coffee and caramel tones .  the mouthfeel is unlike anything i can recall in recent memory . such a thick creamy texture like i 'm drinking thickness of marshmallow cream with the weight of a large marble .
it smells really good . t : brown sugar , cinnamon , light nutmeg and allspice .  thick consistently , but again not overly sweet . very good beer . hides the alcohol well and drinks smooth .

no lacing but lots of oils and resinous hop juice and malt sludge . huge . very sweet and potent vanilla and oak . stings the nostrils . t/m : massive . simply massive . bourbon is massive . vanilla and woody oak is also massive with just a touch of syrupy cherry juice in the back .  the mouthfeel is exceptional -- thick , chewy , syrupy , andincredibly smooth .
fantastic . sweet and slightly acid on the tip of the tongue . very drinkable , an extremely nice offering .  m- great carbonation , perfect balance .

s - absolutely lovely aromas of sweet malt with nice bready hints . very nice aromas . mild cloves and some yeast aromas as well .  viscous , sludgy , creamy , and slick . pretty swell carbonation as well . more bubbly than expected .

smell : rich , toasty , and roasty , with rich caramel and toffee notes with a little bit of smoke in the background . drinkability : medium-high conclusion : this beer has great aromas , nice flavors ( after it gets a bit of oxygen ) ; overall , this is a pretty solid offering from granite city .  there is nothing very `` complex '' about it , just a bitter hops taste and perfect mouthfeel . as mentioned , the mouthfeel for pale ale is perfect ... . perfect amount of carbonation and easy to pour .

appearence : a very nice looking off-white head sits firmly atop a slightly cloudy orange/copper body .  it possesses the best mouthfeel i 've yet to come across , rich and velvety , it just rolls over the palate and tongue , and goes down incredibly smooth .

a hazy orange gold with a nice thick white head that leaves decent lacing on the glass smell is of piney and citrusy hops followed by some pale/caramel malts .  mouthfeel : best mouthfeel of any wit i 've ever had ; this has the milkshake-thick , smooth mouthfeels i 've heard described as ideal for the style .

inviting and complex . this ale is a sniffer . no odors . a good , complex aroma . taste- this ale tastes like it could be the base for the belgian red , except without any of the cherry , sweetness is well balanced by sour and bitter .  the mouthfeel is wonderful . silky smooth .

very nice stickage . nose is packed with cloves , some banana , vanilla , lots of higher alcohols and some clearly present honey sweetness as well , and just a bit of graham cracker . not as impressive as i had hoped from the aroma . mouthfeel is undercarbonated and a bit syrupy .  appearance - dark brown/eggplant color with some brown head smell - this one is faint , picking up hints of coffee , cocoa taste - wow , this is good , these flavors really burst , i 'm picking up dark chocolate , a bit of expresso and hazelnut mouthfeel - this is smooth and creamy , high amount of carbonation , medium to full bodied , flavors really linger on the palate in the aftertaste , no hint of booze at all drinkability - this is going down nice on a chilly night , for $ 1.89 a 500ml bottle , this is really good value .

s - sweet malt aromas ; caramel , molasses & faint dark fruits - maybe raisin & prune .  gentile mix of flavors , not super complex , but with an incredible silky mouthfeel , and an oragne glow that makes it look great .

the smell is a potpourri of various spices and flowery scents . overall it 's a very inexpensive beer with a deceptive alcohol content that i could drink almost any day .  m - wow . so creamy and light .

grapefruit notes from the hops dominate upfront , followed closely by a bit of sweet malt . yep , this is certainly hoppy .  this is a tasty beer ... m - a good thick and creamy full bodied beer ... d - a little expensive for my liking ; however , definitely something worth picking up if you have n't tried one before .

a : very dark stout with a slight coppery head not much lacing on the glass . strong vanilla and caramel scent , sweet smell just like a creme ' brulee or vanilla custard , very very heavy vanilla smell . overall : nice dessert stout that i can drink again and again though i would have enjoyed a smaller pour as this is a rich and very sweet beer .  soft , creamy mouthfeel smothers my tongue with flavor .

s- smells nutty and rich , a really delicous smell . it is very deep and amazing , i could drink it again and again .  awesome mouth feel . thick and creamy with the perfect amount of carbonation for the style .

a - cloudy tanish gold s - the smell was amazing . very complex . floral , citrusy , pine and sweet . m - pleasing , definite carbonation .  the mouthfeel was awesome . just perfect subtle carbonation .

super strong and good smell , maybe the best unibroue smell i 've ever had . t : biscuit malt and tart pretty much dominate . super disappointing after the great smell of the beer .  the beer looks thick and chewy , but the texture is perfect for a brown ale .

the nose is up there with the best . a surplus of those juicy little green cones burst into the aroma with major pine and the bitterest of fresh grapefruit and orange . well balanced and i mean that this is how we hopheads like our double ipa 's , lots of hops with a good dose of caramel malt , but the hops dominate the character of the taste 75/25 . a hop bomb but nicely crafted and easily appreciated , seek this out .  full frothy mouthfeel . incredibly smooth and easy to drink , yet still intense and full in flavor .

smell : a smorgasboard of aromas starts attacking you from the moment you open the bottle . chocolate ( s ) , coffee , caramel , alcohol hitting on you with no mercy . fantastic ! i love it anyway .  mouthfeel is where this beer stands out -- it 's superbly balanced and dangerously more-ish .

s : the smell is rich and full of sweet caramel , molasses , toffee , and vanilla . the brandy blends in seamlessly with the base old ale and the dark fruits such as raisins , plums , and some others that i ca n't quite pick out . t : the flavor is rich and sweet , featuring brown sugar , caramel , toffee , and vanilla . m : the carbonation is non-existent , but the body is quite full and rich . d : sure , you ca n't sit down and enjoy the full 750 ml bottle of this beer , but you could certainly get yourself in some trouble .  t & m : mouthfeel is very creamy and enjoyable .

cinnamon and maple syrup mix with oak notes for wonderful complexity . a dark fruit smell of plums and raisins precede a strong alcohol scent . excellent . very strong cinnamon and birch flavors hit the tongue hard right away . alcohol presence is huge throughout which detracts from the experience .  mouthfeel : awesome ... .crisp , clean , enough of an aftertaste to seduce multiple sips . plain , yet glorious in its understated beauty .
the aroma was fantastic , and the taste while good was a bit of a letdown from the smell .  it has a very soft and thick texture but it 's not weighty at all . a pleasure to the whole mouth .

carbonation is criminally low though ... aroma is ridiculously hoppy . lots of nice plne hops in there . smells great . lots of body in this one .  exceptionally viscous and savory body starts creamy and full on the tongue , developing a wheaty wetness and light carbonation , ends dry .

among the best smelling brews ive experienced . t : flavor not as exquisite as the nose but still tight . i enjoy the bitterness of this imp stout matched with the deeply roasted malt . not the best tasting ris but the best aromas in my opinion .  m - this has a medium body and medium carbonation .
very nice aroma all around .  i love the creamy texture and the suprising full body .

it smells good though ! this is honestly a complete 180 from the slightly disgusting appearance . t - tastes much like the aroma ... lots of fresh glazed doughnuts , gooey caramel , mildly fruity hops , drier grassy hops , and a touch of ethanol . this is pretty good stuff !  a light bodied beer but incredibly smooth . leaves the palate feeling dry , making this an excellent strong summery beer .

this brew pours a medium head of fine creamy light brown bubbles that leaves a fair lacing and a dark opaque black brown body .  m - thick and creamy , very full bodied . complemented by the right amount of carbonation .

the color was the perfect ale color , golden and clear . the head was white , but disipated quickly once poured into a glass .  mouthfeel : a very creamy , very smooth ipa . carbonation is perfect . body is malty and medium-bodied , and aftertaste is mildly dry .

s-nose is complex and balanced . vanilla , oak , and sweet bourbon come through first in the nose with a big roasted chocolate backbone . m-medium tingly carbonation and a body that is balanced with thick stout qualities and alcohol . decent , but a little thinner than i like . d- this is a decent stout , and one i have been looking for for awhile .  mouthfeel is smooth and fantastic as is the drinkability .
smells hoppy before i even finish pouring . smells quite potent . the taste is not quite as good as the smell but very solid .  it 's pretty full bodied and very smooth with a clean , dry finish .

smell kills the idea that this is a stout right away . big floral hops smell that just blows me away . this has to be one of the best smelling beers ever . some sweet malt comes through in the background but it is really the floral smell that stands out .  very smooth and creamy on the palate .

smell : i just had nasal sex with a supermodel . wonderful , powerful blend of belgian yeast , honey , apricot , green apple , clove , fruitcake spice , pale malt with a mild solvent/alcohol scent underneath . it 's awesome -- i ca n't get my nose out of the glass . it 's good , but it does n't live up to the scent 's promise .  on the palate , this beer is nearly perfect with medium carbonation and a nice long bitter hops finish .
it smelled wonderful . very sweet and aromatic , almost sour . it tastes pretty good too .  mouthfeel is absolutely spot on .
good hops smell but that takes a back seat to vanilla , blackberry , wheat , port ... i need to drink this now !  one hell of a mouthfeel with this beer .

s : slightly sour , mixed-fruity aroma upfront -- sweetish lemony+tangerine , figs , melons , preserved pineapple , etc. , with a deeply , exotic fruity-perfumy nose which is so profound but not bursting , mixed well with an overwhelming candyish backdrop ( like chinese green-bean paste ) and `` floating '' floral hoppyness ... complex and simply sublime~~ t : a deep flow of candyish maltiness hits the palate first , followed by equally profound fig-dominated fruitiness laced with slightly sour citrusy flavour running deep ... the initially soft but sour texture gradually thickens , bringing out an intense fruity+floral hoppyness on top of a perfumy , yeasty taste , leaving warmish alcoholic mouthfeel down the tongue and a flow of dryish bitterness lingering towards the med-length finish with overwhelming aftertaste of sour-sweetish fruits and a touch of spice . medium-bodied and medium to full-flavoured tripel , it 's tasty enough but somehow falls short of the promise of the complex and evolving aroma ( quite like several other tripels , come to think of it ) . still a nice beer in its own right .  mouthfeel is divine , creamy and a velvet finish .
pours a large head with a very nice dark honey/amber color to it . wonderful shimmering lacing all the way down the glass .  felt great , and was easy to drink .

smell is slightly roasty , but mostly a dark chocolate and bready yeast aroma . its a good smelling brew . definitely a hybrid stout , as sweet lactose flavors combine with a fair amount of piney hoppiness and a bit of yeastiness .  m ) rich , almost slick . rich , long mouth coating .

a pretty balanced aroma . very nice . t- roasted malts upfront followed by a earthy/spicy hop bitterness that carries through to the finish .  mouthfeel is surprisingly smooth and creamy for such a sweet beverage . very nice .

d - the aroma of this beer is fantastic , but the flavor does n't quite match . overall , it is quite a good beer , but at nearly twice the price of rodenbach grand cru it should be even better .  medium bodied and creamy smooth , the carbonation was really kept in check leading to the great texture .

bottle 11.7 oz 2004 no p 75340 edition poured into tulip-like mc'chouffe glass pours hazy amber/red with a 1/4 '' off white head . a little lacing 7 film that chases down the glass s : huge oaky notes & hints of brandy & vanilla t : warming alcohol & oakyness , then brandy & cherry .  mouthfeel is exceptional and there is nothing objectionable here .

arroma : what a bouquet ! this is one of the freshest , hoppiest noses ever to come out of the bottle . if i could drink this through my nose i would . taste : this is basically a stronger , more full bodied version of arrogant bastard ... which is already pretty damn strong and full bodied .  love it.5.0 d fair plus drinkability as this is a huge beer , one that i could probably only have one of .

minimal head retention & lacing , some oily sheen to this s : apple skins & white grapes & pears once warm t : follows the nose , also getting candi sugar & chipotle pepper spicyness ( ? this one is a bit different , nice change of pace , not really a `` go to '' saison imo .  body is big and very creamy and smooth . mouthfeel of melted velvet .

never took the time to try this , so i grabbed it at the store and poured it into my pint glass ... a : like a typical nitro-can stout , this pours thick like a milkshake and the head slowly creeps away and yields a nice dark brew . the 1 finger nitro head lasts the whole time .  luscious creamy mouthfeel .

pours a clear gold into an american pint and after it settles it has a finger of creamy , thick dirty white head that hangs around for the experience and leaves a beautiful lacing .  it is a very crisp mouthfeel , perfect carbonation .

the us hop experiment works here , as the nose is a surprising but pleasant burst of citrus , with a heap of orange leading the way . a very fresh , clean aroma . soft , sweet , malty start , which is quickly balanced off , too quickly . the us hops come around and push aside the base , and leave a slight off putting perfume texture along side the orange and other citruses in the finish .  the mouthfeel is full , warming and fabulous . flavor is full with lots of yummy esters holding hands with the sweetness and the fininsh is where i get the coriander .

s- very pleasant smell but i had a hard time pinning down exact aromas .  the mouthfeel is full bodied with a silky texture , and low carbonation . overall , this is a really good dipa , but i would n't quite call it great .

the aroma is rife with vanilla bean and a fresh , sharp rye spiciness . caramel sugar daddies and liquefied raisinettes make for a sweet touch that plays well off the rye bill . overall , this is delicious stuff .  its mouthfeel is incredible ; obviously this is enhanced by the nirto-tap . the positive was creating an amazing mouthfeel that fits perfectly with the style .

smell is rich in grassy hops , a light barley nose and a crisp citrus smell . orange and lemon with some coriander and a slight nose of cloves .  very creamy , smooth , and full bodied mouthfeel . this is definitely a stout that i could drink quite a lot of given it 's mild but good flavor and fantastic texture .
i really enjoy the smell of this one .  m : perfect ! coats the mouth great ... slightly creamy , with the right amount of carbonation to bring out the flavors .
very nice aroma .  the mouthfeel is great . very thick and creamy with a gentle and soft carbonation .

s - incredible . i 'm a fan of hoppy beers , so this is right up my alley . lots of great , citrus-y hops . based on the smell , i was expecting a pretty powerful hops flavor , but it 's actually pretty nicely balanced . nothing to write home about when compared to the taste and smell , but definitely not a negative here .  m - smooth , a delicate sudsing that tickles the palatte , and quite refreshing with a subtle warming effect from the alcohol .

s- rich ripe fruit , dark fruits , figs and even apricots , super malty . very boozy alcohol and at 9 % not too many can be consumed .  palate : full bodied and medium carbonation . great feel . full bodied and enjoyable .

right off the bat the smell gets you.. smells just like a pumpkin pie and that can be great for some people . its a perfect beer for when the weather is starting to turn cold as this beer will warm you right up.this beer really hit home for me , reminds me off good times and good company .  medium/full body with an extremely creamy texture , assisted by the fine carbonation from the bottle conditioning .

huge aroma , complex , malty , yeasty , dark fruity . very , very nice but not exceptionally complex .  i bought this beer because some chi ba 's would n't shut up about this beer when the map room had it on tap . but as it warmed up the coffee bean aroma mixed with a creamy , roasted malt and noticeable hops . mouthfeel- good and creamy and malty . inky , oily and silky all at different intervals . just drinki the whole glass by itself and then eat myabe a chocolatey dessert .

12oz bottle from a six pack i picked up last month at green 's on ponce aroma : a very nice aroma to start off with.. the blend of caramel malts and floral hops is a great contrast and better than i expected appearance : a very deep shade of brown , and very little head after being poured into a terrapin snifter .  mouthfeel was exceptional .

when i first popped the cork i was hit with a very pleasant smell of rasberry .  the mouthfeel is excellent . very smooth , with just a little effervescence that gives it a certain crispness . good taste and a perfect feel make this a very drinkable beer , but with the high alcohol content , you 're going to want to take it slow with this one .

it looked and smelled incredible . the taste went off the rails , tho .  a semi-dry chalky exit that counterbalances the heavy malts quite nicely . i believe the heavenly mouthfeel has the most to do with this .
clear auburn with a single finger white head . lots of lace .  mouthfeel - thick , smooth , well-carbonated . right on .
the smell was wonderful . the taste was very nice .  m - refreshingly tingly , with a slow and steady rise in volume , ultimately becoming quite creamy and dense . very appealing .

rich nose of spicy hops , floral hops , some woodsiness . for a beer that looks and smells so great , the taste and mouthfeel are disappointing .  the mouthfeel is medium-full bodied with appropriately low carbonation , and a silky texture .
aroma was very malty with fruit , plum apricot . taste was very malty on the front end with quite a bit of sweetness .  m : quite thick moderate carbonation , love it .

it smelled of musty and smoky dark malts as well as a deep woody scent . best were the aromatic coffee with bitter chocolate notes . with a medium-bodied mouthfeel , this beer was complex but a bit too rough and way too bitter for the malts and other dark notes .  first sip reveals a silky smooth texture and very fine , rolling carbonation .
very appetizing nose . more tartness would have been nice but it 's hard to knock it .  burly , viscous , lusciously dextrinous mouthfeel . outstanding .

smell : it has the aroma of very ripe bananas especially when first poured .  mouthfeel is awesome and is what makes this beer for me , this is a good tasting beer that is enhanced by a perfect creamy smooth feeling as it passes over my palate .

smell is fantastic ... filled w/ piney hops w/ a whiff of cotton candy .  silky , creamy , smooth mouthfeel , the hops are not overly bitter they 're well balanced with the malt . mild on the carbonation .

aroma of caramel , vanilla , nougat , butterscotch ( i guess this is aged in barrels ? ) and plenty of booze . kinda odd flavor . bit of a let-down from the aroma . again , a bit watery with very little carbonation .  mouthfeel : chewy , full bodied . low carbonation , which suited the beer nicely .
poured into an english pint glass with an oily black colour and large frothy tan rocky mountain head , easily aggrevated from a gentle pour .  love the feel in my mouth .
great look - booming 4f frothy cream-colored head , with tons of sticky lacing ; golden amber in color , 50 % opaque , and plenty of visible carbonation .  just about perfect for me .

s : strong hop aroma that is of strong pine and earthy notes . a touch of alcoholic heat and caramel comes through later ... t/m : wow , what an incredible disappointment .  mf : smooth and silky , perfect for the style d : another delicious brew from one of the best breweries in the world !

the nose is quite excellent . the grapes are quite noticeable with a ripe , fruity , berry-like bouquet .  magnificent . drinkability is only average , as this is one once in awhile brew , not intended for or enjoyable on a regular basis .

it poured an amber brown color with an insane tan head that took a while to settle and it left some real thick lacing .  the mouthfeel is awsome , slick , thick and coating , perfect for a winter warmer .

reviewed from notes . 55f $ 7.99 / ea . s : powerful vanilla , caramel , and coffee notes . the scent is rich and thick . a : clear dark brown body with a small creamy head that dissipates quickly leaving little to no lacing and a wispy cover . large amounts of residual sugar leaves legs upon swirling . t : again , a powerful vanilla coffee flavor with hints of sweet caramel and toffee . a lot like a fancy iced coffee . hop flavors are subdued and only make a brief appearance at the very end .  generously carbonated feel . goes down like nothing .

s- smells frickin amazing . its like mostly grapefruit and a bit of caramel and a hint of pineapple . still snorting in the gorgeous aroma of this beer which i hope never ends .  the mouthfeel i think is perfect for the style .
smell , wow , butterscotch , cherries , slight medicinal . taste , wow , butterscotch sweet sour malt .  mouthfeel is crazy smooth and thick .
a - huge true blonde foam with tons of lace and excellent retention .  the mouthfeel was awesome . very heavy and smooth feel .

this smells like mulled wine in many ways . a cachet of spices are present in the nose : nutmeg , allspice , cinnamon , hibiscus , tea leaves . as expected , sour cherry notes also resonate . oaky , earthy smells jump out as well . smells like a bag of potpourri in general . the aroma spices bounce on the tongue also , with not a small suggestion of a hearty red wine as well .  mouthfeel is exceptional , is medium to heavy in body .
the aroma was amazing however . strong notes of fruit and wood and rum filled the room .  the body and finish are absolutely luscious considering this is a 4.5 % abv j-beer out of a can .

12oz bottle , served in an elevated tulip a - pours with over an inch of frothy and fluffy , dark tan colored foam . the beer is just about pitch black . insane amount of thick lacing left behind . almost getting to the point of being annoying is this head just wont die .  very creamy mouthfeel . again , marvelous mouthfeel , probably one of the best i 've ever enjoyed in that regard .

aromas of lemon , lemon zest , spicy , peppery yeast . finish is short , lemony , and a little medicinal , almost minty . overall a good bpa . but the minty and medicinal qualities clash , reducing the overall enjoyment .  m - creamy , silky mouthfeel , with noticeable carbonation .

bottled 07/27/10 pours an amber/ice tea color with 3 fingers of fluffy khaki colored head . insane lacing & head retention s : cakeyness , woody & herbal hops , fusel boozeyness once warm t : follows the nose , toffee sweetness up front , plus some boozeyness .  mouthfeel great creamy thick milkshake like mouthfeel with medium-light carbonation .

smell primarily lots and lots of heavy roasted malt . its also extremely sweet , its a vanilla type of sweetness on this one .  quite smooth and creamy with a good level of carbonation . feels great going down .

750 ml bottle bought last summer at gator beverage a : pours a very dark but translucent red brown with a huge foamy head of fine bubbles that does n't retreat s : big ripe fruit aroma of raisins and banana on top of sweet barley malt t : it 's beer but has a strong punch of sweet fruit up front , followed by bitter cherry notes - unique in my experience m : very full - smooth and soft on the mouth , with mild carbonation d : may be a challenge drinking the whole 750 ml bottle not sure exactly what i paid for this , but do remember thinking it was kind of expensive . with so many very good and less expensive scotch ales available , i probably wo n't buy this one again .  fine carbonation bubbles and a full body give an excellant texture . coats the palate beautifully . more of a bourbon lovers beer than a stout lovers beer .
very nice . a nice somewhat chocolaty taste with some coffee hints on the swallow .  mouthfeel : medium to full bodied and incredibly smooth . just a hint of carbonation tingle .

the nose is a sweet and sour explosion of tropical fruit , pineapple , fresh garden herbs , bright juniper pine , and bubblegum . the slightest breath of alcohol , caramel backbone , and some spice seeps through as it warms . a joyous aroma , i 'd like it in a body wash . the flavor is a tropical and herbal hop jungle . the malt bill is caramel and a bit buttery .  mouthfeel was excellent . very slick and smooth , almost oily in fact , with a medium/thick body .
appearance : as expected this beer pours ink black and easily forms a rich nut brown head with good retention .  an excellent mouthfeel .

dark brown with amber undertones topped with a medium thick to thick head that leaves lots of lace behind .  the most enjoyable aspect of this beer for me was its mouthfeel . just so smooth , with a medium to full body and a higher level of carbonation that keeps this beer formidably sippable , in a good way . all in all a richly decadent , mouth enveloping , alcohol warmth soothing , special imperial stout , that i had the pleasure of enjoying with a friend .

very attractive presentation . this alsatian amber looks phenomenal in the glass . the body is a brilliant deep copper/amber with generous carbonation that gives rise to an rocky creamy white head . wow , looks more like some belgian ales i have sampled rather than a lager . a very beautiful beer .  mouthfeel is just superb . satisfying .

a : a dark brown color with and of white head that sits two fingers high .  a perfect medium body that felt nice on the tongue , and carbonation similar to what one would expect from a top rated wild ale .

smells fucking amazing . giant sticky hops , pineapples , roses , and marijuana . like mixing centennial and cascade hold them up to your nose and breathing deep . tastes good . very good . the hops are more aromatic than anything , and the smell serves to blot out much of the amazingly sweet maple syrup malt that takes over most of the start and lasts throughout the middle .  thick smooth mouthfeel , very silky .
the smell had all the lovely malt of a red and the lovely hops of an ipa , and they were more than the sum of their parts .  mouthfeel is nearly perfect , with a refreshingly light and crisp body .

the smell is floral , piney , citrusy hops , all go well with the yosemite valley setting . the hops are earthy and piney tasting , but the taste also has a toasty and nutty sweet caramel malt that is very appealing .  mouthfeel - 5.0 silky smooth , with very fine , lively , almost creamy carbonation .
s - malty , with a lot of smoke aroma . t - overall very good , nice porter with a strong smoke flavor .  the beer has the perfect amount of carbonation and aftertaste , bringing you back for more .

until you know it 's cardamom , the exotic spice is wonderfully confusing to the palate , and other spices certainly help mask the heavy alcohol load . great winter brew : if the mercury had n't plummeted , i may not have enjoyed this nearly as much .  body is smooth , lightly creamy , and beautifully sparkling .

aroma is lovely and near perfect for style : brown sugar , burnt sugar , prunes , cloves , stonefruit . taste is much of the same notes as the aroma , but more muted , and less pronounced on the fruit and burnt sugar that makes the aroma so nice .  mouthfeel is near perfect with carbonation playing second fiddle to the robust malts .

smell is malty , wheat , banana , citrus ( sweet like tangerine ) and vanilla . complex and very well balanced . taste is tangy , not the malty sweetness i expected . still complex but out of balance . not the smooth wheat beer i thought , more the initial bite of a lager , kind of like a hybrid brew .  mouthfeel is also top notch . low carbonation that goes down very smooth .
real nice i must admit . pretty darn disappointing cause the nose is fantastic .  m : full bodied with an awesome carbonation feel .

s- smell is very hoppy , deep piney notes , resiny , sweet light fruit notes . t- resiny hops all the way through , an unbalanced grainy maltiness followed by a raw alcohol character .  mouthfeel - very creamy and smooth . great body without a sense of heaviness .
s - very tasty . the nuttiness comes out right away , and it does definitely smell like candied pecans .  m- full bodied with medium carbonation . thick and almost chewy in the mouth .
very much exceptional . incredible ; this stout , like parabola is just ace with the chocolate .  body is rich , creamy , smooth , and damn near perfect . another excellent offering from d'achouffe .

chocolate and raspberries permiate the nose and leave nothing else to come through . very rich , smells like a chocolate cheesecake with raspberries on top . very rich  the texture was excellent , not too thick or thin .

appearance : poured with an amazing white frothy foamy head that stood 1inch over the rim of the glass that dissipated very slowly leaving a beautiful lacing all down my glass . the beer is slightly cloudy yellowish gold .  mouthfeel is on the dry side with effervescent carbonation that contributes to the crisp clean finish . its a fascinating brew that manages to be both crisp and refreshing yet still rich and satisfying .

a - very dark , just short of black , some light passes through , looks clear , thick mouse-like tan head s - beautiful caramel notes , hints of toffee and milk chocolate , light herbal hop t - rather `` lean '' tasting , not much sweetness , a light bit of hazelnut , the dominant flavour is some earthy/herbal hop , but even it is quite light , virtually no aftertaste . m - fairly light body , combined with the mild flavours comes across as watery , d - the flavours are just too mild to get excited the aroma is incredible on this beer , but unfortunately it is far and away the best thing about this beer .  much better balance on the palate . crisp , clean feeling with just a bit of drying on the finish .

low carbonation , no head retention , but this is a cask . s - wow . what a nose on this . vanilla , caramel , sour notes , dark fruits ... it was quite a complex nose actually.. t - i was expecting sour notes.. but the front really took me by surprise.. very puckering .. i taste a lot of whiskey and burnt sugar notes on the mid palate and some great oak and deep vanilla on the finish . very interesting . but a tad too much lactic acid coming through . d - like i said . pretty darn sour , but the sourness played well enough against the vanilla .  ever so rich and creamy in the mouth with soft and forgiving carbonation . medium-full in body .
pours out in a clear brown colour with a large fluffy tan-coloured foam .  good moderate carbonation and a crisp , dryish , oily slick , chewy , creamy smooth full bodied mouthfeel .
nose is very assertive and full belgian candi sugar and super sweet cooked peach/apricot nose . sounds better than it is .  the mouthfeel was incredible . very creamy and smooth .

aroma is amazing , very complex for any beer . overall this is a very good offering from one of my favorite breweries and i think it has amazing complexity that is best enjoyed over a long period of time , letting the beer warm a bit and change over and hour or two .  thick and chewy in the mouth - one can definitely understand the allusions to barley wines in previous reviews . hops tingle as you swallow . is it an old ale ? compared to other old ales that i have seen reviewed , i 'm tempted to say old ale ... but a marvelous cold weather beer in any event .

a - pours a deep dark rust color with a half inch of foam that left plenty of sticky lacing s - citrus , orange and grapefruit , hops dominate the incredible aroma t - slight citrus flavor , but malts dominate with an alcohol burn and a nice hop bite m/d - medium bodied , a bit thicker than i expected .  the mouthfeel is perfect . the carbonation , weight of the brew , taste and viscosity are all well matched .

this one smells amazing , there are hints of lemon lime , apple peel , sourness , a hint of woodsy pine , fruity , yeast twang , and a nice blast of sage . the sage smells very fragrant and perfumey . the body is smooth but well-carbonated , in fact some pretty exceptional mouthfeel overall .  although this beer is fantastic it is a little powerful to garner a high drinkability score , but its pretty tasty .

the aroma is , well , hoppy . fresh squeezed lemon juice , handfuls of fresh pine needles , a bit of grapefruit and some lemon zest thrown in , to add a bit of bitterness . the flavor is n't as hoppy as the aroma . the mouthfeel is a bit thin but it really does n't affect the quality of the beer .  m : very nice . well carbonated , creamy , smooth , and very full bodied .

pours a beautiful red/brown with a creamy tan head .  mouthfeel : creamy smooth medium body with superb carbonation . swallow is velvet . tasty and the mouthfeel is truely a dream . goes down easy when you enjoy slowly .

nice dark amber pour with a thick whitish-tan head that slowly melts to a very sticky , thick lacing .  before i get to any flavors this beer has an amazingly creamy buttery mouthfeel amazing . very bitter chocolate character with big bittering hops on the finish.layers of bitter bakers cocoa , black fruits , just thick cocoa tannins and a forever finish .
s : huge hop aroma . smells awesome . t : earthy hop oil , ripe ruby red grapefruit , lemon zest and fresh orange .  nice syrupy body , carbonation is moderate - perfect .

smelled of a warming sweetish malt , caramel but not really , cherry-like , with some shades of thick maple sugar . some milk chocolate scents as well - overall , somewhat similar to a good scottish beer , and a complex one at that .  the mouthfeel is smooth though not super thick , it is a great texture for this style .

the smell was impressive with strong piney hops jumping out of the glass followed by a faint hop smell . the beer was well carbonated leaving behind a slick piney feel .  the carbonation and head give this an exceptional mouthfeel .

s : bright fresh citrus hops , almost slightly cheesy , sweet honey apricots , fresh orange juice . t : a little more cheesy and rustic with a sharper bitter pine finish , sweet honey dwells in the beginning in the background .  this is a big bodied , chewy brew with medium carbonation , and a full palate .
oh god it smells good . notes of malt and spice and brown sugar and nutmeg and cinnamon , it 's exactly what i 'm looking for in a winter beer .  mouthfeel is full and round .

very complex hop aroma . there 's fresh citrus , honey and marmalade . overall , an engaging ipa i 'll probably return if i do n't get around to an attempt a brewing a clone .  m - mouthfeel is great . a medium-full body with good carbonation . perfect . d - the thicker mouthfeel makes it slightly less drinkable .

nice looking beer .  m : this is one of the thickest stouts i 've had in a while - very similar to dark lord in it 's heavy , cream like thickness that coats the mouth very well . d : good drinkability , but it 's definitely a sipper .

lots of leather and clove in the aroma . mothballs . honey flavours but not very sweet . lovely dry finish . brett is the showcase here , along with some noble dry-hop . very nice and worth trying .  mouthfeel is incredible , maybe an even better quality than the taste .

thick foam builds on top and slowly recedes it 's quite pungent and fills the local atmosphere with coriander and spicy hops sweet for a witbier ; certainly not dry .  mouthfeel : light and airy . the perfect match to the flavor profile . well done .
it smells fantastic , but just does n't live up to it in the taste department .  the texture is perfect , though .
s- smell is delightful ! sweet butterscotch maple .  mouthfeel is pretty great . full bodied , full flavored , slick and oily . carbonation is great . super job here .

smell was fantastic . green apple , lemony with a subtle grainy maltiness . coulda been a little more dry , but still decent .  m - nearly full bodied but despite that and the abv , it is extremely smooth and leaves just the right amount of flavor behind leaving you wanting another sip .

the aroma is huge ! full of yeast and sour citrus ; this has all the classic characteristics of a wit except bigger and bolder . could stand a little sharper carbonation , it 's a little too creamy and makes the beer feel slicker and heavier than it out to be .  truly velvety on the tongue . the mouthfeel is second to none , it 's that good . this is a very good stout .

pungent , citrusy , centennial hop nose . very assertive hop bitterness hits the palette first , just a hint of malt sweetness follows .  finishes warm and fruity gain with a very sweet exhale that is not quite cloying but just perfect . thick bodied with a light carbonation , goes down easily .

absolutely decadent . the taste is not nearly as decadent but still very good . the oak really stands out as a great flavor here .  mouthfeel is perfect . low carbonation lends to an incredible full body and smoothness .
s - lots of roasted goodness and definitely the coffee beans .  a beautiful dryness on the finish that makes it pleasant to drink .

i smelled chocolate on dark fruit . overall , a very nice porter . not quite the most complex porter i 've ever had , but it was extremely drinkable .  mouthfeel is exquisite . creamy as can be from the oats , thick and chewy , slick , with a remarkably dry finish . strange carbonation that sizzles like really mellow pop rocks on my tongue . this gets a high drinkability score even though one bomber is enough , because the mouthfeel is so remarkable . glad i got it , and glad i waited to pop it open .

s - vanilla ( what did you expect ? ) , butterscotch and a hint of alcohol . t - vanilla , then roasted coffee , with a very slightly bitter finish .  carbonation is perfect and really adds to the beer .
this brew pours a medium head of fine to large sized mostly lasting bubbles and an opaque black colored body .  mouthfeel - great mouthfeel .
aroma is probably my favorite thing . fruity and tart aroma .  mouthfeel is excellent ; creamy with just the right twinge of foam .
wonderful . t - huge hop flavor without being too bitter .  good body and perfect carbonation .

wonderful aroma with hop floral and citrus fully rivaling the brett for attention . superb depth , refreshing . the hops and brett again tangle in the taste with the hops getting the upper hand .  mouthfeel/drinkability : this beer feels pretty creamy in the mouth , and is just a touch heavier bodied than i expected , actually . excellent .

very , very enticing . the taste is grapefruit rind , bready , biscuit malt , some pithy tropical fruit , and a bit of pine .  mouthfeel is terrific . great , rich , creaminess . completely coats your mouth .

aroma is outstanding , filled with sweet oranges and caramel , not caramel malt , but candied caramel . mouthfeel is a bit cloying , maybe a bit too heavy on the malt , but it coats extremely well .  the mouthfeel is clean and soft , and actually just perfect .

great belgian smell.. dark fruits , sweet raisin paste and brown sugar delights waft gently into my nostrils . tastes very sweet.. very sweet.. fruit is there , but it 's overripe and accented by a slightly metallic disintegrated hop character .  mouthfeel is medium heavy bodied and sticky as fuck , wonderful . the drinkability is very high for a beer of this strength .
golden with pillowy inch + head . bubbly lacing and constant , constant beading .  m/d - full bodied and incredibly smooth and easy drinking .
