smell is excellent on this imperial ipa .  absolutely fantastic mouthfeel , creamy and oily without being cloying .

s : beautiful full barrel , whiskey notes . oak , great integration , complex . t : heavy , heavy malt , gets sweet at the end but never cloying . elegant . d : this is a magnificent beer and makes me wonder why i waited so long to open this . drinking beautifully .  just the smoothest mouthfeel ever , talk about an angel crying on your tongue !

nose is incredibly fruity - strawberry , melon , green grape and cherry . fruitiness subsides some with time , but i 've never smelled a beer so fruity that has no fruit in it . very distinctive , and quite appealing . full malt in the mouth with the fruit moving further into the background than expected from the nose .  mouthfeel : oh mouthfeel is right on . perfect carbonation .

i 'm impressed by the extraction of peat without that burning-tire aroma i frequently find ( and hate ) in whiskey-barrel aged beers . the finish emerges with leather , tobacco , and a distinct aftertaste of spiced honey . very complex and engaging . well integrated barrel character . d : very tasty stuff .  the mouthfeel is some kind of amazing . this brew is thick , chewy , ultra creamy smooth and goes down like heavy cream . if you like your imperial stouts with an unapologetically brash , bold , slightly raw taste , but with a refined , well-mannered mouthfeel , then you 'll enjoy expedition stout immensely .

thats no fun ... a- the beer pours out a glowing golden orange colored body with a minuscule off white head . the head quickly becomes no more than a crown but leaves behind a solid wall of lacing . pretty nice .  i honestly would think this a stout or porter , rather than a bsda ... m : this is soo smooth and nicely full bodied , its literally coats your mouth , and leaves your mouth wanting another sip , just perfect ... d : well this beer is still a little hot , a year or two would make this even better .

1 pint 9.6 ounces no date appearance orange/brown slightly clouded body ; white head crackles away quickly ; very light stream of rising carbonation in body after head disappears ; no lasting lace ; pour slow late to avoid the cloud smell take a deep whiff ; earthy ; woody ; coffee ; fruity - a bit brut-like ; i actually had to step away and smell some ginger to be sure but yes , theres a solid ginger tone taste grapes , caramel and spice ; some alcohol and grains , especially in close mouthfeel steady shot of crispness on the tongue but its not overwhelming ; medium body that thins a bit in the end ; dry close drinkability certainly warming about 2/3rds into bottle ; the dryness drops the drinkability pangaea is not exactly my cup of tea or tulip of beer for that matter .  m ~ refreshing and spirited mouthfeel . truly exceptional .
smell is fantastic , like a reese 's peanut butter cup .  m - the best part of this beer .

a bit one dimensional , but damn does it smell nice . good , but just good . 3.5 m : lighter medium body .  it almost tastes like an ipa , but with a darker malts and a more complex sweetness . the citrusy hops balance it out nicely . the beer is quite heavy , i guess it is following its `` scottish ale '' description here . it is so creamy and goes down nicely . almost perfect drinker .

pours out a pale golden/straw color with a lively carbonation , a thick head that stays around as you drink , and incredible lacing patterns . a true pilsner should strive to look this good .  mouthfeel : silky smooth and creamy . does n't bite too hard , but you can definitely feel it . superb .

s - wow ! really surprised here . light chocolate notes , roasted malt , toasted sweet whole wheat bread .  big , smooth , and slick . this is a particularly rich baltic porter . very dark , dense , and well crafted .
light copper color with a good head and great lacing .  incredibly smooth and creamy in the mouth .

s- an amazing smell . really amazing . dark fruits , cherry . delicious dark milk chocolate- fudgy . o- an incredible smelling and tasting beer , but not quite perfect on the mouthfeel . still a really awesome beer .  fantastic , soft , supple bottle-conditioned mouthfeel .

the smell is full of malty porter goodness . lots of roasted coffee and sweet molasses .  first sip reveals a light to average body with minimal , almost cask-like carbonation and a silky texture . very enjoyable mouthfeel .

s : sticky , pungent hops , with a hint of spice . for a double ipa the nose is subdued in a way that leaves room for some interesting notes . a serious letdown coming off the promise of the nose . m : a tad on the thin side , not having made up for the absence of syrupiness with richness .  the palette on this is excellent thick and creamy not to much carbonation flavors of toasted malts sweetness almost but just enough bitter to balance this perfectly .

minimal head retention 7 lacing s : apple & pear blossoms , plus bubble gum t : green bananas , bready notes yeast bite & peppery spiceyness up front . green apple peels , dryness , a bit of pear , faint lemon , cloves & juicy fruit once warm . finishes a touch dry with more juicy-fruit & a bit of lemony hops mf : medium bodied , low carbonation & nicely balanced drinks really easy , a nice hefe that quenches the thirst  for the style , mouthfeel was superb , and drinkability was too .

very strong look to this lager . strong furious bubbles and a thick head and foam but a little pimpley . a very pale amber , more like a sunrise in hue than a red lager .  medium bodied with low carbonation . amazing mouthfeel with one of the most balanced , robust , and pleasantly malty flavor profiles of any barleywine .
dark orange . lofty , creamy bubbles clung together above the liquid , showing very good density .  mouthfeel- super creamy , lower carbonation and silky smooth .
color was black , taste was dry , bitter , and to me , burnt , with a thin mouthful .  mouthfeel is very nice , i enjoyed it a lot .

a : poured a 1 finger fluffy , creamy chocolate head with unbelievable retention . frothy lacing was full and outstanding .  very soft carbonation that makes it feel creamy and silky smooth one of , if not , the thickest beers i 've had . love it .

this beer looks great , feels great , and smells great . it tastes awful . a beautiful , rich cherry smell is most noticeable in the nose , backed up by chocolate espresso .  the mouthfeel is super thick and heavy , just awesome . the drinkability is pretty good for an 11 % brew as well .
aroma - awesome aroma of malt and hops . probably too hoppy a beer just from the aroma for me .  mouthfeel is excellent . it 's creamy and almost chewy .
a nicely balanced scent on this one .  m : outstanding , deliciously creamy , thick , rich for an ipa .

smells absolutely wonderful . very sweet but not overly malty or boozy . overall , an amazingly good dipa , and at a great price - i believe i paid $ 7.99 for the bomber at binny 's .  mickey 's ice has an amazing mouthfeel to it , one of the best in my opinion . the carbonation comes on strong then fades to a creaminess .

has a huge earthy and pungently roasty aroma -- coffee and raw , bittersweet chocolate . strongly flavored , but pretty smooth . more tangy than sweet . smokiness that reminds me of a rauchbier , but only vaguely . nevertheless , this is an incredibly flavorful stout and you 'd think it would be heavier based on that .  a very big complex beer that is very well made and has exceptional mouthfeel .

s. wow , this is one of the best smelling ipas i have ever had . amazing . t. not nearly as smooth as the nose indicates .  good carbonated bevy . the mouth was superb . top tier of coffee stouts although i do n't know that its the best i 've ever had .

awesome . taste- greeted with the normal citrusd peel , but more emphasis on grapfruit zest and some malts .  a : jet black , no head s : traditional russian imperial stout , dense , licorice , oxidation , great t : dense , true russian imperial stout , cloying , deep burnt caramel taste , great beer , tastes like it has been aged for several years d : very good m : excellent

s- lots of orange , grapefruit and other citrus notes . o- had this fresh at port around thanksgiving and really like it , but the bitterness overpowers the beer and you do n't get the citrus notes like in the nose .  great mouthfeel , full bitterness balanced with light maltiness .

aroma is strong and sweet ; brown sugar and dates , raisins and prunes . the surprise was that the finish was very clean for a beer of this heft . flavor : strong and intensely sweet .  very dark with no light coming through and light head n : nose has lots of chocolate and sweet malts and a touch of hops t : starts with lots of chocolate and coffee , some sweet malts but very slight , a touch of hops are prevelant , some oatmeal taste as well , it 's got a sweet earthiness to it which is somewhat unique , a slight bitterness shines through m : it has a velvet feel in the mouth as it slides around , very thick and smooth f : a touch bitterness comes out in the end with the nice stout and oatmeal taste , coffee lingers on the back of the tongue , it has a sweet quality to start but gets drier as it fades and finishes really dry , its got a great smooth feeling in the mouth to go along with the great taste final thoughts : a great stout , it would be great if it was labelled as oatmeal or irish stout since it seems to have qualities of both , but listed as imperial it makes me wonder since its lacking a lot in the hop category .
clear lava body with an active sudsy brilliant lavender head which recedes to a persistent half-pinkie of foam .  mouth- full , creamy mouthfeel . fine carb .
a : poured a pitch black with a dark tan colored head . minimal lacing .  mouthfeel : fantastic . so smooth in the mouth and goes down easy .

s - strong aromas of banana bread , rum raisin and cinnamon t - dextrin malt tones , hints of the aromas above , but the 11 % alcohol dominates , especially in the middle , and mutes a lot of the potential this beer has .  chewy , and creamy , a perfect mild carbonation level for this style.. a lil warmth on the finish just to let you know , as chris rock would say `` slow down !
very pleasent . the taste kind of suprised me .  great body and nice hoppiness on the finish .

just like wine it is meant to accent and add different characteristics than take the lead in flavor . one smell of this brew and you can tell it is nearly a perfect length of barrel aging . roasty chocolate aomas , with vanilla and black currant esters . mollasses as well as the slightest bit of prune , are accented by the subtle oak aromas that seem to be nice and toasty . very roasty and a long finish that is very tannic and chewy . nicely balanced and largely complex . i think i would have rated a little higher if it were n't bone dry . nice burn in the chest .  m : actually leaves nothing - quite remarkable for a style that literally erodes the parts of my body it comes into contact with .

color is a deep reddish amber and a thick tan head leaves exceptional thick rings of lace .  m : man this just feels like it belongs in my mouth . o : excellent taste , exceptional mouthfeel and just an overall amazing experience .

pours dark amber with crimson and brown tones .  lightly carbonated with a great aftertaste of wheat & blackberry . other than that this beer is tasty , the malt shines through , the hops are just mild enough to notice , mouthfeel is amazing ... but the blackberry is just overpowering .

s- the aroma is fantastic , big espresso coffee aroma , roasted malts , oats , some cocoa and chocolate come out in the background . o- this is a solid beer from founders , love the roasty notes , and the big coffee presence , perfect winter beer .  incredibly smooth , and fairly easy drinking for it 's strength . absolutely excellent .

nice prominent frsh citrusy hop aroma . west coast style apa all the way . a nice apa but a bit light in body ... ( $ 1.89 / 12 oz .  damn this is one thick beer ; milkshake is about the best way to describe it .

smells incredible , like hickory or mesquite smoke and just a hint of the malt reminding me this is a beer and not beef jerky .  it was lush , creamy , smooth , rich , decadant and full . a very full bodied stout with a low carbonation .

from bomber to pint a : pours a copper-tan , light carbonation , little head and no lacing n : pumpkin and nutmeg , light lemon-citrus hop poking through t : hearty rich pumpkin pie , lightly bitter hops with an earthy , tea edge .  m : by far the highlight of this brew for me . rich and creamy with a perfect level of carbonation . nice feel here .
poured from a 22oz bottle into a glass a- beautiful ! a dark black color with a moderately thick tan head .  the mouthfeel is impressively creamy .
however the smell and taste was excellent . it tasted of roasted coffee and raisins .  m - very creamy . just a small sip seems to coat the inside of the mouth very well .
one of the best smelling ipas out there .  mouthfeel is perfect , goose island is the best of the best in this regard .

aroma of the classic quad , full , thick and rich . dense , complicated , rewarding , vinous . taste follows the nose and delivers a quality traditional quad , full , thick and rich .  a : as others have said , its an opaque black ; the head is tan , and leaves a very slight lacing along the glass s : coffee , dark chocolate , spices , and alcohol ; only wish the smell was a bit stronger t : the flavor is intense with chocolate , caramel , and dark fruits followed by a spiced aftertaste ; it is only slightly bitter and there is no alcohol apparent in the taste m : carbonation is perfect ; definately does not feel watered down d : at 13 % alcohol any more than two drinks is excessive , and one may be the perfect number overall , its a great beer .
smell dark malts , a inviting chocolate smell with a beautiful sweetness .  incredibly smooth , despite lingering bitterness .

some of the freshest hops i have ever smelled in a commercial brew ... quite reminiscent of a batch of homebrew deliciousness . assertive floral hops with hints of pineapple sweetness / tartness given possibly by the malt . very clean finish . overall : truly amazed at the smell on this one .  thick , creamy , velvety , perfection . the mouthfeel in big stouts is key , and this hits spot on .
smells of very fragrant hops .  '' the mouthfeel was silky , the body full and the carbonation perfectly soft . enjoyable , but it 's really an american stout contrary to the label at the bar .

the aroma is fucking badass . not some insipid , bourgeois , fine-ground and drip-brewed coffee ; more like french pressed boutique beans . very strong and very impressive ; the beer hides underneath with the same quality dark malt character as usual .  chocolate nutty goodness md - smooth and perfect off the cask .

its decent but lets get realistic fellas ... .a very light but clear copper , very good retention , even better lacing ... the aroma is super nice and balanced , malty caramel on the front with an awesome slightly grass and floral and strong hops , the hops really make this aroma nice . light lemon citrus on the back ... the taste is a big let down from the aroma . get rid of the malt and this might really be good . worth a shot , especially if you like esbs .  mouthfeel - this is superb . a little sticky ; its creamy and thick with the perfect level of carbonation .

if this beer was n't brewed just days ago , i 'd be extremely surprised . the nose is a perfect example of why freshness is paramount in ipas .  taste the weizen gives way to the bock as it warms mf : medim/heavy bodied with low carbonation & nicely balanced drinks very easy for the abv , a really nice weizen bock .
s : simply fantastic . i think i literally spent more time smelling this beer than i did drinking it . great stuff .  silky smooth and creamy mouth feel . such body without being cloying .
smell deep , rich coffee aroma with mild chocolate scents . the heavily toasted malt smell came out as well in this nose .  medium bodied and oily . simply exceptional .

a : nearly faultless . rich mahogany color , incredibly puffy 1 '' head that lasts forever , nice lacing .  mouthfeel is thick and creamy , which is what smooths out the bitter roast flavours so well . carbonation is not overdone , just right .

served in a pint glass this beer pours a motor oil black . it may be categorized here as a smoked beer , but this has the rich sexy dark brown foam and black body of an amazing stout .  the mouthfeel really shines here , it 's bright and crisp and creamy . good body .

aroma : smokey ? coriander rules ! all in all , enchanting . appearance : oddly , viewed from the side it showed significant hazy , but it was clear when viewed from the top .  mouthfeel is thick , chew , viscous .
a : this is a great looking imperial stout : black in color with a nice mocha colored foam .  feels like velvet on my tongue and one of the smoothest stouts in recent memory .

weihenstephaner vitus | 500 ml . appearance : hazed , glowing , straw-colored concoction . the massive , wintery head and abundance of fine lace warms the cockles of my heart . aroma : big banana/plantain aroma , peppered with clove , on bready background . taste : nutty , lightly toasted bread , spicy alcohol , fruity banana and asian pear . mouthfeel : sticky , chewy , slick , prickly , sharp . good carbonation . harmony : you 're doused in flavor towards the end of the sip , though the beginning is a bit lackluster . i actually found the taste to be the least endearing aspect . i was blown away by the nose . it works cohesively , though i sense a strong and unfavorable imbalance of flavor towards the end of the sip . the bros. are absolutely right : this is fine on its own but would go oh so well with some fine bread and cheese ( i 'd call for some aged gouda or edam ) .  the body of this beer was exceptional , thick , clean , and enjoyable .

d : great start , with looks and smell , but once i really got to know this beer , its palatability went downhill .  maybe a peachlike taste in the mix , but honey and herbs are the main ones i sense , mouthfeel- super smooth and low carbonation . very creamy and velvety . nice !

smell was immense and powerful , i could smell this brew several inches away from me . smell is pleasant , with notes of malt , apples , and yeast .  this has a wonderful mouthfeel which i absolutely love .

very hoppy when taking a nice whiff ( cascade mostly ) w/ bright citrussy aromas ( grapefruit ) and a distinct grainy malt that reminded me of dry cheerios . also a slightly sweet sugary maltiness creeps through as well making this seem very interesting . taking the first sip , the hops comes through with a vengence .  t & m- impeccable smoothness within the lush full body .
smell was exceptional - vanilla , wood , almonds , caramel ... very , very nice and remniscent of a cognac or similar nice sipping liquor ( w/o any strong alcohol smell ) .  wonderful mouthfeel .
it smells roasty , the way a brewery smells when you take a tour . inviting . spicy bitterness up front , and not too much else .  palate is sticky and smooth . wondrous ...

s- smells of `` big red '' chewing gum . cinnamon spice . t- cinnamon , maybe some nutmeg . m- very pleasant medium mouthfeel . d/o- drinkability is not bad , but is n't great either .  its actually really tasty ... hints of booze throughout keep you honest but this is really nice ... one of the most luxurious mouthfeels ever in my opinion ... it feels thick and creamy and coats the mouth on the finish very nicely.. overall , another winner ... i do n't like it as well as the first one of the series but this is really nice

appearance : ruby with chocolate hues , though this beer takes on brilliant strawberry pink hues under light . pours a big one inch head , with sticky lacing and good suds . the development of the beer under light is pretty unique and impressive .  m - i had it on tap , carbonation was perfect . a refreshing balanced beer .

wow , a strange sweet fruity mixture of smells . perhaps the most interesting beer i 've smelled . smooth and just a tad heavy . quite stout like . '' i could n't drink a lot of these , although it 's very nice . it 's not as heavy going down as much as the way it sits inside you .  m big for sure with high abv , grapefruit hops but surprisingly smooth mouthfeel which is made that way by a consistent and thick carbonation .

gorgeous , i can hardly wait to drink this beer it looks so good ( i write that after having drank it ) . beautiful light read with perfectly accompanied head .  m - exceptional . creamy , medium body with strong carbonation .

that said : the aroma is quite special , and definitely brings memories of the holiday season . it 's almost nice enough to enjoy by itself ; reading a leatherbound copy of `` a christmas carol '' in front of a low burning fireplace with its sweet and spicy aroma continually reminding you that your glass is sitting beside you . the head is pillow-like at first , but receedes to a nice 1/16 '' that lasts to the end . this year 's seems to have much less hop flavor and a reduced bitterness which gives the malt and spice a rounder flavor .  creamy and luscious body and wonderful layered complex flavors . pale malts , lead into corainder and tropical fruits with a yeasty belgian spice induced finish that lasts into a tingly carbonation with some hop bitterness . very nice .

this is overflowing of hop aroma . tropical fruitiness ... a bouquet of citrus ... the taste does not live up to the aroma . i love the aroma . at fist the taste is great , but wears down as it progresses . alcohol and plastic become more noticeable as it progresses .  i love it .

s : i love the smell of brett . some sourness , kind of tart , and sweet fruity aromas linger on . this is good , but the nose made me think i was in for something a bit different . a very interesting beer . the nose is full of bretty goodness . i think i would have preferred more of the funky brett flavor to come out instead of the hop bitterness . still this is very good , and something i would recommend .  m : medium to full bodied , lightly carbonated , and just the smoothest beer i have ever had . absolutely perfect .
appearance- a rich golden amber with a full head of foam that slowly dissapates leaving lacing on the glass .  creamy medium-full body with soft carbonation .
sweet nose of gingerbread , with faint roasted tones as well .  it 's full bodied and smooth with a very clean finish .
s - it has a very pungent sweet aroma . smells great ! m - full in body with light carbonation .  mouthfeel is luscious and creamy , very well done there ; average carbonation .

s- like a caramel macchiato : coffee , butterscotch , vanilla , toffee , cocoa ... lots going on here , and very pleasant . i only wish it were stronger . t- thin roasted malt with a little bit of bourbon coming through , but not much .  good balance of sweetness and alcohol warmth full body creamy mouthfeel rich is a good word sippability is great would n't mind having a few of these for special occasions

a : pours a very dark , but clear , maroon-amber body that passes glowing red light at the edges . two fingers of light tan head fill the snifter and recede over a minute or so into a light collar and tons of scattered bubbles on top of the brew . thick , sticky sheets of lacing left behind as the head vanishes , and more sticky lace during a sip . great appearance .  mouthfeel is great , really silky and smooth , perfect carbonation , very dry and a nice warming sensation .

the nose of the beer was simply amazing ! probably the best smelling beer i have ever experienced . something about it was very comforting , it reminded me of buttered toast with cinnamon and sugar piled on then a hint of alcohol .  its thick and syrupy and full of body and character . the alcohol warmth is soothing as it makes its way to the back of the tongue , leaving a sweet resin .

aromas are malty and almost burnt , with some graham cracker and chocolate in the nose . a very complex bouquet , with each sniff yielding new aromas and smells .  velvet mouthfeel ; tongue coating and heavy .
the smell of this beer is very sweet , and wonderful . however , the taste in my opinion did n't match the smell .  pure velvet mouthfeel here , no better bock .
smell is fantastic , pure belgian .  mouthfeel is full and round .

nose was exceptional - crisp , cool , very obviously citrus .  mouthfeel : wow this is a big beer with some nice carbonation on it . drinkability : well the alcohol taste was a little bit too much , but its wonderful mouthfeel just blew my mind .

i love the aroma of this beer ! just a hint of diacetyl butteriness , but i really did n't find it objectionable . mouthfeel is surprisingly thin , with some grapeskin-like astringency on the finish . drinkability is very good . a 22 oz .  gorgeous mouthfeel .
very nice overall .  mouthfeel : a perfect amount of carbonation .

nose is hoppy alright , juicy with bubblegum and minty notes . has a nice aroma , but i prefer nn over it . i prefer nugget nectar to this , but it was a fun beer to try .  perfect mouthfeel , actually .

amazing smell , roasted coffee , milk chocolate and heath bar . very earthy-mild hop character that is more pronounced than i have experienced in a porter , but it is pleasant . biscuity consistency with each sip , malt forward with a heavy roasted presence .  m : lovely viscous feel . perfect .

then there is the smell -- noble hop heaven . layer upon layer of delicious hops . the taste is similar to the smell : a lot of hops .  m- surprisingly creamy with the visible amount of carbonation . very smooth . d- very drinkable and smooth .
smells : sweet but spicy smells protrude though a spectacular wave of citrus and floral hop characteristics .  the carbonation is medium and perfect . mouthfeel is great .

s : bright tart raspberries , chocolate , caramel and sweet sugars . dessert wine-like . incredibly inviting with layers of all things sweet and desserty . very rich , too rich in fact even for the pairing with the chocolate brownie .  the feel is smooth , full , creamy and rich ( without being overly thick ) . nice texture , coating .

an aroma like fine brandy with hints of cherry and black cherry . wow again i am remindec of brandy .  taste : toast , caramel , white pepper , coffee bean , tons of malt , chocolate , banana , vanilla bean , ripe strawberry - the most flavor i 've gotten out of a brown ale mouthfeel : soft , calming mouthfeel with nice smooth tannins leaving the mouth coated with a slowly vanishing flavor profile that 's rather fun to dissect .

great 1 finger dark brown head . head is much darker than most stouts i see these days with the body pitch black . funny i do n't really detect the espresso .  also was surprised by how creamy this went down . this is a pleasure on the tongue .
good-looking black color with creamy head on tap .  mf & d - sticky and delicious . just the right amount of carbonation and alcohol content to keep the porter balanced .

s- malty heaven . i love the sweet malty aroma and will sometimes just sit and enjoy . how cool that a beer smells this strong . t- malty sweetness up front with dark sugar notes . sweet in a very good way ... but hops keep things in check . this is far different . very good !  creamy , almost soupy mouthfeel .
the taste is equally as enjoyable as the smell . very fresh taste , crisp taste , great hop to malt balance .  very nice on the palate a very full and pleasing mouthfeel .

the beer poured into the chalice crystal clear ruby red with a white frothy head which rose and retreated slowly to lace the chalice from top to bottom .  the lack of carbonation really helps the mouthfeel of this .

s : very aromatic . aromas of raspberries , caramel , apple , plum , apple and cherry pie , cheesecake , and sour candy . t : same as aroma . does n't taste like beer at all , tastes like liquid raspberry cobbler . exquisite in every category .  perfect . overall , i think it 's really nice beer and i 'm enjoying it .

nose is still incredible - just exploding with tart fruit ( currants but could easily be mistaken for raspberry ) and some hints of his wheat origin . this is an excellent summer beer and would be great with spicy food .  wonderful body .

it is a big bold german style hefe with a wonderous banana aroma mixed with what i really believe to be brett . now , i know this is not really true to style at all but this smelled like heaven -- all funky et all . the flavor was definately a bit of a let down , as the brett character was not as prevelant , but i could see that it was still there .  mouthfeel is a regal velvet ( likely due to the oatmeal ) , coating the mouth with a smooth creamy layer . so smooth . excellent .

a very delightful smell . some traces of malt in the background , but this is all about the hops .  mouthfeel is creamy and exceptionally full , yet really heavy , on the lighter side , and very soft . mouthfeel was clearly the biggest beneficiary of the addition of the bivalves .
before i could even pour it , my entire kitchen smells like mexican mocha . huge chocolate aroma . impressive !  the mouthfeel is great , perfectly coating .

t - taste is like the aroma , complex , fruity and overall fantastic . overall , a beautiful and fantastic smelling beer only knocked down by the strong alcohol flavor .  mouthfeel is a great chewy , creamy and smooth ale , the way a brown ale should be .
the aroma is fantastic . it 's a boquet of floral hops .  mouthfeel- creamy and a bit thick . super smooth and very drinkable .

nose is great , offering bold notes of bitter chocolate , coffee , and roasted malt with secondary characteristics of anise and molasses . still a damn good beer , but this there 's so much fierce competition in the style that , for me , you really have to earn your as .  there is the perfect amount of carbonation for the style .
s-smells of banana bread , some dark fruit , and a bit of roasted and chocolate malts .  m : surprisingly light and smooth . excellent for style .

a wonderful , piney smell with alcohol that is balanced well with the malt . exceptional taste , which is similar to the smell . does n't taste like a double but a well balanced , very hearty ipa .  mouthfeel is amazingly smooth . almost creamy , but not annoyingly so . very good . overall it 's pretty good , the mouthfeel is great .
really impressive . complex as hell with everything blending together well . straw and musky funk up front . brett comes through much better though .  excellent mouthfeel .

pours a jet black stout like color . leaves a very nice creamy , slow sliding lacing around the glass . a great looking beer !  $ 11.88 a : near opaque with ever-so-slight deep copper color peeking through , poured nice brown head that dissipated within time s : mild nose , treacle , roasted malt and oak t : mellow , well-aged with leathery oak up front and nice , deep roasted malt with a bit more hop bite than expected , etoh is noticeable and deep whiskey is dominant m : chocolate , oak , velvety and creamy with a nice light hop bitterness finish o : very good beer

s : honey , malts , wheat great nose on this . t : banana and cloves dominate the flavor .  feel is very nice - medium bodied with plenty of carbonation . the carbonation makes the beer feel so smooth in the mouth .

the smell on this brew is fresh hops , almost but not quite citrus , and a sweet malt forward honeyed tingle . the flavor has some spiciness to it but on the whole was actually quite unimpressive i thought , including the mouthfeel in that i was suprised at how thin and bland it tasted and felt .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with appropriately low carbonation , and a silky , creamy texture . the mouthfeel of this beer is one of the best i have encountered in a beer .

a thin bubbly tan head disappates quickly , though lots of carbonation is visible . the aroma is quite sweet , reminding me of caramel , burnt sugar , and malt . a unique rendition , but not what i look to get from the style .  m : really nice and unique .
quite nice . taste : unfortunately , the taste does n't stand up to the smell .  touches of carbonation throughout , the mild breakups of tingling yield a remarkably smooth bevvy .

the aroma calls to mind pleasant afternoons in the cool of spring meadows , much unlike the weather in columbus right now . lemon zest , lemongrass , prairie grass and crisp , fresh apple . distinct clove note without being overly spicy . floral and pollen-like . whereas the aroma is devoid of any booziness , alcohol hits the palate hard . warmth finds the flavors more at ease but they never fully shine against the booze .  this has a very good mouthfeel .

the smell is the most reserved of any surly i have had , but very lively for the style . it 's either the pils malt used or the hops contained in this very fresh can . gummy candies right away , this fades revealing a subtle toasty aroma .  full bodied . perfect . the oats add some awesome smoothness .

solid , spot on aroma of strong nutmeg , vanilla and clove , lovely fruit scents of deep orange , tangerine and banana . oddly enough , this is slightly sour especially on the mid-palate and in terms of flavor , this reminds of hitachino nest weizen and that is a good thing . an odd beer for sure but quite tasty .  mouthfeel is exceptional , very smooth and soft carbonation and is not cloying or sticky on the palate , has a relatively dry finish .

pours a hazy orange-amber body , with a 1/2 '' slightly off-white head that sticks around for a while , then fades slowly to a thick film . spotty curtains of sticky lacing are left behind , and cling to the glass for quite a while .  mouthfeel is amazing . velvety .

aroma : this smells really delicious . there 's grapefruit , sweet orange , apricots , peaches , and cotton candy sweetness .  the mouthfeel fits this beauty of a beer - it is thick and pleasingly rich . the full amount of suggested aging did this beauty wonders .
s : smell really good . a bit too medicinal for me , but still pretty good .  mouthfeel is silky and full with a dry finish that reminds me of a light red wine .

just an enormous complex smelling stout . bits of flowery esters float around as well .  the mouthfeel is fantastic , crisp , clean , refreshing , but tasty as well . highly dirnkable , i think drinkable best describes this beer .

puns aside , this is an incredible-smelling rauchbier - the rich , authentic , pungent smoke is literally the only thing i can smell , and that 's perfect . t : smoke , smoke , smoke , wood , smoke , malt , smoke , smoke , bacon , smoke , cake , smoke , spam , eggs , spam , spam and ... sorry , got carried away there . nice . notes : awesome rauchbier , but not quite as awesome in the end as i found their urbock to be .  m - the shining characteristic of this brew is the well-balanced mouthfeel that 's thick and viscous but nice and smooth . i wish more stouts had the balls big john does , in terms of the mouthfeel .

it also exposes the most beer to the air developing one of the best beer aromas i have ever known . this is a beer for the nose . it always starts strongly floral and changes with the tempature . there is some hint of citrus followed by fresh hay , and yeast . the beer itself is dark amber and cloudy . i always dump it all in . the taste is at least as complex as the smell . the is just enough carbination to keep it all light . it is an amber ale and exhibits all the malty full bodies character of an ale . orval is in some class of its own and must be experienced to fully understand .  t/m : a silky mouthfeel , with a smooth mellow finish . the finish is a crazy good bold , non-carbonated brown sugar smoothness that can not be beat . a mellow body with the sweetness of brandy , this is truly a great brew .

s- perfect . a hop monster being over taken quickly by malty goodness . t- amazingly hoppy and bitter , but still almost balanced by caramel malt that makes it delicious .  mouthfeel is thick and creamy and everything i could ask for . the tartness keeps pulling you in like a siren , and i am totally captivated by her song .
jet black , with complete absorbance . lofty , dense , steadfast light bister head leaves sticky , coating lace .  all things considered , a perfect mouthfeel .

it 's a great , thick , luxurious smell . thaste is much the same , but the burned malt/coffee flavor blanketed by cloying sweet/sour taste .  mouthfeel plays a big part in the taste , with the just-right amount of carbonation spreading the tastiness around and the nice medium body giving the brew a very creamy character .

s- big nose of hops mostly pine and grassy . hard to pick much else out through the hops but some roasted malt and caramel is hiding in there . t- big blast of floral hops right away that lasts through to the finish . hops change in character from floral to bitter at the finish . some notes of malt , chocolate , and caramel at the finish as well but hidden behind the bitterness of the hops . finish is astringent , boozy and with the lingering feeling of the hop oil .  m - fantastic mouthfeel ; one of the best imperial stouts out there in this respect .

great divide hercules ipa 22oz bottle 3 month recent bottling of review date 07/06 slow pour in a tulip glass poured copper with a thick fluffy , slightly gunky , yellowish long-lasting head smelt of floral and citrus , a hint of pine and alcohol taste was a deceptively fast accent to hops with a lingering hoppy finish .  exceptional mouthfeel - almost perfect , no , actually perfect ! smells & tastes great - nice carapills caramel sweetness after a trip on the c hops ( cascade for sho ' ) train .

it 's the smell that 's the stunner on this one . absolutely gorgeous aroma ; one the best-smelling beers i 've come across .  mouthfeel is top notch though , smooth as hell , velvety , chewy and creamy , medium-bodied and showing a perfect amount of carbonation .
this is wonderful . t- a lot different than the smell .  m : this beer is full and lush . it is almost chewy . the carbonation is noticeable .

s- sweet cranberry/strawberry.some pines but not as much as i would have expected in reading the label .  this beer is full bodied and velvety smooth . it is a little high in alcohol , but the smooth mouthfeel and nice flavor would go a long way .

pours opaque black with a 1 inch creamy tan head that lasts for a lifetime after the cascading brown bubbles stop and settle ; great looking stout that sets the standard for stout looks with great lacing that leaves thick rings . guinness is always impressive to look at when it poured properly from a tap .  m : great silky smooth feel . definitely a creamy feel .

very dark chocolate in color with a beautifull soft creamh white lace ... .the smell is fantastic ... i think it 's the yeast strain but i love the smell of this ... unique smell that is tough to put words to ... .the taste is non descript ... almost a bit of sourness to it so maybe the bottle is going bad ... this has to be a bad bottle ... the sourness is really shining through ... not much to speak of in regards to specific flavors because the sourness is killing it all ... i 'm a trooper though and will finish it ... hey maybe that great yeast strain i like is actually spoiled beer !  mouthfeel is rich and creamy .

great fresh hoppyness in the taste , great green grass smell , pine , together with some apricots , i would say , and some milky chocolate malts .  mouthfeel : full-bodied . medium carbonation . very soft and velvety on the tongue , like the texture of melted chocolate ice cream .

very unique and intriguing . light-medium bodied and thirst quenching . great refreshing flavor , mouthfeel and aroma . just a really great beer all around .  m= really smooth tastes really smooth . really nice . smooth crisp clean and sweet at the same time .

smell is huge . molasses hits up front , dominating all else . everything is taken to the next level by the great alcohol aroma . taste is sweet , fruity , and boozy , nowhere near as complex as the smell . super roasted , the only balancing factor is the bitter alcohol on the finish . drinkability is actually quite good , if you 're in the mood for a strong old ale . overall , not the best i 've had , but a good beer nonetheless .  a big dose of chocolate . so let 's do up the chocolate . some malts and some hops , all to support the chocolate . smooth and creamy .
smell - very fruity and sweet . raisins , cherries , and honey . delicious ... smells like dessert .  mouthfeel is superb , creamy , velvety , perhaps the best i 've had for this style .
i thought this smelled wonderful , these guys do get the aromas ' of there brews right .  creamy palate , just awesome . not as cedary as i 'd expected given the title , but i like the subtlety .

nose : ripe bananas , nilla wafers , lemon zest , tiniest touch of clove . taste : clove bite , peppery , sweet unidentifiable fruit ( not banana like i would expect , but maybe ripe pear/pear skin ?  mouthfeel , on the other hand , is superb . medium thickness , outstanding creaminess and richness .
yes , the cellar cleaning continues ! smell is rich & enticing , chocolate , malts , yumm . very nice . happy ending is n't as sweet as advertised by the stink .  mf is creamy , and quite nice .

aroma is amazing , the best i have felt in hemp beer , it feels like lingering next to coffee shop entrance in the netherlands . overall , the flavour was average , but i enjoyed the aroma immensely .  effortlessly coats the mouth completely and finishes sticky & sweet with a bit more of the peppery hops .

aroma-powerful hefeweizen aromatics-overripe bananas , ground cloves , and wheat bread . it smells sweet , spritzy , and fresh . one of the better ( and most powerful ) smelling hefeweizens i 've ever encountered , this one falls a bit short in terms of flavor and mouthfeel . still , a delicious beer .  m - beautiful mouthfeel and impressive balance for such a powerful brew .

wonderful peachy aroma . some tartness , but mostly sweet , syrupy peaches .  feel is thick yet subtle soft and a fairly easy clean finish . this beer is a politician : drinkability talks an easy talk but once this gets going , the abv will lie and before you know it ... . thanks to our fellow ba resident calvinist geofffromsj who astutely taught me today that `` jesus saves , moses invests .
a decent dopplebock , smells awesome , but down here fom there .  smooth on the way down and a very dry finish . this stuff is heavy and good .
smells fantastic . loads of caramel , toffee , dried fruits , nuts , and earthy hops with wisps of roasted and toasted malts .  perfect carbonation , which i am growing to expect from oskar blues .
different , but good . ( t ) - heavy on the spices up front .  mouthfeel : excellent . thick yet balanced with the carbination .
mix of citrus and tropical fruits , possibly the perfect combo .  supremely smooth . it 's just silky smooth across the tongue , the carbonation working to prevent it from becoming syrupy .

loved the ginger flavor , but not one of the best spiced ales i 've had . definitely worth a try , especially if you like ginger . the beer spells fantastic ! it 's fresh and easy to drink .  medium bodied and very creamy . carbonation is perfect .

poured into a dfh snifter , formed a 1 1/4 '' tan head over the clear burgundy brew . dense head lasts and lasts and lasts , with thick coating lace .  not as strong as i anticipated from the aroma and color , but the flavors pop out very easily m : very smooth , almost like milk and very full bodied with a low amount of carbonation . there is a creaminess that lingers on the forefront of the mouth for a few seconds d : very drinkable for a stout beer .

although the hops are very aromatic the malt comes through nicely in the background sweetening it up a bit and leaving a pleasant grassy character . d/n - pretty drinkable stuff here .  rich , velvety mouthfeel , unctuous and puckering .

wow , this one smelled great . tastes of caramel , vanilla , bourbon , wood , nuts , raisins , and a light earthiness .  much lighter body than the bottle of extra stout i just had ; also a little more tart which was what i was looking for . roasted malts and hard water . mouthfeel is where it really shines . smooth like silk . goes down like water .

very balanced and great complexity . definitely shows its age . the nose on this beer is absolutely amazing . one of the most dirty , stinky , and funky gueuzes that ive ever had the privilege of smelling . however , taste wise , its not much different than a well-aged classic gueuze .  first sip reveals a rich and firmly textured beer of elegant character . an encore presence by the hops closes out the taste in a long and seamless finish . faultless balance , beautiful complexity both in the nose and on the tongue make this beer , in my opinion , a perfect desert beer or soothing winter warmer .

the aroma is fantastic . juicy red wine notes mix to perfection with deep roasted malt tones . very enjoyable .  superb . d - this is a tasty beer , but the fusel alcohol character and high alcohol in general make me appreciate it less fully .
very promising smells . tastes sweet , spiced and with some definite squash flavors along with dark chocolate and roasted malt .  very full , creamy body that 's quite impressive for the abv .
the smell is quite nice , its a bit yeasty , and smells like raspberries and oranges .  light and full in the mouth , just a lovely feel .
s - smells like pumpkin pie , with some anise and roasty character in the background .  perfect for the style .

this is a tough one to grade for me since its a pumpkin ale , and i hardly noticed any evidence of pumpkin in it . smell and taste are very similar and are just like fresh ginger snaps right out of the oven .  m- the mouthfeel is fantastic . full bodied with a perfect amount of carbonation .

two inches of light brown head with nice retention . the thickest of lacing . this looks perfect .  dark coffee , bittersweet chocolate , toffee , dark wheat bread , smoke , spices that are tough to identify but clearly at work ... all mingled together in perfect measure . super smooth and velvety , although not what i would call creamy . largely because the body is n't a heavy one , but this texture comes with a terrific caress that does not leave me wanting .
this poured a lovely pale with nice white head that would not go away .  it has a velvety mouthfeel .
s- i love the aroma , this one is packing a lot of hops . overall , i think this is a very good dipa that i 'm glad i tried .  incredibly smooth and goes down easy .

smells great but fake .  there was a nice hop bitter punch right in the beginning , but then it just mellows out with a malty smoothness that is unreal . mouthfeel is one of a kind , smooth , chewy , sticky ... .very nice . this could be a very dangerous beer as it goes down ultra smooth ... would you like another ?

pours a deep dark brown with thick creamy dark khaki head that leaves lots of lacing !  creaminess only found in the most fattening of milk shakes . oppression at its finest . : ) one is perfect for me , thank you .

pours from the bottle to a nice copper color , with thousands of infused carbonation bubbles and a thick off-white head that lingers thru most of the glass and leaves very good lacing .  t - bananas , caramel , and mild dates swim around sour-yeastiness and vanilla , concealing well the alcohol that lies beneath ... m - very , very smooth , medium body massages the palate and dries the cheeks . d - nice , very nice , do n't know if i 'd get it again , but very nice .

black with 2+ cm of brown head , some lacing s - espresso , alcohol , some chocolate , roasted barley t - roasted barley , coffee , and then some hops . it 's somewhat subdued for an ris , but it 's still a great , cheap beer .  mouthfeel : wow is this stuff smooth . very silky and perfect carbonation .
smells pretty damn amazing and changes as it warms up . i 'm very glad i had to chance to try this , but i prefer kbs .  the mouthfeel is great . what a light and delicate brew .
the beer pours a pitch black thick viscous color with a dense spongy tan head formingup 2 cm easily and fading slowly .  mouthfeel is ideal : medium bodied and a medium-high carbonation .
it 's a beautiful looking beer , very clear .  on the first sip , the feel was like i opened my mouth , closed my eyes , and had someone pour silk into my mouth . beautiful . hence the 5 .

s : great mix of grainy/bready malt with clean and crisp , well defined banana ester and clove like phenol character . d : great nose , i wish the taste was as good .  mouthfeel is super creamy , milkshake like .

a - medium to dark brown colored body with a good inch of medium tan head . the head fades slowly into a frothy foam at about a quarter inch .  quite unique . perfect mouthfeel - enough creaminess and carbonation to soften the bitterness and create a warm , rich feel .

1/8 '' head , chocolate milk in color . i am loving the smell . taste - 4.5 way more subtle than i was expecting .  m - the feel is surprisingly rich for the genre , smooth and oh so drinkable , nicely done !

this beer smells absolutely amazing once the cap is off . it pours a nice dark stout body , with a nice tan head . the first sip of this beer is really overtaken by the aroma . definitely serving it at 42 like described is a good idea .  mouthfeel is exceptional . thick and rich but not too much .

ample white , creamy cover has a good amount of stickiness and lace , nice . aroma - juicy pineapple , grapefruit , and a resiny pine as well . taste - fair biscuity malt base , followed immediately by a stiff resiny smack of hops .  mouthfeel is very soft and smooth on this medium-heavy brew .
beautiful hazy golden , with a large frothy head . very lovely and thick 2-finger lace . a beauty !  smooth as velvet , i love what oak-aging does to impy stouts .

wonderful aroma . mix of bright , citrusy , fresh hop aromas and a cookie-like malt sweetness . malty sweet presence comes on surprisingly strong and overwhelms some of the hop complexity . still , a very drinkable , flavorful ipa .  the mouthfeel is delightful . up front the beer is very rich and the oak really shines through with this age on it . nicely mouth coating , and the intense finish with a great deal of carbonation and bitterness refreshes the palate for another sip . love this beer , 2010 and 2011 review to be added another day .
this beer poured really dark with a thin head as about as dark tan of a head as you will ever see .  a very smooth and creamy cask ale , that goes down very well .
i love it . nice golden amber color and beautiful frothy head and lacing . good steady carbonation .  very soft carbonation but a full , chewy body .

( edited after finish 2nd bottle ) a : dark and roasted coffee lacing with a pitch dark chocolate brown color to match the head . lacing is like cake .  m : thick , syrupy viscosity with light carbonation -- exactly as a beer of this style should be .

appearance - nice copper red color with a bold head smell - wonderful citrus nose which was really distinctive ; after smelling it i could n't wait to taste it ; in the end , i found this was a beer that i would prefer to smell rather than to taste taste - first the malt hits you and tends to coat your tongue in a very odd way and then the hops kick in and make their presence felt ; for me , the sweet and bitter combination could have been great if it was n't so unbalanced .  the mouthfeel is very much like drinking liquid chocolate or marshmallow fluff . so rich , creamy , and very full in the mouth .

'' the scent is amazing . floral , extremely hoppy , and thick . taste is a little odd after inhaling that wonderful scent . i expected much more of a kick than i got . very interesting . flows smoothly over my tongue .  looks like a stout should , dark and opaque , not quite black , with a slight tan head smells like burned caramel cookies tastes like coffee with the forementioned cookies great mouthfeel , not too chewy i could drink a couple of these
very beautiful to look at . the color is just awesome !  mouthfeel is perfect , medium bodied with a champagne silkiness that is delectable when swirled .

the best part about this beer though is its aroma . just plain hoppy goodness . citrus with some pineapple , maybe a touch grassy .  mouthfeel is extremely smooth & this is one of the most drinkable beers around .
the smell is wonderful , fruity at first , and then chocolatey , with maybe a hint of coffee .  the texture , in its sublime perfection , is creamy like a milkshake ... unbelievable .

great look , really .  whoa was it thick ! an outstanding beer , i was extremely excited to be able to say i 've tasted it . as it warms in the glass , the bite grows stronger . maybe this brew would be better appreciated by some experienced brewmasters , i thought it was a good beer but i ca n't justify rating it an a+ or 5 , because i would n't buy a bottle again . the two beers that ultimately create this beast are exquisite , but this monster was n't for me .

aroma is sweet , fruity , ( raisins , plums ) malty with a little milk chocolate ( whoppers candy ) . lively mouth-feel . flavor does not quite come together tho . it has a mix of sweet fruits , sourdough bread , bitter citrus pith , but it just doesnt seem to be balanced .  t & m- lush creamy smoothness in a heavenly full body .

what a fantastic smell to this one . a bit lost there ... it 's a good ipa but it 's not quite as well rounded as i 'd prefer .  this one is thick and chewy , coats the inside of the mouth , and the flavors linger , especially the burnt coffee .

i poured a 12 ounce capped bottle into a tulip . a : it poured a dark thick black with a dark rich chocolate head that was massive , sticky and lingering . as the head slowly fell it left a bold lacing around the glass .  mouthfeel is smooth and heavy bodied with a very light carbonation , excellent .

taste- sweet , tropical fruits as in the nose , hop bitterness . feel- medium carbonation.. creamy ... yummy overall this is a really good ipa ... kind of reminds me of union jack .  texture is silky smooth and it does n't feel nearly as strong as it actually is .
great retention with a ton of lace .  mouthfeel : omigaw , it 's so creamy . so very , very creamy . `` luscious '' is the word that comes to mind .

the nose promises a lot , but the taste is something of a disappointment . i do n't think i 'll buy this again unless i want to stand around like an idiot swirling and smelling my beer without ever tasting it .  the body is surprisingly thick and coating with a rich slick mouth feel .

smell : upfront is a nutty note that seems to be a nut brown mixed with a stout so it creates a unique nuttiness . there is some roast to the beer as well and of course some chocolate notes smells exactly what a black n tan should smell like taste : the taste for me kind of falls short and kills this beer for me .  mouthfeel is beautiful with sweetness up front followed by a sting from carbonation and finishing with a crisp dry bitterness .
wonderful floral hop aroma right off . appearance is just above average .  feels great . 5/5 d : yes , for the style and abv , it is .

s - caramel , campfire , fresh grapes ( not an aged grape smell , which makes me think this will have a lot of life still ) , black cherry . overall - mute flavor , but the nose is amazing .  very smooth . mouthfeel is full and round .

4.5 s : toasty malts give a nuttiness . sweet caramel and toffee with a slight roastiness . complex with the flavors all working together . 3.0 t : while flavors that worked so well together in the nose , do no such thing in the taste . in any case , i do n't know where this sour grape component is coming from , because there is no mention of it in the description .  mouthfeel is top notch , so smooth and light yet complex at the same time .

the aroma however is a little more impressive , smokey , burnt toffee , mocha , and roasted grain were pretty strong , definetely got my mouth watering .  a nice , balanced beer with a clean taste and a smooth , exceptional mouthfeel .

s : wow , that is the greenest nose i have ever smelled . huge fresh/wet hop aroma ... i ca n't stop smelling this beer . i have put my nose to the glass at least 20 times before tasting this one . t : wonderful crystal malts lay down a biscuity flavor which is very nice . very `` green '' hop flavor .  the mouthfeel is exceptional , big thick viscous and sticky and is amazingly velvety over my palate . really quite incredible .

12oz bottle poured into a pint glass a : very dark , opaque , with an inch and a half of dark tan head .  m : silky and creamy . d : i 've never had more than one chocolate stout at a time , and so i do n't know if i would get sick of a beer if i overdid it .
hop haze and alcohol feet are evident . the aroma is a good one , with predominant citrus and slight bitterness , with a nice malty , caramel aroma .  m - the mouthfeel of this brew is really nice .

the beer pours a coppery amber color , topped with a thick , creamy ivory head . great lacing and retention , leaving tons of clumpy lace all the way down the pint glass .  carbonation is perfect . with such a fantastic mouthfeel and perfectly bittersweet flavor profile , this is a breeze to put down .

this beer pours a lovely opaque black color fitting for its style . only a little bit of off-white/brown lacing clings to the sides of the glass a few minutes after pooring .  m- full bodied , creamy , thick luscious mouthfeel .

s - reference quality barrel-aged barleywine . surprisingly little overt alcohol too . m - full-boded , sticky , chewy , and just plain weighty - perfectly suited to the flavor profile and abv . d - i finished this faster than the other two , lower alcohol , beers .  4.5 m : thick , surprisingly thick and velvety , dry , warm alcohol , excellent . 5 d : easy drinking beer for the strength , excellent flavors , balance of spice and malts is nice , really a great beer .

for a fruit beer it is exceptional in smell . smell is of pure fresh blueberries .  the mouthfeel is astounding . with all the charged up carbonation , i was expecting a soda like fizzy mouthfeel , but i am pleased at the silky smooth , well rounded and succulent body of this ale .

smell is smokey burnt wood and malt -- exceptional . the taste is a little dry but its quite pleasant .  m- huge in the mouth chewy , creamy , and smooth . mild carbonation . nice clean finish , indicative of the nice alcohol levels .
the aroma is pretty nice . there 's definitely cocoa powder there .  m : feels great . perfect amount of carbonation .
granted it looks cool , but it 's a bit tough . a - clear orange with a big rocky head and amazing lace .  mouthfeel is light bodied and creamy smooth with a powerful refreshing carbonation .

excellent . t at the start , candy sugar , malt , low spice ( same as smell , a bit more peppery ) and an orange peel aftertaste with a nice bitter middle which is a bit of a plesant surprise .  the mouthfeel is the ultimate strongpoint on this beer . it is ridiculously creamy and very chewy , complemented with the perfect amount of carbonation .
aroma characteristics are of orange peel , coriander , and quite peppery .  mouthfeel is exceptional . big , small foam mouth , which smooths down , edgy all the way -- but never sharp .

very elegant . the taste is ... it is a very fine strong/old ale , but the flavours are disturbed by a dry smoky-salty flavour in the start .  may be a bit heavy heavy for some people to consider for a session , or for a really hot day- due to the thickness of the mouthfeel , but this is damn freakin good .
overall , bad appearance , but good aroma , feel , blend , and body .  mouthfeel is light medium and pretty smooth , crisp .
amazing aromas of strong caramel , maple syrup , coffee , chocolate .  m- good smoothness in mouthfeel .
lots of lacing . beautiful , simply beautiful .  nice and heavy feel . too big and lacking flavors from the malts to balance off the alcohol and bourbon .
looks awesome for a white beer in the glass .  m -- -medium bodied with good carbonation .

but here we go ... batch 8986 a : a nice transparent , light straw colored beer with a bone white head that quickly dissipates . this has the most crisp , citrusy , delicious aroma . perhaps the best smelling ipa in my opinion . i detect a grapefruit like aroma with a sweetness on the tail end . t : the hop aroma delivers . not as well balanced as hopslam , but never the less delicious . it is overall an exceptional beer , and among my favorite ipas .  mouthfeel : heavy bodied .

poured a massive tan frothy head ( granted it was a bit warmer ) but retained itself at a half finger for quite a while . very dark , almost black , but not hazy .  m - slightly oily , but not cloying at all , which is quite nice . the chewiness is enjoyable as well especially in the throat . i did n't feel ruined for the night from this beer , which i worry about with such strong flavors in this style .

zero head retention & lacing s : bubblegum , peaches & passion fruit t : fruity with hints of rome apples , peaches , apple skins , some earthy hops & rubber bands up front . kind of thin despite some alcohol presence at the end drinks alright , this seems a bit green for the style .  the bight of carbonation is very apparent and pleasing .

aromas of spicy candied pralines , red hots , licorice and lots of citrus esters and also honey after some time in the glass . very tasty now but will be curious to see how the hops and alcohol fades and whether more fruit and secondary flavors come through over time . very nice beer overall .  ever since , this has been a complete struggle to drink and one i wont go back to . it 's a good looking beer with good texture , and probably a valiant effort for people who do n't get onions from the hops .

pouring the color of old orange peels , that sort of burnished light ocher , this beer gives off a very pronounced floral & herb kind of yeasty aroma as a meagerly thin white head forms but then disappointingly dissipates . smells good , tastes ok , makes me want an oberon .  the mouthfeel was nice , however - nice and fizzy and refreshing .

s ~ a good dose of coco , chocolate syrup , hint of vanilla in there ... t ~ bitter chocolate ... .dry on the back ... lingering flavors of coco that stay behind well after the sip is gone m ~ lighter to medium bodied bock ... i like my chocolate beers thick and rich - s. tier chokolat ... this was a random bottle i picked up.. o ~ not bad ... i remember the hype behind the beer a year or two ago when it was in the bigger bottles for $ 15 per..glad i did n't buy one then and held out for the $ 1 something 12 ozer ... worth a try..but nothing super special..  mouthfeel - very carbonated , but good smooth texture overall .

aroma is cured meat , coffee , and roast . dry lingering smokey maple-y finish very nice i have had this in growler form before the hype train .  mouthfeel has a medium body with a slight creamy aspect . fits the style well and is enjoyable .

pours opaque , very black ... beautiful cascade resulting in one finger head of creamy foam . smells as if the nitro is masking it , very subdued and light malt ... but it is a light beer in body , so maybe thats jsut what you are stuck with .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation .

the nose is likewise attractive and is easily this beer 's best feature . there 's considerable orange citrus as well , but i suspected right off that this beer would be on the sweet side . as expected , the flavor profile is east coast ipa all the way , with the sweet malt completely overwhelming the hoppy bitterness in this dipa . the combination of sweet malt and noticeable alcoohol make drinking this beer very much a chore , and i ended up dumping my glass mid way through . what can i say ... this is just not my cup of tea .  mouthfeel : good carbonation , medium to full body , a slight dryness on the finish .

smells incredible -- huge vanilla bean notes over a chocolate and coffee presence with plenty of very-well-integrated brandy notes . overall -- wow . i shall not doubt the fff boys again when it comes to using the brandy barrels !  whatever it is ( or was ... ) seems to take over , i can taste nothing else m ) fine carbonation , bottle conditioned efervescent .

the retention of the delicate cap was terrific and the lacing prodigious . it looked great , felt great and smelled good but the taste just was n't what i wanted .  mouthfeel - light but not watery , possibly due to the big airy body carbonation .

smell is huge brandy . lots and lots of brandy followed by a strong sweetness . one of the most drinkable barrel aged beers i 've had and one of the best smelling beers i 've ever encountered  mouthfeel is very smooth .
a great aroma and a smooth taste make this a great beer .  m : nothing special , but not bad either . nice viscosity and carbonation .
a : dark brown , nearly opaque , lovely cappuccino-colored head that falls into a persistent cap with nice lacing .  their is a pleasant caramel base behind it with a good creamy mouthfeel .

like i said before , i love just smelling this beer . not too bad overall . i would love to try this on tap .  the taste is of a very crisp , dry lager . crisp as a cracker . someone said you drink this after cutting the grass .
22 oz . the aroma is extemely full and rich -- - a supersweetness slings tothe resinous that is wrapped around a loaf of bread .  mouthfeel : medium body with moderate carbonation .
incredibly complex , balanced , and appealing .  mouthfeel is dry and crisp , with a medium-light body .
a : the beer pours a rich dark color with a huge foamy caramel/parchment colored head .  m : smooth and nicely carbonated . the feel compensates for the taste .

s - pine upfront with citrus fruit and caramel in the background . t - very light caramel sweetness , some citrus tang in the middle and a good dose of bitter hops that continue into the aftertaste .  m : full , heavy body . really smooth .

smell is wonderful . perfect amount of vanilla , working with the roasted coffee notes . smells decadent .  not if you like an imperial stout , no . there is a little too much pitch ( black ) in the brew . that is a yummy chocolate nose about half way through , but a little chipped too much with yeast over-all , and maybe a bit too much biscuit ? you can have both better beers and better baltic porters .
after poured into a glass it 's great looking . extremely dark , white foam .  mouthfeel smooth and creamy with a dry hop bitterness at the finish .

big thanks to tayner for this great little brew.. into the dfh pint glass goes this pitch black brew , forming a very impressive khaki head and some of the best lacing i 've seen in a while.. terrific aroma of dark roasted malts , perhaps some cocoa and coffee , and what i 'm guessing is the brewers licorice talked about on the bottle .  average . m- very refreshing feel .

that 's 90 % of what 's there , and it 's beautiful . taste : this shows more of the alcohol than is perceptible in the nose , as well as a nice firm hop bitterness and bite . this is a bit simplistic , but good . mouthfeel : big and smooth drinkability : pretty high conclusion : the aromas are so much more pungent on-tap than out of the bottle , and are some of the best i 've ever smelled on a dipa .  m-really pretty rich and smooth in body with medium carbonation and a slightly slick mouthfeel .

real juicy malt aroma . caramel and toffee wrapped around fig and spices .  m : wow , that nitro widget adds a lot . light bodied but sooo seductively smooth and creamy ... it makes me think of a milkshake .

aroma - dark chocolate dominates the nose . overall - it smells much better than it tastes .  it has a medium body and a smooth mouthfeel , with the sour flavor laying on the tongue slightly . inbetween a medium and high carbonation , but fairly drinkable .

i pour this chilled sample into my pint glass and the hop aroma hits me immediately . but back to the appearance first . the aroma is dominated by hops , floral scents first then i pick up hiints of pine and some sour citrus notes too . i get a quick hint of sweetness coming through and then the hops take over .  you can smell the sweetness as well expressed in dark honey notes at the back end of the inhale , very nice taste etc ... the after taste is quit cloying and has my face contorted in all sorts of ways ( as if i aint ugly enough ... ) , the alcohol is a little hot also , this is at cellar temp and at only 8 % ( 8 aint what it used to be ) i was surprised . whew , have to take a break for a second and go grab some strong cheese to cut this with ... the sweetness on the second take was a little more negotiable but not exactly what i enjoy as far as my personal tastes go , this hangs out somewhere labeled `` just thick enough '' in terms of the ride through the mouth , the carbonation is dead on , it just rolls across the palette extremely well , the flavor is pretty straight forward ... this one lacks depth for me .

in all its a very nice , rich and sweet smelling beer . t- the taste is a bit disappointing based on the nice smell .  mouthfeel : medium bodied , the carbonation was right on the button as soon as i cracked the bottle .

smell : much better than the redhook , this smells pleasantly of floral , perfumy hops , with a little malt thrown in . drinkability : i 'm captivated by this beer 's aroma -- it must be similar to some perfume my mom wore when i was a baby , because i 'm irresistably drawn to it .  mouth was thick , not much alcohol , but that sour-grape aftertaste took control and finished as if it was champaign . there are a lot of flavors in this beer , but nothing really to rave about .
a - pours a huge puffy white head into a pint glass . the head sticks around forever and leaves some very nice lacing .  m : light bodied and crisp like a pilsner should be .

a - a very great looking beer . a black body on the bar , very dark brown if held up to some light , with red shining through on the edges . awesome fine bubble , off-white , two finger head that left intricate sheets and lace on the side .  m : full-bodied , frothy carbonation , pretty smooth , easy drinking for its size .

this smells like the perfume isle at dillards . very aromatic . for a pale ale this is a very interesting and different beer .  very rich , the sweetness pours over the tongue and almost demands a slow drinking pace .
a : pours a dark brown with some ruby around the edges .  light , crisp , refreshing body and feel- would be great on a hot day .

glass bottle- color of black , with a thick frothy tan head - nose of red fruit , malts , and roasted coffee taste of chocolate , subtle red fruit , malts , and roasted coffee- body is slightly watery , and with medium high carbonation aftertaste of red fruit , malts , and roasted coffee  '' m- as with most milk stouts , the mouthfeel is nice and smooth . almost creamy with a little carbonation to add a nice spritz .

s. a very pleasant scent of raspberries , raspberries and more raspberries with a hint of hops and sweet malts . one of the best smelling beers around . t. the taste starts off with some earthy floral hops , followed by some sweet sugary syrup and than some tart raspberries and finishes off with a hint of more hops . it has a nice smell and mouthfeel , but the taste was a let down , so unless i get it as an air freshener i know i 'll never buy this beer again .  mouthfeel is full and mellow in the carbonation .

good lacing & avergae head retention s : big-time citrus & piney hops t : piney & citrus hops up front , then a little fruittyness .  m : medium body . moderate carbonation that finishes with some fizz on the tip of my tongue .
pleasing pale yellow with sticky head , wonderful hoppy scent . the malts are so mild , they are hardly even there .  very light nicely carbonated .
beutifull beer with a huge white cap of dense white foam.clear or cloudy depending on the pour amber body .  medium bodied .

a - poured into a goblet and has a typical ris dark black color . great hot cocoa-colored head on this one that lasts for a while with tons of lacing .  m 4 the best part . medium plus body , creamy carbonation .
the aroma is nice , full of coffee and sweet cocoa . it is well blended with slight roasted notes very nice .  mf : light and carbonated well .

22oz bottle into a duvel tulip pours a deep almost opaque black with a nice frothy khaki head that lasts and leaves nice lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel : nice well-balanced carbonation with little hop bite .

s- smells exclusively like apples and cinnamon . a blend of apples , both tart and sweet with a slight hint of cinnamon at the end . t- it tastes like a cider more than a beer .  m- dry and crisp with good carbonation .

s : orange peel and grapefruit dominate , a syrupy sweet bitterness that is wicked bitter . the hoppiness is as floral as it is sharp , covering up all traces of malt ( and therefore all semblance of balance ) . t : the floral intricacies of the nose disappear in the face of an all-out assault on the senses ( at least taste ) . the hops are floral and full , awesome in their own right .  it does have a great thick mouthfeel and if i could n't taste anything i would enjoy this well enough .
s : great smell , so complex . really sweet and hoppy . malty over & undertones . excellent nose . got ta be the best part of this brew .  best by 4/25/11 .

one of the best smelling beers i 've ever had . huge , gushing pineapple notes lead the charge , followed by some pine notes . some pale malt notes in the background .  mouthfeel : fairly heavy and smooth overall : i 'm not at all sure the whole 'double wit ' thing works .

s : wonderful , i could really pick out the chocolate and coffee notes .  m - light bodied and dry just like a dry irish stout should be . medium carbonation with nice carbonic bite to aid in drying sensation .

a - it looked big . poured out black as black , with a huge 3 finger brown head , that settled down and layered the top of my glass .  a touch of burning alcohol on the finish , shocker . mouthfeel : actually pretty full , smooth , and round drinkability : 1 can after two other beers ( earlier ) is gon na get me buzzed i think , but the sweetness means i could never have more than one of these ( even if i wanted to ) conclusion : we were having crappy beer night tonight as a joke .
smell is a nice sweet citrus scent .  taste/mouthfeel : medium body with nice carbonation .

smell is dry and sweet . strong citrus , yeast , wet bread , and slight hits of alcohol ( stronger alcohol smell as the beer warms ) . a full bodied aroma with a fair amount of complexities . starts off strong and sweet and then finishes dry and bitter .  m : smooth , medium-heavy body with light carbonation d : pretty one dimensional in the chocolate note with little else there .
a - pours a brilliant dark reddish orange with a finger and a half khaki colored light bodied head that dissipates quickly .  mouthfeel is actually pretty good .

pours a cloudy golden ruby hue with a thick , light tan meringue-like head has amazing retention and leaves stunning cloud-like lacing .  this one has a `` bottled on 8-5-08 om it . i like the dating of beers . taste is warming , alchohol burn warming the inners . malty , raisins , figs and woodiness . i am tasting the mettalic aftertaste in this.good beer if i could get paste the metal .

the smell really got me excited for trying this , but the flavour is lacking a pumpkin finish . the pumpkin and cinnamon fad almost instantly .  it had a medium feel in my mouth and good carbonation .

tart and sweet ... just as a lambic should be . notes of berry , plum , tart , wet paper , and some definate earthy notes ; alot like eathing a blackberry that has yet to fully ripen . accordingly , a sour tongue-lashing ensues after each sip .  ah well ... mouthfeel is fine - it 's not as heavily carbonated as originally thought ( from the head ) . smooth and even .

on-cask at the brewpub : lovely off brown yellowy color as it casacades from the pull . finally settles to a very solid dark brownish black color with some dark ruby slivers nearer the bottom . it looks like chocolate milk sitting on top of used motor oil . gorgeous !  mouthfeel - a good mouthfeel . smooth and slightly oily , crisp carbonation , one of the better areas of the beer .

nice thick , vicious look to this ; above average lacing & some head retention s : green bananas , dark fruit , fusel booze and brown bread . t : dark fruit , candi sugar , & green bananas up front , pretty much mimics the nose , some doughy notes plus green appleskins .  m - highly carbonated with a medium-light body and soft , dry finish , the feel of this brew is still quite nice !

pours a very dark brown with a beautiful lingering head and good lacing as well .  citrus is there but should be stronger m : a bit sticky as well as quite refreshing in the finish d : could drink this one all night .

none of these ordors is particularly powereful but all are present and pleasant . not much subtlety in the flavor .  banana , pear , perhaps a citrusy taste as well m : good creamy mouthfeel d : i think what throws people with this beer is the appearance to it , looks like a miller lite .

the smell of this beer is outstanding ! the young malted barley scent pouring off this inexpensive brew is to die for . i love it . taste its not great , but bready , light-citrus , orange-peely tastes swim throughout this beer as well as the super-young-malt taste i loved in the smell . theres nothing noteworthy about its finish .  body is good and so is carbonation .

pour was absolutely beautiful .  m : mouthfeel is creamy and slick . let me say would have enjoyed the mouthfeel a lot more had i been consuming , say , a milkshake d : so thick , so chocolatey , that it took a lot of effort to finish this off .
s - pretty nice , like a tripel-lite . this was nice to try , but i 'll stick with other wits i have preferred .  very coating mouthfeel , stays with you .
cockeyed cooper pours a clear garnet color into the glass with a massive , frothy off white head on top .  medium mouthfeel .

to me this is a perfect pour ! a frothy 1 inch head that became pourous foam after about 1 minute but holds for a good 2 minutes .  active , tiny bubbly carbonation and a crisp , dry , smooth light bodied mouthfeel .

the aroma is very assertive with candied fruit , sugared hops and a touch of alcohol . the hoppiness has faded in this one a bit . a really nice way to end an evening .  carbonation was spirited making for a tingly mouthfeel .

t. not as sweet as the nose leads you to believe . decent malt sweetness , festive spices , cinnomon , cloves . d. a decent representation of the style , nicely spiced , not overpowered by sweetness .  effervescent up front , slight creaminess , good chewiness .
