went down to spuyten duyvil and figured i would have a gueuze during the night . the aroma was the big prize here . i could have kept smelling it all night , but i really wanted to taste it as well . i got a big whiff of apricot tartness in the smell and a large amount of barnyard funk . flavorwise this was quite nice , sweeter than i figured it would be , but it also had a sour quality that was much appreciated . this was the fruitiest gueuze i have ever tasted .  mouthfeel is decent , not too thin or thick .

the aromas blend together perfectly , creating a smell that is , in my opinion , perfect . t - whoa . this is a pretty bold beer - i think this was the strongest first taste of a beer i have ever taken .  mouthfeel is again average . fairly light with a decent amount of carbonation .

nose is unique , wonderful perfumy malt . sadly a slight sourness picked on the first few sips , then just more sourness noted messing up the usual lovely malt/hop balance , heady alcohol running throug the mix . this is tasty , distinctive stuff , worth seeking out , paying the $ , and savoring .  mouthfeel is good , chewy almost .

smell is enormous floral hops , lots of fruity citrus . one of the best i 've ever smelled . taste is fruity and hoppy like the smell , but without the maltiness i wanted there to be . i 'm glad i tried it , though .  fairly full in the mouth considering the abv .

the pour epuals a even 50/50 split , half head , half body . body is black which is very dark for a brown ale . head is a thick light mocha brown that stays a long while .  the flavor may have been off but the body is very nice as it has a semi-thick viscous texture without overwhelming the drinker . the body allows the flavors to be conveyed more smoothly than a higher bodied beer while the carbonation is mild enough to not contribute any carbonic bite .

s - the smell is right there where you want it : boozy , older , spicy , with notes of grape and caramel . t - it tastes as it smells , plus wood , and a caramel-toffee flavor .  m : medium-bodied , smooth , crisp carbonation , nice overall feel , but not a great finish , too bitter .

22 oz bomber poured into a duvel tulip glass . massively massive head . that is fantastic head ! the color itself was a very dark ruby red color . that 's an interesting color for an ipa , which i 'm guessing is due to the rye .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , some effervescence and a lingering bite .
a - clear golden orange colored brew , nice head , great retention and some bubbly lace .  mouthfeel is pretty good but at this point who cares ?
s- smells awesome ! very sweet and coffee-y with strong roasted aroma .  even so , it was pretty decently textured and carbonated .
s- the aroma really is fantastic . there is a lot of sweet malt and caramel along with some citrusy hops .  mouthfeel - smooth and full bodied with good carbonation .

smell : the nose is juicy and firm with a very hoppy smell . strong and potent , but a balanced smell . taste and mouthfeel : for a beer that is `` blessed with hops '' - it almost too balanced .  mouthfeel : lightly hop-oiled , ample carbonation , slightly chewy .

the aroma is the highlight of this beer , distinctly belgian yeast with floral hops and fruit , namely grapefruit and pear . the finish hits you with a bold hop bitterness that lingers for a while then slowly dies off , leaving you with a hint of sweet fruit . a great variation of one of the classic ipas .  it is very smooth , though , although that 's one of its few positive notes .
great aroma . coffee , roasted malt , brown sugar , rumlike molasses . decent .  mouthfeel : the body is on the thick side of medium . the carbonation is tingly with a dry finish .

s : piney with hints of citrus and some herbal notes with just a hint of sweetness . this smells like an ipa should t : flavors kick off with some nice herbal notes and a dash of caramel sweetness from the malt .  very very sweet . maybe the sweetest beer i 've ever had . i do n't taste any hops , and i ca n't say i really enjoy this one . chocolate cherry syrup comes to mind ( with some alchoholic kick ) . maybe dopplebock is not my favorite style . it might be good- its just too much and too concentrated for me to really enjoy . huge candy sweetness is not my thing , but if it 's yours - this might be good .

smell : heavy doses of caramel , chocolate , coffee , and black malts - all in equal proportion . alcohol is extremely faint but still there , and hop aroma might be even fainter . the perfect mix of malt aromas is the star here though , and really comes on in full force . this beer really seems to restrain itself , especially after such a promising , robust aroma . i tend to be skeptical of the trend for more , more , more , but it seems like this beer could actually use it .  well bodied for such a low abv beer .

a light maple amber . off-white head has great lace and nice retention . brackish , salty notes deep in the nose .  because i found higher allcohol beers overpowering i struggle to find a lot of other flavours however this did have a sweetness and some toasted grains lurking about but didnt really asault the palate the mouthfeel was the best part of this beer being balanced smooth and sweet.the swallowing was the disappointment .
it smells very good . effing amazing to be honest .  mouthfeel has a good medium body with a good hit of carbonation .

a dopplebock that has avoided me so i bought a pack recently . s : all dark fruit and burnt wood . i actually like the smell far more than the taste . t : dark chocolate , raisins and malt .  m : medium bodied , relatively light on the carbonation . it feels like a nice fall drink .

truly a wonderful smelling beer rivaling that of rodenbach itself . taste..what a c-tease from the aromas . it just seems like tom left this one in the barrels a bit too long .  m- medium bodied with ample carbonation .

smelled wonderful . fruity sweet , slighty floral hoppy .  in texture , the ale is very weakly carbonated and quite smooth ; the overall impression is more like a pinot noir than a beer in this respect , and i probably enjoy it more than i should .

from notes : pours pitch black and completely opaque with a large frothy mocha head that has excellent retention , only slowly fading into a lasting cap that coats the glass with rings and large chunks of soapy lacing .  mouthfeel has a nice body , decently cleansing .

s : holy chocolate and coffee batman ! this is extremely interesting . i 'm not sure if i 'm drinking a chocolate latte or a beer .  m - i really like the mouthfeel of this beer . it is perfectly carbonated and that takes over when it first hits the tongue .

lots of haze from suspended particles and visible carbonation streaming up , looked wonderful . s - smell was very light and had many fruity esthers , most notably hints of plum , raisin , figs and pears .  m : pretty good . some creaminess , enough carbonation to keep it from getting heavy .

appearance - 5.0 pours clear at first , then becoming hazy with fine moving particles . bright golden yellow in colour with a towering , meringue-like , white head that leaves sticky lace . overall - 3.4 a rather average belgian pale ale , with the exception of the beautiful appearance .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel although sticky and overly sweet is not harsh at all in terms of alcohol bite .
after settling it is a pure black color . a very nice thick cream head . the head stays and laces throughout the beer .  the mouthfeel has a nice full body , with active carbonation .
smells fantastic ! can detect slight caramel and alcohol in the background . delicious . tastes a little hot right now though , slightly decreasing its drinkability .  '' thick mouthfeel .
a great aroma though .  the mouthfeel was reather smooth and easy-going .

smell : the wheat creates a pleasant aroma that combines fruit characters with a slight spicy note from the light amount of hops . a lot of complete fruit smells are noticeable .  i must divulge that i am somewhat ignorant on strong belgian ales . smell is super caramel and alcohol is present . it says brewed with rasins but the alcohol is so overpowering that it could be mangos for all i know . addmitatly this beer has a time and place to be consumed and at my house tonight is not it .
appearance : gently hazed champagne body with a soft , stiff , enormous , airy , white head with great retention .  m - it was crisp , sharp and very smooth .

dark , dark amber color . leaves really excellent lacing .  ehh.. let me start by saying i adore irs 's . the anise , in my humble opinion makes this beer taste absolutely terrible . do n't get me wrong , you still get the nectar like , frothy delicious chocolate experience in the background , which is almost good enough to save this beer for me . theoretically the sweet/bitter flavor of the yeast should play off of and enhance the chocolate and coffee flavorings , but it does not . a change in proportions could make this a great , unique brew .

this brew pours a bright , crystal-clear gold , with lots of beads of carbonation and three inches of beautiful head . there is a bit of haze at the end of the pour , and a huge amount of lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel was good ... decent body ... right amount of carbonation .

pours foaming from the nitro can medium amber with a huge boiling white creamy head that settles to about one finger of white creamy head . plenty of lacings .  the 8.1 % abv is completely hidden except in the back of the throat on the way down , which totally bewilders me considering how light and simple this is . mouthfeel : airy with a bit of spicy zip . medium bodied and somewhat chewy .

cloudy with lots of yeast particles floating about , dark orange rust color , thin head of very fine foam , slow to dissolve , moderate lacing left behind . sweet nose , the cherry fruit comes right through with honey , molasses , black licorice and candied orange peel accents , heavy on the malts , rum raisin cake , lingers for a long time . the sweetness of the cherry , raspberry , plum fruit not to be denied here either , even slightly cloaks the ginger , clove spice , licorice , brown sugar and honey . syrupy texture has it clinging hard to the mouth pores , lack of lift makes it hard to get a clear impression of the malts , never mind the hops . you damn well better have a sweet tooth to pop one open .  the thick and coating mouthfeel means the tongue ca n't escape the fusal fumes .

s : this is one of the best smelling brews i 've come across in the summer ale category . i 'm not sure what kind of hops they added in the aroma portion of the brew , but it 's outstanding . unfortunately , it 's the best thing about this brew . t : really good . for a summer ale , it 's great .  it has a medium to full body , with ample carbonation , a prickly middle and dry finish .

pours very opaque black , the tiniest touch of brown from the edge , seems to have some decent floaty chunks in the bottom of it ( which of course makes them sinkies ) . head is deliciously huge , ochre-coloured , sinking steadily and consistently but leaves some pretty shit-hot beige lace sheets behind . yeah , it 's a stunner .  feels smooth .

i get the strong scent of deep woods to begin - green , piney vegetation , quickly followed by the continuing characteristic from their holiday beer - a thick and wonderful spicy gingerbread . no year is ever an outstanding beer , but it never lets you down either - consistently good .  mouthfeel : medium bodied . lightly crisp and dry at the start , smoooth and dry at the finish .

s - potent smell . incredible amount of citrus power that comes from something like cascade hops . its almost sharp on the nose . earthy and grassy as well . very bitter , but does have some malt notes .  decent amount of carbonation , which seems to fit with the flavor .
pours an opaque black with one finger of frothy mocha head and speckles of sticky lacing on the tulip .  it 's almost bitter with the spiciness . it 's light and crisp and refreshing .
the smell is absolutely amazing with strong waves of chocolate fudge.and coffee .  medium bodied and lightly carbonated .

if nothing else , olde mecklenburg makes gorgeous beers . the head is ample , pale-cream , and tight . mecktoberfest is , over all , a solid sessionable , gorgeous beer , whose only fault is a hit of diacetyl .  surprisingly here the mouthfeel is smooth and fairly enjoyable - not much carbonation .

the aroma to this is awesome . lots of coffee and roasted malt with a touch of chocolate . decent medium body with a sweeter , watery mouthfeel . a decent beer but nothing worth rushing to the pub for.nice change of pace for coffee lovers .  medium-full in the mouth with soft and fine carbonation . a meager beer by all accounts .

rather nice aroma consists of cocoa , roasted malt , milk chocolate and slightly vinous .  mouthfeel : just the right amount of carbonation on this one which i was delighted with but the aftertaste is a bit tart .

s - this beer smells amazing . if you enjoy the smell of smoke and/or smoked things you will find this aroma exciting . t - the smokiness is most prominant , with some swet maltiness underlying .  mouthfeel is creamy and good for the style .

aroma is a rich sweet malt with hints of raisins , plums , figs , port , and brandy and a slight floral hoppiness -- -right on for a barleywine .  medium body and the malts do not linger as much as expected .

pours a deep brownish orange ... nose is great ... has some doppelbock like scents of sweet malt ... also ... dark fruits ... big time plum smell ... ..also blackberry 's and blueberrys ... . mouthfeel is about medium ... certainly not overthick ... .sweet , slick feel as you drink like a doppel ... taste is very good ... sweet malt flavor ... does n't taste like a doppel but it has a great malt load ... i guess more of a scottish ale taste , but i do n't get much smokiness of peat ... a bit of a try finish which is nice because this could be a little too sweet without it ... i love the nose on this beer , and overall it is a pretty tasty winter beer..  it is extremely smooth with only a tingling initial mouthfeel that smoothens in its finish .

medium gold color with an enormous , billowing white head that shoots an inch over the rim of the glass . luckily it 's dense enough to keep its shape and not overflow . outlandish amounts of sticky lacing as it slowly recedes , displaying excellent retention . one of the best appearances i 've seen on a beer .  has a fairly refreshing clean finish , and nice body .

orange and grapefruit burst through immediately ... sniff more and get the graham cracker of the malts , trying desperately yo catch up . i was hoping the taste would copy the smell , but it does n't ... still nice . excellent hop combination going on here and a great example of an american dipa .  there just is n't much hops in both the smell and the taste , the mouthfeel is crisp but this is the only really redeeming quality of the beer .

pours pitch black with not even a hint of light coming through . has a large billowing dark cocoa colored head that takes forever to go down - nice lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel ... .creamy and good drinkability ... .ehhhh i would drink it again but is not worth the 4 bucks plus i paid for it

the appearance is one intangible , with a thick , clumpy froth leaving gorgeous lacing down the glass . brilliant orange .  a slightly creamy mouthfeel with moderate to low carbonation is present throughout .
the aroma is quite pleasing . juicy banana , bread . a very nice smelling hefe .  all that being said it felt quite nice on the palate with good levels of carbonation .

smells like a pumpkin alright when you pop the top . yep , you can taste the spices alright . i 've had a few pumpkin ales , this one is better than the others i 've tried .  m - mouthfeel is nice and full and goes down nicely d - pretty decent dunkel .
wow this really has a lot going on in the aroma !  m- medium bodied , moderately carbonated .

smell - exactly like banana bread.. smells delicious . that 's all i really can smell .  it has a refreshing dryness that definitely aids this beer and makes it very drinkable . it is a decent beer but i wish the jasmine was complimented by hops instead of ( maybe , if they are there ) overpowering them completely .

pours out light yehoow and sits amber in the glass with a good sized white fluffy head . great sticking power with wonderful lacings . some of the best head retention i 've ever seen .  the mouthfeel has a medium to full body , with light carbonation .

a - very clear medium amber color with a thick , foamy head that is well retained ; leaves a nice lacing s - light toasted grain scent with some alcohol noticed and a very faint touch of hops t - dominate malt flavor with some light toasted grain taste ; slight yeast fruitness with a slight hop finish m - medium body , moderate carbonation d - this is probably one of a-b best mass-marketed efforts .  very smooth and slick mouthfeel . moderate carbonation keeps it lively ; which may or may not be a good thing .
looks the color of iced tea . s : a very appealing and complex aroma with sweet notes of gingerbread , caramel malt , bright sour citrus and brown sugar , perhaps .  mouthfeel is pretty good .

straw yellow with a nice white head . smells really floral , fruity , white peaches , juicy . not really intricate , but fruit forward and a solid sour . not much funk overall , but a really nice , crisp and well done sour .  m - really well carbonated , yet smooth .

a : dark brown , slightly hazy , trickles of carbonation upon deeper view , thick foamy head settles to finger thickness , good lacing s : nice slightly sweet wheat aroma with bits of banana bread t : moderate malts upfront , followed by plum flavor and finishing with a tart fruitiness m : lots of carbonation but almost a light body , which was a disappointment d : misleading until i re-read the label - bavarian dunkler weizenbock .  good carbonation .

a : pours a cloudy orangish color , 2 finger width frothy white head , good lacing down the glass s : metallic smell , earthy , peppery t : peppery , earthy hop flavor .  m : full body with little carbonation .

in particular the genuine hoppy aroma ( i think i detected cascade hops amongst others ) , was sublime and a true feat for a new zealand microbrewery . big floral and herbal bouquet with some yeasty and grainy notes . there was also a sourness in the finish which was n't very appealing .  the malty flavor remainded in my mouth minutes after tasting . i had a trappistes rochefort 8 a couple days ago , and i am not certain of the age of this beer , but it tasted like a younger , more crisp belgian beer .

s strong aroma of extremely floral , piney hops .  a smooth , creamy , but still slightly crisp-feeling beer , with enough body to keep a better tasting beer on par with the best of them . the mouthfeel tries to carry this one , but there 's just not much there to propel .
a. pours an incredibly dark brown with a sizable head . impressive color considering most of gi 's saison offerings .  thick , smooth , lightly carbonated .
this is one damn good looking pilsner .  clean , smooth , and light mouthfeel , and here we go again , light carbonation . everything about this beer screams light .

this is what you would expect of a drink based on cherries . it is a good session drink . however , as it warms up , the aftertaste and mouth feel is degraded by the sourness of the brew . but , i would recommend this beer .  m : lighter side of medium body , medium body , slick feel with a sticky finish .

smell : the aroma of the beer is a cleaver blending of caramel , vanilla , suggestions of hot fudge , brown sugar , melons , berries , banana , dark toasted and roasted aromas , spicey earthyness , its boozey but in the way that a nice single malt is boozey . taste : this beer taste good but not nearly as good as its smell . the beers flavors bring an undefinable fruityness to my mouth . sweet honey brown sugar , vanilla , the alcohol comes across as boozey .  m : medium bodied , ample carbonation , clean finnish , dry . the mouthfeel and clean finnish saves this . average dipa
bountiful and fragrant fresh hop aromas . very inviting for those who enjoy the hop bite of a good ipa .  full bodied and nicely carbonated .

nice ! maybe this one suffers from where i am in my own personal `` beer journey , '' but i 'm getting a little tired of ipa that smell great & fragrant & then assault you with aggressive , tongue-battering bitterness .  mouthfeel - the mouthfeel was pretty good . even tho the head was essentially nil , the carbonation was very active which was noticeable in the mouth .
amazing . the taste is full of cherry as well , and just a bit of tart flavors going on .  nice carbonation .

sweet and fragrant . t faint taste of caramel comes through and just barely a hint of the sweetness in the nose . o nose on this brew is very good but the taste lacks a bit .  it had a very nice texture on the tongue as well as in the back of the mouth .
the smell is all hops .  m : full body , smooth texture , medium carbonation .

s : primarily malt notes , with a good deal of chocolate as well . smells delicious ... t : i wish i could say it tastes like it smells , but that 's where this beer falls short for me .  yet , fragrance is almost soapy . mouth feel is creamy . this beer has an unusual consistency for an ipa ; it is smooth , almost silky .
s : very fruity , specifically mango/papaya/tropical fruits , very interesting and enticing !  the mouthfeel is creamy and the finish has a creaminess to it as well .

this is one of the most attractive brews i have ever seen . a light ruby color with creamy light head that has a finger and a half upon pour and settles to a ring . no lacing , but good legs .  m : decently carbonated but morphs into a nice creaminess . pleasant .

nice rich nose , balanced but the roasty coffee is in the lead with a touch of toffee-like sweetness .  3.0 mouthfeel - nice heavy mouthfeel , smooth like silk . the carbonation level is pretty low , but i drank it warm so that could have cut it down a lot .

beautiful caramelized malt , slightly roasted nuts note , and a whisper of oxidation . amazing . taste : the caramel is soft and not overly sugary which is good , but the chocolate notes coming from this vintage are what really amazes me . 9 years has taken away a bit from the look and mouthfeel , but has greatly improved the nose and changed the taste from a hoppy alcohol driven barleywine into a malt bomb .  m : creamy . d : it 's easy to drink , but as stouts go , this was a dud for me .

there was an immediate aroma of berries as the beer was opened . there was some tart to the beer , but left a very sweet after taste in your mouth .  it had a smooth feel with slight carbonation and a crisp finish .

smell is of roasted malts , and both dark and fresh red fruit . all in all , quite a good experience in the smell . for the rest it 's decent , not exeptional .  clean mouthfeel , good carbonation , crisp , refreshing , and easy drinking .

smells . awesome . bourbon leaps upon the nose carrying licorice , vanilla , molasses and raisin . honestly my first thoughts ( following `` wow , this is good stuff '' ) were this is founder 's kbs done belgian style .  mouthfeel is nice , feels full , with good carbonation .

source/serving : 750ml bottle smell : very spicy with cloves and cinnamon prominent . yeasty . a lot going on . taste : very spicy ! ginger and cloves and a rush of sweet molasses .  4.0 m : heavier medium body . good moderate carbonation .

a - pale gold with a quickly thinning fluffy meringue head s - unfiltered honey and lush floral notes - smells like i 'm in an orange grove t - lightly floral and zesty with a slight grassy hop finish .  mouthfeel is medium and appropriate .
the aroma is nice and fruity with an added floral essence .  body is light with good carbonation .
it 's not a natural smell but it is enjoyable . t : plain , dry , bitter grass fruit .  smooth and creamy mouth feel off of a medium body .

served at cellar temp . smell : i can smell this beer from across the room . cherries , caramel , and other confections . all work together smoothly . coming down layer after layer and fitting together perfectly . legit .  m : light-medium body , with moderate carbonation .

appearance/smell - appears clear gold with high carbonation and a quarter inch of soapy head . nice head retention surprisingly , and sticky , soapy lacing . a ring of foam retains well throughout entire consumption , very inviting !  the amount of bitterness is perfect for an american pale ale but the type of hops they used disagrees with my palate 100 % . their website said they used summit , nelson sauvin , and alchemy hops in this beer . i 'm assuming its the summit or the nelson sauvin hops because i like their ipa and it has alchemy hops in it . would be a great beer if they used something like cascade instead . but then i guess it 'd probably just taste like sierra nevada .
the smell is really interesting . sweet , malty , with a bit of vanilla and maybe some cinnamon . really pleasant , interesting nose .  m : nicely carbonated and feels good .
nice . t - overrripe melons combined with a roasted malt quality , a bit boozy too .  smooth mouthfeel .
i love it . smooth mouthfeel with ... somewhat dry finish .  m - intese , and full .

poured into a tulip , this one has a blood orange tinged amber body with a light beige finger of head sitting on top . lacing is all over this thing . this looks great .  a sweeter fuller tasting brew than maybe a budweiser m- medium bodied brew , carbonation was pretty good .

smell was incredible . tons of rich , dark chocolate and some coffee . surprisingly hoppy and quite dry ( almost bitter ) on the back end . this definitely was not one of the easier drinking oatmeal stouts i have tried , but it was one of the most interesting .  a light texture at the front , that gains weight as it reaches the back of the palate to become more medium bodied . the comforting look , pleasing aroma and solid feel can not bring this beer up .

smell is strong with cherries . you can really get a feel for the lambic .  t- refreshing , smooth , subtle . very crisp . bitterness of hops , works well with the carbonation . d- moderately high . this beer is n't strong or flavorful , but it has a very nice subdued flavor that plays on it 's carbonation and hops bitterness .
s - chocolate , booze , bourbon , roast . t - chocolate , coffee , bourbon , roast .  m : chewy . good feel .
best before 19-03-16 pours a deep red/brown color with lots of off-white head .  m : the mouthfeel was pretty good for the style .
the color is beauitful and the head looks nice sitting on top of the glass .  not pleasing m- creamy , full bodied . low carbonation .

nose is fantastic on this , it 's fresh , light and citrusy with some mango sweetness as well , fantastic . taste is solid , but off the bat it 's a bit grainy ( reminds me of shut the hell up from the alchemist ) .  m : chewy o : ehh i 'm not so pleased with this whole concept .
opaque brown , little light comes through , mousse-like dark tan head of good retention .  m - smooth with a slight carbonation sensation .

crazy lacing .  first off , let me say that unibroue is my favorite brewery and belgians are my favorite style . that said -- dude , the smell of this beer is definitely funky . pretty disgusting . luckily , the toe jam does n't come through in the taste . it tastes like a witbier with a hint of apple . if i want a witbier , i 'll buy ommegang witte instead .

appearence is a beautiful amber with a nice frothy head .  appearance : dark chestnut brown with ruby highlights , good clarity , medium layer of tan froth aroma : light roast and malt ; bit of brown sugar flavor : medium malt sweetness with a weak coffee bitterness on the back end ; hints of brown sugar and vanilla pipe tobacco ; finishes semisweet mouthfeel : medium body , spritzy carbonation , soft texture other comments : meh ... fairly lacklustre .
aroma is a big whiff of citrus hops .  m- feel is good . a little thick d- meh .
a- pours a dark black color with two and a half fingers of brown sugar foam .  the mouthfeel is smooth and light , which is suprising for a double imperial russian stout .
fantastic sheets of lace coat the glass in one hell of an attractive manner .  m & d - mouthfeel is nice due to viscosity but the tart twanginess is not attractive .

nutcracker ale pours a brownish-orange and is transluscent almost opaque . its head is off white , fluffy , with great retention .  m - right to style . medium light body mated to a good amount of carbonation d - i had a difficult time getting through this one .

appearance ; thick , stiff white head , excellent retention and messy spider web-like lacing .  in a pinch i 'll take yuengling 's lord chesterfield over this , but both are poseur craft beers with crisp carbonation , appreciable hop bitterness and easy drinkability .
an interesting smell for sure .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation .
very good smelling beer . t -- sweet caramel and toffee flavor .  good body from the slightly sweet taste .

sundance is the best looking amber ale i 've ever seen . true to its name , it looks like a setting sun . the body is a deep , translucent amber with a pillowy , stable head sticky like melted marshmallow .  decent mouthfeel . medium bodied and briskly carbonated .

s- big amount of port , scotch , whiskey , even a little hint of bourbon , and of course a huge amount of oak and vanilla . t- huge alcohol with a nice big chocolate body to back it up . all the aromas come in and a sweet dominating caramel body . very nice and complex . m- full chewy body that is really oily with no carbonation at all . d- i think it is really good but not easy to drink .  mouhfeel is sticky with a full body and medium carbonation .

lots of hops in the nose . herbal spicy hops , hints of tangerine and a lightly earthy malt aroma . very nice ! the combo of hops that make the nose so good make the flavor a bit haphazard . juicy sweet citrusy hops intermingled with some coarse herbal hops , like amarillo or something of that nature . pretty tasty . i wish the bittering hops blended more nicely .  m - medium bodied and slightly chewy . moderate carbonation .
awesome retention and lacing as ive come to expect from hotd beers .  i dunno i expected more from this m - medium bodied with a decent amount of carbonation .

served in a nonic , the 75 min ipa appears with 2 fingers worth of silky , creamy white head . displays a solid amount of retaining power that lasts with a full finger 's worth until the last sip . the lacing on the glassware appears as a webbing just about everywhere it was in contact . the brew itself is a hazed golden orange color .  this has a nice body to it ; light , but with a reasonable heft to it that has a nice presence on the palate .

smells of cork . brettanomyces , acid sour that 's not quite cherry , cough drop , plastic , lemon , chocolate , earthy hop oil ( tettnanger ) , marigold , clean alcohol sting , mild dry chocolate , dried hay . great balance , thought i 'm not fond of brett character .  m- good carbonation and quite smooth .

leffe , a bold golden/blonde ale that shines , really , im looking at it and it 's shining . a big white rush of foam on the top part of the glass leaving window covering lace with legs .  m - this has a nice smooth feel to it .

the most striking feature of this beer is the fantastic aroma . there are so many things going on in your nose but the most prominant for me were the vanilla oakyness and rich , spicy bourbon . this is where i felt slightly let down in the taste , there 's just so much going on and compared to the original and blonde the drinkability suffers .  a nice mouthfeel , with plenty of creaminess .

creamy head poured loose and frothy and faded almost instantly to wispy covering ... no real lacing to speak about ... lots going on in the aroma ... lots of rich oaky bourbon notes mixed with sweet nuttiness - hints of almond and pistachio , toffee and treacle , very woody , musty , some overripe ( rotten ? ) fruits - apples and bananas , grainy malts , lots of booze , toasted ( burnt ) raisin bread , light smokiness , some chocolate , butterscotch ... taste - very strong ( overpowering ? ) boozy bourbon mixed with lots of belgian yeastiness , bready , very woody , musty , toasted nuts , vanilla , very light toffee sweetness , sweet overripe fruits , some vegetal traces , anise - hint of cough medicine , burnt butter ... m & d - fairly sharp and dry ... medium bodied ... way too boozy to be very drinkable ... overall - a decent enough experiment ... not something i 'd want a lot of but worth trying ... definitely a sipper..  a-black color , finely carbonated off white head s-a hint of yeast , some roasted malt t-hints of bourbon with a touch of bug spray and brett yeast funk m-smooth bodied , very creamy , nice d-the bourbon sting is a little too much for me o-did not care for the combination of brettomyces and bourbon stout .
pours a slightly hazy golden copper with a medium frothy head that retains well and laces the glass .  m - feel pretty spot on for a wit .

sweet jesus this is an aromatic beer . had a pint of cask conditioned last night , and halfway through it my saliva glands had gone dry . this beer has a wonderful fresh hop aroma . aroma might even be too subtle a word for it . it was a powerful smell , obviously it had been dry hopped .  more like a cider , apple-ish and very sweet , low carbonation . mouthfeel is full and round .

the retention in this one is phenomenal , just a sticky , dense pillow of just over a finger the whole way .  mouthfeel has a pleasant sheen to it , but the flavour is either thin or phenolically unpleasant , so it does n't have much to work with .

on tap ( in a 32oz masskrug ) at the brewery , it has a beautiful orange glow and the perfect cloudiness .  some how the spices dont drown out the actual beer . m- light , prickly , crackly and drying . very crisp despite all the insane herbs and spices . d- not as drinkable as a normal saison . this beer is wildly herbal and spicy .

s : bouquet is well presented and complex . pine , citrus and flower all come through well . d : a decent dipa , but definitely has room for improvemet . the hops were a little clashing as well . i liked it overall , but if this one is to be brewed again i would hope that they tweak it a little .  less then exciting , sub par for an ipa . flavors are more citrus , the carbonation makes it brighter , and the obligatory pine is noted , more balanced then other ipas , i would say this is more balanced then most `` east coast '' ipas , really borders the pale ale territory , which is what i always thought this beer was . i remember liking this beer more when i was just getting into craft , either my palate has matured past c hops as a preferance or i got a lame batch .

anyways it is extract brewed here so i didnt expect much poured into a standard pint a deep copper with a well formed two finger slight off white head that had great lasting power , aromas of earthy hop and deep brown sugar maltiness neither overpowers the other really.not a real big hop profile on the palate mainly earthy tones with a touch of citrus finishing with that ever present brown sugar/molasses malt extract flavoring in the finish.not bad really with some nuance to it you would never know the alchol content of the beer but it is what it is a extract brew but a decent one at that .  t - sweet taste , can taste the alcohol , malty , spice and gingerbread flavor m- medium thickness , coats the tongue , lightly carbonated once the foam settles .

s - as soon as the beer started pouring you get the classic smell of an ipa and with pliny the smell is exceptionally strong . the aroma of the pine in the beer drew me in immediately .  moderately heavy and smooth mouthfeel .
smell : smells of chocolate , caramel , and coffee .  the mouthfeel is good . it is a low bodied beer with good carbonation .
poured brown , dark , semi-translucent with a rich tan head that had a good amount of retention .  mouth feel is smooth and crisp with an average carbonation level .

a two-finger high frothy head sits atop of the body . after sustaining itself for a few minutes , the head leaves behind a clingy white surface layer with soem lacing on the glass .  medium , almost creamy mouthfeel with low carbonation .
real nice dark brown pour , white bubbly head .  the mouthfeel is well balanced , carbonated well and not sticky at all .

black as night , with a head the color of chocolate milk . it 's a full pint , so it fits the glass perfectly .  very creamy mouthfeel , but i must admit that this brew was far too heavy for my taste .

nothing too unique in the aroma , but it was fantastic . smelled like it was fresh out of the conditioning tanks flavor was sublime . overall an incredibly impressive ipa and glad i landed this .  m : good medium body with a smooth feel throughout .

huge cherry and oak on the nose , followed by an earthy mustiness and barnyard funk . a bit boozy . a damn fine flemish sour ; ranks with the best .  t & # 8211 ; it tastes a lot like a macro lager , and a little like a wheaty spicy belgian-inspired summer beer . blue moon is probably better in some regards , though i guess not on an overall basis ( i have n't had blue moon in a , well , you know ... ) m & # 8211 ; pretty crisp and refreshing .
the smell is bright , piney hops , backed by some citrus , and the merest hint of bread and sweet caramel . i prefer a little more balance in my dipas .  light/medium mouthfeel .

the look of this beer is fantastic . deep , dark black , with a champagne-like head that bubbles gloriously only to recess into obscurity moments later .  the carbonation is medium low the mouth-feel is quite smooth .

appearance is perfect . pours into my snifter a bright , translucent pale yellow with lots of bubbles and huge amounts of froth just tons of head , thick , foamy , bright clean white . a stunning beer .  mouthfeel is soft over the tongue , and drinkability is not bad .
it arrives at the table a cloudy brown with a dense , persistent tan head . it leaves nice lacing and makes me thirsty looking at it .  body is medium with medium-low carbonation .

pours a hazy pale golden yellow with sky-high , frothy white head with great retention and generous lacing . beautiful beer !  m : good , a pleasant heaviness that does n't become too viscous or clinging .
the head retention was incredibly long lasting and left light lacing .  it is like a glorified malt liquor , it is n't awful and has a great mouthfeel actually but it is still an adjunct laden brew .

smell : was outstanding , one of the best smelling beers i have encountered : great caramel , honey , malt ... with hops in the distance .  500ml bottle poured into tulip mar27 2011 a pours out black with some oil like globs towards the bottom of the bottle , thumbs width of mocha head quickly falls to a thin film leaving a partial ring of lace followed by some unorganized patches s worcestershire sauce and soy with a little booze and mint , not what i was hoping for t slightly better with some smoke , woody earth , vanilla , cola and whiskey but that worcestershire is hard to miss after you catch wind of it m fairly thick and creamy with just a little heat that could be better concealed but still feels good o lea & perrins would be proud , that worcestershire smell and flavor is holding this one way back hard to believe that before this hit the barrel it was one of my all time favorite stouts , i love the beer geek breakfast but this one just did n't do it for me , not a bad brew but i 'd rather drink one before the barrel aging edit : after reading some reviews i suspected i got a bad bottle and tried another .

banana very assertive on the nose , a bit like rice pudding . mouth slightly spicy but far from the belgian models because the entrance is very sweet and gives a very easy drinking brew .  a - hazy golden orange with 2 fingers of white head that produces some good lacing s - cherry medicine , a little wheat aroma hidden in there as well t - basically a generic wheat beer with a bunch of cherry flavoring thorwn in m - medium body with medium carbonation d - to sweet to be enjoyable all the time .

the head is nice , but quickly dissipates , and leaves scant lacing down the glass ... s : the smell is awesome , i really can not tell if there is any malt in this beer . yes , it is hoppy , but nowhere near some dipa 's .  the mouthfeel is smooth and crisp with a high carbonation , and the drinkability is pretty high also .
this ale pours a copper brown with lots of carbonation and has a big head .  the mouthfeel is well carbonated , light , and smooth .
smells wonderfully complex . imitation vanilla extract mixed with bock malt , milk chocolate , alcohol , and black licorice .  light to medium bodied . descent carbonation . crisp finish .

it has a copper color but has a great smell . as i poured it into my glass the head was very large  ... the aroma is super malty , brown sugar , bread , prunes , dark fruits and grape soda dominate , a hint of yeast and alcohol on the finish . a super malty aroma , taste crushes your senses with hops and alcohol . almost makes me gag . this is so bitter , like they confused a dopplebock with double ipa . the hops are totally misplaces , trying to be creative , just ruined the beer .
appearance - perfect light color with a think almost chewable yeasty head .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , with a fairly long , sweet finish .
s : nice blend of roasted coffee and chocolate . probably my favorite part of this beer .  crisp and heavy on the palate like fine bourbon .
nice reddish amber color that had huge aroma of berries . awesome tart raspberry flavor accompanied with the burn from the alcohol .  m- assertive carbonation , light body and fairly smooth .

pours a very clear but very dark scarlet , clear enough to se through but dark enough to soak up a lot of the light . buttery tan head froths up out of control and sits there as if it were a solid object . it leaves frothy , thick lacing behind , and absolutely refuses to diminish to less than a full finger throughout the glass .  in some ways , this makes it better than a number of other fruit beers out there ... nice mouthfeel ... lots of tiny bubbles make it very refreshing and a good match for the tartness .
perfect lacing . i mean perfect lacing .  the medium body is smooth and prickly , and leaves an almost medium finish - nice .

generally very nice . t : does n't live up to the nose unfortunately . out of nowhere the spices briefly explode in the finish , which is nice .  m - light body and low to moderate carbonation . a nice crisp body .
luscious malt aroma .  it tastes nothing like a real peach . i would compare it too a jolly rancher piece of candy . i do like the fizzieness , and crisp finish , but thats it .

`` first off , the smell is what hits you first , lots of dark fruits , sugar , rum , plums . . is massively bitter , yet still a tad sweet- never has a beer been so wide in that spectrum ! the flavour is complex but at colder temps , the alcohol can be a bummer , wait ! -- - & gt ; warmer shows some real class , tasty yet assertive .. bold .  some subdued hop flavors kick in a bit later , and the finish is slightly bitter but tastes a bit off ( some of the butter lingers through the finish ) mf - medium body and moderate carbonation .

appearance : great head on this one . very fluffy that , after a few sips , recedes to a lower head . frothy would be the word for this head .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with moderate carbonation , and a velvety texture .

the smell is intensely fruity , this is a very unique beer . lots of strawberry in the aroma , not much of a malt aroma in the background , just fruit .  the mouthfeel is huge , especially compared to most other witbiers .

s - very complex ! grape , sherry and port wine-type aromas are dominant , with hints of raisin , nuts and esters . alcohol is apparent , too . very sweet altogether . m/d - hardly any carbonation . i look forward to trying another one a year from now !  mouthfeel is a medium with good carbonation .
incredible retention and beautiful lacing .  a really nice creamy feel to this which matches the beer , not the style imo .
again , wow . fantastic .  quite thick body , but also slick enough .

the pour results in a very cloudy liquid throughout the glass , with the impression of foam falling to the bottom before rising to the top . the cloudiness slowly clears to form a thick and creamy one finger white head above clear reddish gold liquid . the head stays forever , and leaves excellent lace . the mouth is very flat , with almost no carbonation at all and a thick body that is not at all sticky .  m- medium/high carbonation . fairly smooth .

bottle : poured a dark brown color ale in my trappist glass with a good inch of off-white foamy head with excellent retention .  palate : this is the best part of the beer . medium body with low end carbonation . goes down smooth with a nice little bite at the back of the throat on the finish .

appearance : this is a real beautiful pint . gold in color , slight chill haze . great 2 finger , fluffy beige head . diminished into a real tight lace that slides all the way down the glass .  mouthfeel is silky and lightly carbonated .

smell : a wonderful array of hops -- resiny , floral , piney , and spicey . crisp and quite refreshing . tastes better as you drink more . overall : very refreshing beer with pretty decent flavor .  medium mouthfeel .

pours pitch black with a huge huge tan head , fades incredibly slow , if i was in a rush to drink it i 'd be kinda peeved it took so long to settle down , leaves a good amount of sticky lacing .  m : thick and smooth , the way a beer that tastes like this should feel .

a : black as night , with no light passing through . great retention on this baby .  nose is a creamy butterscotch sweetness , and palate of creamy sweet butterscotch with a balanced bitter and a touch of gypsum . absolutely one yummy ale and a must try for anyone . bass pale ale has been on my list of beers to buy when the price is right . bass pale ale is a good tasting pale ale that has been around for a very long time . well , i just went through a twelve pack and lo and behold this brew has turned to banta podo , it is nothing at all what it used to be !
this wicked brew is topped with a big creamy , frothy , three finger head . outstanding appearance !  m : alcohol warmth dominant , full bodied , moderate carbonation .
this poured a very tall , thick and foamy head . clear , vibrant light amber color .  body is quite good and so is carbonation .
looks delicious . very good looking beer .  mouthfeel is good .

s - smells a lot like a winter warmer should ! the finish is a bit confusing , a wheat-oat malt flavor comes in that is would be a perfect finish to it if it were not for the strong alcohol and cherry flavor in there again .  m : crisp on the palate , dry finish .
gold orange in color . large creamy white lasting head .  mouthfeel : light carbonation . good to form .

the exceptional nose presents a bouquet of orange , banana , pear and piney hops -- this brew smells like a basket of fresh fruit .  medium carbonation and a thin body that finishes mostly clean with a touch of dry euro-hops .

lotr polotmavy 14 ( a semi-dark lager beer ) 4 clear dark reddish mahogany with lasting tan head that leaves lots of laving 5 unique aroma ; groll beers are fermented and aged in wood ( oak ) barrels .  mouthfeel is light , dry and highly carbonated .
appearance-pitch black with a three finger tan head that dissipates and clings to the glass .  good mouthfeel ; much more lively than the original pour indicates .

smell is good , and exactly as expected based on the beer 's name . taste is similar to the smell , but with more pronounced bitter chocolate and rich oaty sweetness .  m- full bodied , and average carbonation .
s : it smells great ! very citrusy/fruity and somewhat spicey .  good mouthfeel ... everything about this is good except the smell and taste , lol .
i was really impressed with the overall appearance of this beer .  it has a good mouthfeel , thick but creamy , goes down smooth .

the spice aroma is intense : strong clove with hints of cinnamon and nutmeg . its has a complex flavor that is quite delicious , once you get by the initial sourness .  without all the technicallity , this beer tasted like sierra 's pale ale revisited . the only difference was added depth of character through the heavy use of malts . otherwise , the same hop profile pulls through . when looking objectively at the style , i 'd say they were confused as to what they were producing . stouts and porters are my favorites ( i know , hop heads are scoffing now ) , and as such , i was expecting less hop character ( again , for the style ) . if i wanted a pale ale , or ipa , then i 'd go get one . overall , i give it a `` c : '' there is a `` chance '' i 'll buy this again .

pretty awesome looking beer , you can definitely tell they took full advantage of the blood oranges .  the medium bodied beer , feels pretty good , with a nice creamy quality to it , and a complimentary amount of carbonation but the spices pretty much ruin any redeeming qualities the beer may have .
50cl bottle from system in lund sweden a - beautiful ! very dark indeed . head is a nice chocolate color .  the mouthfeel was decently thick . this beer needed carbonation and some balance to it .
light , hoppy , refreshing= excellent .  light-medium body , ideal carbonation smooth .
poured from the bottle into a stemmed tulip . a - nice orange amber body with a white fluffy head on top . lots of sticky lacing on the glass .  good carbonation .

i got some fruits immediately ( some apple in there ) , followed by a decent dose of hops . a little sugar as well . smell was very complex . the taste revealed darker fruits than the smell . this one started strong with a bountiful appearance and complex aroma , but it hit its peak too early .  very creamy and thick on my tounge . i 'm not sure what to make of this beer , i like the appearance and mouthfeel but it is just too sweet & tart for me .
it pours a dense ink black with an amazing looking dual tone caramel/tan head .  m - nice mouthfeel . does n't feel thin .
and it smells fantastic ! a truly great smelling beer . t- wow .  m : has a good body for the style , though it is a bit seltzery .
pours a bright amber color , with an awesome head . great looking ipa .  mouthfeel was pretty good , it was medium bodied , on the thick side , and quite creamy .
gorgeous pour , wonderful cascading effect .  mouthfeel : drying and fairly clean and light .
the aroma is quite pleasant - fresh citrus and hops are very noticeable .  mouthfeel : medium-thin body . medium carbonation .
the smell is a very nice bourbon smell with a hint of vanlla and mild spice notes .  mouthfeel : very smooth .
this beer looks very pretty in the glass .  mouthfeel is smooth and creamy , however .
beautiful smelling brew , strong hoppy aroma , relatively fresh - considering the journey across half the world .  m - the mouthfeel is actually right on point .

a : guinness just looks great in the glass . good contrast with black color with a creamy white head .  mouthfeel : thick and creamy , not nearly as assaulting as i 'd figured it would be with the carbonation level .
the aroma is pleasantly malty with dry fruit odors and hints of spice with sour undertones .  it has a good mouthfeel , with that silky nitro body .
smell was incredible . i really enjoyed the chimay blue which had similiar flavors but without the dryness .  medium to full bodied and smooth .

appearance clear orange/yellow body with carbonation that drops instantly ; massive and rather sturdy , billowy white head that comes forth in a big pour ; fabulous lace smell bitter and more bitter ; big fat hops ; a bit spicy ; and a light dose of alcohol ; this is what i want from an ipa taste models the nose with more malts ( caramel , bread crust ) coming through midway but the citrus hops still run the show ; pink grapefruit and grain aftertaste mouthfeel moderate body for an ipa ; smooth base and a crisp edge ; very light hop sting balanced with a light oily sensation drinkability damn thats a boatload of hops ; theres easy turnover ; the hop stick smacks hard but if you 're the hophead , it 'll spin you back around easily so youre ready to roll again high hop tide warning ! this ones good from 50 yards .  does have a nice , smooth mouthfeel , which would make it easy to drink , if i cared for the smell at all .

getting the rich toasty and sweet malt with the huge bourbon and vanilla scents as well . rich and delicious . all of the richness that is described above . with some age , this one would be perfection . full bodied , hot and dry finish with soft and smooth carbonation . this stuff is so deliciously tasty and flavorful that i have to keep drinking it .  m : a soft and fluffy texture , no carbonation , medium body .

a vigorous pour shows amazing carbonation for an oak aged beer . the result is a huge three finger rich tan head with big fat bubbles . leaves lots of lace .  mouthfeel - i actually have no complaints in this department . it 's comparatively crisp and the carbonation is appropriate .

i treated myself to a bottle of this sweet stuff . as for aromas this maybe the most aromatic beer i have ever had . tootsie rolls and chocolate pop tarts is what comes to mind . good but not great . oh and tampa bay stunk up my parlay today too ..  mouthfeel is light with good carbonation .
pours a lovely mahogany -crystal clear and brown-red with a slight fluffy khaki head .  mouthfeel : it 's just about right .
bottle : poured a pitch-black color stout with a big foamy dark brown head with great retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is very thick but a nice amount of carbonation .
a-golden amber . nice tight white head that settles on top .  m- there is a very slight creamy note to the light body that gives it a nice mouthfeel .

quite a unique and pleasing odor . tastes very hoppy , with strong floral hops that give off a spicy taste , piney hops , sweet malt , caramel , grass , flowers , orange peel , grapefruit , apple , brown sugar , pepper and spices .  really good smooth , medium mouthfeel in this one , probably its best feature .
almost too sweet , but beautiful none the less .  at the least the mouthfeel is , typical of apas , nice and creamy .

man , this stuff smells great . i think i 've been smelling it for 15 minutes now ... taste . starts out good , but there 's an herby , floral bitterness in the end which i did n't enjoy very much . after being one of the best smelling barleywines i 've come across , i was bummed to find that the taste did n't live up .  granted , i know this is cask beer , but would a little bit of carbonation be such a bad thing ? mouthfeel is soft and smooth , and this beer is very light and easy to drink .
the wonderfully strong raspberry aroma is all i can smell .  decently carbonated beverage with a mild body .

s - no lie , one of the best aromas on a beer , ever ! tons of resinous , sappy , piney hops along with pineapple , grapefruit and lemon . basically a massive fruit salad of smells ! t - juicy grapefruit and grassy , piney hops meld well with the doughy caramel malts . damn good beer !  mouthfeel : nice carbonation level , medium body , smooth texture .
very , very nice . the taste is surprising .  4.0 m : this is easily the best part of the brew . good carbonation , but might be a tad high . very nice creaminess on this , especially for the body .

s_unique pale ale aroma going on here . i really like the way this smells . t_not quite as hoppy as the smell suggests .  one saving grace for this beer is its mouthfeel , which i thought was quite good : light and not too carbonated . a poor geuze , overall .

the gorgeous smell was probably the two hearted 's highest high : peachy and apricot-y floral hops that are downright memorable . tastewise , less bitter than many in the style , slightly fruity , with enough flavor on both the hop and malt ends to go around .  fairly smooth . would n't be able to guess that it weighs in at 6.5 % .

it has a strong aroma of roasted malts , coffee and lots of semi-sweet chocolate . the hops are very bold , but not quite over the top .  medium body and syrupy with a good amount of carbonation keep the beer from being too heavy .

fuller 's esb is a crystal-clear solid amber ale , atop which sits a rich , frothy , cream-colored head that leaves excellent lacing .  medium-light body with a pleasant carbonation and an apparent slickness and oiliness .

aroma is like a beer desert , sweet with candy like aroma , some mild cotton candy , caramel , plenty of malt kick , a touch of fermented dark cherries and a touch of alcohol .  one positive is the full bodied presence of the malt , although the carbonation comes across as lighter than expected .

a- this is the funnest beer to watch while it settles , as it morphs from a caramel colored , bubbly state to a completely dark brown/black brew with an amazing tan head that has an incredible retention from start to finish s- deep roasted aromas ... cocoa , coffee beans , black tea , kind of earthy .  the mouthfeel is tasty and slightly creamy for a pilsner , but i am liking it .
appearance - good thick white head and solid lager yellow color .  the body is medium with a soft creamy feel to it .

12 oz bottle from my trip out west over christmas app : a wonderful blend of dark amber , ruby , and garnet . fluffy tan head that fades to a nice cap and thick lace .  mouthfeel : thick and creamy with low carbonation . has an element of smoothness to it .
black with cocoa-brown highlights and a very good head for the abv .  medium bodied carbonation .

poured into a tulip glass . the appearance of ommegang in a tulip glass is one to behold .  good mouthfeel , with just the right amount of carbonation . found the flavors to be very mild , and it took a lot of sips to really get the full feel of this brew .

smell is very enjoyable , lots of thick fruitiness and burnt sugar , with a stab of wine-like alcohol . unexpectedly complex , with a great grape and olive finish .  the mouthfeel was good with real depth .
it 's interesting , strong citrus aromas from start to finish .  medium , creamy mouth feel with light to moderate carbonation .

very well . t - a little dissapointing . o - the nose is great , and the flavor is good , just does n't last .  the willamette & tettnang hops gave it an interesting bittering character , although i 'm not sure i liked it that much . you do get some malt up from but the hop bitterness really overshadowed any malt character .
a very nice white head , good amber color , nice malty aroma with a light hop aroma .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation . pretty smooth here . it did have a very nice mouthfeel though .
poured a cloudy yellow with a huge head that displayed pretty good retention .  a buttery mouthfeel which is unique and nice . medium body and medium carbonation .
pitch black colour , impressive brown head .  the mouthfeel is a bit creamy as the name implies . overall i 'd say the mouthfeel is the best part about this beer but nothing to get excited about .

a - big thick black brew with a perfectly creamy , thick , and tight head that lasts for the duration of the beer . solid tan sheets of beautiful lace .  the carbonation of the beer was good , like a pilsner should be . the beer was light , but not watery . an innocent beer that would offend very few .
12oz bottle poured into a tulip . appearance - black body and thick medium brown head with good retention .  pretty nice texture for an aal .

delicious coffee smell , you can really tell its added for aroma . but a nice bittering finish to carry out the nose . d : a good beer to definitely be drank chilled . i am pleased that it is now in a 341ml bottle as opposed to the 650ml of old .  the hops jump right out from the bottle and sting your nose as the beer pours into the glass . do n't get me wrong there are plenty of hops , maybe too much , but i think as an effort to try and dry out this beer , the brewer added a lot of simple sugars which created more alcohol , and then to counter or mask , he added more hops . the finish is dry and clean with very little lingering hoppiness at least for a iipa . i was very excited to see this brewery 's beer being distributed in ohio . we do n't see many style defining west coast iipas in the midwest so it 's a real treat to find something that stretches your palate . even though this beer deserves low marks for drinkability , its intense aroma was worth the eight dollars i paid for the bomber .
this stuff honestly smells stellar ! it smells like christmas .  mouthfeel is pretty good .

wow , one of the best looking beers i have ever had . pours a clear dark copper hue with an extremely generous light khaki colored head .  it leaves a taste like fig newtons on the palette that 's not too enjoyable ... m : the mouthfeel is actually right on .

interesting . sour is n't as present in the taste as the smell . disappointing after the smell especially . mouthfeel is ok. a little too highly carbonated but goes a bit with the wood/fruitiness , although it 's less of a beer feel and more like a wine feel . the smell is excellent but the flavors just are n't blended in the right way to make it a great beer .  the mouthfeel was smooth , creamy and fuller bodied with a fine , moderate effervescence .

the pour on this is awesome like every nitro can , nice tiger stripes as it slowly settles out , then you get theat signature nitro one finger white head .  it has a very thick mouthfeel and a kind of grapefruit like flavor .

poured into a pint glass.. copper orange color , fizzy head at the perfect proportion .  m - not bad ( if it were not for actually having to experience the taste to experience the mouthfeel ) full and smooth with active carbonation .
3.0 d : great aroma , but the taste and mouthfeel simply are n't up to par .  feels good in the mouth , mostly sweet to start , but there is a hint of bitter at the end of the swallow .
very nice . it appears slightly cloudy with particulate floating , yet just dark yellow enough to say this is not like the others .  m - very smooth with good carbonation , well rounded .

no head no bubbles , like a liqueur . s : smells like heaven . a boatload of butterscotch , caramel , vanilla and maple bars . an easy 5 . d : i almost passed on this because of the cost , but i 'm glad i did n't .  m - a bit fizzy and tongue-tingling , but develops well in the mouth . swallow is creamy and nice .
nice smell . t starts out with a nice roasty flavor .  m : thick and heavy , but not cloying .
a - black with a thick , brown head , some lacing , reduces to a ring one third way through the beer . very satisfying .  mouthfeel : lightly crisp throughout . short and spicy aftertaste .

aromas have a fruity sense with mixes of apricot , oranges , cranberry and cherry . also , interesting mixes of toffee and butter could be sensed . taste-wise was ok. a little watery with burnt , fruity flavors and a nice touch of vanilla .  appropriately carbonated and smooth going down with a little resiny aftertongue .
very enjoyable . the taste is sweet at first but then the bitterness hits .  nice , fairly full mouthfeel .

poured very cold from bottle . pretty beer , nice deep golden orange with smooth carbonation and light tan foam that sticks to the glass . very nice appearance .  carb level and mouth feel is actually quite pleasant , though .

s : nice , big candy caramel malt , some dark fruit hints and very good backing of citrus hops . big but very balanced . t : caramel malt , little hint of some dark fruit , faint citrus and slightly pine hops , fair amount of bitterness in the finish .  m : despite the awful flavor of this beer , i have to say that the mouthfeel is fine for a porter . thick and creamy .

the aroma is a stand-out , a very complex mixture of ripe fruit , tobacco with a hint of smoke , chocolate , molasses , vanilla , brown sugar and various spices . a very nice scottish strong ale and another bottle may give it a better score .  i 've used pine to describe beers before but never has it been so true . smells like they really got the spruce tips going in here . lingering earthy bitterness and an aftertaste that kind of reminds of what it feels like when you eat something that is n't meant to be edible ( like for instance a pine cone ! ) somewhat crisp , drinkability only suffers because personally i am put off by the flavor .
the smell is what i liked best because of the caramel & chocolate , smelled like the worlds best desert .  pretty full bodied brew with moderate carbo .

a bit of lacing & minimal head retention s : bubblegum , cloves & white pepper t : cloves , grainyness , juicyfruit & grassy up front . crackery notes along with lemony hops as this warms .  the mouthfeel has nice carbonation but the smell is bland .

s- second brew i 've tried from kuhnhenn , second absolutely intoxicating aroma . deep raspberries much like new glarus raspberry tart but there 's something behind it , namely a well hidden alcohol aroma that lingers in the nostrils . t- much more interesting of a brew than the aroma let on . nice , however truncated , raspberry flavor followed by quite a bit of alcohol warming .  good carbonation with a medium mouthfeel .

full , thick ivory head , lacing all the way down , keeping strong all the way through . leaves a dollop of head at the bottom of the glass .  mouthfeel/drinkability ; the mouthfeel may be the best thing going on with this beer . full bodied , and close to syrupy in feel , with a very low carbonation .
this beer smells so good i 'm considering replacing my current cologne selection .  m - nice medium-full body and creamy . low carbonation .
snifter and was greeted by a massive 3 finger head that left a nice web of lacing down the glass .  m - on the thin side of medium bodied , nice and foamy carbonation .

a sign of a good nose is that i keep coming back and burying my face in it , and that 's what 's happening here . it 's like dessert , rich and buttery . t : brown sugar , cinnamon , subtle roasted pumpkin , graham cracker .  moderate carbonation .
very nice . the taste is lighter and more astringent .  ) m : smooth , bubbly , crisp finish with a lingering dry hops spiciness on the tongue .

rose d'hibiscus smells ... good . just good . different , for sure : this is a belgian wheat base with a heaping helping of floral , sweet , gentle hibiscus aroma that actually smells like hibiscus ! unique , memorable and - yes - outstanding . the flavor is n't quite up to snuff ( ha ! good stuff , wet , clean , floral , spicy , drinkable .  the mouthfeel is fine could certainly session .

pours a deep dark brown , almost pitch black with slight mahogany edges when held to a light source and a two finger frothy pillowy tan head . very good retention , only slowly fading into a lasting cap that coats the glass with sheets of soapy lacing .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , with lively carbonation .

s : strong hop aroma with many characteristics- fruity , flowery , grassy , and slightly earthy all at the same time . a mysteriously delicious aroma laden with hops- those tv commercials are n't lying .  m : nicely carbonated lifting the sweetness making way for a light feel .

the complexity is through the roof , the balance is perfect . and it just smells so quality . coffee and roasted nuts as well as chocolate , caramel , and molasses , still with decent hop bitterness . nice ! i really enjoyed drinking this , and i really wish we could get it locally .  taste : light body , smooth mouth feel .
quite a good nose ! taste- the beer has a little too much alcohol coming through .  mouthfeel is full and round .

12 oz bottle poured into pint glass a : hazy orange color little bits of yeasties floating around with lots of creamy off white head.. about 2 fingers worth of head and the foam stick around ... . wonderful lacing .  mouthfeel is medium - light with good carbonation .

it smells great . there isnt much head on this one sadly , but the color and smell make up for it . its good but not very balanced . it 's not the most drinkable but its still enjoyable . maybe a little time would balance this puppy out . overall , a good brew .  pretty good body .
s : huge coffee nose ! awesome nose . m/t : slightly watery to medium body .  medium mouthfeel .

poured from the bottle into a standard us tumbler *side note* this is my first stout besides guinness , so take this review with a grain of salt a-this one one of the prettiest beers i 've ever seen . almost completly black with a medium thick brown head . perfect lacing .  low carbonation with a nice chewy mouth feel . very thick !
smells really good . appearance : golden color , nice white head , clear .  mouthfeel is medium with very nice light carbination .

lively ( could still see a bit through the red haze ) smell & gt ; caramel , sweet grasses and malt . excellent taste & gt ; true to its style , it started sweet before bursting with barley flavor .  very good for the style .

a- copper colored with off-white head that stayed for a really long time s- has a pretty damn good smell , slight malt and a pretty floral hop character t- considering the strong hop scent , the taste is a little bit of a let down , much more mellow than i was hoping for .  medium body , medium effervescence , good aftertaste where the malt comes out after the hop start .
a - pours clear and yellow . the massive head sticks around for a while and lacing is excellent .  the mouthfeel is full bodied for the style , with subtle carbonation .

lightish amber with a nice head that retains wee , good lace . one time it 's in solid sheets , the next in beautiful rings .  mouthfeel : big exploding bubbles , thin , lots of good , filling , `` evaporation '' feel . very interesting .

lots of sticky lacing coats the side of the glass.. aroma - strong sweet fruits ( definite pineapples . grapefruits and some passion fruit ) , creamy vanilla , very light maltiness , sugary / honey notes , some spiciness / pepperiness , some cloves , yeasty notes , floral hops , some grassiness ... taste spicy fruits ( apples , some pears , light pineapples and grapefruits ) , nice spicy floral hop bitterness , light sugary sweetness ( not as sweet as aroma would indicate ) , vanilla , light pale malts , light biscuity hints , some alcohol coming through ... mouthfeel quite sharp and dry although some smoothness comes through afterwards ... light body ... pretty refreshing and drinkable considering the strength ... overall an excellent beer . probably my favourite chimay brew ps - have also had this on tap at the mort subite bar in brussels . also had slighty more spiciness to it ... .  the feel is actually pretty darn good considering . nice crispness in the middle .
it 's got a beautiful brown body with a fantastic , super long lasting tan head .  it starts off with a slightly fizzy mouthfeel then settles smoothly in the finish .
it still looks and smells great . a nice brown/amber color with a two finger tan head .  m - medium body , medium carbonation .

a : appears a brilliant clear copper with hues of red , creamy white 1 finger head , little lacing s : the aroma is quite muted , not picking up much more than some sweet malts and a touch of caramel .  the mouthfeel is the strongest point , which is pleasantly carbonated if a tad slick .

smell - absolutely wonderful hops smell . its best qualities are appearance and wonderful aroma . taste and drinkability are a little challenging but tolerable .  the mouthfeel is at least good . very crisp and clean .

pours a deep black with a dark chocolate head . one of the darkest heads i have seen ! head comes alive from deep within the beer mountaining up to build a three finger head . as the head falls , a thick sheet of head remains on the glass , legs for days .  the mouthfeel is a nice , decently carbonated , finishes a little dry , but overall good .
an interesting spiced apple aroma on the finish . ( t ) - nice fruity apple , pear , and melon flavors with a dry , hoppy finish .  good body with a slight metallic underlay .
quite impressive . t : starts tart and fruity , but instantly dies into a nothing sweetness .  the mouthfeel is done well , pretty thick , with low carbonation .

pours a crystal clear light golden color with a pretty nice cap of creamy white foam . retention is above average and the lacing is excellent .  the mouthfeel is thick and sticky , with little carbonation , as you 'd expect with a barleywine .

it has a clear , light amber color with a nice head and fantastic retention .  taste : just as smooth as it is crisp with a creamy medium body , not too much on the clove spiciness but it is there and holds on through the finish .
i downright love this style , which is hard to find but sooo good . this is one of the better !  mouthfeel was fine , not too thin , smooth going down .

aroma is intense , incredible , overpowering . what 's in that nose ? blueberries , of course , and nothing else , but it 's a very pleasant , tasty flavor .  feels good in the mouth with average carbonation and the beer coating the mouth without sticking .

s- cherry is definitely the main component here . it has a dark warm chery cobbler aroma , as well as an ever so slightly tart nose . seriously though , huuuge kudos on masking the alcohol- this drank like 5 % ... crazy  mouthfeel is nice though , smooth and just right in the carbonation .

intoxicated by the aroma , i detect sweet floral notes with clover honey , caramel , banana , and a touch of nail polish . definately the highlight of the beer , the scent is different than any other duck rabbit beer . an intense rush of flavor greets the palate : liquor-esque banana and honey notes hit first . the salty presence makes the tongue sweat a bit , but the finish is lacking . i ca n't say that this is my favorite offering from duck rabbit by any means , but that may be a result of the style .  m : medium bodied with a medium level of carbonation .

fabulous pour , heavy and jet black with a modest 1/8 '' head that dissipates quickly . very nice garnet color under strong light .  mf : low carbonation , medium body , smooth d : interesting pairing- coffee with doppelbock.. ca n't say that it 's my favorite combo , but i 'm not sure if that is more due to the stale coffee character or if it is the pairing i 'm not the biggest fan of .
) the smell is outstanding , not just for its magnitude but its spmlicity as well .  mouth : milky smoothness . bit frothy .

it 's aroma is exceptional , intense , and enchanting . it 's a dangerous beer , with it 's high abv , but it is also very rewarding . great stuff .  mouthfeel was the best part of the beer to me . lightly sticky with a good amount of carbonation to make it feel slightly creamy and smooth .

no head whatsoever s : upon pouring the room filled with the aroma of dark caramel , toasted walnuts and cookies , with a foundation of oxidized , sherry-like sweetness . t : sweet sherry flavors and oxidation hit the palate first , followed immediately by strong toasted walnut and nearly burnt caramel .  very good mouthfeel . the malts and hops dance around the edges of the tongue with the adequate carbonation .
pitch black color . two fingers of thick creamy medium brown head with pretty good retention and a glass absolutely plastered with lacing .  mouthfeel : adequately fizzy .
smells just like the best thing ever . barley and fireplace .  ( m ) light to medium body with a creamy feel .
the toffee head is absolutely massive and rocky . retention and lacing are both out of this world , probably the best looking brown ale i 've ever seen .  active carbonation suits the style well .

a - crisp , brilliant clarity . bright orange with hints of red . head is initially thick then fades to a persistent thin layer with gobs of lacing on the glass .  good and refreshing crispness in the mouth , which provided some balance to the flavor .
s - wet hay , damp musty basement , light pear , green apple , lemongrass and a bit of funk .  mouthfeel is good . it 's got a decent thickness with nice carbonation .

a hasty pour into my urthel tulip results in a well carbonated , clear crimson beer with a massive , frothy light tan head with great retention . as the head recedes , it leaves a ton of lace . pretty !  m : nice light mouthfeel .

everything sweet and wonderful that you could imagine . gets more complex as it warms . t - chocolate and roasted , smokey malts . not super complex but finishes wonderfully . m - slightly thin but it ups the drinkability .  mouthfeel is light-medium and a touch creamy with low carbonation .
appearance : dirty crimson , like bloodied water .  good feel here , this is a decent body with good carbonation .
the aroma is amazing with strong fruity hops and maybe even a hint of coffee ... although i may be crazy .  mouthfeel : very light and crisp .
the look is just outstanding . full orange unfiltered goodness with a clingy head . beautiful beer .  m/d good mouthfeel carbonation is about right , not to sticky .

it just smells sweet and rich . flavor wise it starts out on the bland side but finishes with a bitter kick .  m : medium-bodied , nice smooth and even carbonation for the style - helps deliver the peppery flavors all over the palate .
smells quite nice , gets the salivary glands working overtime .  m & # 8211 ; kolsch always has good mouthfeel , it is one of its hallmarks , to me .
this brew smells wonderful ... .  mouthfeel is big surpy almost very full but how could it not be considering the malt in this beer .
a-black with a thick tan head that stays with good lacing s-smells very hoppy . i 'd say this is a terrible stout but a very decent beer .  medium body with a sweet creamy spicy mouthfeel .

smell is great , dark roasted malts , coffee flavors , some butterscotch , with a slight sweetness to it , very impressed with the smell . the taste is a very much dominated by the burnt coffee flavors , but with a nice creamy sweetness coming through with some bitterness on the finish .  m - full and smoothh d - this is a decent stout .
s : really surprising aroma for an ipa .  the mouthful was crisp and nicely carbonated .

anyway , this beer pours a nice mahogany color ( no surprise there ) with some ruby highlights showing through . nice head , good head retention .  viscous , almost syrupy but thankfully not cloying , with little noticeable alcohol .
appearance - big white head with great retention .  m : good feel , nice level of carbonation and just the right thickness .
aroma is sigh-inducing with great pine , citrus , floral and peppery hop notes . what kind of hops are in this thing ? it smells like fresh hops .  m - great prickly carbonation , light and crisp .
