s : great smelling beer . extremely herbal , coriander , yeasty and fresh like a spring breeze . if the beer tastes half this good i 'm in luck . d : too many spices added , detracts from the flavor of the beer .  the mouthfeel is light to medium bodied , lightly carbonated , and smooth .

solid caramel malt in this as well , this smells magnificent . hints of alcohol detected as well . d - very drinkable , great stuff here .  it 's the opidomy of light , the smoothness of velvet , and the price of mexican dreams . degrading this beer comes at a great insult to anyone with a ba , mba , phd or techinical certificate for the lessor of us . i swear the old texts , properly translated , would describle jesus actually making water into natty . it 's constant . this beer is the appertif of beers .

nose is a conglomeration of aromas , sweet malt , bread dough , port wine , cotton candy , caramel , and spices , clove i think . start has a deep malt sweetness , some alcohol bitterness at the back with the top moderate in feel . magnificent beer , as belgian strong ( s ) are my favorite style , this was a most enjoyable beer .  medium bodied with a slightly viscous mouthfeel and decent carbonation ( so where 's the head ?

the smell was of cranberries and some jasmine , with a hint of alcohol . the cranberries and jasmine were both present in the taste , but the alcohol was very much in the front . this beer is not totally undrinkable , but there is no way i would want to even smell another one of these after having one .  mouthfeel : sits in the mouth well . great carbonation level though .

s : piney hops , cotton candy , brandy , and toast qualities are all detected in the smell -- unusual , in a good way . t : begins off-dry , fruity and acidic , with hop aromatics providing some citrus and earthy complexity .  the mouth feel is light , crisp and refreshing .

garlic and citrus fruit are very present . pine also makes an appearance as well as marijuana . i love it ! t : tastes almost like it smells . i do n't get much garlic , not nearly as much as the smell offered up .  mouthfeel is nice and creamy-thick .

the smell is quite strong , and can be detected a few feet away from the glass . it ; s a sweet pink grapefruit aroma , with a bit of a pine scent along side .  m - carbonation is in check . light bodied as it should be .
very attractive smell . they could make this into a perfume .  medium body with a nice mouthfeel .

appearance : pouring creates a swirly cloud of foam that looks like milk being poured into espresso , in beautiful , downward-moving cascades of soft , creamy bubbles . foam comes to rest in a luscious , impossibly dense and creamy almond-off-white head with incredible retention . a very , very attractive brew .  maybe i had chilled mine for too long , do n't know but i found very little going on in my mouth to make me like this . the only positive comment i can make is that the taste did surprise me in that it was far smoother than what i was expecting . m. light , clean and much smoother than i imagined .

this beer smells positively freaking divine - full of spice and oats and raisins . i mean , i was practically huffing this like glue .  there is a definite hop bitterness that tries to balance out any sweetness that is left over , but gets lost in the wash. that being said , it 's bold in the body and has a pleasantly smooth but lively mouthfeel .
wow ! ... . the taste falls down a bit after the nice smell ... .  f - medium bodied with good carbonation , refreshingly smooth .

really enticing , a pleasant mixture of smells . t : pretty good , but pales in comparison to the smell . taste and feel are alright , but there 's no hint of the alcohol and the smell is quite nice .  mouthfeel - a full body whit lots of carbonation .
attractive red-amber with a thick , off-white head . beautiful lacing -- lovely and meticulously detailed . a in presentation , for sure !  mouthfeel : very clean and crisp with a light body .
i got a hint of golding hops and a solid offering of caramel malt .  m : thick and creamy . yummy d : very drinkable beer .

it gathers in my wide-mouthed glass very close to black . the head is very nice and lush . retention is decent , but the full sheets of lacing are left up to a wide collar .  the beer is light and refreshing with just medium carbonation , so it leans towards the smooth side .

the beer pours a blackish red color its very attractive and pours a thick head that disaperas in a couple of minutes but leaves lacing till the end of your beer .  a metallic bitterness just lingers on the back of the tongue ... but , the mouthfeel is good ... medium , high carbonation and medium-full bodied without being syrupy .

appearance- pretty dark pour with some cherry colored highlights . full fairly creamy white head with nice hardened sticky lace left upon the finish .  smell - malt smells dominate , chocolate msotly from what i can detect , not overpowering , in fact it 's very pleasant to the nose . the first thing i thought of was wine , sour and not pleasantly so . frankly i do n't like it . overall - a beer that 's exceptional in every area except the most important one : how it tastes .

cinnamon , clove and a natural `` pumpkin '' aroma that does n't smell faked or overdone . light ginger is a good accent to the smell . nutmeg is n't overdone which is key in my opinion . amazing complex yet not overdone spice presence . nicely balanced , nicely spiced .  m : the light body is slightly dry and has ample carbonation .

poured a very crisp transparent gold with 3 fingers of bright white creamy head . got some really good lacing . this is a beautiful beer . the bubbles are exploding up to the top of the glass like a mini a-bomb got dropped in my glass .  the liquid 's nicely velvety , smooth as it moves about . body between medium and medium-heavy . very light fizziness .

a - cloudy pale straw colored brew with a 1-finger head s - this is by far the most enjoyable brew i have ever sniffed . the spices are amazingly up front and pleasent . green tea , ginger , orange and coriander all blend together beautifully t - the scent follows though in the flavor , but not as much as i would 've liked . although i 'm from milwaukee , i have n't been able to come across this very easily , so i 'll definitley be looking for it .  light bodied , smooth and crisp .

pours a beautiful copper color with great clarity and a foamy white head that sticks around a while and leaves soapy rings of lace . the aroma is strong on pine , floral , bright citrus like grapefruit and apricot , and some grassy qualities as well . interesting and complex combinations on top of a brown sugar , honey and leather backbone . hints of toffee and leather lend a strange off flavor . strange leather-like musky notes throws things off as well . overall an interesting sipper .  this is my first review on beer advocate and i will try to do my best with reviewing beers . a very sweet taste goes down very smooth .

it starts bubbling up and i think `` hell , it 's a barleywine , not much will come of it ... '' seconds later i have a pool of tan foam on my counter and a whiff of whiskey in my nose . the rocky head falls slowly into a thick cap , leaving sticky lace .  m- medium body with good carbonation .
great big froth of beige over basic bubbly copper .  smooth yet thick on the palate .

poured into a snifter a : very dark pour which gives a huge head , coffee colored . fantastic sticky lacing all over the place s : roasted malts dominate the nose , but there is some coffee present too .  mouthfeel : crisp and clean , it feels more like a pilsner than an ipa , which , in my book isnt necessarily a bad thing , but it is unusual . overall : alaskan made a half-way decent ipa here , but it seems much more suitable for a hot night in georgia than anytime in alaska .
bottle courtesy of fonefan : poured a dirty beige yellow color ale with a huge foamy head with great retention and perfect lacing .  mouthfeel pretty good , medium carbonation and mouthfeel .
clear amber ale with an unbelievably thick three finger head of pure white foam . pretty decent retention , and a fine web of lacing .  nice medium- to full body . smooth .

a - perfect pour/appearance . a clear , golden orange color with a three-finger , thick , khaki colored head of foam that had amazing staying power . when it did finally start to recede , it left sticky patches of lace . good balance and amazing appearance ( or maybe my bell 's tulip is the perfect glass ) .  medium carbonation . a bit dry for my taste .

an excellent lambic with an wonderfully pungent black currant aroma . the flavor is full of fresh crushed fruit and herbal notes .  mouthfeel : light- to medium-bodied and pretty smooth . good amount of carbonation to go with the stronger parts of the flavor .

s- i can smell this all night . crust comes through a ton , making this a pumpkin pie beer , instead of just pumpkin . pumpkin , spice , vanilla are all prominent as well . t- not quite as nice as the smell , but still great . cinnamon , vanilla , clove , ginger , pie crust , and oh yeah ... pumpkin ! o- this is most likely the best pumpkin beer i 've had . it 's not for the sugar-wary though , but if you have a sweet tooth , ( i usually do n't ) this is a perfect beer for you .  m - medium , lots of carbonation , coats mouth well .

on tap @ east village tavern 09-14-08 a- hazy orange or a reddish yellow , the head piles high on the body , creamy , an off white color , s- nose has a big fruit like aroma , bananas , over ripe peaches t-m- start has a decent malt presence , sweet and a bit of hops at the back , top is middling in feel .  mouthfeel : decent . probably the best part of this beer the carbonation level suits the taste .

the nose has a nice honey/caramel malt backing , along with some hop aromas that are typically citrusy but also contain some unusual spice notes ( sage !  -original gravity : 1.052 -final gravity : 1.013 -abv : 5.2 % -abw : 4.06 % -attenuation : 74.2 % -real extract : 5.04 p -calories per 12 oz : 170 -malts : two row harrington , wheat malt , vienna malt -hops : east kent goldings , spalt spalter while i like the fact that bbc ( or anyone for that matter ) makes a kolsch style ale , i dont think this ones that great an interpretation . the fairly delicate , softly carbonated body is subtly malty , but even more subtle so that this lover of subtlety can appreciate . the slightly zippy , almost citric tail is pretty much what ive come to expect from american-style kolsch beers , though not having had a real koln kolsch , i dont know if this particular flavor is present in the classics .

smells of chocolate , roasty , earthy malt , and resinous hops . alcohol is present in the nose , but it has a way of tying the other smells together . this beer marries a sweet chocolatey maltiness with a sturdy hop kick .  m : a light and refreshing mouthfeel that i feel was the best part of this beer . unfortunately , it is more alcoholic than malty , which takes away from its decent body and mouthfeel .

nose is pretty good , however - hazelnuts come through with a nutty , milk chocolatey presence , with the spicing from the rum coming through pleasantly much more than the rum itself . really , surprisingly nice nose considering my initial impression from the appearance . fairly straightforward , not too complex , but what 's here is pretty nice . any richness or fullness promised from the beautiful hazelnut presence in the nose is completely missing .  mouthfeel is pretty good .
pours a nice deep dark amber with tons of beautiful bubbles constantly coming up to a small one finger slightly yellow creamy head .  the mouth feel is great , but the musty basement taste is not .

drank from a bottle into my rodenbach tulip , bottled last week of january 2011 ... looks great , a super dark dark with amber , shiny . the head is tope , great retention and lacing ... the aroma is equally nice , very hoppy ( light car pissyness and a hint of citrus ) but balanced with some spicy rye notes .  s- i noticed a very present woody aroma mixed with what i have to guess was agave and poppy seed . but since i dont know what either of them smell like alone its just a educated guess on my part thanks to the label . i clean freshening bite of hops and reminded me of pine trees . m/d- good sipper but faded as i continued to drink it .

smell : extreme . from smelling the bottle after opening to the glass after pouring , this barley wine screams hops ! very pleasant suprise ! overall : an impressive almost `` west coast '' interpretation of a hoppy barley wine , a must try !  feels good in the mouth , but , the taste is ... unfortunately awful .
this beer pours black as night with a creamy amber foam . nice carbonation .  on the plus side , very smooth .
the smell is awesome . think if someone dropped a banana in a glass of orval .  mouthfeel - somewhat of a thick body with medium carbonation .

s : wow , seriously ? this is as tropical an ipa as i 've smelled . tons of citrus , namely orange , mango , and grapefruit . a good amount of pine encompasses the aroma providing much of the body with the pale malts . t : a little less fruity than the nose . i get a solid dose of orange , pineapple and grapefruit up front riding the wave of pale malt . good citrus flavor .  the carbonation and mouthfeel were good , however .

maybe the best beer smell ever to wander up my nostrils . this stout sit below a thick vapor that is sweet and boozy with anise , chocolate and coconut . smells a little grapey , like a heavy red wine . goodbye , beer , down the drain .  m : the beer is light but feels full in the mouth with a good amount of carbonation .

smells like a delicious tart raspberry . it has a very framboise-like aroma . nice tart fresh raspberry flavor upfront followed by a rather weak / bland malt base .  m- smooth and well carbonated , with a little zing on the tip of the toungue .
s - nice smell , quite sweet , herbal and perfumy , some notes of chocolate . good point : i can not smell the alcohol !  mf- good medium body with the right amount of carbonation .

decent head that sticks around for a while the smell is amazing . a strong cherry scent with hints of fruit and hops . a very strong cherry flavor with some earthy tones and a hint of hops .  m : nice . light and crisp just like a wheat beer should be . an interesting beverage .

crystal malts provide the body and structure that supports the intense centenninal and chinook bitterness . the snappy hop finish is topped only by an intense cascade nose . all in all , this beer is typical of the bj 's approach : bigger and bolder than the style calls for .  it does have that nice slightly creamy mouthfeel that bitburger and a few other quality pils have .

lacing is awesome and so is everything else .  smell & gt ; bih-tuuur taste & gt ; sweet start , bitter middle , rye-ness , finishes almost lagery which i 'm not a fan of mouthfeel & gt ; goes down smooth and easy . good mouf .

one of the best looking beers i 've seen . pours a gorgeous dark copper brown ale , with a lovely foam head that sticks around .  the mouthfeel is light-medium bodied with lots of creamy carbination ; probably the highlight of the beer .
a : pours a clear golden-amber , tons of carb bubbles flowing up through to support two fingers of foamy white head .  not very sweet . solid body with a lot of carbonation .

s- smells delightful . i can smell the maple in the pour . very good .  mouthfeel : thin- to medium-bodied and very smooth , especially for a wheat beer . especially not when there are so many great wheat beers out there .
s- smells like a pretty decent single malt scotch , with clove , cinnamon and some smokiness coming through .  mouthfeel - medium . crisp .

fruit , hops , mango , still the same from the first time . it was bitter and hoppy , like an ipa should be , but not in the disgusting way it was the first time . it had a lot of bitterness , along with toasted grains and a little malt . the only flaw was that i feel it was not as balanced , in maltiness , as an ipa should be .  mouthfeel - light-medium body , well balanced carbonation .
a great irish ale presence with 1 cm head and a nice light brown tranlucent body .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with smooth carbonation .
a - pours a deep brown with a finger of tan head and decent retention . an excellent looking beer !  smooth moderate mouthfeel and not too filling - not a bad beer , too .

what starts as a dense , orange-tinted , thick head of about an inch and a half settles rather quickly into a film covering . the beer itself is a rich , vibrant , slightly hazed copper-orange coloring . looks great .  m : very light and crisp , moderate carbonation .
it opens up with a beautiful floral hop aroma that is sweet and begs you to take a sip .  medium bodied and decent carbonation .

smell is dominated by sweet coffee . a nice change from some ba 's that are like taking a shot of maker 's every sip .  m - this is really one of the most redeaming qualities of this beer . its crisp , dry and thin . quite refreshing , but not what i expect from the style .

very very nice smell . flavor follows the nose , but a bit more bitter than i expected , but dark fruit dominated ris .  m : big body for the style with low carbonation to give it a nice creamy smoothness .

vintage 2009 bottle ... a : midnight black with a super thick mocha colored head that stands 2 inches tall . perfect !  the mouthfeel was surprisingly not too syrupy , but at almost $ 7 a bottle i wo n't go back for seconds .

pour was the high point , deep amber / oak with a massive frothy ivory head . nice lacing .  the funky yeast just does n't quite meld with the hops . its very spicy on the finish as well , and it feels like the hops and the natural spiciness are fighting with each other for control of your palate . light and zesty on the palate in a good way .

it 's beautiful , with a hazy gold because of the yeast and cascading lacing , and it smells and tastes estery and wheaty to start before a good mouthful of bitter herbal hops and a funky finish with lots of green apple esters .  mouthfeel , in nice and smooth for an adjuct lager , not overly dry ( maybe it 's supposed to be ) .

s. smells of honey , sweet malt , citrus hops , grains , and grass . t. a bit let down on the taste after the wonderful look and aroma . an interesting honey backbone with some graininess starts off the brew only to quickly change into a citrus hoppy bitterness with some earthy hops as well .  medium to full body , quite crisp . hops slightly dominate flavor over malt . finish is long , dry , coffeeish , almost stout like .
a : pours a hazy amber color with a fluffy yellow head . about one finger in height and leaves some great lace down the glass .  m - oily creamy and frothy .
brett funk t : very tannic . overall a very very good beer .  nice , filing carbonation , medium-high drying at the end . very nice .
this one goes into my glass colored deep crimson brown with a fat head and amazing lace .  the body is fairly good .

bomber into a snifter a-deep orange with a nice white head that floats on top for a while ... the bubbles are there but not over the top ... s-caught me off guard ... u can really smell the sweet and dank amarillo hops and the citrus from both amarillo and cascade from the dry hopping ... really surprised this stood out in a wild ale ... the funk is here with the acidity ... t-semi sweet grain starts this off then follows with the twang ... the sourness and the wood take over the middle ... with a little acidity ... .the funk is def there seems this is very brett forward with a good amount of must to even out the sour ... finishes extremely dry.. m-thin but i imagine that is from the maturation in the wood ... the carbonation is perfect and the acidity doesnt wreck my palate or my stomach ... .very very dry ... . o-a very good sour ... far superior to last years la folie ... .but not on par with erics ale ... .quite pleased with it ... will go back for more..  mouthfeel : medium body with tingly carbonation and a dry finish .

aroma is bready , hearty , and contains everything a rich slice of pumpkin pie should . wonderful spices on the nose - strong cinnamon , nutmeg , some cardamom . sweet and spicy , very fulfilling aroma . wonderful pumpkin pure taste , with a noticeable hop biterness .  m - it was crisp , sharp and very smooth . a medium bodied beer with a dry finish .

mild haze ; looks pretty good . lovely smell . big tangy , floral hop aroma giving me passionfruit butter , lemon zest , pine resin and orange blossom . great fresh , light aromas that is really just the result of lots of dry hopping , but hey i like it . decent , needs a bit more malt to balance , hops are both too dominant and a bit too 'swimming ' in the unsubstantial , watery base .  m- medium body with a moderate carbonation .
the beer is an incredibly dark ruby color .  mouthfeel is good and the drinkability is below average just because of my personal opinion of the taste .

it smells of donut-topping sweet huckleberry fruit , and creamy malt - very reminiscent of the huckleberry ice cream i had somewhere on that trip .  the texture in the mouth is quite good , remaining effervescent and enjoyable throughout this tasting .

some dark fruits even this out and make for one wonderful scent . taste is strong on roasted malts and coffee beans with some dark fruits and a bit of water .  m : medium bodied with medium carbonation .

the smell is overwhelming , right out of the bottle . there is a dryness to it , with some good , balanced alcohol burn . the aging in cabernet sauvignon oak barrels , coupled with the addition of currants ( and perhaps lactic acid or brett ) makes this a beautifully crafted beer .  the smell is rather odd , but that 's a lambic for you i suppose . taste is quite sour , which i am not used to in my americanized lambic drinking . an interesting approach to the style .
the smell is very nice , with some chocolate , ripe fruit , vanilla , and strawberry-banana yogurt .  good carbonation makes for a crisp and clean mouthfeel .
aroma is great and not your typical apa/ipa . elegant . very balanced , ending just a tad bitter .  m - it was crisp , sharp and smooth . a light bodied ale with a dry finish .
very bright and crisp looking with a nice one-finger bright white head and noticable carbonation .  the mouthfeel was full and approaching creamy .

smell : wow . immediate blast of yeasty bread . very complex and unusual ; i 've never smelled anything quite like it .  decent mouthfeel , medium-full with the right amount of carbonation ; probably the best aspect of this beer .

it is true to the style and smelled fantastic . it was called flowers and damnit it smelled like flowers ! overall it is worth getting if you can find one , very unique .  m : the mouthfeel is good . it 's creamy with just the right amount of carbonation .
a lot going on here . chilled is ok , but warm is sublime .  m- feels good in the mouth for the style .

s - beautiful light tartness , pronounced blue cheesy funk . really great nose t - nice light tartness , some cherry .  mouthfeel is watery with a lackluster carbonation . would n't seek out again as the finish was too medicinaly and the feel was thin and watery .
great orange/tan color with a fantastically huge head that lasted forever , leaving stupendous lacing .  mouthfeel - watery and thin .

the nose is bright and full of fruity esters : pears and apricots come to mind , perhaps some fresh green apples . a rather inviting aroma . the invitation accepted , things slump a bit on the tongue .  sweet , lacking much body . basically a soda pop with a very low abv .
it feels very uncomfortable .  mouthfeel is thin and watery .
kulmbacher 's moenchshof pours nicely to produce a thick amount of head .  felt thin in the mouth and did n't have any of the body i was expecting .
nice amber color with a fluffy two fingers of head that leaves nice lacing .  m : watery . far too watery , even for this style .

s - unbelievably good . sat there and just savored the aroma for a while . it steps in and distracts and overwhelms the wonderful aromas . m - medium bodied , flat .  drinks : warm , the obnoxious funk flavor , paired with the unsettling mouthfeel , makes this beer nigh undrinkable .
i love everything else about it . perfect blend of hops/malts , looks great , smells wonderful . this looks like amber honey with a nice fluffy head to it .  the mouthfeel is light and watery .

appearance was exceptional ruby-red to light brown with a frothy head smell was somewhat bland more so than i had expected for a beer of this quality and reputation , and the drinkability was limited by its hefty alcohol percentage otherwise , an all-around outstanding brew that certainly warrants recognition enjoyed this one recommended  m - there simply is n't enough texture here for a great dunkel . at first it seems almost medium but the brew quickly becomes far too thin for the style .
beer poured black as night with a very nice tan head that sustained wll .  the body is decidedly watery , or maybe that 's the too-high carbonation producing a spritzy , foamy finish .

smell is incredible - full of citrus and piney hops with a bit of pineapple and a little malt underneath .  mouthfeel is awful due to the lack of carbonation . absolutely no carbonation whatsoever - none , nada . a very interesting beer but the lack of carbonation easily keeps this one from being world class .

cloudy brown with sienna hues and tan velvety smooth head with fantastic retention . good clear flavors meld well and are thoroughly enjoyable , not to mention it is a beautiful looking beer .  m - medium body with a dry finish , yet an odd carbonation that again reminds me of soda .
great clumpy off white head , with impeccable retention . the body is light copper in color and has only a slight haze to it .  mouthfeel was watery and dry with nothing to stick on the tongue .

as you pour its a light cloudy straw with a huge and lasting white head . the head itself if very attractive as it is very fluffy and creamy .  mouf & gt ; overly carbonated and full . the mouthfeel sucks . '' drinkability & gt ; we finished the bottle because it still tasted good , but it was not as good as the 2008 .

the appearance is almost perfect for the style the smell has very little hops in it , and actually has a lot of yeast smell to it .  the head was minimal and the level of carbonation a little too high for my liking . the smell was weak and the mouthfeel was too harsh .
pours a dark amber with a massive dark amber head of dense foam that slowly melts to very sticky and thick lace .  this beer was very watery for a porter .
s- bottle a- looks delicious . just a beautiful looking saison .  mouthfeel is very thin , which i suppose is an asset in tropical countries .

the head began as a big , rocky , bubbling mass of bone-white foam that settled into a finger of marshmallow-fluf like head which finally just sat down entirely . color was a magnificent golden yellow , like sunshine in a glass .  really thin .

this stout is a deep brown/black with a good-sized , frothy red/brown head with good longevity that leaves great lacing .  body is thin and woefully under-carbonated , but in it 's defense , roswell alien amber does n't have any detectable off-notes .

a : a huge , frothy , mocha colored cap that leaves behind huge clumps of lace sits atop a black body .  mouthfeel was a bit flat and watery , and the carbonation made this beer seem harsh and scratchy .

appearence : pours an oh so gorgeous creamy orange with a thin , sustaining nearly white head .  mouthfeel is where it really lets me down again . lots of bitter taste , lots of carbonation , but other than that it 's pretty watery and does n't do much for me on the way down .

a - extremely dark , nearly black . a huge , pinkish-brown head that just does not go away . lots and lots of lacing .  overall , a good beer that would be better if the carbonation levels were dialed down .
excellent retention and beautiful lacing .  it was overly carbonated and thin to my disapointment .

as dark as a moonless desert night , the head is quite modest in size , the texture spumescent , light chocolate in color and as it degrades leaves behind a fine coating of lace upon the glass .  had the banana and clove aroma and taste but the body is just way too think and the lack of carbonation makes it tough to drink .

a -- deep dark mahogany with killer amber red head and tons of lacing , beautiful , scores a perfect 5 .  the mouthfeel is very lively , very slippery/oily and buttery . too carbonated , which is strange for a stout . drinkability is ok given the high abv , but the bitterness , aftertaste and carbonation cancel that out somewhat .
poured into a snifter , revealing rich brown body and a very thick , very tall tan head .  carbonation is out of control and really distracts from truly enjoying this ale .

beer poured a clear golden orange with a generous 2 finger white head that is leaving a perfect lacing behind .  the taste is allright ( besdies the odd must ) , some roastiness in here but the thing that bothered me was the mouthfeel .
a - poured a beautiful black color with a dark tan head . the head retention was moderate .  mouthfeel : wow -- so very watery .
a - hazy orange color . thick , white head with good retention . good lacing .  the body is really watery for the style and unsatisfying despite the flavor being pretty good .

i sat and smelled this beast for a good 5 minutes . taste follows the smell with the vanilla upfront leading to the oaked bourbon finish . was expecting more bourbon on this one , but still very nice . silky smooth mouthfeel will definite traces of the alcohol , but that 's what is expected . made a trip out today with the girlfriend just to get away from home and am pleasantly surprised to find they tapped a keg today .  thin bodied overall , and mild maltiness .

from the second i cracked open the cap , the room filled with the sent of vanilla , as far as smell goes this the best smeling beer ever ! the tast is good but not as good as i had hoped this one is sweet with a fair vanilla kiss and a carmalised malt flavor . i think it might be the hop aftertaste on this one , i would rather have this one finish sweet .  mouthfeel : watery texture , medium body and low carbonation .
reviewed from notes taken 4-02-2010 served on nitro at the left hand tasting room a - black with red highlights and a thick , dense off-white head that lasts the whole glass .  m - thin . very thin .

a- nice looking beer , bright white head with a clear light copper color . leaves awesome lacing and has nice head retention .  its corona , does it really need a review ? tastes like lime juice and pulp . head n/a as much as i would avoid buying a corona to drink with a nice steak dinner , theres always a certain appeal to buying it as ambience at a cookout .
head retention is amazing , as is lacing . a great looking beer .  mouthfeel - seemingly flat , or very undercarbonated .

really spectacular aroma that calms my annoyance at losing so much beer . it comes together beautifully . delicious taste that just barely fails to live up to the aroma .  mouthfeel is equally uninspired , with body on the lifeless , watery side .

a : deep copper color with compact , dense and full head , tiny bubbles , clear s : medium deep roasted , burnt malt nose with etoh presence , some oxidation t : nice beer , some hints of oak aging , good deep roasted/burnt malt with yeasty qualities , reminded me of an amped dubbel , slight amount of sourness in finish ( barrel aging or infection ?  taste is very mild , with almost nil carbonation . no hops , only water , malt and honey as noted on the label .
nice and dark like an imperial should look .  sweet maltiness in the front , but very thin . watery and plain .

a : dark cloudy orange , decent head , decent carbonation ; lacing is n't bad s : floral bouquet , very hoppy ( pleasantly so ) , much in line with the style t : tinny right at the front , but moves quickly to a decent ipa-style -- floral , bitter , hoppy ; but the metallic notes linger , unfortunately ; the alcohol is blended rather nicely ; were i given this without being told its style i would have guessed straight up ipa . the main detraction for me is the metallic notes , which i 've detected in other saranacs too , some more than others .  mouthfeel : very clean but the body is way to light even for the style . feels like water really .

poured from bottle into my trusty irish pub pint glass , dark opaque ruby hue with a nice thick khaki head with minamal lace .  there is medium carbonation , but the body really falls off at the end . the thin feeling is not pleasant .

i poured this into a palm tulip and belgo made a good two finger thick head , and the body is nicely filtered and is copper in color . head retention is outstanding .  mouthfeel : i 'm disappointed . it is very watery and the carbonation is almost non-existent . it tastes/feels almost flat ( and this is the second one i 've tried tonight ) .
brilliantly clear dark copper hue . covered by a thick , rutted , persistent ivory white head that leaves rough lace .  mouthfeel seems remarkably thin here , even for style .

s- mmmm , ruuum . but , the smoke still comes through underneath the rum . t- this is really quite nice , almost liquor-ish because of the lack of carbonation ( there is just the tiniest amount ) nice smokiness upfront with the sweet tanginess of the rum dominating the palate in the middle all the way to the finish .  extremely watery .

i know it is a fallacy to say this on this website , but here goes nothing : i am not a huge fan of ipas . i know , sorry , but it is the easiest beer to make and everyone goes crazy for it for some reason . i am just not a huge hop guy , and for an ipa , the hops are there , but not overpowering .  this beer is way too carbonated to the point where it almost hurts to drink . much more carbonation than a soda .

a : exceptional , should be the example of perfect lacing ! it pours a golden hue topped with a frothy white head that leaves you feeling the beer wants you to drink it .  since it is so thin compared to other stouts , i do have to rate it accordingly . sorry but it could be thicker .

this is a barrel-aged version of florence with brett . notes from my phone : beautiful hazy orange gold with thick creamy bone-white head . this is perhaps the most beautiful beer that i 've ever seen !  tastes very watery . low ratings on taste and mouth feel reflect the lack of flavor rather than bad flavor .

poured into my guinness pint glass a- really does n't get better . black with a nice creamy two inch tan head s- mostly roasted malts , some chocolate t- chocolate malts is the initial taste , then the bourbon kicks in nicely with some coffee notes as well m- fairly heavy , with fair carbonation d- very good .  mouthfeel is thin and watery .

very nutty aroma with some surprising chocolate smells . t : caramel malts with some surfacing hops that balance the sweetness nicely . o : very good , i only had a single 19 oz .  thin and watery mouthfeel with more carbonation then desired for the style . carbonation comeing through strong and man , i just cant get past this watery thin , frail mouthfeel .

the beer is nearly black . some deep scarlet red streaks can be seen against light . decent size and retention as well .  woody creek white , flying dog 's 'new ' summer seasonal , pours as near white as one might imagine possible for a beer , which makes for an impressive look that is countered ( and unfortunately not enhanced ) by a fizzy , quick-to-dissipate head . across the tongue , this really just disappears , and the initial spice and malt flavors turn watery . this is not my favorite colorado wit nor my favorite flying dog brew .

a- thick , motor-oil , dark brown beer , slow-growing 1cm creamy thick oatmeal cookie head . nice initial lace ring .  light-medium carbonation and light bodied . grapefruit hop nose and flavor is same - grapefruit hops with hints of caramel , watery . $ 1.85 for a 12oz bottle from colonial spirits acton , ma .

one of the coolest looking labels that i 've ever seen . it is blacker than charcoal and forms a great mocha colored head .  extreme level of carbonation here . it seems like this is more carbonated than a soda would be even . i am not sure if it is meant to be this carbonated , but i do not care for this . overall , this a good beer but the carbonation is not what i expected from this style .
'' really dark with a thick and creamy dark brown head . nice head retention and great lacing all the way through .  the mouthfeel is off , it is way to thin .

pours a ruby color with a 1 finger fluffy pink head . good amount of carbonation rising . just beautiful to look at .  appearance = 20 % red , nice color , cloudy , low carbonation , litle to no head smell = 20 % citrus smell , slightly sour taste = 40 % cirus flavor , slightly hoppy and bitter mouthfeel : very light , not impressed .

the exceptional head is just about 3 fingers thick , and a rich chocolate cream color . on the way down , this brew leaves a considerable amount of lace for it 's abv . truly the best stout i 've ever seen poured ( along with a yeti ... tied for first ) .  mouthfeel- very thin and watery with a brisk , small , tingly carbonation . drinkability- this beer is very different .

a- wow , what a great looking pour . nice one finger pink/cream head s- the smell really through me off on this .  it was like a melted milkshake , but really watery . if they made `` dessert beers '' this would qualify . very sweet , very chocolately , almost like a milkshake .

such good fresh tastes and aromas . great easy drinker , good session , could sit back with tons of these on a warm evening .  a text book pilsener-which is a positive note but the bready quality is not full . finish is clean but it has the after-taste of the gaterade power water . drinks ok , and i would enjoy this on a hot summer day-just a bit pricey for a miller lite clone in a nicer bottle .

a : one of the most beautiful beers i have ever seen . it pours a murky creamy brown color . the head is monstrous . it is sooo large and fluffy kind of like whipped cream in appearance . this baby reminds me of a root beer float . the head absolutely refuses to die . it 's a very solid example of a dubbel .  the body is light with a super watery feel .

this stout looks as delicious as it tastes .  it 's body , unfortunately , is fatally flawed : this beer feels more watery than water . an interesting beer that starts off at a sprinter 's pace for excellence and quickly slides downhill .

the aroma is really interesting here . wonderful aroma . not quite as complex or intense as it could be , but this is instead a refined , subtle , sophisticated , and very approachable lambic .  mouthfeel - thin , a little oily from the hops , with very strong carbonation that hits you in the palate towards the finish the drinkability of this beer is very high , it is smooth , and makes a much better impression on people than budweiser , a good transition beer , but not too much to write home about .
a - totally clear golden yellow with bubbles constantly coming up to a well formed white head . good retention with moderate lace left on the glass .  mouthfeel is slightly flat .
a nice pour from the bottle produced a frothy , cream-colored head settled on a dark amber body .  it 's almost watery .
black with ruby highlights to a light source , a nice creamy tan head , and nice lacing .  much too much carbonation .

large dense deep brown head , it almost looks like it has reddish tints as well . great retention and clumpy streaks of lacing all over the glass .  overly attenuated , skimpy and lean in overall body , with a mouthfeel that lacks any firm viscosity .

it is eerie how perfect this beer looks.. from that reverse cascade pour comes a perfectly consistent black liquid under a similar khaki head . stain is crazy thick and solid like the lace .  fairly light and crisp on the palate , the hops snap an edge to it , but then it goes watery on the finish . not an epic beer , but a decent cold mug type brew .

a phenomenal , cascading pour fills the glass with a thick , seal brown stout . great retention on the head , too .  mouthfeel is very strange . then an odd meatiness and tannin-laden tongue coating descends upon the palate , rendering all flavors void and unable to be enjoyed .

appearance : the beer poured a nice 3 finger chocolate colored head . also , beer is pitch black with no clarity and no signs of carbonation . the head of beer has not come down yet and will have to say the retention is fantastic and lacing on the glass .  carbonation is too high , only further deteriorating that dry finish .

a : great looking beer with a one finger head and no lacing on the glass .  too thin and the carbonation is too high given the taste . overall : the taste and smell of this beer are amazing , but the mouthfeel really took away from the beer .

poured from nitro-tap into a pint glass a : black and frothy with a thick , chewy , off-white head , very similar to what a layman would see in a guinness , but with an even thicker head .  a very enjoyable coffee tastes swirls on the tongue ... hmmm ... ... then it breaks my heart , and completely fades away into a watery , thin , no hops finish..not even an aftertaste . if they wanted smooth , they got it by neutering this beer on the tongue and letting it fade into a bad memory . too bad .
22 oz bomber in to pint glass a- looked great at the start , dark black with an inch of tan head .  the body was very thin .

a : pours a very deep brownish-crimson color with a sizeable off-white head that retains well and lays down a bit of lacing on my snifter . very impressive appearance .  i had a really weird reaction to this beer - it caused me my mouth to water . the mouthfeel clings , even as my mouth is fighting back with spit . did i mention it makes my mouth water ?
a beautiful deep red , yet clear .  the feel of the beer is very dry - too dry for me but others may like it .
i may be a little biased , but i love to just admire and look at beers this black and opaque .  m : seemed really thin and with a tad too much carbonation .

the brew is bright light gold with a magnificent , thick creamy head that slowly dissipates to leave thin bubbles and a slight lacing around the glass .  m- thin , watery with crisp prickly carbonation throughout .
the beer pours a cloudy yellow with a rocky off white head that holds wonderfully and laces incredibly .  far too over-carbonated , and watery mouthfeel .

12 oz bottle poured into a pilsner - fridge - 2008 appearance : pours a very dark brown with orange/brown highlights . a tall , 2 '' head that is cakey and shows great retention .  this is a cheap-o beer that i drink when i want a beer but want to save money . its not a great teasting , smelling , looking , or feeling beer , but once you get a to your 3rd one you can drink about 50 . this is the perfect cheap get hammered , tailgaiting beer .
poured into a la fin du monde tulip glass and this one has a huge , rocky , foamy head of about three fingers . very nice looking .  m : awful dry , tannic bitterness d : not so average
s : smell is actually quite nice . it 's fruity , sweet , and yeasty .  m - dry finish , kind of tough , alcohol harshness , medium bodied .

simply awesome . unrelenting head , upwards of 1 inch , deep gold color , radiant .  the flavor is only surpassed , or should i say , harshened due to the over carbonated mess of a mouthfeel - i 'm left with a harsh boozy almost acidic/sour flavor in my mouth .
a-pours a very clear light copper color with two fingers of thick , frothy , off-white head .  m - medium bodied with poor carbonation levels . the carbonation is just wrong for this style of beer .

a- the color of red wine but less translucent with a beautiful sparkling pink head that surprisingly leaves some lace s- smell is sweet and tart berries but also has a mask of farm scent .  m : quite watery , with vague carbonation and a slight stickiness to the finish .

coming from my hometown , i was psyched to try this one , and it looks like my excitement was justified . pours dark as night with a wondeful nutty coffee aroma .  throw on a rather watery mouthfeel , and i am not much impressed .
winter 2003-2004 sampled in oct 2004 this beer poured a pitch black body with a very thick dark brown/tan head .  mouthfeel - very light , watery .
poured black with no light passing through . wonderful tan , frothy head which diminished to nice lacing .  mouthfeel is disappointingly watery .

pours black with a huge cascading head that filled up most of the glass and left tons of lacing , one of the best looking beers i 've had .  very little mouth feel or body and not much that reminded me of the beligians i miss so badly .

this beer is one of the more complex beers i have ever smelled ! it takes awhile to discern specific aromas . mildly tart and funky . nice . o - very enjoyable beer . i had had this beer many years ago and did n't remember it being so amazing .  extremely thick headed but dissipates rather quickly . it has a nice balance of bitter and malt to it . the biggest problem though is the after taste . it is terrible . really ruins the whole thing . easy going , but after the initial taste , it loses it 's luster .

a dark green cover now drapes what was , just a few short hours ago , a crystal blue liquid paradise . freshness date is l 184 h. appearance- much more yellow than amber , this supports an incredibly sustaining four finger crown . lacing is outrageous , draping the inside of the entire glass .  an intense taste , but at the same time , somewhat light and delicate . flat body .

12oz bottle a- pours a golden amber color with a very nice creamy off-white head that possesses excellent retention and lacing . a great looking beer to say the least .  unfortunately the lack of carbonation turns this into an overly sweet and cloying mess .
it reminds me of a good piece of saddle leather . simply beautiful !  m - light bodied , harsh carbonation level , odd , gritty texture .
a - deep brown black with 4cm thick cream head that last to end of the glass .  very thin in the feel though .

appearance : pours a mostly clear reddish amber color with a persistent creamy tan head that is about 1/4 '' it is leaving some pretty thick lacing on the class as you swirl it a bit . there are quite a few bubbles rising to maintain the head , and it is still very active quite a few minutes after the pour .  palate is watery , but drinkable . as i commented to the purveyor , for a pale lager in a can from wisconsin , its not bad .

had this out of a bottle poured into a dfh pint glass ... a : copper color with a nice 2 finger white head . the lacing on this one is fantastic ... s : smells of floral hops and sweet malt .  mouthfeel is the real problem here . very watery and insigificant .
a : this beer looks heavy . it pours slowly , and looks very viscous .  no carbonation whatsoever , so it pours like an extremely dark port .

the first thing one notices about bond street brown is its livid scarlet color . my bond street was served on nitro , which delivered the customary frothy properties to the head and lace .  mouthfeel is water . i prefer it over bud but this is still a very weak lager .
appearance : a deep reddish brown beer with a very nice head .  mouthfeel is watery and not that great .
a : pours a smooth black with a good 2-3 fingers of khaki brown colored head .  m : i know this is big , but there just way too much residual sugar here .

this faded to light ring around the edge ... decent stream of carbonation bubbes rush to the surface ... light patchy lacing ... aroma - tons of typical strong barnyard lambic funkiness with some very light strawberry jam notes in the background , real cider notes , cut wet grass , some sea salt , very light honey sweetness , quite floral - hints of lily , light oakiness , raw nuts - some pistachio traces ... taste - lots of sour apple notes ( cider vinegar ? ) , no real discernable strawberry flavour , strong typical tart lambic notes , no sweetness , some oakiness , very floral and perfumed , grassy , lemons and limes , salty notes ... feel - almost completely flat - just the slightest hint of carbonation ... very sharp and dry ... light bodied ... fairly drinkable although more than one would a bit of a struggle due to the tartness ... overall - a pretty good lambic although a bit more ( or maybe some at all !  mouthfeel is watery , spicy , with light coffee lingering .

after searching for this beer for a few weeks i spotted a 4-pack at publix in coconut creek florida ... after looking at the bottle 's message 'an intense hop experience ' i figured that it would be very hopy , not pure hops a : this beer pours a beautiful cloudy gold color with particles floating around ... a big three-finger head that leaves a thick spotty lace on the glass ... if you buy this beer , i strongly suggest that you pour it , because it is very hard to notice the beauty of this beer thru the brown bottle s : hops !  dry as anything , with an unacceptable watery finish . the second bc stout lately to be really watery .
loved the color ... dark caramel , with a rich look and feel to it .  mouthfeel is thin and watery , with little-to-no carbonation .

there is no information given about freshness , but some nutriant info is given , and there is the cool widget inside the bottle . this beer is one of the more impressive looking beers out there . as it was poured into my bell 's pint glass , a creamy head instantly formed , with nitrogen bubbles cascading to the bottom of the glass . after settiling a bit , a creamy tan half inch head remains throughout the whole experience . the beer is very dark , hints of brown are visible when held to the light , but this brew is pretty opaque .  ah coors ... pours a honey color with a nice head , and lace . the look is the best part of this beer . smell is of light skunk.mouthfeel is watery and flat . taste is light with a hint of spice . the beer was not awful , but i would not go out of my way to buy this beer .
gorgeous looking beer ... bordering on too dark for the style .  m : incredibly light body .
this is an exceptional beer . it is a very dark color with a milky head .  m- watery and uneventful . no fizz or carbonation factor .

a : pours a clear red color , 2 finger width head with great lacing down the glass s : real sharp spicy piney hop scent .  thin body with a high level of carbonation ; pretty good hop bite but the malt is nearly missing .

this beer poured into my pint glass absolutely beautifully . it was a brilliant , clear , amber color and the head pillowed over he rim of my glass like a thundercloud .  thin finish . ) the feel is watery and fizzy .
appearance : great looking dark lager with gorgeous dark hue , nice lacing , and medium carbonation .  overcarbonated , somewhat bloating despite the very light body .

s - the nose is pretty damn enticing . it still has admirable qualities , but the taste is sorely disappointing in comparison to the nose .  the mouthfeel is syrupy and cloying , the alcohol goes relatively unhidden .
a : slightly hazy orange light copper color with pillowing white head . great head retention especially considering the abv .  mouthfeel is flat , thin , & watery .

s : classic sculpin nose , mango and apricots , very tropical and distinct . there is some heat on the back end from the chiles , but nothing that grabbed me , nothing that screamed habanero . still a solid effort .  mouthfeel is watery , very flat .

appearance : the pour gives a 0.3 '' off white head that gradually falls back , though never quite all the way ... leaving a nice layer behind for awhile . the beer is a bright medium amber in color .  not much in the way of mouthfeel except water with a little something extra .
great retention and lots of coating , spongy lace .  the mouthfeel is extraordinarily watery .

a=pours a dark amber color with a huge 2 finger head with awesome retention , huge clumps of lacing down the sides of the glass . great looking beer .  appearance black with just a brief , tan film of a head smell only the slightest aroma detectable ; getting mostly cocoa notes taste & mouthfeel surprisingly thin body and low carbonation -- big letdown ; fairly tame from beginning to end ; good flavors of cocoa and roast in the mid-palate ; pretty small overall for a ris .
a little boozy , but still very tasty stuff .  light to medium body with a watery texture .
this beer looks great though .  m : the mouthfeel was very slippery .

bomber into pint glass , awesome label of 2 surfers looking at a mighty wave of hops . pours a hazy very light orange , huge sticky 3-finger white head on every pour , leaves crazy chunky lacing and retains easily at 1 finger or more .  mouthfeel- thin , and light in body .

presentation and appearance 12 oz bottle with a bland blue label . poured into my pint glass it is dark brown with red highlights on top sits a 2 finger creamy mocha head that leaves nice lacing .  mouthfeel and carbonation is poor , i could n't even get a head to form with a hard pour .
modest to light pour called up a massive five finger head with excellent retention and beautiful copious lace .  the palate is thin .

a : pours a deep dark black with a moderate-but frothy off-white head that dissipated quickly but clung to the glass well .  m- i was dissapionted , it was not nearly as thick as i expected , almost watered down . tooo thin , not very thick for a dark beer .

3.5 s big hops citrusy , great aroma , maybe the best part of this beer 4.5 t malty sweetness with a bitterness that hits the back of your tongue and stays .  m - thin mouthfeel d - very easy drinking beer but not much character .

from the bottle . poured black with a small tan head with some lacing .  i think there are some malts in the aroma and some vague hint of caramel . it is watered down and goes down quickly . better than some mich products but not as good as others .
the beer comes out pitch black and has the darkest head i 've ever seen . this is a really interesting looking beer .  body feels watery , especially in the finish .

pours a dark orangey-brown but sits nearly black in the glass . tan head takes a while to develop through the thick liquid but it puffs up to a solid three fingers before melting away to leave thick fine-bubbled lacing .  mouthfeel : lacks any significant body , very thin , just a step above a light beer .

had very good lacing as there was still plenty on the glass at the time it was finished . very nice deep golden color .  body is terribly watery , the pacman yeast ( which i usually like ) just does n't fit with this beer . the mouthfeel is as hearty as a hawiian death metal band .
looks perfect for a stout of this kind .  mouthfeel - watery , no bubbles , flat . drinkability - obviously not very drinkable for the fact this is 98 % flat .
xingu appears just on the edge of black , with a light brown head that fades to a blotchy film that retains well and leaves nice lacing .  mouthfeel - thin and watery .

poured from a bottle into a dogfish snifter a- pours a perfectly transparent shade of yellow/orange with a big two finger white head that 's very puffy . looks perfect s- citrus hops with a big of a bite to them ... .lovely t- getting a lot of citrus , but it almost tastes like dishwater ... no real bite to the hops at all .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and watery with no carbonation .
pours a nice hazy dark copper with a three finger white head that subsides to one finger .  m - thin and watery with a weakly carbonation and a flimsy neutral finish .

a - poured out a deep copper hue with a tan , bubbly/soapy , 4-finger head that left sticky rings of lace .  i find it to be very flat in both mouthfeel and complexity though . mouthfeel : flat and surprisingly disappointing . it is thinly bodied and is quite bitter . the flat body is a disappointment .

lots of lacing and spectacular lacing . tons of effervescence fed from the etching in the perfect pint . this beer really does have a beautiful color , there really isnt anything like it .  the beer is very thin and not very flavorful .
it had a nice amber colour with a thick foamy head and a fruity aroma .  very little aroma , mouthfeel 's watery .

a - black color , dark brown head . one of the darkest heads i 've seen in a beer .  yikes ... this is supposed to be an ipa ? this tastes like a half assed version of an apa . thin , watery , no head , no lacing , very little taste . where the hell are the hops ? this is a pale ale right ? wow , not a good beer .

poured from an 11.2 oz bottle into a stemless wine glass . a ) pours brown , and resembles apple cider in color/consistency .  some sweetness at the start , but the palate gets watery and thin quite quickly ... so not much body to speak of .

thick pillowy tan head with great retention . lacing is great . color is deep black with just a touch of brown at the very top .  as stated , the body is on the watery side of light . a poor showing from a brewing giant .

incredible nose a huge bouquet of fresh hops backed by a nice bready malt profile . another great beer from three floyds .  m. the mouthfeel is a little creamy and syrupy that leaves an unpleasant feeling in the mouth .

smells fruity , very citrusy , alot of orange and tangerine here ... after the initial por the nose was pretty week but after a few minutes i swirled the tulip a bit and a nice robust nose has appeared ... interesting .  m : just to thin for me . i expected it to be thick and creamy , but it feels like a flat soda in my mouth .

had this out of a can poured into a pint glass ... a : nice dark amber and red color with a wicked head . just huge and rocky as hell , great lacing .  could barely detect any spices , very thin body .

pitch-black body with a light-tan , almost white head . the body betrays itself as a dark red when held directly to the light , though . retention is awsome as would be expected for a nitro beer ; lacing is spotty but thick . the nitro camouflages this intricacies of this beer - all that 's left is bitter brown water .  feel is thin .
lots of bubbles float to the top ... truly great stuff here .  m- extremely thin , too carbonated .

-very black body with a tall , fluffy brown head with a nitro look to it . good lacing as well -at first it is mostly bourbon ... as it warms , chocolate comes through as well as some roast , vanilla and some warmth -milk chocolate throughout the taste .  a- light , golden , clear , no real head or lacing s- sweet , honey , cinnamon , hint of liquorice/mint t- very light , not much pumpkin m- very light and thin d- i could drink this for hours ( not in a good way ) it does n't have any of the weight or warmth that i want in a fall beer .

a-orange/amber ... leaves a nice lace on glass as i drink s-great aroma ... tons of toasted malts ... also some candied toffee ... i guess that is what toffee is : ) ... some caramel notes too ... very sweet aroma and a fresh hoppiness complements perfectly ... great smelling beer . t-where the nose is malt forward , the taste is more balanced ... some good hopping to this ... a citrus like grapefruit rind bitterness is evident..but it mingles nicely with the great malt backbone.. m-medium bodied ... .seems sessionable but still loaded with flavor .  again , completely flat .

beautiful lava lamp look when the yeast diffuses down through the hazy straw body and fluffy white head .  m slightly thicker than water and moderately carbonated . the mouthfeel and flavors make the beer come off feeling weak and thin .
stunning citrusy orange-grapefruit-lemon-passion fruit and pine aroma . could sniff this one all day . exceptional aroma carries the day here .  m - light bodied , overly acidic .
a - poured a beautiful and clear copper - i wish i could brew my homebrew to be this gorgeous a color and sheen .  m/d - it is unbelievably thin .
dark gold/bronze with a full pillowy beige head and very active carbonation .  it 's extremely sticky and flat .

i expected more - the flavor that most reviewers describe as dark coffee came across to me more like charcoal . the color was its best characteristic ; deep , rich , and dark .  the feel was too thin . what smoothness there was came more from thinness than anything else .
4.5 a : exceedingly dark brown , nearly black . a very good start .  m : mouthful was disappointing , bland and thin .
served in a pint glass , the beer pours dark brown/black with a frothy 2 inch tan head ( the pour was a bit vigorous ) .  not what i want from an ipa . mouthfeel - watery . flat .

pours out a rich deep black with two fingers of sandy tan froth , medium levels of lacing left behind with each sip .  lightly hopped and sparkling on the tongue , this brew is quite flavorful , and has a mouthfeel of carbonated water .

s : this beer kicked me right in the nose and said hops ! ! ! m : super bitter , it says so on the bottle , not my preference , but it truly lives up to this , the rating i 'm giving this is very generous .  m : thin and watery .

the cascades really linger on in the nose - wonderful aroma without the lingering bitterness of some beers . exceptionally fine beer - has become a staple in my fridge .  really thin mouthfeel , but super easy to drink .
the pour was a spectacular deep red , like the color of sunset with an almost yellow head .  mouthfeel is disturbingly thin and does n't have a lot of body at all .
it is really a nice looking beverage .  taking a small sip of this beer is very watery , but no unpleasant chemical taste like most cheap beers . beer is very light on the tongue .

pours from can a very dark auburn . orange highlights , a thick , creamy looking head , two-fingers thick . beautiful beer . first time i 've ever seen a decent head on a welli , must be the can .  by having a high carbonation with a watery finish .

) so i 'll try to play be the rules this time : appearance : solid black and thick as hell ( great looking stout ) smell : mixture of spoiled prune juice and nail polish remover taste : something is wrong with this .  the beer itself had a prickly & spicy feel that stuck in the back of your throat and atop the tongue . drinkability is affected by the prickly mouthfeel and odd aftertaste .

pitch black color , topped with a very dark tan , thick head .  refreshing and great regular ol ' beer . personally : i struggle to write a `` beer review '' when talking about pbr . you ca n't really talk about slight notes of anything really ... pbr is a state of mind and a good one to be in every so often . she glanced over , looked at my can and said `` i guess we 're all out of money this time of night . '' a classic .

scored this at goebels in wichita pours copper/auburn with 2 fingers of tan head . superior head retention & insane lacing s : faint breadyness t : caramel , breadyness , earthy & herbal hops , dryness up front , plus just a touch of woody hops well .  the carbonation is way too strong with small sharp bubbles .

wow , the pour was amazing . the off white head stuck around for a while over the amber red .  it 's very lacking in the body department . d- due to the lack of body and carbonation , this beer is very easy to put away .
but i loved the sugar toast aroma that wanders in and out of cherry , strawberry and kiwi .  m - thin .

when i finally got it open , it poured a rich dark ruddy brown with a firm head with a marshmellowy consistency .  mouthfeel was light and thin , due to the low carbonation , so it was lacking the smooth velvety body that you would expect from a oatmeal stout .
you can not top that for a weizen pour . dark gold golden with a large , rocky head that spills over the top of the glass .  mouthfeel : flat . flat .
it looks beautiful in the glass , kind of a smoked ruby color .  very thin .
three finger white , fluffy head . great head retention with at least two fingers remaining the whole time . superb lacing with thick rings . lovely .  mouth feel is watery and dilute .

bottle poured into a tulip glass . generous beige head with pretty good retention and nice lacing . flavor-flavor falls flat .  t : watery mouthfeel overall is saved by light yeast , malty goodness and peanut shells in the finish .
appearance - pours a dark ruby with a creamy cratered tan head , lots of sticky lacing .  mouthfeel is unremarkable , almost like water .

very belgian appearance with a large head above a bright orange body .  in the appearance , is a coppery color , with a poor head of foam , the bottle and the logo are retro ; lot of caramel and sugar in the smell ; some essences of caramel and roasted malts in the taste ; the drinkability is good ; the mouthfeel is watery and fizzy , with a low bitterness .

impressive head with lots of rockiness while it recedes slowly . nice lace . the color is deep , dark brown .  the mouthfeel is very gaseous . i 've had 3 of their beers now and they have all felt shitty in the mouth .
a- nice pour ... 5-finger head , nice espresso color and a great deep brown body .  mouthfeel is super thin and watery .

poured with an absolutely beautiful , huge , foamy , fluffy , frothy , billowy , off white head that soon settled down and some lace . color is cloudy amber with a few tiny bubble trails .  almost no head and very thin mouthful . this reminds me of cider .

from a 500 ml brown bottle . massive head development on the pour , a solid foamy mocha coloured entity with amazing retentio that settles very slowly . the body is deep pitch opaque black , faint almond nimbus when held to light .  the palate is thin .
s - really impressive aroma , oak and alcohol , also fruity and caramel-like notes .  mouthfeel is watery , medium carbonation levels .
a : pours very dark brown , almost completely opaque , with a large tan head . the lacing on this is very nice .  m- thin and carbonated . probably the worst dimension to this so-so beer .

nice black color with some faint brown hues around the edge . big frothy root beer float looking head that leaves sticky lace .  flavor is malty with a thinnish mouthfeel . high carbonation , too much alcohol , not very drinkable , however it does n't have a bunch of absurd off-flavors like most organic beers .

12oz bottle , served in a sam adams `` perfect pint '' glass ... a - good solid amount ( inch+ ) of puffy and pillowy bright white foam ... barely fit all of this beer into the glass .  mouthfeel is thin and fizzy , not at all what i want in a chocolate bock .
smells awesome . little spicey .  m - did n't care for this , too thin with too much carbonation .
opaque black with a large mud brown head . cavernous retnetion and multiple droopy lace rings .  astringent and unbalanced . the mouth feel is a mixture of sandpaper carbonation and water texture .

12oz bottle into a delirium tremens goblet . absolutely gorgeous , awe-inspiring pour that fills the glass with a fiery , peach body infused with a yeasty haze . a sizable tuft of off-white head clings to the glass as it slowly recedes to a thick cap of foam . great carbonation and lacing to boot .  mouth feels a lot thinner than it looks , almost watery overall not a bad beer , but almost to overpowering with the nutt flavor and not enough else going on .
pours a deep golden color with a solid 3 finger creamy head that retains well .  very thin .
sierra nevada 30th pours a inky , impenetrable black with a deep brown head .  the mouthfeel was thin , soda like with little real substance .

hazy amber body with a frothy off-white head , the retention of which is pretty impressive considering the abv . a thick ring of lacing up top , with drippy streaks down below .  flavor was shallow , sweetness was hardly there at all , and mouthfeel was really thin .

wow , this brew has a really nice color . a nice clear amber that insist you to drink it all up immediately . : ) ) the head is frothy light white and quite big .  this otherwise very nice beer fails in the mouthfeel and carbonation for me .

this one is a nice bright glowing amber orange , with a hefty amount of white fluffy foam .  first impressions , which you only get one of , is that this beer is anorexic , not enough body to carry this off ; not even sure if this would reach porter territory . and it 's not just that , i do n't care it 's not to style , it 's actively watery . decent enough , but one of the thinnest mouthfeels i 've ever experienced in a dark beer .

appearance : pours a clear dark orange color with a 3 '' fluffy head that lasts a long time .  very light carbonation and very light bodied . starts malty , some hops , way too watery , finish is clean , not a typical lager .
on cask at aobf a fluffy tan head rises over oily black , black , black .  mouthfeel : on thin side .

poured into great divide tulip ... appearance-dark burnt orange body . just an absurd amount of of carbonation bubbles clinging to the side of the glass . the head is about 2 fingers with sticky lacing clinging to the glass . very nice .  pretty much flat with not much of a mouthfeel .

hazy orange color , very belgian looking . like the artificial flavor you 'd put on bagged chips to make it taste like a real foodstuff . feels like the countryside , aromas of barnyard . yeast all around , very belgian .  there 's no bite , no kick , to the mouthfeel , and it 's not creamy or dense either . that said , there 's nothing to prevent you from having many , because it goes down like water .

s - really like the smell on this one with lots of green apple . lots of bready wheat in here , but this was a letdown from the nose . m - medium bodied with a lot of carbonation , seems fine .  m - low carbonation , slick , flat finish .

atwater dunkel poured a deep , dark brown with red highlights and a nice creamy off-white head .  it was thin and very carbonated , with a bitter aftertaste . the body was poor , although it was bland enough to still be reasonably easy to drink .

a : pours a pitch black body with 2 fingers of dark mocha head capping the brew .  thin taste of belgian white beer . most other beers i 've tried from unibroue has been fairly strong , maybe that 's why i thought this one lacked body ? still , it 's not as good as hoegaarden if comparing to another belgian wit .
a- very dark in color , amber with hues of maroon . pours with a luscious strong head .  mouthfeel is generally flat , sticky , and unappealing .
s- fruity , flowery aroma with a hint of yeast .  thin , spritzy body .

pours a viscous , deep black , like old motor oil head is a nice burnt tan color , with decent weight but not sticky .  a thin beer , it 's a bit watery with a heavy orange and clove taste . the smell and flavor of this beer is great , but the mouthfeel really takes away from it .
12 oz bottle poured into a tulip glass a : pretty awesome looking beer .  rather thin for the style ; almost like soda rather than a stout .

toward the end of the pouring , the beer did n't even make it beyond the head- it hit the foam and just created more . beautiful dark golden color , the head dissipates slowly , and leaves lacing all down the glass . beautiful .  t/m : the mouthfeel is thin and quite watery ; the taste is equally limp . mouthfeel and a general weakness of character ruins any chance at more than a passable brew .
black as night with a thin brown head , as to be expected from a stout .  mouthfeel is thin , typical saranac . why do all their brews lack body ?

the head color in particular is incredible with a kind of dark chocolate brown that resembles ice cream . s - i think if there was a weak point on this beer , this is it .  mouthfeel : smooth but horribly dry , especially on the finish , which is reminiscent of a stale cracker .

the aroma was amazing . smells like a perfect roast of coffee . also lemon zest and coffee bean aromas . overall , this beer is awesome . i really enjoyed this beer and i plan on buying more of it , if i can still find it .  the watery , loose texture certainly did not help things .

completely opaque with a two finger frothy , yellowish beige head that has excellent retention , only slowly fading into a lasting cap that coats the glass with huge chunks of soapy lacing .  not much compexity and feel was very thin .

pours a swirly dark brown , turning into pitch black with a huge two finger head .  taste/mouthfeel- watery feel to the beer , some grain and alcohol , hops and malt are present but do n't really make much of an impression . drinkability-refreshing on a hot summer day , other than that the thin feel dissapoints .

s : fantastic big malt t : american sweet malt , the hops have faded substantially , to be expected , slight caramel .  it 's cheap , surprisingly light-tasting ( for a 40 ) and packs a mighty whallop in terms of buzz . as a long fan of steel reserve 211 and st. ides , i admit that they do n't stand up to double malt in terms of taste and mouthfeel .

pours a lovely burned clear copper in color with very , very thick and sticky white head that not only lasted the entire pint ( s ) , but also left thick lacing on the glass .  diluted watered down light to medium feel that washes back with a diluted overall feel , however lending to some drinkability , but lacking in carbonation . tacky cloying aftertaste .

magnificent appearance on this beer . crystal clear dark amber and full of skinny bubble streams . just enough creamy , thick head to cover the beer in a dignified manner.. a beerkini ! lacing is solid and unflinching . looks meaty .  the beer is very thin bodied , so much so that it almost seems to develop a tartness .

pours a beautiful red-pink with some fizzy head that lasts for about a second and recededs to a glass that looks more like wine than anything , carbonation rising on the sides of the glass looks great .  it watery and thin and does n't taste completely crappy therefore i say it 's pretty drinkable .

wow , what a fantastic looking beer . pours a deep yellowish golden color and is very cloudy like most unfiltered wheat beer . the head on this beer is just absolutely ridiculous .  lots of carbonation and quite watery .
pours an opaque brown with an off-white head . almost 0 light was shining through the liquid which was pretty cool .  body is way too thin for the style and way too filtered imo .

pour a brown and ruby with streaming carbonation and a lasting , firm , sticky head .  this was a strange one for me - i was only able to try this one bottle and i have thought it might have been infected pours muddy dark amber brown with a huge huge head ( my first thought of infection ) that left lacing all down the glass smells of some apples ( # 2 ) but could be raisins - get some brown sugar and oatmeal taste - has lots of roasted malt and chocolate which surprised me - cinnamon and other flavors that reminded me of xmas - those same raisins/apples that seem a bit off mouthfeel - was lacking - the body thin and was flat ?

it 's as delicious smelling as it is complex . with the president set by the nose , the taste is a small disappointment , even though it carries through with the same elements in varying degrees . while it has a couple rough patches , it 's an enjoyable weizenbock .  mouthfeel suffers for the overenthusiastic carbonation job .
appearance - total black pour with a finger of smooth , rich , mocha foam .  awful thin too .

nogne- imperial stout purchased a bomber from circle liquors- pennington , nj a- thick dark black with a big creamy frothy head .  a weak attempt at a flemish sour . the beer has good light redish color and the lactic sourness is present but it is thin and watery . no hop aroma or other funky lambic type aromas , just a lactic beer .

pours as a very dark reddish-brown caramel color . appears fantastic with the first pour .  the addition of the yeast helps , but not much . d - good beer that will be much better if i leave it sitting for awhile so the carbonation will disperse . addition of the yeast make a huge difference in all aspects and is highly recommended , but overall drinkability is negatively affected by the mouthfeel .

copper coloured clear ale with a foamy white head . head retention was brilliant .  talking of flat ... here 's the signature low level of carbonation . fortunately the body is a bit fuller , so it partially overcomes this .
appearance- mahagoney-cherry colored elixer . great large bubbled lace chunks cling for life over much of my glass . a glorious sight .  feels flat for how much fizzing is going on .

great looking beer . good sized head that settles to a heavy film that lasts throughout your drinking session and also gives up some good looking lace . looks appetizing .  this beer was pretty damn flat . no getting around it , the lack of carbonation is definitely gon na bring the score down , and i 'm honestly not sure i 'd buy it again unless i knew it did n't have this issue . there are certain styles where a lack of carbonation does n't matter much , an iipa is not one of them .

i had this on tap at the brewery into a tulip ... the beer is medium black , light tan carbonation , does n't last long ... the aroma is super strong , exactly like coffee , too strong though . a little too sweet ... the taste is sweet milk and vanilla , interesting , really hits the creme brulee on the head . tone it down a bit and maybe this will be really good .  i really love the taste but the complete lack of carbonation is disappointing . i like this but even with some mild carbonation i would love this !

s : very interesting ! dark syrupy malts , prune , licorice , bitter orange . t : similar notes from the aroma , but far more dominated by the malty flavors .  first of all the palate was very thin , with hints of chocolate and a slightly smoke flavour .

from notes : pours pitch black and completely opaque with a three finger frothy mocha head that has excellent retention , only slowly fading into a thick lasting cap . large rings and chunks of soapy lacing coat the glass .  unfortunately , the mouthfeel really takes away from the flavor ... far too much carbonation rips through the flavor profile and prevents it from getting through cleanly .

it poured a cloudy burnt orange color that was beautiful to look at . it was like looking through a stained glass window . there was also a nice light tan head but i was too busy looking at the brew .  m : extremely thin body ; low carbonation ; watery texture .
poured from a 12 oz bottle into a pint glass . crystal clear pale gold color with a 1 '' firm , fluffy white head .  mouthfeel : very light , watery body with not much to recommend it .
held to light it has a nice hints of red peeking through . has a nice tan head that hangs out for a while . great lacing .  ) and a thin , almost watery mouthfeel .
pours a dark , hazy amber/brown color .  a slight tartness was overcome by a sticky mouthfeel . the mouthfeel was heavy and coating , and a slight acid burn on the throat .

a - black as night with the smallest amber/ruby highlights and an enormous tan , dense , and lumpy head which seemed to refuse to go down .  mouthfeel is where this brew suffers : it 's really just pretty thin .
