the aroma was intense . quite sweet overall . chocolate notes dominated . a nice mix of dark chocolate and powdered cocoa . somewhat bourbony and boozy . the lingering finish was very roasty and hoppy , with the hops being leafy , piney and sharp . overall , the beer was rather pithy , dry and bitter on the back end . the mouthfeel was creamy and smooth yet noticeably thin for the style .  m - very thin ... too thin for me .
it smells pretty delicious . taste : lots of dark caramel and vanilla come to the forefront on the palate .  the mouthfeel is very thin .

a - three fingers of light blonde foam with solid retention and gorgeous lacing . while it looks a touch overcarbonated it 's otherwise pretty attractive .  carbonation fails to hide the watery feel of this beer .

smells of citrus fruit ( grapefruit , orange ) , sweet malts lie underneath . very unique aroma . i said , `` summer strawberries in a hay field , '' while my brother said , `` watermelon bubblicious . clean with good carbonation ; tickling but not overbearing . an easy ale to dring with a great mouth and a top-notch nose .  goes down kindof harsh with carbonation and alcohol .
a- dark brown with a off-white head that laces nicely .  thin bodied with a watery finish , this could still be a passable summer brew for when you have little else in the fridge .
fresh herbs and attitude .  mouthfeel was very light in body and watery in texture with a flat carbonation .

it pours deep brown , almost black , with light head .  m : this is where the beer loses me ... it feels thin and watery where i was expecting a richer , creamier texture . it 's just too bad it 's so thin ... if they boosted the maltiness a bit this would be a killer beer .

from the token `` snow '' effect to the jet black body to the creamy firm head , you ca n't beat the visual effect . it leaves nice rings down the entire glass .  the taste is disappointing , just a german macro really . too thin , not much taste.barely average , but sub-par for the price .

pours black with notes of ruby when held to the light . the head stays very well and leaves pretty nice rocky lacing .  very thin with little carbonation with a slight oily feel and a buttery aftertaste that lingers .

a- comes to me with two fingers of coffee and cream colored head that rises above the glass and holds for a good bit . one hell of a nice looking brew .  m : the lack of malts hurt the mouthfeel and the endurance of flavor . i realize that apwas are meant to be light , refreshing quaffs but gumballhead , in my opinion , would benefit from a slightly beefier body and thicker texture . the amount of carbonation is average or below and leaves a little to be desired as well . d : despite the low mouthfeel score , gumballhead is still an excellent brew and i would purchase cases of it during the summer months if only fff would distribute to pa , the greedy sobs .

s- very fresh pale cereal grains and fruity floral pineapple and fruit blossom aroma . i appreciate pilseners with ale complexities . t- very crisp and perfectly bittered and balanced .  the mouthfeel is hot as hell . let a mouthful of this rest on your palate for 10-15 seconds , and it feels like the insides of your mouth are being dissolved . it 's very astringent and has a monster bite.the aftertaste is just ... boozy .
pours a beautiful dark black colour with tan creamy head .  t/m : very thin ... highly carbonated ... gives more of a champagne quality than a sour yeast ... lacks body . just fizzy . lacks body .
this looks like a perfect power beer .  the mouthfeel leaves a lot to be desired . thin , and too much carbonation .
gorgeous clear and deep mahogany oak pour , topped by a massive ivory head . really liked the sediment goodies at the end of the bottle .  the mouthfeel is thin and watery with little carbonation .

a - espresso brown with a one finger cream/tan head with impressive retention and a nice amount of lacing .  however it 's not very complex and is lacking body . thin and somewhat lost to where it should be .
a- a very hazy orange/ brown liquid with a massive light brown head that has astounding retention .  2.5/5 m : thin and carbonated . unimpressive .

a steady pour yielded 2 fingaz of semi dark tan dense foam , well not that dense as it 's dying down quickly . some flimsy spots of lace .  let down in the mouthfeel however..very sticky and cloying .
really beautiful looking beer .  felt very thin in the mouth .

this brew has a hefty hop character ... maybe even over done , but i happen to like it ; pine more than citrus . the hops are more pronounced in the odor than in the flavor but it is strong all around . the socks may come in somewhere with the malts ... not too sure ... a solid all around ipa , if a bit on the abrasive side .  next to no beer flavour of any sort , may as well be soda water with a lime wedge .

listening to the brabanonne as instructed on the label while enjoying this - although the hymn is only about a minute long , and this certainly takes quite a bit longer to finish ... seal brown , impenetrable liquid , with a hefty sandy brown cap which recedes to a thick mocha-like finger . superb retention , especially for the abv .  nutty as well , flavored almost like a typical dark lager very flat feel . watery as much as it is heavy . decent brew but leaves me wondering if they could n't kick up the carbonation at all .
poured a oily and thick blackish brew , with a great topping of tan whipping cream .  m - thin with too much carbonation .

it is a good looking beer . it has a clear gold color and perfect whit head and lace .  mouthfeel medium-thin , but with low carbonation . not sure if the cork was improperly fit , but this was almost flat .

pours amber/caramel with humungous white head that held a 1 '' head throughout . lacing was very good smell : some fruittiness and hops , but very subtle for style taste : intense hops bitterness followed by some malt fruitiness .  however water overrides any other flavor m - very thin .

this beer pours out of the bottle a dark amber , with ruby highlights , topped off with a thick , frothy faintly tan-colored head . the head foams up into a large cloud , but soon dissipates leaving lacing down the sides of the glass as it goes .  the mouthfeel is the beer 's downfall . it is very poppy ... rather , it seems almost too effervescent , which leaves a sort of stinging sensation on the tongue . there is some decent flavor , but the body is weak and not well-rounded .

pours with a huge 3+ finger white fluffy head that has great retention and layers with every sip . exceptional is an understatement .  mouthfeel is a weak point with this beer being thin & watery , just nothing to hold on to .
bottle : poured a clear golden color ale with a huge pure white foamy head with good retention and some good lacing .  * mouthfeel is thin and watery , with a plethora of fine carbonation .

hoppy , approachable , and ( like most southern tier beers ) a highly attractive appearance . most southern tier beers have a clear body and brilliant color , and this beer is no exception .  the middle is thin and sweetens some . when cold , the finish is slightly metallic with some obvious alcohol . this is n't bad compared to american macros and some other strong export lagers , but that 's about it .

a beautiful amber color , clear , nice head .  the taste was descent enough mostly bitter coffee with a bit of fruit but there was little , to almost no , carbonation that really made the beer fall flat for me ( no pun intended ) .

a - beautiful burnt orange with copper tones . off-white , foamy head that took several minutes to simmer down to a small ring . ample carbonation that held throughout the long life of the beer .  scarce body , quite watery .

aroma is of bitter orange peel and spicy yeast . smell is wonderful . upon sipping , the first thing that struck me was the medium to heavy body on this one .  overwhelming carbonation , especially for the style . it is refreshing though , once you get past the overwhelming carbonation .

pours a slightly hazed honeyed orange in colour with lots of visible carbonation . the head is absolutely massive , taking up almost half the glass and leaving a patchwork web of lace on the walls of my glass as it slowly recedes .  come to think of it , drinking peeber is like drinking water . very thin .
a - poured into a tulip a clear amber with a two finger head that sinks to a thick blanket and leaves huge creamy side lacing .  very watery in the mouth , virtually no carbonation .

appearance : dark copper brown , great clarity , thick tannish creamy head on hard pour , some lacing aroma : upfront banana-like fruitiness , big hit of caramelly malt , some molasses , no hops , touch of alcohol flavor : mellow sweetness initially with a rich melanoidin roundness to the palate , toasty caramel sweet smoothness balances out with just enough hop bitterness in the semi-sweet finish , sumptuously tasty mouthfeel : medium-full bodied but not syrupy , gentle carbonation and a tantalizing alcohol warmth without any burning sensation overall impression : this is a supremely well-crafted beer , one of the hallmarks of the style .  smell-fairly clean , i do detect some malt but not much else , no hoppiness , alcohol , or otherwise . taste-fairly tasteless , some malt does come through again but for the most part this tastes like water . drinkability-somewhat malty and low abv , you could pound these that 's for sure . overall-yawn , sorry for the not so detailed review but this is another not so detailed light beer , even from an ok brewery like pocono .
smell : malty sweet , with rich dark fruits and nuttiness . very appealing . taste : malty and nutty , lightly sweet .  mouthfeel : thin and watery .

appearance - copper orange poured into a pilsner glass . a finger of cream-colored head creates a solid film of lace on the glass . mad bubble action keeps a thin blanket on top of the beer .  mouthfeel this was the porters weak point , imo . the light carbonation was cheap and fizzy , and the body was so thin i wouldnt even call it medium .

great retention and great lacing .  t/m-weak , watery body with only the bare minimum carbonation required to hold the beer together . the dominant flavor is slick , estery yeast , and even that is muted by the overall watery mouthfeel .

this ale pours a beautiful chestnut brown with an off-white head that clings to the sides of the glass . looks grand in a scotch thistle glass .  t - the biting hop profile completely overwhelms the malt to the point of it being thin . there is a touch of what tastes like a sour infection but it plays out more in the mouthfeel . m - thin , light-bodied , and under-carbonated , there is a dry bitterness from the hops but it 's more of a dry , almost lactobacillus-like sourness that seems to be taking a hold of the brew .
pours a deep , opaque black-brown with a fairly thick and fine-bubbled light tan head , quite appealing .  m- carbonation is too harsh for a hefeweizen .

the beer pours a very inky dark mahogany color with a rich creamy off white head with billowing laces and a nice retention .  except for the very poor mouthfeel , a great beer , one that i would recommend from the bottle .

bottle , from whole foods in tustin , ca , a : pours a dark maroon red , with a thick rich cap of white foam , great head retention , extensive thick lacing .  poured chilled in flared glass a : dark caramel , clear ; very thick head ; good carb beads ; great lacing s : a bit univiting ; thin , malty ( sweet ) aroma ; but i do n't smell a bock here t : one-dimensional bock ; little double about it m : watery , thin , dead it looks fantastic , but 'tai n't .
a- opaque dark red-brown with a creamy tan head .  flavor is one dimensional : black coffee . just tastes bitter and thin , like someone aged seltzer water in a used-coffee-filter-lined barrel .

a- dark black looking , held up to the light a dark ruby tint appears and you can notice definite clarity from such lively carbonation . leaves an amazingly full lace . as it is consumed the head turns more cloudlike .  m : whoa , way too carbonated , reminiscent of the swill called bud light i used to drink as one of the ignorant unwashed .
pours the obvious trademark guinness look , prefect creamy white head and the opaque black liquid they call beer .  mouthfeel - pretty thin .
this beer looks amazing . the smell reminds me alot of shiner bock , but much richer , ca n't say i am very impressed with how this smells though .  the palate is thin .

pours the darkest brown head ive seen , which thins away quickly .  the puffy body apes airiness up front , but soon gels into a coalgulated syrup , yet still maintaining a thin indistictness of structure . everything here seems to compete against itself . the result is atonal and abrasive .
a : exceptional . very nice brilliant copper with a good foamy head .  it has an ok flavor , but it 's very thin .
not a huge imperial stout fan , but i enjoy one now and then . this beer is night black , and no light through it . solid  thin and filmy .

33cl into a tulip . pours an excellent deep dark rich garnet , highlights and bright back lights reveal a gorgeous red . inch of clumpy froth , decent retention & decent lacing .  my biggest disappointment was the mouthfeel with no lasting carbonation or creaminess .
pours a beautiful black with a slowly forming rich and creamy head .  slight caramel flavors present mouthfeel : thin and highly carbonated .

very pleasant smelling beer . very fruity with citrus and maybe a pear or apricot smell to it as well .  mouthfeel is really quite thin , with the flavour kind of releasing itself more from an emanating aroma than any substantial body .
poured with a thick foamy head that faded to a half inch solid and lasting layer that leaves a ton of lacing .  poor amount of carbonation .
a- beautiful rising 2 finger head with moderate retention .  mouthfeel : thin body , watery texture , moderate-lively carbonation drinkability : well , not bad for the style .

with a vigorous pour you get a beautiful effect . almost two fingers of rich foamy milk chocolate colored head , that lasts long and leaves lace as it fades .  m : pretty dry and heavily carbonated with an unpleasant metallic aftertaste . body is pretty thin and in line with other macro lagers .

pours to a chill-hazed medium amber , forming a nice white head with excellent retention and lacing despite being served in a tiny 4 oz sampler glass .  it is thin bodied despite the nitro , with a masked , watery aroma . the beer may perhaps be too traditional to appreciate as it shows more modesty than american craft beers usually do . shannon 's core values are a dry grain and chaff taste with some show of dark lace . but the lack of body and flavor are obstacles to appreciation .
a ) bronze in color . poured with a thin creamy head . nice lacing along the edge .  mouthfeel : sharp at first , but the carbonation quickly fades away to a watery limpness .

it 's a combination that works incredibly well . at first the chardonnay does n't come through so well , it 's more of a vinous acidity that blends with the funk .  m - the one flaw . too wet and smooth .

pours a deep darrk amber/brown with a creamy thick light brown head , very sticky .  taste : i thought it had a burnt tar like flavor with some coffee and chocolate tones mouthfeel : it was very thin and watery for a stout .
cherry is very present and smells amazing . slight grain smell .  mouthfeel watery + light .
lion stout pours out almost black with a huge , dense , rocky head .  this is too loose on the mouthfeel ; no structure at all .
this brew pours an almost opaque black color . the head is massive , creamy , and brown .  weak body and watery mouthfeel .

appearance - high marks in every way ! from the midnight black color to the coco powder brown head . leaves a superb patchwork of lacing just to push the envelope a little bit more .  feel is flat , untextured , un-nuanced .
the aroma is strong , powerfully of roasted barley and black malt .  relatively poor mouthfeel .

pours a dark dark dark brown ( pretty much black ) with a crazy thick inch of dark brown foam/head which leaves a boat ton of sticky brown lacing .  with better carbonation , i think this beer has the elements to be phenomenal .

s : huge grapefruit nose . some wildflowers in the background . best ever ! t : very smooth . hoppy to the end . d : very drinkable ... maybe too much so .  a thinner mouthfeel too . feels like carbonated soda on the finish .

pours a nice amber color with a billowing 3 finger head when poured directly into my 16 oz . a nice web of lacing is left behind despite the fact that this glass had some residue on it before pouring .  mouthfeel was loose and watery ( though the taste did not seem to reflect the watery nature of the beer 's feel ) .
lots of lacing left behind , incredibly impressive appearance .  the consistency of this beer was watery , and the mouth feel was rather weak .
poured into a pint glass a : moderate pour yields 1 finger of tight eggshell colored foam with great retention .  the mouthfeel is very thin and kind of disappointing for a high-ish gravity beer .

s - aroma is insane . up there with sculpin as one of my favorite aromas . serious west coast hop character . this is a truly great take on a west coast double ipa , which is my favorite flavor profile generally . o - overall it is brilliant . one of my favorite aromas , with a every balanced taste to match .  mouthfeel is very thin , almost watery .
a- this beer looks very , very nice .  it 's heavy and a little cloying . the mouthfeel is thick and unpleasant .

it pours an almost opaque black that 's capped by an extremely creamy chocolate-colored head . but the best part is the effect given by the carbonation as it 's reabsorbed into the liquid : it looks like an hourglass , the brown bubbles `` falling '' down into the black abyss at the bottom of the glass .  m - again thin and watery .
a : black . a nice espresso head formed from the pour followed by a good lacing .  mouthfeel : pretty thin and watery for any beer , but especially so for a stout .

smells of an overload of milk chocolate , but in a really good way .  however , i was very distracted from the taste of this beer with a watery and flat-feeling mouthfeel . this is a good tasting beer , but the mouthfeel issue led me to be slightly disappointed with it .
a - high points for appearance .  super fizzy carbonation works for this beer but i still wish it was n't so fizzy .

3 fingers of gorgeous creamy of white head . excellent retention w/ a little less lacing down the glass .  thin may be a good description , but it was certainly not in line with what i would expect from an imperial stouts of this style .
it pours a hazy golden orange beer with a creamy two finger head . retention and lacing are both exceptional .  a little too grassy , and excess carbonation , not nearly enough hop bite . thin body .
a : a nice , light amber color with a foamy two finger head that sticks around for a while . nice lacing .  mouthfeel is way thin , and drinkability is just not that great for me .

s : fruity notes of sherry , some alcohol , fresh fruit , cherries , peppers , some wood and spices . biscuits and toffe , and also some strawberries . very hoppy .  mouthful is thin and reminds me of rice .

poured a slight hazed well blonde of course with a huge blooming white head that caught me off guard almost overflowing the glass and it took its sweet time coming down leaving a soap-scum like trace behind.love the hops in the nose citrus oil dominates with underlying pine and lightly toasted grain , a grainy lighter mouthfeel not watery just on the thinner side.bright flavors of floral hop and citrus not overly complex by any means a light toastiness underneath the hops but not much in malt complexities but it goes down oh so easily for 7.5 % alc let me tell ya.hmm a good beer if not complex , a good summer quaffer and the biggest blonde ale i have had to date .  m : thin . very dissapointing .
a - pours a ruby red/light brown colour with good carbonation and a creamy off white head of two fingers that fades to one leaving good lacing .  mouthfeel : way too thin for this type of beer .

the aroma is relatively strong delivering a ton of vanilla on the nose with a finish that provides some nice depth with oak dominating followed by some distinct bourbon flavor .  too carbonated for my taste and has a dry character on the tail as it warms that i do n't care for .

all kinds of yeasty scents going on , funky and horsey mixes with fruit . very nice . the flavor has the same components as the aroma , but i notice them in the opposite order . i think the flavor was a little bit of a letdown after how amazing and funky the aroma was , but i still liked my first fantome beer quite a bit . i know that this brewery is known for their spices , but i would prefer a little less of a spiced taste so that fantastic yeast profile could shine .  m - no body to speak of and a bit of unpleasant starchyness .

pour is beautiful - black with a thick creamy tan head that just hovers on top , leaving thick lacing all the way to the bottom of the pint .  again , almost no carbonation at all , and it just feels watery and heavy at the same time . flavorful i guess , but i did n't care for what there was , and the lack of carbonation really makes this unpleasant .

the smell runs the gambit from brett funkiness , pineapple , lemonade , some biscuity malty undertones , sour cherries , orange rind , and a slight bit of medinciney phenols mixed with faint all spice . the aroma has a certain weight to it and is delicious . the taste is actually a bit more focused and reminds me more of a syrupy lemonade with some brett musti/tartness mixed with granny smith apples .  nothing at all in the middle except an annoying hard carbonation , watery . finish - a bit nutty , astringent and very mild fruit esters overall - this beer is not bad , but very average in taste . i liked most aspects about this mild except for the taste which i felt could have had more roundness and a bit more plump , just too watery .
almost perfect lacing , like somebody painted it on the glass .  too watery though - a beer this thin ought to have more carbonation to stay interesting .

pours that customary imperial stout used-motor oil black - totally opaque - while yielding a solid 1 '' mocha-toned head ; surprisingly great retention and lots of lacing . wow , what an appearance - even in a style where it can be tough to stand out .  mouthfeel was a bit thin and slippery .
nice tight tall waterfall foam , that lasts a while .  mouthfeel is lacking as this beer just feels watered down in all aspects .
the aroma is delightful with intricate notes of bourbon-drenched caramel , raisin , fig pudding , and vanilla bean .  some light but lasting carbonation . leaves mouth feeling bubbly and sudsy .

a- amazing head and lacing . looks like fresh , powdery snow .  it is watery and just doesnt taste as strong as i think a porter should . you taste what you smell , but the mouthfeel always leaves me thinking , `` why did i buy this again '' ? if you like the taste of porters but do not like the thickness and wish it felt more like a light beer , this is for you !

this is a beautiful beer , it has good color and looks quite appealing , however i thought that the mismatch of its grapefruit aroma and it 's highly tart smell and it 's low citrus draw made it oddly unstable on the palate .  m : extremely thin , almost water like thickness .

it was served in a snifter and had an almost black colour and a good head that was surprisingly long lasting .  the taste can only be described as `` extremely watery '' . as far as mouthfeel goes , once again the key words are `` extremely watery '' . flat and dull .

huge three to four fingers of very white head . looks great . great head retention with some lacing , but not much .  a - appealing , very red color , but less than a half-finger of head and no lacing whatsover s - mostly malt scent , slight roasted , with a hint of coffee t - nice , roasted malt flavor , stronger than the smell but not too strong m - highly carbonated , to the detriment of the flavor d - a good red , but too carbonated in that it masks the flavor .
this beer pours a beautiful head .  ok mouthfeel is pretty bad . thin and watery .

the beer poured a hazy straw gold color with a fantastic 4 finger white head that lasted several minutes . lacing was also plentiful .  ) version of carlsberg 's elephant bock . this is one of my standard `` crap beers , '' the ones that you 're ashamed to admit you enjoy ( hey , we ca n't drink belgians all the time ) . it 's cheap , easy to stomach , tastes decent and has a cool elephant head on the label .

it has a nice dense tan colored head that is just sitting right on top of the beer . great lacing down the sides of the tulip glass .  nutty with bready malts some hints of caramel and a bit of smokeiness malty taste with some cherry flavors and hints of wet tabacco thin body , little carbonation , very watery , i was incredibly unimpressed with the body of this beer a very sessionable abv which is appreciated , but i found the mouthfeel of this beer so offputting that i have no desire to try it again anytime soon

bottle poured into a nonic , the american amber is clear bronze with a large , fluffy off-white head that leaves heavy lace . a pretty good pnw amber with no flaws and pretty light for a decent abv .  light roast lingers in the finish , not much bitterness , but again a very thin body detracts majorly from this beer and keeps it from being recommendable .
a tremendous frothy tan head billows out of the top of the glass .  finally , the finish of this thin bodied beer was short and watery .

... pours a brown dark brown colour ... has oak , chocolate , cherries , tar and other grab bag candies ... tastes like cherries a bit ... bold yet still quite balanced , a great brew indeed ... quality and crazy mixed in a 750 bottle..  the beers got a big body , almost too big for its style . its not terrible , the body is really killing this one for me .
fantastic presentation . very light and frothy head over orange-yellow .  mouthfeel : pretty thin and watery .
a lovely brew .  f - pretty limp , even more than i remember . like stout-flavored water .

nice robust smell for this style : light cappuccino notes , with burnt sugar and whole-grain bread notes in there . the sugar and bread flavors that were promised by the smell are there , but they play a background role .  m : 2.0 a very watery beer , while the flavors are constantly present there are no real stand out characteristics in the feel . d : 3.0 goes down easy thanks to its thin consistency .
the appearance was exceptional . it is a caramel brown color with a very good looking thick head .  m - watery and very light .

smell is like i dropped a spice rack and all the bottles broke open ! wow , there is a lot of stuff going on in this beer . all of the herbs plus that great stone hop smell ! with a nice hop finish !  finish is flat and lackluster . as a bartender , i 've tried to steer newc fans toward better micro versions of brown ale , like goose island or moose drool , and they order corona instead .

poured from 12oz bottle to pint glass a : pours a deep amber color with a beautiful two finger off-white puffy cloud-like head that has very good retention and a nice amount of lacing all the way down.. s : smells quite bold .  really thin , like a light beer . best thing from this brewery .

pours a beautiful deep , dark , burgundy/brown/amber with a very thick medium head of very tight bubbles that has fair lasting power with a nice lasting lace .  mouthfeel is flat and has little carbonation which surprises me .

beautiful domed head that leaves plenty of ring lace on the glass . dirty copper color . okay , this beer has a dirty , pungent earthy smell .  pours dark dark brown almost black with a 1/2 finger tan head that faded to nothing and left no lacing smell is almost identical to dfh palo santo - very intoxicating taste - again palo santo clone with out the wood - vanilla booze chocolate mouthfeel is not good - the body is too light and the carbonation mixed with the booze stings my mouth drinkability takes a hit due to the mouthfeel but the flavor on this beer is great and maybe some age will mellow the carbonation ?
flawless visuals , a cloudy , light reddish brown color with a hefty , almost creamy in it 's thickness froth .  the real problem here is the utter lack of carbonation . nearly completely flat .
the beer looks great . deep red and oranges with a sticky off white head .  the mouthfeel was weak bodied and highly carbonated .
an aggressive pout ( i was in a hurry , dammit ) made a unbelievable snow-cone pile of tan head on top of a chill hazed amber orange brew .  m/d : sticky , syrupy , and way under carbonated .
